<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Decaying Corpses</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Kjata Holythunder  (<a href="mailto:KjataEQ@aol.com" class="credit2">KjataEQ@aol.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
I would like to share an experience with you, and express some of my feelings on what happened to me.  I am doing this in the hopes that the right person will read it, and maybe a change will be made.<br><br>First of all, I must speak about twinking.  I realize that many people are opposed to the practice of an already established character making a new one with items and money that they obtain for them, bypassing the normal hard struggle that is common to almost everyone in EQ.  I do not want to address this issue any further than to say I twink characters and I do not see anything morally wrong with that, especially given the amount of help and information I give to struggling newbies on a daily basis.  That having been said...<br><br>Recently I was playing my rogue character, he is level 23.  I will not go into great detail as to what equipment he had, but I spent about 15k platinum on him from the start, making him a pretty great rogue.  In addition to spending that money, he had some enchanted fine steel that I obtained during a GM event in Najena recently, and which no longer drops in the game.  Anyway, my wife and I had been hunting in South Karana for a couple days, having been bound close by in the arena for short corpse retrievals if we died while fighting Aviaks.  We were starting to get bored, so I offered to take her to Conium Darkblade, the poison merchant located in Dagnor's Cauldron on the continent of Faydwer.  So I shout for a port, find one pretty quickly.  We are ported to Greater Faydark, where I show her around (she is not well travelled yet) and hang out at the Kelethin bank for awhile.<br><br>Now this is my second halfling rogue, the first one was my very first character in EQ, and although I am very fond of him I gave him up because I did not give him the most important stats.  (knowing very little at the time I invested into INT and CHA *chuckle*)  My second rogue was to be done right.  Well.. my first rogue had a mask of deception, a bard and rogue only item that casts illusion: dark elf with infinite charges.  This item is no drop, so I couldn't buy it.  I had to brave the caverns of Lower Guk to obtain it, dying quite a few times in the process as I had little assistance and the zone is generally level 35+.  Anyway, I used my dark elf illusion in Kelethin with my first rogue all the time, the only person who was KoS to me while using the illusion was the banker.  I had good wood elf faction, and that is why.<br><br>So I am sitting outside the bank with my second rogue, and I decide I want to be a dark elf for awhile.  So I wear the mask, right click to activate, and morph into a dark elf.  Having had no problems with my first rogue, I assumed that I would not be killed this time.  Well that was a stupid mistake, for the very moment I changed into a dark elf, all nearby guards swarmed me and quickly knocked my health down.  In a panic I jumped from the city, and since the bank is very high up I took 225 damage from the fall, dying upon impact.<br><br>I had also not been smart enough to get a bind right away when I arrived in Greater Faydark, since at level 23 I did not forsee any immediate danger.  So when I respawned, naked, I was back in the Arena at Lake Rathetear, which was my bind point.  Before I could even zone out of the arena, real life issues demanded that I get off the computer.  So I left my corpse to get later, believing I had one full week to retrieve my belongings before it decayed.<br><br>The next day, I didn't feel like making the trek with my rogue to get his body.  So I logged on as another character and proceeded to hunt with him.  I did not know it, but doing so was counting against yet another corpse decay timer that makes it disappear after 24 online hours, whether you are logged as the character with the corpse or not.  After three days of playing my other characters, a wizard friend of mine got on and I was able to get a port, so I quickly logged back on as my rogue and ran to the North Karana spires to catch my ride.<br><br>I arrived in Greater Faydark, happy that I was in the zone with my corpse again and I could go ahead and retrieve it.  So I went to the spot beneath the city of Kelethin where I had died three days earlier, but to my growing dismay I could not find my body anywhere.  Quickly I enlisted the talents of a bard to locate my corpse, who immediately told me that I had no corpses in the zone.  This can't be, I thought, so I got a second opinion from another bard and he had the same answer.  At this point my heart was pounding, I worked for months to save enough money to really get my rogue some nice equipment (my highest character is level 35 so getting 15k platinum together took me a long time, using my master smithing abilities to make most of it)  Right away I petitioned, and within a few minutes a guide, Nanya, answered me.  She was very friendly and polite, and also comforting.  I explained to her the situation, and she told me that there was nothing she could do, that she would escalate my petition for the server GM to review when he got on later.<br><br>So I waited for a few hours, I logged on my other character to try and get a few things done instead of sitting in the Faydark with my naked rogue.  About 7 hours after my first petition, I recieved a tell from GM Danoctilous of the Rodcet Nife server (my server).  I again explained the situation to him, and asked that he please return to me the items I worked so long and hard for.  He told me that he was not allowed, that the policy on decayed corpses is that the items that decayed with them are not returned, despite the fact that they keep records of the items that were on the corpse.  He offered me a "leg up kit", which consists of items with the name of Issued, and having the same AC as ringmail.  Also included in the kit were weapons with the same dmg/dly as fine steel, but with the ability to hit magical creatures.  To give an example, the Issued Medium Rapier I recieved was Magic, No Drop, piercing 5 dmg 23 delay.  The primary weapon that decayed on my corpse was a Slime Coated Harpoon magic piercing 10 dmg 25 delay.  BIG difference.<br><br>This to me was a joke, I felt like I was being punished for not getting my corpse in time, and also being ignorant to the fact that it would rot so fast.  And I agree that ignorance is not an excuse, but the fact remains that the policy needs to be changed.<br><br>I worked very long and very hard to earn the items that decayed along with that corpse.  Some of those items came from a GM event, and can never be replaced.  Most of the others I could save up my money and buy again, but I don't think I should have to.  For starters, the server keeps a record of all the items that I had before I died.  They know exactly what I had, how many charges were on an item if applicable, down to the last detail.  GM Danoctilous said that himself.  But my items were not returned because the policy on decayed corpses is that any items or money that were on the corpse will not be returned to the owner.  In addition to all the items, I had approximately 2k platinum that I was carrying (high str allowed for plenty to be carried on me).  <br><br>I admit fault in this situation, as far as my corpse decaying.  It was my fault I did not retrieve it in time.  However, not everyone has as much free time as I do to play EQ.  Are these people being penalized as well, even though they cannot play as much?  It would seem to me they should be rewarded, since they are still playing for the game, but not adding the server load that their character produces when actually logged on.  (one player does not make a big difference, but there are many such players and that adds up)  You have to realize also that Verant is a business, they are interested in making money, not catering to all our desires.  It really upsets me when people get upset because they don't have it really easy.  Those people need to realize that if Verant made it easy for them to level, they wouldn't play as long, and hence would not end up paying Verant as much money.  Verant does whatever they can to keep you playing as long as possible.  Verant is a moneymaking business... That is why there are so many rare items that must be camped for long periods of time to obtain, that is why there are hell levels, that is why there is such a huge 50+ exp penalty, that is why grouping is so encouraged (since it slows down the rate you level), and I also believe that is why my items were not returned.  Because it slows me down, forces me to make do with less effective equipment, making me do less damage and also take less damage when in a battle.  I believe the reason Verant does not refurbish items lost on decayed corpses is because it slows a character down.  There are some that would claim they don't do it for one person because then they would be swamped with people wanting the same thing done.  Well I hate to break it to ya, but Verant, you are here to serve us, not the other way around.  I am tired of bending over for you.  There is a widespread and ever-growing feeling among the EQ player community that the customer service stinks.  I think I have a right to be angry when all the things I worked so long and hard for, which could have been EASILY GIVEN BACK if you had an inkling of what serving your customers actually means, are now lost forever.<br><br>I have no problem with Verant making it more difficult to level, or making it so you have to camp for desired items most of the time.  I have no problem with grinding through hell levels.  All this is tolerable.  It does make the game fun to have danger as well.  What I have a really big problem with is the decayed corpse policy.  Verant knows good and well what they're doing, they're trying to slow us down.  And that is OK with me, as long as they don't take my hard earned money and items that I aquire over long periods of time just because I couldn't get to my corpse in time, or had more important things to do.<br><br>To the guides and GM's involved in this, I do not hold you responsible.  You are doing your assigned duties, and I respect that.  Much in the way a police officer has to do his job, however unpleasant, you have to do yours also.  The problem is not, for the most part, the guides and GM's, it is the force behind them.  The ones that make the rules, Verant.<br><br>In closing, I want to again stress that us players need to start fervently fighting against this type of treatment.  It is only through our protest that anything will be accomplished.  I will continue to hound Verant, posting on the boards, and trying to get this decayed corpse policy changed somehow.  This just isn't right, and I can't stand for it happening to me or any of you.  What happened to me I wouldn't wish on my worst enemy, yet I am a customer of Verant, and they have treated me this way.  Think about it, doesn't it seem odd that Verant gets to dictate everything about their world, and player suggestions are exactly that: suggestions.  We can make as many suggestions as we want, but until we demand better service we aren't going to get it.  At times I feel like a rat in their maze, but I want to change that.  United we stand, divided we fall, let's demand better service!<br><br>Kjata Holythunder<br>Child of Tunare<br>Rodcet Nife Server

<!-- End Content -->
