<a name="newsitem972001589,38814,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Some of the Psychology Behind EQ and Random Loot </SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Fafner Wabbitslayer  (<a href="mailto:fafner_morell@altavista.com" class="credit2">fafner_morell@altavista.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
EQ's success is not inspired merely on the fantasies of JRR Tolkien and Gary  <br>Gygax, but on the realities of Ivan Pavlov as well. Yep, the Nobel Prize  <br>winning physiologist who gained fame by ringing the bell triggering the  <br>salivating dog is the real wizard behind Verant's curtain.  Actually, there's a  <br>truckload of later psychologists who have contributed to much of the underlying  <br>theories, but everyone remembers the bell (actually a metronome) and the dog  <br>(you really don't want to know how Pavlov knew the dog was salivating), so  <br>Pavlov gets the credit and the Nobel Prize. <br> <br>Positive variable-ratio reinforcement is the psychological principle underlying  <br>animal training, slot machines, and EQ. Since most folks find being equated  <br>with a salivating dog somewhat demeaning, let's examine the slot machine  <br>example instead. The subject (that's you or me) performs the desired action, be  <br>it inserting a dollar and pulling a lever or sitting outside the ruins waiting	<br>for a necromancer to spawn every 20 hours and auto-attacking, and is rewarded.	<br>Sometimes. Only sometimes and at unpredictable times. Hence the term  <br>"variable-ratio". <br> <br>The uncertainty of the reward reinforces the commitment to the behavior. One  <br>can't help but think that with just one more try or five more minutes, maybe  <br>I'll hit the jackpot - if I walk away now, I might be missing out a  <br>life-changing opportunity. A slot machine which always paid out 96 cents on  <br>every dollar would languish unused - it would merely be a defective change  <br>machine. But one which pays out a thousand dollars every once in awhile  <br>(averaging out to once every 1042 dollars) will attract millions who spend  <br>billions. <br> <br>I think it's actually the anticipation of the win that helps ingrain the  <br>conditioned response (called a "habit" by those who don't remember the fancier	<br>terms from Psych 101). That's why even the electronic slot machines will spin  <br>for several seconds rather than immediately respond. It's the momentary thrill	<br>of fate undecided - the adrenalin rush from uncertainty. So, EQ is designed so	<br>that much of one's time is spent anticipating rather than actually doing. We  <br>claim we don't like it, but our habits say otherwise. <br> <br>Well, back to slaying bears in hopes of getting a High Quality Pelt... 

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem970859384,18624,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">The Mystere Incident</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Aurum  (<a href="mailto:aurum@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">aurum@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
<b>This editorial is probably this site's last article on the matter.  It's written with the hopes of explaining the comments I made last night with better clarity.  No, I have not reversed or changed my stance from last night, so if your looking for a "revolution" it's time to close your browser's window and look elsewhere.</b><br><br>You know, I hate taking up "wrongfully banned" cases on the Vault.  There are two main reasons why.  The first, you can almost never find out both sides of the story accurately.   The second, even when you do get an accurate account Verant never does anything about it, or at the least comments publicly about the case because of the policy they have in effect that in essense states "This is between you and I."  It's a good policy for the most part I believe.  <br><br>In this case, everything is different.  Verant has publicly commented about the case, and it appears we do have a complete accurate description of what happened.<br><br>Here's the story thus far:<br><br>Mystere, a well-respected member of the Brell Serelis Role-Playing Community was banned for writing a roleplaying story containing violent scenes of the rape and torture of a female.  This story was written and posted about three months ago to our Brell Serilis Board.  The Brell Serilis Board is one of the more unique EQ sub communities in the fact that a lot of authors frequent and post their works there.<br><br>Now as you might gather, Verant had a problem with the story due to the fact it had some pretty violent and gruesome scenes (both physically and sexually) depicted with the kind of rituals and spells Dark Elves and Necromancers used in the story.  Because of this content, Verant decided it did not want this kind of content associated with its flagship product.  The punishment they deemed was necessary for this case was to ban Mystere, the story's author, from EverQuest.<br><br>Now I fear I need to pause here and write something that I know may sound a little blunt, but I feel it needs to be said nonetheless.<br><br>We live in a post-Columbine world.  The paranoia levels of this country toward violence and <I>suspected violence</I> are at an all time high.  The Congress of the United States of America has blasted virtually all forms of entertainment, including the gaming industry, with several threats.  It's been said and implied that many public officials are on a witch-hunt, whether it goes that far I'm not sure.  But because of all these factors, Verant has to careful, very careful in my estimation.<br><br>We all know the reasons why and we all know what kind of things could happen if they're not.<br><br>I cannot speak for Verant, I don't work there, but that's how I see their side of this issue.  It's an important side regardless of your feelings in this situation you have to realize and attempt to understand.  <br> <br>Now, lets clear up a few misconceptions people have with the story itself in FAQ style:<br><br>---------------------------------------------------------------------------<br><br><b>1.1) Wasn't the person who was depicted as being raped in the story a child?</b><br>The story stated that the female was in her 14th season.  People new or unfamiliar to the game might translate that to be 14 years old.  Veterans to the game would recognize that this would not be the case.  The most likely age this EverQuest character would have been between the 20-30 years old.<br><br>That said, I don't think it really doesn't matters whether it was a child or young adult.  Rape is rape no matter how you look at it.  <br><br><b>1.2) Isn't it true that the violence in this story wasn't really that bad?</b><br>Everyone has his or her own values and tolerance for violence and sexual content.  I do not, nor am I qualified, to be your moral compass on this matter.  Everyone's opinion of this differs.  To the best of my ability I will describe the scenes as being very descriptive and very violent and disturbing.  It would be rated R or NC-17 if it were to be made into a movie.<br><br><b>1.3) So what about the violence, there are zillions of EverQuest assassination quests and torture references in EQ!    </b><br>Yes, there are.  None of them are as descriptive, vivid or contain sexual violence as the events that took place in Mystere's story did.  Examples of Verant's work can be found on the <a href=http://everquest.station.sony.com/hht/h_profile_zatozia.shtml>quest pages</a> on Verant's official page.    <br><br>---------------------------------------------------------------------------<br><br>After thinking about it, and trying to sort things out, I see a couple of interesting issues here that I understand and to an extent agree with:<uL>1.)	Verant banned a paying customer for writing and posting a fan fiction on EQVault's (That's IGN's, not Sony/Verant's) message board.  This person didn't technically violate any of the rules in the EULA.  This person didn't do anything in-game or on Sony's web property that would jeopardize his/her account.  What's more, this is the first time to my knowledge that Verant banned someone for creating EverQuest fanworks.  (not counting hacking utilities of course)  For the record, Verant Interactive did not consult or contact this site regarding the story, author or removal of it.<br><br>2.)	Anyone who has played a Necromancer over the last, oh say two years knows that this isn't exactly a class renowned for it's kindness and gentleness.  Even though the rituals and events depicted in Mystere's story aren't directly spoken, written and done in-game to some extent I believe they are implied.  By Verant's very description of the class, Necromancers dabble in death.  Because of this, I see a little hypocrisy here on Verant's part.  They set the stage for people to think of the class in the way depicted in Mystere's story.</UL>Naturally, this has raised a few questions and eyebrows as to what's acceptable according to Verant's rules.  Among those are:<br><br>1. What are acceptable guidelines for fanworks?<br>2. What are the acceptable ways to roleplay?<br>3. Are EverQuest fan fictions a banable offense?<br><br>I believe these are questions Verant should publicly answer; it would clear up a few issues and rid of the community of fears that they you won't be banned if you try to contribute to the community via creating stories and art.  I urge Verant to in the near future to address these concerns.<br><br>As I've maintained since I tackled this issue, I believe this situation could have handled this better.  A simple email or message to the author would have been sufficient to prevent all of this and maybe even future cases.  This case tackles new ground for this community and I believe the instant and immediate banning was the wrong approach in this particular case because of its entanglement in so many delicate issues. <br><br>What's lies a head in this controversy?  I don't know.  Realistically speaking Mystere will probably not be given a second chance.  If I remember correctly, EQ's EULA allows Verant to terminate any person's account without notice or reason.  <br><br>This has been one of the largest issues to come up in the last few months, and maybe the largest in EverQuest's history.  For many people it has become an issue of "Freedom of Speech", fairness and morality.  In this article I've attempted to do my best to explain each side's story and views and list the important facts.  I do hope some good comes out of this.  I hope we have the questions many of us are wondering answered and I hope that Mystere will be given a second chance.  <br><br><b>To conclude this article, I will direct you to a <a href="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?topic=7172670&start=7172670#7172670">special board thread</a> I started on the Brell Serilis board, the place where the whole ordeal started.  You are free to comment and discuss this issue to your heart's content.  The comments section in the news have been closed due to the tremendous interest in this issue.  The server simply can't handle the load.</b>

<!-- End Content -->
