<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">What Do You Want from EverQuest? - Reader Responses</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Shadoe  (<a href="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault Columnist</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
I know when one of my articles has hit the target squarely in the bullseye when two things happen.  First, it must start up controversy on both sides of an argument.  If I get nothing but e-mail coming in agreeing with me, then I feel like I've merely wasted my time stating the obvious.  If I get nothing but e-mail coming in disagreeing with me, I've either failed to make my point or I need to reevaluate what it is I said.<P>The second thing that needs to happen is a wide dissemination.  Word needs to get out to a widespread readership to the point where enough people actually found the material in the article interesting enough to read in the first place.<P>Considering the responses I've received in e-mail and in the comment boards, I'm extremely happy with how this one turned out.  Not only were there very impassioned responses from people who both agreed and disagreed with me, but I hear the shockwaves touched a number of other commentary web sites out there - not the least of which was Lum and his band of Merry Men.  (You guys are just so adorable, I could just pinch your rosy cheeks.)<P>On top of it all, I'm happiest about a number of the responses I got, which refuted my stance on playing EverQuest.  These particular posts and e-mails detailed, in a direct way, why they choose to play the way they do, and why they think I'm mistaken in the way I choose to play.  The fact that I couldn't disagree with them more still stands nonetheless, but it's obvious to me that these people know where they are and why they're there.  They're contemplative people who've taken the time to render a rebuttal deeper than "you don't know what you're talking about," and I wish to take the time to thank them now for their time in replying to this latest article, and wish to respond in kind with a few of my own thoughts about what they had to say.<P>We'll start with a posting from the comments board, written by Thane Morgan.<P>----------<P><FONT COLOR="#0000AA">Shadoe has done a fine job of towing the company line on why they don't need to listen to<BR>their customers. It was real hard for him to come out and lift whole sections from Gordons<BR>posts. How Courageous. <BR><P></FONT>You couldn't pay me enough to do Gordon's job.  I don't know how much that man makes, but if you double it and place the earnings in a tax shelter, it still wouldn't be enough.  Catering to a group of people who profess that the game is unplayable, yet who insist on paying ten bucks a month to play it anyway is a task fit for the lowest pits of hell.  At least here, if someone gets too impudent to bother with, I can let them know exactly what I think of them and tell them to take a ten-mile hike.<P>As far as towing the company line, you're mistaken.  One of Verant's faults (or strengths, depending on your stock options) is their refined ability to go through the motions of listening to their customers, while at the same time ignoring them.  This holds especially true for guides.  It's the truth, and I'm not going to sit here and pretend it's not just because I happen to empathize with Verant on this particular issue.<P>Whether you agree with this statement or not is really immaterial, though, since Verant is going to do with their game as they please, and there's nothing anyone can do to change it.  To be blunt, it shouldn't be any other way.  To Verant, the cries of the playerbase are merely a melting pot of ideas to draw from.  If they find something they think is a good idea, they'll do it.  It doesn't get any more complicated than that, and shouting louder certainly doesn't help.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>The problem, of course, is that it is utter BS, spouted to belittle those who ask the game<BR>live up to its promise, or at least its advertising. <P></FONT>What promise is that?  Since when did Verant advertize that "We will provide an online game with which Thane Morgan approves"?  Last I heard, Verant's only obligation is to provide a massively-multiplayer online game for their subscribers to play.  It doesn't even have to be a <I>good</I> game, at that.  Of course, if such were the case, they'd never have stayed in business this long.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>When I was young, there was an annoying little kid in the neighborhood that loved to<BR>compete over everything. And almost always lost. But he never admitted it. "You didn't beat<BR>me", he would whine, even though you had made 10 baskets to his 2, or had beat him 500<BR>points to 200 in rummy, or had pinned him to the ground for the past half hour. <BR><P></FONT>I know the type.  I think every neighborhood is required to have one.  <FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>That kid probably now works for verant. Yes, you do beat everquest. You beat it when you<BR>have done everything worth doing in the game, which really doesn't require much more than<BR>endurance. There are just not that many things to do, and new content is rare, and often<BR>buggy and non-worthwhile when it does come out. How many times do you have to kill<BR>Innoruk, or clear guk before you can say you have beat it? How many comparable things are<BR>there in the game to "challenge" you? <P></FONT>Perhaps <I>you</I> beat the game after you have done everything worth doing.  Another person may think reaching level 60 is somehow beating the game.  Yet another person might consider killing all the gods at least once to be beating the game.  To someone else, beating the game means getting a million platinum together.  My point is, there's no clean-cut, undeniable, designated end to the game.  It goes on with or without your participation or whatever small contribution you make to the world.<P>I would also argue that there are far more things worth doing in Norrath than you will ever be aware, and the reason I say this is because of your next statement...<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>The truth is, there is nothing to do in verant BUT kill things, and no reason to do it but to<BR>gain exp and loot. Nothing you do as a platyer will ever affect anything in the game - the<BR>game does not grow to challenge you as you become more skilled, there are no puzzles to<BR>figure out, no intrigues to solve, no damsels to rescue. Yes, you can go out with some<BR>buddies on another sky raid, but is there anything more satisfying about that form of hanging<BR>out with buds compared with Quake, or a chat room, or a board game at home, or shooting<BR>hoops in the driveway? <P></FONT>If that's all I saw in EverQuest, I'd have stopped playing months ago.  It's too bad you and others like you refuse to break the mold of original thought, because ultimately it's you who comes up short.  It's doubly sad to think you're paying actual money for such a thing.  Such behavior is beyond me to explain.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>The idea that the fun is the journey is silly - the journey is incredibly short and repetitive. If<BR>there was an actual challenge to the journey besides endurance you could possibly say that<BR>the journey is fun, but there is no real challenge. The game was built to facilitate and reward<BR>the camp style of play, and punishes those who want to explore new things. There ARE no<BR>new things, and Verant's zone designers too often focus on one little area as being<BR>rewarding for the effort, leaving the rest as level 40 creatures with 4000 HP, bad AI and<BR>pathing, and cloth caps for loot. <P></FONT>Let's go over your criteria for silliness...<P>"The journey is incredibly short and repetitive."  Well, of course it is.  With the approach you have, what do you expect? <P>"The game was built to facilitate and reward the camp style of play..."  I won't argue that point, because it's valid in many ways.  All I can say is that the human mind is capable of far more than going through the motions of game mechanics, if you allow it.  Otherwise, you're no better than the NPC AI that you complain about later.<P>"There ARE no new things."  So you've seen it all, have you?  You've experienced everything Norrath has to offer?  Nothing takes place in EverQuest that you haven't already seen?  You've played every class, and completed every quest?  You've hunted every spawn in every zone?  You've attended every player-run event that could possibly be thought up?  You've been a member of every guild?  You've met and played in the company of every player?  You've attended every wedding and every party that could possibly be thrown?<P>That's quite remarkable. <FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>And this is the real cause of people trying to get verant to improve the game. The fact is,<BR>content addition needs to be priority number one for these games, and the content being<BR>added needs to address problems within the game as well as catering to the players who<BR>have surely become more powerful since the last addition. <P></FONT>They want Verant to add better loot to Veeshan's Peak because there's no new content?  They want Verant to make travel faster and easier because the journey is incredibly short and repetitive?  They want warriors to be able to bind themselves because camping is presumably the catered play style?  Huh??  You lost me.<P>Have the kahooneys to call a spade a spade, why don't you?  Players want these things because it serves their enlightened self-interest in the game.  Dive any deeper than that and you'll drown in a conundrum of weak excuses, justifications and rationalizations.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>The problem is complicated by the poor choice of monster gameplay options Verant took.<BR>Instead of developing AI to let a group of monsters present a challenge to the players,<BR>verant decided to give massive advantages to the monsters over the players. This means<BR>that players can't help but notice that as they gain levels and power, they actually become<BR>weaker compared to things that they actually earn experience for. This should be a very<BR>important consideration for those making the next generation of MMORPGS. Creature need to<BR>present new challenges to the players, istead of just "Well, we'll give him 10K hp and let him<BR>hit for 3X the damage any player ever could." <P></FONT>That's a good point, but it's a perpetual argument.  Even the best AI ever conceived could always withstand some improvement.  It always has, and conceivably it always will.  A few decades down the road, we'll have people complain that the AI of their favorite game is only at a tenth-grade level, and can't diagnose quantum equations.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>One company has done superb job at this - Turbine. Not only do they add significant new<BR>ground to the game every month, but they actually do recognize that the player base will<BR>have much more experience with the game play than the designers, so they treat them like<BR>they know what they are talking about, and make improvement when they are shown to be<BR>needed. Of course, Turbine does have a huge advantage over verant in that regard - their<BR>engine is not a bug filled mess. <P></FONT>One of Asheron's Call's strengths lies in their ability to add new content on the fly (ie. Not having to download a whole new zone for one little edit.)  Sadly, EverQuest wasn't made with that design feature in mind -- Verant has openly admitted it.  Now we'll see if they learn from that lesson with their future releases.<P>As far as Turbine treating their customers like they know what they're talking about, that I haven't been around to see, and honestly it's out of the scope of the article.  If that's what you value most, and if it will provide you with the mechanism you need to enjoy the game, then by all means go play AC and let Turbine know you appreciate it.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>It is simply wrong to blame the players for EQ's poor gameplay, or criticize them for wanting<BR>more. <P></FONT>You missed my point.  I blame the players for their own professed lack of having fun in EverQuest.  I contend that these players are their own worst enemy in that regard.  I further contend that the pervading attitude at large is self-defeating, even in the face of any hypothetically flawless game.  My own philosophy is that if you want to enjoy EverQuest for what it is, then you should stop and smell the roses once in a while.  Take time to rest on your laurels a bit.  Kill a green creature on the odd occasion, just because you don't like the look on its face.  Help a friend.  Be a part of something bigger than yourself. Live a little. You've earned it.  And if you do, it won't take long before you discover that you can do these things while questing as well.<P>As far as wanting more, it comes with the territory whenever you deal with the public.  That doesn't necessarily mean they should get their hearts' desires.  If they're happier going to a company that makes such compromises as a matter of policy, I say more power to them.  Verant chooses not to, and that's their prerogative.  Until you learn to cope with it, you'll never be happy.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>It is not billed as a big party icebreaker, where it is up to the players to make"Pictionary" fun. This is a GAME, which means it should be challenging and rewarding on itsown merits.</FONT><P>----------<P>How quaintly Hollywood of you to say.  It's come down to players sitting on their asses and saying "here we are now, entertain us."  (Don't you just love Nirvana?)  I'm here to tell you it doesn't work that way.  If you want to find all that EverQuest has to offer, you're going to get off your butt and quit waiting for Verant to deliver your slice of fun on a silver plate with cherries on top.  It's your choice, and if you choose to ignore what I'm saying and find you're still unhappy being brutally forced to play EverQuest at gunpoint, it's no skin off my nose.  You're the one with your finger on the trigger, even if you don't recognize it.<P>Let me attack this from another angle, and maybe it will become clearer...<P>Some people (most of us, in fact) see EverQuest as a chain of things to conquer.  It's about attaining that next milestone, be it a certain level or getting that full suit of Crafted Plate.  Achieving these goals is fun, we can all agree.  <P>Where we disagree is how we choose to handle the road that leads to achieving these goals.  <P>Some see this road as work and little more.  It's the reward itself that's considered fun, and not the effort required in order to achieve it.  It's the reward for the endless days of camping that makes playing EverQuest worthwhile.  If for some reason it's not worthwhile in their estimation, well Verant had better soften the road or boost the reward.  Otherwise it's no fun -- hence the cries for change on the message boards.  With this approach, having fun is a byproduct of achievement. <P>Others see this road as an opportunity to have fun while working to attain these goals.  They feel that game mechanics don't enter into it whatsoever, as it's their own attitude and indulgences that provide their enjoyment.  It doesn't matter how long it takes to reach the next milestone -- it's irrelevant, or only marginally important at best.  They're there to have fun while going through the motions.  They figure that if you're having fun while walking the road, then the end of the road will attend to itself.  And if the road is all that much longer, the anticipation is heightened and the sweeter the victory is when their goals are finally met.  Achievement then becomes a byproduct of having fun, and not vice-versa.<P>Now you tell me, which is the more silly approach:  Stressing day after day in order to achieve and have fun?  Or having fun day after day in order to achieve and have even more fun?  <P>Seems like a no-brainer to me.  I'll favor the latter, thank you very much.  If the former is your cup of tea, then I won't argue, but I personally can't see myself enjoying that approach to EverQuest.  The game would have been history on my computer a long time ago.  I've chosen to have fun, and I have few things to complain about.  Can you say the same?<P>What Thane touched on in a general way, "Zem the Mattress" below probes for more of the specifics in his e-mail, as he picks apart the article in much the same way I pick apart reader responses...<P>----------<P><FONT COLOR="#0000AA">--------------------------------------------------<BR>>>"If so, you'll be disappointed. From Day One, EverQuest has never been<BR>intended as a game with an end."<BR>--------------------------------------------------<BR><P>Verant claims the game was not made to end, but if this is so then why is it<BR>CLEARLY designed with a linear progression of levels?<P></FONT>A better question would be: "Why have such a progression method in place, and then cut it off at level 60?"  I personally would like to see players progress indefinitely to the point where everyone levels off at a point where they're most comfortable.  Of course, the way EverQuest is put together with skills and spells being awarded at various intervals would make such a prospect absurd, so it would take some fundamental changes in how things work.  We'll see what the future holds.<P>Oh, and by the way: progression in EverQuest is hardly linear.  Level three is much more difficult to attain than level two.  Similarly, level four is more difficult to attain than levels two and three put together, and so on up.  Unless you're from some sort of parabolic dimension, progress in EverQuest is very much based on a curve.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>This goes much deeper than level two coming after level one; EVERYTHING in<BR>the game is designed and oriented around linear progression. Everything in<BR>the freeport newbie area is for a certain level bracket. Everything in<BR>blackburrow is likewise. After hunting ground A you can proceed to hunting<BR>ground B in order to gain levels quickly.<P>So you ask yourself "Why not do something other than level?".   The answer, my friend, is obvious: BECAUSE THERE IS NOTHING ELSE. Nothing else enjoyableanyway, unless you start treating the game like a chat room. "I did not payten dollars a month for a graphical chat room, hence, I will level."<P></FONT>Finish your sentence.  "BECAUSE THERE IS NOTHING ELSE <U>VERANT PROVIDES ME</U>."  Again, it's the Hollywood mentality that if you go to a movie, you expect to be entertained.  We all do it.  It's expected in the performing arts.  I dare say it's expected in single-player games. Now that people are trying to fit that expectation into massively multiplayer games, they're finding themselves frustrated for the first time.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>Where's the end? Level 60. What do people do then? Make a twink and startthe whole cycle over.<P></FONT>That's an awfully broad claim to be making about nearly 300k people.  I personally know of three guilds rife with people who directly contradict that statement by the way they play.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>--------------------------------------------------<BR>>>"What do you want? What in the game do you find entertaining? Is it<BR>finally getting that magic weapon you always wanted, or is it the journey<BR>you went through to get you there? Which should it be?"<BR>--------------------------------------------------<P>Most often it is getting the magic weapon. It *should* be the journey,<BR>however. Why isn't it?<P>Simple. Because the journey sucks.  It's pocked with time wasted inmind-numbing time sinks. It's usually covered with unpleasant experienceswith rude or ignorant players (since you *are* forced into thier company)and is most often paved with pure frustration - dying, walking ALL the wayback to your corpse, losing precious experience, etc. etc.<P></FONT>Isn't that rather cyclic reasoning?  The journey's bad because it sucks?  Haven't you even once asked yourself if there was something you could do to make it "unsuck?"  (Beyond bitching at Verant, that is.)<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>--------------------------------------------------<BR>>>"What do you want? To labor and slave away...Or would you rather have fun<BR>while working to achieve it?"<BR>--------------------------------------------------<P>I would really like to see how you propose we go about doing the latter.<BR>Rather, tell me what *you* do to achieve the latter. The general frustration<BR>with EverQuest goes much deeper than just a mindset coincidentally shared by<BR>a large fraction of the player base.<P></FONT>You make that statement glibly without even hearing my response to your question.<P>For starters, I surround myself with people who enjoy taking the time to play out the trivial things with their characters.  Quantifiably useless things, like dark elves complaining about the bright sun and the oppressive heat in the desert, or a journeyman who dumps that annoying rock from his boot during downtime.  None of these things have any bearing on the actual quest, and they certainly don't bring us any closer to our goals, but they lend a certain degree of richness and diversity to the journey that I personally find appealing.<P>Another thing I do is not stress over my milestones.  "The crested spaulders can wait; Gahlstad's forming a party to invade Runnyeye, and wailing on goblins with my friends sounds more fun to me right now.  After Runnyeye, I'll be that much more powerful for the next time I head out that direction."<P>I try to keep a positive attitude.  Not every setback is necessarily a liability.  I've lost count of how many times a death of mine has lead to an incredible advancement because of sheer circumstance.  They're easy to spot if you keep your eye open for them.<P>I'm also not afraid to sit back, relax, and just have fun -- even if it means not advancing for the time being.  Parties are a blast if you have the right people there to share the revelry with.  It's amazing the things you can discover about people when your character's three sheets to the wind, and dancing the lambada with an ogre.<P>Those are a few of the things I do.  You may laugh and say it's all a waste of time, but I figure if it's what I think is fun, then it's time well invested and I'm getting my money's worth.  I'm not advocating that this is how <I>everyone</I> should play -- only answering your question of what <I>I</I> do to have fun during the journey.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>--------------------------------------------------<BR>>>"Don't count on Verant to provide your entertainment, because they're not<BR>going to give it to you...You are the one in control of your entertainment,<BR>and you have nobody left to blame if you fall short of that goal."<BR>--------------------------------------------------<P>A common theme among the mindlessly supportive: That Verant is simply making<BR>a product that you are supposed to entertain yourself with.<P></FONT>The "mindlessly supportive," as you so adroitly put it, only appear that way to you because they have no complaints.  They're satisfied with the game, and find the issues under which the roaring crowds are pummeling on Verant's door to be trivial in the extreme.  They resent that such things cloud what they consider to be genuine issues that would serve to enhance the game.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>This is very, very much not the case. A competent developer makes it EASY to<BR>have fun with his "product". This is the definition of a well-designed game.<BR><P></FONT>You're welcome to your opinion.  From where I'm sitting, you decide if you like or dislike <U>any</U> game you buy, regardless of how "easy" the developer makes it for you to enjoy.<FONT COLOR="#0000AA"><P>The object of the designer isn't to shut the "complainers" up, it's to make<BR>it so that they don't have anything to complain about. This, of course, an<BR>impossible dream - even the best game will always have flaws. In the BETTER<BR>games, however, there is so much that you really can't complain about that<BR>you really have no motive to complain about the things that you can.</FONT><P>----------<P>Ask anyone who deals with the public -- people will always complain, regardless of what you do.  Make party A happy, and party B is offended.  Fix a balance issue with rangers, then suddenly the bards think they've been given the shaft.  No game is so overwhelmingly good that people will stop complaining about the bad points.  I wish I were wrong.<P>Two good letters.  Thanks to you both for writing in with your respective points-of-view.  <P>Those of you who're familiar with my reader responses know that I never like to leave things on a negative note, if I can help it.  It just so happens that there were several very upbeat postings in the comments board and in my e-mail box, which supported my argument and even took it a step further.<P>Here's one of them...<P>----------<P><FONT COLOR="#0000AA">Simply put Shadoe and I heartily agree. Myself, I keep mum while some idiot will stand on his<BR>soapbox and tell us why HE thinks this game sucks and you know. I laugh. It is essential that<BR>you ask yourself why you go there. I realized that a long time ago it was not about looking<BR>cool or bragging rights, it was pure adventure. Think back kids. <P>Remember the first time seeing the dreaded gnoll train flying at you and getting that lump in<BR>your throat? Remember gaining your first piece of real armor after a hard quest? Remember<BR>exploring your first dungeon, scared white that you were gonna turn the next corner and find<BR>death? Remember running for the zone as the named beasties slowly cutting you down and<BR>praying you make it? Remember giving a helping hand to a dying newbie by taking the brunt<BR>of a MOB? Remember such things as triumph over adversity, vowing vengence, rescuing,<BR>gaining your first spells, being alone in a bad place, seeing your first dragon? <BR><P>I remember such things as sitting at the dock at Oasis, watching the sun set. Seeing the<BR>Sarnek Fortress for the first time. Finding the first frozen body done in by Vox. All good<BR>memories. <P>If the only thing you can remember is KS that named to gain Uberweapon of so and so with<BR>stats up the ying yang or laughing at the stupidity of VP loot or farming everything worth for<BR>Ebay sells or bitching at the nerf or a thousand other things... <P>Here's a thought, try using this in the real world. For the real world loves ppl like you.<BR>Because you know, its sad that you have lost what Verant has bestowed to us. You have<BR>lost the reason they invented this world. <P>Adventure <P></FONT><P>----------<P>Thanks for your thoughts, Kinelti!  As with all things, there are people who "get it," and people who don't.  The way you detail the experiences you enjoy in EverQuest, it makes me wish I played on your server.  (For all I know, I just might.)<P>And lastly, here's a gent named "Tween" who puts another spin on the issue.  This is in response to the posting Thane made on the comment board...<P>----------<P><FONT COLOR="#0000AA">Thane, <P>I have to agree with you that you can in fact 'beat' Everquest... but not in the way you<BR>mentioned. You beat Everquest when you *think* you've beaten Everquest. Let me give you<BR>an example: Your character is a wood elf, and his mission in life is to defeat Emperor <BR>Crush.<P>So you get to level 15, and group in the tower in Crushbone.. and after a tough battle,<BR>Crush dies. Guess what? You've beaten the game. <P>A great deal of your post is subjective, just like mine is - you seem to argue that Everquest<BR>isn't challenging to you. That may be, but it's only your opinion. There are obviously people<BR>out there who enjoy the challenges that the game has to offer, the same challenges that<BR>you chalk up as 'bad AI' and 'bad pathing'. I would disagree with you; sure the AI could be<BR>improved, and so could the pathing, but I prefer to look beyond that and see the game for<BR>what I believe it is: a chance for me to make the challenges and overcome them. <P>As far as 'lack of content' goes, I'd have to disagree with you. Norrath is HUGE. Again, in<BR>your opinion there's nothing new. How long have you been playing? How many places have<BR>you been? You have to remember that there are people who haven't even /seen/ half of<BR>Norrath, let alone the Planes. These people seem to enjoy the game just fine, and continue<BR>to play regardless of the complaints and threats of account cancellation from people who've<BR>been around for x amount of months. <P>But to argue that the game isn't fun, and to only point out the issues that you have with<BR>the gameplay and mechanics, is again subjective. Everquest /is/ what you make of it. The<BR>game is there, the story is there. It's up to you to take it where you want to take it. If you<BR>choose to be restricted by the camping and mindless killing, don't be surprised to find<BR>yourself bored. <P>Thane, the journey *is* part of the fun. Half of the fun is getting there. Try it sometime -<BR>insted of downloading the dungeon map from your local spoiler site and marking down the<BR>locs and drops of the rare spawns, just head into the dungeon with a group of friends and<BR>look around. Those who say the game rewards those who camp really are missing what the<BR>game has to offer. There is more to Everquest than loot and exp, but you have to want<BR>more out of it. <P>This game *is* fun. The challenges are there. Getting together with a group of friends and<BR>overcoming that thing that presents a challenge to you, after much hard work and<BR>preparation... That is part of the reward. If you don't agree, then perhaps this isn't the<BR>game for you. </FONT><P>----------<P>Tween is, of course, a regular reader of my articles who often sees the issue with a fresh perspective.  Thanks for your comments, once again, Tween!<P>And so concludes this installment of Shadoe's Corner.  Tune in next time when I touch on salt corrosion of fine steel weapons in Lake Rathetear.<P>- &lt;Shadoe&gt;

