<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">What Do You Want from Norrath?</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Shadoe  (<a href="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault Columnist</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
I have to wonder at some of the things I see posted on the message boards sometimes.  Those of you who frequent the boards know what I'm talking about.  "The loot in Veeshan's Peak sucks!"  "The loot in the planes suck!"  "Item stats are too low for my Black Featherduster of Doom!"  "Give monks better class weapons!"  "Why is the necromancer able to give himself mana, and not wizards who need it most?"  "The game is unplayable for me after 35 because you don't care about my class!"  "I'm tired of taking so long to get anywhere in Norrath!  Make NPCs able to teleport!"<P>I find myself questioning how people became so egocentric about their characters.  Is it so hard to take a step back from your own selfish desires and take a look at the big picture of what Verant is trying to deliver with EverQuest?  Is it so hard to see that if Verant bowed and scraped to each and every player demand presented on the message boards, that the game itself would quickly become the very icon of boredom and drudgery?<P><I>"I am the ultimate character on Norrath!  I am the super-being with the best equipment and abilities the game has to offer!  Tremble before my wrath, all who oppose me!  I am all-powerful!!!!!! . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . uh, now what?"</I><P>Soon after, players would be leaving the game in droves, searching for another game that actually presented some tangible degree of challenge, and EverQuest would be a forsaken memory.  Not only would Verant lose future revenue they otherwise would have made, but the players would remember EverQuest as that game that was way too easy, so they left.<P>It smacks to me as being the peak of irony that the demands the players cry for in the message boards are collectively the very things that -- should their wishes ever be granted -- would spell the very doom of their enjoyment of the game.  Chalk up yet another paradox of the human genome.<P>So I ask you: What do you want?  Is EverQuest all about acquiring loot and gaining levels?  If the answer you give is "yes," then ask yourself why this is so.  Is it game mechanics?  Is it because the only way to advance is to hack and slash until you're blue in the mouse?  Is it because so few trivial things exist in the game to make it truly immersive?  Are you forced into playing this way because of the way the game is designed?  Or is it because you've conditioned yourself to think this way every time you double-click the icon on your desktop?  Think carefully.<P>What do you want?  To beat the game, like any other computer RPG?  If so, you'll be disappointed.  From Day One, EverQuest has never been intended as a game with an end.  There is no such thing as ultimate power, or the ultimate class, or the ultimate item.  In EverQuest, there are no means to an end -- the means are an end unto themselves.<P>What do you want?  What in the game do you find entertaining?  Is it finally getting that magic weapon you always wanted, or is it the journey you went through to get you there?  Which <I>should</I> it be?<P>What do you want?  To sit alone and wait for a creature to spawn whom you've killed countless times that day already, praying that <I>this</I> time he'll have the Holy Grail on him?  Or would you rather delve into a dungeon with a group of trusted companions, determined to avenge the wrongs those creatures have done your people?<P>What do you want?  To labor and slave away for hours at the keyboard, hoping to one day have fun once you achieve your agenda?  Or would you rather have fun while working to achieve it?<P>I've had to ask myself these very same questions of late, and I'll clue you in on a little something I've discovered that will help: <B>Don't count on Verant to give you what you want.</B>  Your enjoyment of the game is dependent on one, and only one person, and if you're smart enough to be reading this article, you're smart enough to know who that person is.<P>Don't count on Verant to provide your entertainment, because they're not going to give it to you.  The most you can expect from them is a vehicle for you to use in providing your own enjoyment.  The time and effort you spend in the game is yours and yours alone to spend.  It's up to you to decide if what you get from your adventures is worth what you put into it.  Nobody else is going to make that determination for you, and nobody else is going to make your decision work.  Not Verant.  Not the GMs.  Not the guides.  Not other players.  Not your guild.  Not your auntie who enjoys hiding rare and exotic coins in your birthday cake.<P>You are the one in control of your entertainment, and you have nobody left to blame if you fall short of that goal.<P>- &lt;Shadoe&gt;

