<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Grouping</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Lonnie E. Plott Jr.   (<a href="mailto:lonnieplottjr@hotmail.com" class="credit2">lonnieplottjr@hotmail.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
A lot of people get mad when they can't solo anymore. And you can always tell when they realize it won't work anymore. Depending on class and such, they say things like: "Not enough hit points anymore! Warriors got nerfed!" or "Root doesn't work it's too easy to resist!". Same goes for mana.<br><br>What people don't seem to realize is this game is specifically made for group adventure. Now I'm not saying it's impossible to solo: I managed to when I felt like it up to level 23. (By that time I just didn't want to, I have no idea whether you can or not past that.) It is just much more<br>difficult.<br><br>With a team behind/in front of you, particularly a well made one (lots of pets to avoid personal damage or healers and tanks), down time is a lot slower, without as much of a risk as getting ganged up on.<br><br>On the other hand, solo, you use your own health, own mana (if you're a<br>mage) which typically gets exhausted fighting one or two blues/greens, and<br>having another monster sneak up on you is an easy way to die. You have no<br>one watching your back!<br><br>With a quick eye, a good set of tactics, and knowledge of the zone line,<br>soloing can be very fruitful. BUT...You still may as well plan to die twice<br>as often.<br><br>The moral of this story: group up when possible, solo when absolutely<br>necessary.

