<P>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My name is Eshkin, son of Drell.  I am not an educated man, although my travels of late have brought me both knowledge and clarity.  For my skills with the pen I thank my Erudite friends, Lanzera and Chiada&#8212;who have taught me the value of words well spoken.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Let me begin at the beginning.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I was born in the hills above Surefall Glade, in the summer of 3140.  My father was Drell, the  blacksmith of Surefall.  My mother, a druid, I am told, died bringing me into this world.  My father to this day puts flowers on her grave in the Glade.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My father was a hard man, but a fair one.  His rules were few, but strict.   As a boy I worked more than played.  Most of my young days were spent at the forge.   I suppose it was his way of rearing me without a woman at his side.  My earliest memory is of him hammering at the forge and seeing the angry light of the sparks leaping from the steel as he bent it to his will.  He never spoke of my mother.  I believe it must hurt him very much that she is gone.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It is a pain I know too well.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Druids of the Glade would, for a modest fee, teach the children of the village lessons in reading and arithmetic.  It was a fee that we never had trouble coming up with&#8212;my father was a very successful smith.  However working at the forge, I rarely had the time to attend the lessons.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was a rare day in my 13th year that I first laid my hands on a bow.  My father, for the first time, left me with charge of the smithy and the house, to go and visit his sister in West Karana.   He would be gone for sixteen days.  And while I was of ample age to watch the house and minister myself to my reading and writing lessons, I was not able to run the forge.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In short, my father&#8217;s holiday to West Karana was a holiday for both of us.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I was ecstatic.  I would leave the house for a fortnight and not look back!  I could go down to the glade and listen to the Druids teach.  I could fish in the lake with my meager cadre of friends.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The walk down to Surefall Glade is not a short one, but it was good to be out of the smithy.  I tucked my wax tablet and stylus under my arm (my father never believed in wasting good coin on parchment) and headed for the Glade.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I arrived to a scene most unexpected.  The Druids of the glade were not at their guild tree, but they and many of the Jaggedpine rangers were gathered by the lake, listening enrapt to a stranger speaking on by the bridge.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He was a tall man, lanky of build and bare of face.  The lines of his eyes were deep and defined and his gaze set for a great distance.  He was an adventurer&#8212;the first I had seen.  He was a far-traveler, and he wore the dust of the road gladly, almost as a second skin.  As he spoke, his eyes were bright, and his smile quick.  He was speaking of gnolls.  His stories were of danger and intrigue.  Grappling in the dark with gnoll raiders for the lives of the prisoners they had taken from the villages in Karana.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;His name was Tamryn Scholl and he had come to hunt the gnolls of Blackburrow, at the behest of Antonius Bayle himself.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;These were all fine tales, to a boy of thirteen, and tales I would glady tell again.  But it was not his tales that took me.  Leaning against the rail of the bridge, behind him, was his bow.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was a thing of mesmerizing beauty.  Its graceful curves and even taper were perfectly symetrical.  It&#8217;s tips were capped in silver, and the material was something I had never seen before.  It was black, with a depth of finish that, it seemed to me, pulled in the light and consumed it.  It&#8217;s grip was polished mother-of-pearl and the silk of it&#8217;s string shone like gold.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;So enrapt was I with the bow, that I did not notice that Tamryn&#8217;s stories had ended.  In fact, the only sound was a murmur of muffled laughter&#8212;at some joke I had missed.  My reverie broken, I glanced about to see everyone staring at me.   All the boys of the village and the glade&#8212;and the Druids and Rangers as well.  Tamryn&#8217;s face was lit with bemusement, and I know I flushed red to the gills.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Boy?  Are you still here?  Or did someone steal your soul?&#8221; He said.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Sir?&#8221; I replied, suddenly more embarrassed.  I was never social&#8230;in fact I was quite shy.  &#8220;Uhh.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Has that trinket caught your eye?&#8221; asked Tamryn.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Uhhhh&#8230;yes, sir.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At this point, one of the other boys, whom I knew from my studies (perhaps as the only one less present and more tardy than myself) interrupted.  &#8220;Hehe!  Eshkin never looks a girls like that!  Boys sometimes, but never girls!&#8221;  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This boy&#8217;s name was Kartum Trueshot and he was the son of a renowned hunter in far-off Kelethin.  He was here at the behest of his father to study with the Jaggepine Rangers.  He was a half-elf whose mother was the sister of Hager Sureshot&#8212;who moved and married in Kelethin.  He had generations of consummate hunters in his bloodline and he was an excellent archer&#8212;a fact that he allowed no one to forget.  As a ranger, or rather an apprentice ranger, Kartum actually lived in the Glade.  He would frequently bully the other boys&#8212;myself included.  But as I lived in the village, and seldom even attended my lessons in the Glade, I thought little of him.  That would change one day.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Gnoll hunter, spoke up, &#8220;Now, boy, don&#8217;t be that way.  I&#8217;m sure...Eshkin, is it?  I&#8217;m sure he likes girls just fine&#8230;&#8221;  There was a pregnant pause where Tamryn glanced at me and then back down the to bow.  He saw something in my eyes I suppose, that caught his interest.  &#8220;Would you like to hold it, boy?&#8221;  he asked.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For those of you unfamiliar with the customs of the woodsmen, a Ranger&#8217;s bow is a sacred item.  Often times, it is passed down, from generation to generation.  I am told that the oldest and finest of bows retain the spirits of their owners&#8230;a little at time, until they attain a life of their own.  I could tell that this was one such bow.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;So could everyone else.  So could Kartum.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Uhh&#8230;&#8221;  I was not the most eloquent child.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Tamryn laughed and pressed the bow into my hands.  It&#8217;s surface was warm&#8230;unnaturally so.  I fancied I felt it throb in my hands.  I fancied, in a strange way&#8230;that it liked me.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The bow enchanted me.  At the age of thirteen I lay alone on my bed, thinking of all the stories I had heard told, and dismissed as boasting&#8212;stories of great hunts, and magnificent battles with elusive  quarry.  Tales of tracking and exploration, told to me by others over the years, suddenly held new meaning for me.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I was going to be a Ranger.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;When my father returned from West Karana, he nodded quietly at the news of my decision.  Perhaps there was a bit of sadness in his eyes, at my not choosing to master the forge as he had.  He was supportive, however, and sponsored my apprenticeship to Hager Sureshot of Surefall Glade.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If, as I suspect, the bow of Tamryn Scholl guided me to the path of the woodsman, it was not wrong in its estimation of my talent.  My newfound passion for archery, swordsmanship and the wilderness erupted.  I excelled in my training.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As the years passed, I became a masterful archer, and a passable swordsman (although I still prefer the simple utility of an axe over the flash of a sword).  My I had found my place.  It was magnificent.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At age 20, I was presented with my laurels, as an initaite Ranger of the Glade.  In a gruff, rather unceremonious ceremony, I was given my guild tunic&#8230;and sumarily tossed off the bridge, into the lake, by my friends.  The fishes in that lake are not friendly, but I was able to climb out mostly intact and smiling, despite several bite marks.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kartum&#8217;s laurels were presented at the same ceremony, and it was this ceremony that finally opened my eyes to a rivalry that had been brewing since the day, seven years before, when Tamryn Scholl came to Surefall Glade.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The thing that I noticed was the difference in the way the other rangers and initiates treated Kartum.  There was no cheering and he was not tossed to the fishes&#8212;just a few, mild supporters clapping,  and the ceremony was over.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was not because of Kartum&#8217;s lineage as a half-elf.  There were many half-elves in Surefall Glade.  We were all woodsmen, or druids, and we respected each other for that.  It was just because&#8230;of Kartum.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In retrospect, I chide myself for not paying more attention to politics and such around me.  They have never interested me.  However, had I been paying attention, I would have noticed then that Kartum was held with great disdain by his peers. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He was a braggart and a bully, when he was younger.  But as the years passed, that evolved into something worse.  He turned to wine and womanizing, sometimes vanishing for days, whoremongering in Qeynos, when the rest of the initiates were supposed to be patrolling for gnolls and hunting the hills for game to feed the village.  Rumors were that he had spent such an extended time in Surefall Glade because his father in Kelethin did not want him back.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Things took a turn for the worse in the winter of 3169.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The snows had been heavy and game was scarce.  Hailstorms from the previous season had damaged much of the crops and so we had little reserves.  All the initaites were called into service to hunt for the Glade and its outlying villages.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Hager Sureshot was not a man to give orders he himself would not follow, and so was also hunting.  This particular frozen day the wind pierced through our cloaks like a driven nail, and dry, stinging snow whipped our faces raw.  Our group was five strong; myself, Master Sureshot, Kartum, and two of my fellow initiates.  We had hunted far, tracking a herd of elk over several ranges of the Qeynos Hills.  At length, with the cold aching through our gloves and boots, we descended through hip-deep snow into a sheltered valley.  Our focus had been entirely on the quarry, and the cold and exertion had worn us down.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No one suspected exacly how close we were to Blackburrow.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Master sureshot was in the lead, pressing through the snow after the now clear tracks of our game.  The arrows came out of nowhere&#8230;hissing hatefully through the air like angry insects.  We were taken totally by surprise.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The first volley dropped one of my fellows in his tracks, and Master Sureshot took a shaft through the leg.  I felt the air sing as the feathers of one grazed by my face.  Cries went up and our small party lurched into action.  Master Sureshot staggered back to his feet on his wounded leg and hobbled to the shelter of  large group of overhanging rocks.  Kartum and the other initiate were close on his heels, as I labored to drag the inert body of our fallen comrade through the snow to the shelter of the rocks.  It took me only a few seconds watching his blood pour into the snow to realize that he was dead.  Persued by another volley of arrows, I stumbled through the snow to the others.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;By the time I arrived, Master Sureshot was groggy with loss of blood.  The bladed arrowhead had severed an artery in his leg and the ground around the rock was slippery with blood.  For a moment, I stood in shock, in disbelief that a man could bleed so much.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The howling war-cries of the gnolls on the hill above us woke me from my shock.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Kartum, your belt!&#8221; <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kartum was pressed against the rock, his eyes wide with fear.  His bow had dropped useless to the ground. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Kartum!  Pick up your bow and give me your belt!  I need to bind Master Sureshot&#8217;s wounds!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The other initiate, a young half-elf named Cheskin, cursed, snatching Kartum&#8217;s bow up off the ground and pressing it into the shivering woodsman&#8217;s hands.  He then whipped off his belt and helped me to bind Master Sureshot&#8217;s leg.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our Master  had lost much blood.  My hands, tightening the tourniquet were shaking with fear, but Master Sureshot opened his eyes and looked into mine.  It was not the gaze of a dying man I saw there, but the resolve of a hunter.  His eyes were unafraid.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No, I thought to myself, We will not die here.  Not here.  Not today.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cheskin and I quickly wrapped him in our cloaks, shivering form the cold and the fearful howling of the gnolls.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We had all but forgotten about Kartum.  He was huddled in a ball beneath the rock.  The fear had taken his mind.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cheskin looked at me and nocked an arrow to his string,  &#8220;How many are there, do you think?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I shook my head, &#8220;I saw no tracks, but the arrows&#8230;three, perhaps four.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cheskin put his back to the rock and tried to crane his neck around to have a look up the hill.  An arrow sparked off the stone next to his face and he jumped back.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He blew out a breath, &#8220;Have you ever fought a gnoll before?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;No&#8230;I have not.&#8221;  I laughed, the situation was suddenly funny to me.  &#8220;In fact, I have never drawn blade, nor bow in anger against&#8230;.anything.  Have you?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cheskin loosened his sword in the scabbard, &#8220;I once got punched in the face by the bouncer at Fish&#8217;s.  He is large and hairy, but that is as close as I have come.  What should we do?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I thought for a moment, surveying the slope of the hill.  &#8220;We can&#8217;t wait.  Even if we could out-shoot them, they would go and get their friends if the fight went agianst them.  Runing is out.  Master Sureshot will die if we leave him.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Then we fight.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Aye&#8230;&#8221;  I was thinking fast.  They could take us simply by coming down both sides of the rock at the same time.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The howling continued, growing closer, and all about me I fancied I heard the snapping of twigs.  We had to act fast.  &#8220;Give me your quiver.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Aye.&#8221;  Cheskin handed the quiver over.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I turned to Kartum, huddled against the rock, &#8220;Kartum, snap out of it, we need you!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In response, he rocked slighly back and forth fetally on his hanuches and shivered, looking up at me.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dropping to one knee I grabbed him by the tunic and shook him,&#8220;Dammit, Kartum we need you! You are the best shot among us now!  We need your skill!  If we are to live, we need your skill <b>now</b>!  Cheskin is going to run, and draw their fire&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Err&#8230;I am?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;&#8230;while you shoot them.  I will protect your back when they come for you.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was true.  I was the strongest in close combat, being much bigger than either of them.  Kartum was the best shot, and Cheskin was the fleetest of foot.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Somehow, Kartum composed himself, wiped the tears from his eyes and gripped his bow.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I handed Cheskin&#8217;s quiver to Kartum.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cheskin unsheathed his blade and glared at Kartum.  &#8220;Shoot straight, please.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I leaned my bow and qiver against the rock and bared my sword. &#8220;Go Ches!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&#8230;And he was off.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Arrows began to whistle through the air and the howling echoing through the ice-locked woods increased its frenzy.  Cheskin zigzagged back and forth between the trees, as shafts buried themselves in the trees and raised dusty puffs of snow where they hit the ground.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kartum rose to the challenge and stepped out form around the rock.  In a single, fluid movement he drew back, fired, and snatched another shaft from his quiver.  I heard the piercing squeal of the gnoll as the arrow struck it.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Expecting what came next, I weighed my sword in my hand and turned my back to Kartum.  Ches had drawn at least some of them out of their cover and I would have to rely on Kartum&#8217;s prowess with the bow to deal with them.  But the others&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Suddenly, it was before me, skidding around the rock on the slick snow.  My impresion to this day, though I have since seen much more fearsome monsters, was that it was the biggest thing I had ever seen.  It was fully a foot taller than me and hugely muscled.  In it&#8217;s hand was a rusty mace, still caked with the black blood and hair of previous victims.  The stench of its fur filed my nostrils as the mace whistled down at my head.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My sword swept up and around in an arc and the shock of the blow ran down my arm as steel screamed against steel.  It was enough&#8212;instead of caving in my skull, the monster&#8217;s mace grazed harmlessly down my shoulder.  I slashed with all my strengh across its snarling mouth.  The sound of my blade crashing through its teeth and the feel of it slashing through the soft flesh of its mouth twisted in my gut.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For a second, the gnoll was blind with pain.  It stumbled back, its strange legs peddling against the slippery ground.  Pain exploded in my side as the wild swing of his mace pounded into my ribs.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Against the pain, I drove forward, spearing with the point of my sword.  In an instant&#8217;s decision, the gnoll&#8217;s mace thudded to the ground and its paws flailed before it, trying to stop the point of my blade, but too late.  I felt the steel pass effortlesly through fur and flesh of it&#8217;s neck before grinding to a halt against the bone.  As I had been taught, I turned my body, twisting and raising my arm as I yanked the blade back.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Hot blood erupted from its open throat and its grasped feebly to try and contain the geysering flow.   As it sank to the ground and leaned against me, I looked into its yellow eyes.  Strangely peaceful, it gazed back.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Its paw slid down my arm to my limp hand and gripped it strongly, as might a friend.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This was my first taste of war.  Inexplicably, I was overcome with a wash of pure sorrow, and for just a moment, I held its hand as it died.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kartum&#8217;s bowstring sang again through the strange and sudden quiet in my mind, and vaugely, I heard his voice calling to me.  I gently lowered the body of my enemy to the snow, feeling the warmth of his blood seeping through my tunic.  It is difficult for me to remember, but I believe I was crying.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Eshkin!&#8221; Kartum called over his shoulder,  &#8220;I have killed two of them!  I see no others!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I was only vaguely aware of  his words.  As I looked up, a tall and imposing gnoll stood before me, its yellow eyes gazing evenly down.  He was not black of fur and clad in rags, like the one I knelt beside.  Instead his fur was a light gray, touched with brown.  In its hand, it held a staff of red wood inlaid with runes of silver, and it was clothed in clean, ornate robes of red and black.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My hand gripped the haft of my sword and I slowly rose from my knees.  This could only be some kind of gnoll holy man.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For a long moment, the shaman stared at me, and at the body of its fallen comrade (or more likely, servant).<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And it suddenly&#8212;silently&#8212;it was gone&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kartum&#8217;s hand on my shoulder startled me out of my skin.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;We got them!  We kiled them all!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I shook my head slowly to clear it, &#8220;..Not all&#8230;&#8221;  I mumbled.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Master Sureshot had recovered a bit during the fight, he was groggy and in pain, but he was awake.  Cheskin&#8217;s voice echoed through the woods from a distance, &#8220;They aren&#8217;t shooting at me anymore!  Did we win?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I managed a laugh, looking down at my clothes.  I was bathed in blood.  Fortunately, other than the dull pain in my side where the mace had hit, I was uninjured.  None of it was mine.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;What happened next lives still as the most revolting display I have seen by a man.  Kartum grabbed the body of the fallen gnoll and flipped it roughtly over onto its back.   &#8220;Thought you could best ME, did you!?&#8221; he laughed, &#8220;Filthy thing!&#8221;  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kartum unclasped his breeches and moved to urinate on the body of the gnoll.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The force of my shove sent him sprawling in the snow.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He struggled to rise, holding his pants up with one hand.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;No.&#8221; I said simply, &#8220;You&#8217;ll not do that.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As he rose, his hand fell to the pomel of his knife.  There was rage in his eyes and his face was flushed red.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Master Sureshot&#8217;s weak voice broke the tension.  &#8220;Boys, we must go.  We will send a crew back to collect the bodies...of ours, and theirs.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Had  I the time, I would have thought much of that battle, and of the strange gnoll shaman.  In the days that followed, however the glade was abuzz with the news of our battle.  The druids of the Glade cared for our Master, and through their healing, both magical and herbal, he was on his feet again in no time.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kartum again disappeared to Qeynos, which was just as well.  Cheskin&#8217;s account of the battle was not kind to him.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I had nothing much to say about the incident, save that I was glad we got out of it.  I never spoke of the shaman.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Three days afterward, Kartum, Cheskin and myself were called to the Glade to attend a memorial for our fallen comrade.  The entire Glade was there, both the Rangers and the Durids, as well as many of the villagers of the outlying areas.   It had been so long since we&#8217;d had a funeral in the Glade that I had forgotten how many people might be around.  The place was simply thronging.  The high druid gave a short, but well-spoken speech and spread our comrade&#8217;s ashes over the water.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Afterward, Hagar Sureshot stepped up onto the bridge and motioned for silence.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Now, for those of you unfamiliar with ranger ceremonies, let me state that if you were not familiar with them, you might  simply walk by one  without noticing&#8212;so informal and brief are they.  For Hager Sureshot, this was a pageant&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Ahem&#8230;&#8221;  he shuffled a bit on his sore leg, &#8220;In the wake of our bidding farewell to one of our own, I would like to take a minute to honor those who saved my life.  Cheskin, Eshkin and my nephew, Kartum.  Please come up here.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There was whispering and some quiet clapping as the three of us stepped up onto the bridge.  He bowed before each of us in turn, gripping our arms warmly.  Everyone in the Glade began to clap...filling the air  with clamor. I was embarassed, and I know I was blushing.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With a wave of his hand, he once again quieted the glade.  &#8220;Please, quiet&#8230;Also, I&#8217;d like to take a bit more of your time to commend one of our initaites for his exceptional valor, and honor, in battle.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Master Sureshot motioned to the crowd and a druid stepped forth holding a long, narrow box of polished oak.  He took the box and turned to me, opening it toward me, so that I could see its contents.  I glanced back and forth, wondering what he was doing&#8230;or rather, who he was looking at.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Eshkin kept his head in the crisis.  He pulled the party together and hatched the plan that saved us.  He fought with courage and honor--both to his friends and his enemies.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Next to me, I heard Kartum slowly exhaling a hissing breath of suppressed malice through his teeth.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;&#8230;Eshkin, I would like to present you with this arrow.  Carry it with you always, and it will never fail you.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If  I was thinking about Kartum and his jealous reaction at that moment, it was quickly dispelled at the sight of the arrow.  Its head of forged of steel blades and its vanes were of bone.   The shaft was of darkwood; that same material of the magic bow, I had seen so many years ago.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Uh&#8230;Master,&#8221; I said, &#8220;This really not necessary.  I only did what I could&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Nonsense, Eshkin&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;No, really sir, anyone would have&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;ESHKIN!&#8221; he yelled suddenly.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Uh&#8230;yes, sir?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Shut up.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Aye.  Yes, sir.&#8221; I took the arrow and placed it in my quiver.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The air of the glade was filed with wild clapping and cheering.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was the proudest moment in my life&#8230;back from a day when I could feel pride..<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My trade as a hunter was, from that day, touched with a blessing from Tunare.  My skills solidified and no quarry seemed able to elude me.  When I went into the hills to hunt, I suddenly found myself in need of other intitiates to help me carry the game back to the Glade.  My pelts wre always of the best quality and brought good prices form the merchants of Qeynos.  Even the gnolls of Blackburrow seemed to vanish from sight for a time.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My father was getting old now, and expressed a desire to leave off the smithing business.  One day, in the sumertime, he called me back to the smithy.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Eshkin, I will be straight with you, you have made a good name for yourself as a hunter.  I think that by the next harvests, Hager Sureshot will declare you a Ranger.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I poured my father another mug of coffee and seated myself at the table.  &#8220;Thank you, father.  That is my hope.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;You have done well, and I have raised you right.  I raised you to never lie.  So you must tell me something now, in perfect truth.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Of course, father.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Do you have any desire to keep up the smithy, after I am gone?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This was nothing like the question I had been expecting.  I am not certain what I was expecting, but that was not it.  &#8220;Father?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Do you wish to smith here in the village, or hunt with the Jaggedpine Treefolk?&#8217;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was not a hard decision, &#8220;I hope I do not offend, father, but I am a hunter now.  I wish to continue with that.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He was not surprised, &#8220;Very well.  I ask it because I am quitting.  I will travel next spring to the Karanas to live with my sister&#8230;permanently.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I paused for a moment.  He was trying to tell me something, but I was not sure what.  &#8220;What of the smithy, father?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;It is yours, son.  Take it.  Do with it what you wish.  If you do not wish to smith, you can get a very handsome offer on it from the merchants in Qeynos.  It will be good money for you.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;But what about you?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He laughed.  It was a rare and welcome laugh; one I had not heard in a long time.  &#8220;I will be fine, son.  You don&#8217;t think I have been smithing all these years without squirrling some plat away, do you?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;So that was that.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My father left in the spring for the Karanas and the smithy was empty.  He left with me the rolled parchement of title that declared the smithy mine.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was at the harvest festival, in the Glade that spring, that I met my wife.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Tables had been set out in the Glade and the kegs sunk in the lake to cool.  The ovens had smoked all night for a week before and the tables were heavy with meat and fish and bread.  There were wines from Qeynos and grapes, imported all the way from Karana.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bards and merchants had come from the city to sing and sell their wares.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The whole glade was alive with celebration, and free of care.  Kartum was not present.  In the eighteen months since our fight with the gnolls, he had become an incorragble drunk, only showing his face in the Glade when he needed a party to hunt with---so that he might get pelts to sell for more liquor.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I was standing with Cheskin, taking a moment of indulgance with a cup of mead.  He was knelt down on one knee, playing at magic tricks with his little daughter.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Esh, you really should spend more time in the Glade.  You are hunting all the time.  Or come with me and Tuvar to Qeynos for a few days.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Why would I want to do that, Ches?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Because it&#8217;s social, ya big fool!  Because it&#8217;s fun!  My wife can watch the babes for a few days, as long as I care for the house before I go.  We can see the sights!  I hear there is a place in Qeynos that sells gnoll beer.  You seem to have a fascination with the brutes.  Wouldn&#8217;t you like to try their beer?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I don&#8217;t like beer, Ches.  Besides, isn&#8217;t gnoll beer against the law?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Bah,&#8221; he said, &#8220;The laws of Antonius Bayle.  What harm is there in a little gnoll beer?   I have heard it&#8217;s quite good.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I don&#8217;t like beer, Ches.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;But it&#8217;s <b>gnoll</b> beer, Esh.  It&#8217;s an oddity.  It&#8217;s an experience.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Hmm.  But if I don&#8217;t like beer, wouldn&#8217;t it be a <b>bad</b> experience?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cheskin shook his head, &#8220;You are impossible.  What about the girls, then?  There are dancing shows&#8230;and I hear the ladies are like wild animals.  A new quarry for your hunting, eh?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I laughed, &#8220;You would have me chasing dancing girls in Qeynos?  You have me mistaken for Kartum.  The girl for me won&#8217;t be found&#8230;in&#8230;a&#8230;.tavern&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Where, then Eshkin of the black arrow?  You spend far too much time in the company of men.  What girl could take your mind off the hunt?  Esh?  Esh?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I could barely hear him.  Amid a group of people gathered around a young bard, was a young woman.  Her dress was simple brown cotton and there were flowers in her auburn hair.  She wore no shoes on her feet and about her waist was a simple belt hung with medicine pouches.  She was a Druid, surely, but none I had seen in the Glade.  I would have remembered.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;She was swaying back and forth to the ballad of the bard and clapping her hands softly.  The smile on her face was luminous and her eyes shone with mirth.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Uhh&#8230;.hello.&#8221;  I was instantly embarassed.  Was that the best I could do?  Faced with the vision of her before me, I  suppose I should be happy that I could speak at all.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;She turned and looked at me, and her smile broadened, &#8220;Hail&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ok Eshkin, what now?  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Are you from here?&#8221; I asked.  &#8216;IwasonlywonderingbecausehavelivedherealongtimeandIdon&#8217;t remembereverseeingyouhere.Youlooktobeadruid,butIthoughtIknewalltheDruidsoftheGlade&#8230;umm&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;She laughed and took my hand.  The touch of her soft fingers sent a warm shiver through my entire body.  &#8220;Dance with me,&#8221; she said.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We danced.   I barely remember it, and for that I am grateful, because I have always been a terrible dancer.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;That was it for me.  It was instant and undeniable.  For the rest of the festival we were never apart.  After I composed myself, I was able to speak again and we talked long into the night.  Her name was Layla and she was a Druid of Surefall, an initiate, sent from Qeynos by her family.  Once again I hadn&#8217;t been paying attention&#8212;I should have noticed her the moment she arrived.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I got little hunting done that summer, and Cheskin complained that he saw even less of me.  However, I didn&#8217;t care.  I had Layla.  She could tell a tale like a bard and the music of her laughter was beter than the finest lute&#8230;.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I will stop this here and move on&#8230;.I do not feel that I can write more on her just now&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We were married in the Glade, by the fall and Cheskin was my best man.  At the druid guild tree, the druids placed wreaths of flowers on our heads and declared their blessings.  I have never had a happier moment.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Druids and Rangers are people of the land, but when the land is harsh, everyone loves a house.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I decided that, in short order I would build Layla a house.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The title to the smithy was still safely stowed in Qeynos Hold and it did not take long for me to secure a buyer for the place.  A fully outfitted smithy is an expensive affair, and buyers would be rare.  However, my terms were simple and eagerly accepted.  I sealed the deal, with Cheskin at my side, over a Blackburow Stout, in Fish&#8217;s Tavern by the docks in Qeynos.  Ches was delighted that  had finally tried his gnoll beer.  He was right.  It was good.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The merchant would not take delivery of the smithy or open busines there until I sent word that the house was completed.  Additionally, he would help me find woodcutters and craftsmen to help me build it.  It would be built in total secrecy, as a surprise for her.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cheskin was my accomplice in this, claiming to Layla and the rangers of the glade that I had accompanied him on his hunting&#8212;to cover my absence from the hunt.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Because Layla was a Druid, I decided that the house would be very close to the Glade, perched atop the steep rocky ridge down from the waterfall.  From inside Surefall Glade, it was invisible, the crest of its roof just hidden by the towering rock walls that protectet the home of the Jaggedpine Treefolk.  It could be accessed by a narrow path around the back side of the mountain.  It would be built of treated logs, and I made sure that all the joints were well chinked with daub.  The crowning finish of the place was a window of polished glass panes, imported from Erudin.   This was so that we could sit and look out over the Glade in the winter.  There were two fireplaces for warmth and a clay cistern on the roof  to catch rainwater and snowmelt.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was magnificent.  All false modesty aside, I had outdone myself.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cheskin helped me with the work when he could as did the craftsmen sent by the merchant.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Had I taken time to stop and reflect, I should have considered myself fortunate to have the hidden wealth to bring such a project to life.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;All through  the months of building the house, Layla was distraught at my long abscences.  She complained that she wanted to see me more and missed our long talks.  In response I told her that I was hunting hard and saving my pelts to sell&#8212;so that I might surpirse her with something.  Despite her questions I kept my secret safe, and before autumn, the house was complete.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I stood in the main room and lit my pipe (tobbacco was a habit that the decadent Cheskin had addicted me to). Watching how the late autumn daylight played over edges the amazing glass window.  How the High Men must treasure the secret of changing sand into glass.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The door opened, at last and Cheskin and his wife Maurita carefuly escorted Layla into the room.  She was blindfolded, but smiling.  &#8220;You two had best not keep me much longer in suspense.  My master is teaching me to summon a stinging swarm of pests to put you in your place&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;No more suspense, my darling,&#8221; I said, removing the blindfold from her eyes.  That look of wonder on her face is the most beautiful thing I have ever seen&#8230;before&#8230;or since.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We made love that night in our new home.  Perfect, passionate&#8230;love without doubt.  Life was going to be perfect&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Layla and I had lived in the house for almost four months.  As soon as the secret was out, we were the subject of much gossip in the Glade.  Questions as to where I had gotten the money for such an endeavor were quickly laid to rest by Cheskin, whose wagging tongue could rival any bard.  Everyone paid a visit&#8230;espically to see the wonderful Erudite glass window.  Well&#8230;almost everyone.  Kartum never came.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The black arrow that Hager Sureshot had given me that day had treated me well.  While most other arrows splintered and shatterd in the prey, the black arrow never did.  Part of its enchantment, I suppose.  With it, I had dropped grizzly bears in their tracks in a single shot.  Throughout its service it had not so much as scratched or tarnished.  Its shaft was still straight and true and its path never erred.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At the bottom of the hill I shook hands with my hunting party and bid them good evening, looking forward to a quiet night by the fire with Layla curled up against me in our favorite chair, reading to me from one of her many books.  I was always literate, but only just so.  Layla had made it her personal task to make me, not only the top gamesman in the Glade, but also the most alacrit.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The path to the house was slick with snow that day, but the warming weather was sure to melt it away.  I was thinking as I rounded the corner of the house that I should save some more money and build a wooden walkway in its place.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My smile broadened as I stepped up onto the threshhold and opened the door.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Layla darling, I&#8217;m&#8230;back&#8230;.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The house was not as it should be.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Furniture was overturned, and papers and books&#8212;her precious papers and books&#8212;were strewn wildly about the floor.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My hand fell to the hilt of my sword, and the pelts I had ben carrying in my arms fell to the floor.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Layla hung by her wrists, tied to a crossbeam in the ceiling.  Her dress was in tatters and she was covered in blood from the long, deep razor cuts on her arms&#8230;..and her face.  There was a gag in her mouth&#8230;or&#8230;rather&#8230;what was left of her mouth&#8212;to silence her screams.  The flesh of her hands was black where the ropes bound her.  She must have been hanging there all day.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Her, swollen, beaten eyes opened slightly, and the light of recognition lit in them.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It felt as though the soul had been drained out of me&#8230;all the world was cold and frost.  The bile rose in my throat, and the tears rose in my eyes.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A feeling of utter helplessless like I have never felt&#8230;and will never feel again, swept over me.  However long she had been here&#8230;like this&#8230;I had not known&#8230;and could not help. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Instanly I was torn between two overpowering urges.  First to get her down from there.  And second&#8212;to destroy whatever monster (for it could be no man) that had done this thing.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The only piece of furniture left standing in the room was our chair.  The same chair the only a moment before I had imagined Layla and I nested in for the night.  It was a wide, high-backed chair, that we normally kept in front of the glass window.  Now, however, it was facing away from the door&#8212;pulled into the center of the room as a single seat for a madman&#8217;s private show.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The figure in the chair rose and tunred to face me.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was Hager Sureshot.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He looked at me for a moment, or perhaps it was a month.  There were spatters of blood on his face and scratch marks over his eyes that must have been made by Layla, in her desperate defense.  In one hand, he held a cup of mead from our kitchen.  In the other, my shaving razor&#8230;covered in Layla&#8217;s blood.  He cocked his head sideways in a curious gaze, and a slight smile touched his mouth.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;When he spoke, his voice was not the gruff, terse tone of Hager Sureshot, but the delicate musical sound of my Layla.  He&#8230;or it&#8230;said my name.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Eshkin&#8230;my love&#8230;where are you?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My sword whistled from its scabbard in a blur and my entire being erupted in invincible rage.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Had I known the name if Innoruk then, I would have forsaken Surefall, forsaken Tunare, and called on the Prince of Hate, for the power to crush this thing bare-handed&#8212;to dine on its screams and lavish in the feeling of tearing the flesh from its bones.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The shock of my own blow ran up my arm as the blade choped into the flesh of  its neck.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And it smiled.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The blow that impacted against the side of my head was mericful.  Blood exploded in my sinuses and warm, white light flashed before my eyes.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I don&#8217;t remember much of the fight&#8212;save that it was hopless.  My last recollection of it was that Sureshot&#8217;s arms had changed&#8212;growing into disproportionate claws&#8230;.like the blades of a scythe.    They scissored in on my forearms, cutting deep holding me helpless off the floor, like a bloody marionette.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It&#8217;s held me up to her; to the tortured, mutilated face of my love.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Again, it spoke in her vioce, &#8220;Eshkin&#8230;kiss me, my love&#8230;we can&#8217;t be late for dinner&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I screamed then, I think&#8230;and it laughed.  Hager&#8217;s body, Layla&#8217;s voice&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Through my tears  I wished for death.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Hmmm&#8230;delicious&#8230;&#8221; it said.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And, as a child might skip a stone over the water, it cast me out the window.  The strength of its throw, as it propelled me, was unearthly.   I remember the shattering of  Erudite glass, and the cuts it dealt me, only vaguely.  I remember the fall, and the feeling of weightlesness, and a dream of pain, of blood erupting up into my mouth&#8230;and of bones splintering like glass.  Was it an hour, or only a moment, I do not recall&#8212;but my blood-blind eyes opened to find me on the roof of the Rangers&#8217; cabin in the Glade. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My body had made a dent in the roof.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Broken ribs, legs, fingers&#8230;everything was a dull  haze of pain.  Everything was growing cold&#8230;and my body began to shake.  Death would come soon&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;From the roof of the cabin I could see the very top gables of my house above&#8230;.and the creature.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It had cast off all pretense, and was now not even vaguely human.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It had climbed  to the roof, with my Layla cradled in its claws.  It must have unbound her mouth, because I could hear her screams&#8230;and I remembered it&#8217;s word&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Delicious.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Agony&#8230;fear&#8230;sorrow.  It loved these things.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Layla was terribly fearful of heights&#8230;and so it would finish her&#8230;by casting her down into the glade.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;NO.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Though my legs did not work, somehow my arms did.  I managed to roll onto my side and pull my bow from it&#8217;s quiver.  My bloodied hand shakily felt for the one thing I needed&#8230;a last hope.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The black arrow.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Laying in anguish I fitted it to the nock and drew with all my strength.  I could hear the fiber of the bow splintering from within, from the force, as I drew.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;One shot&#8230;one hope&#8230;with the black arrow that had never failed me.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I missed.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I closed my eyes and relaxed into death as I heard my love&#8217;s screams silenced against the stone.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I would be with her soon.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Layla&#8230;I come.<br>****************************************************************************<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I woke in the Druid tree, in the Glade.  Their herbs had taken the pain away, and their healing had restored my legs.  I had slept the sleep of death for a fortnight.   It had taken the high druid himself three days of meditiation and casting to save my legs&#8230;but they did it.  Had the incident happened farther from such a powerful healer, I&#8217;d not have my legs now&#8230;had I lived at all.  For their aid, I will always be grateful.  Somehow, I was whole&#8212;save for the eerie scars the creature had left on my forearms from where it grabbed me. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The creature&#8230;whatever it was, had been thorough.  It had not forgotten to light the house as it left.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My life was over.  My Layla, and the beautiful home I had built for her&#8230;now all just a pile of ashes.  Now, in the place of her laughter there is only a cold, empty space&#8212;a cold vacum without joy or light.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As soon as I was able, I left the care of the druids and climbed the ridge on shaky legs to see the ruin that was once my life.  The black soot and charred hulks of the logs were thick on the ground.  One could vaguely tell that it was once a house.  Only because the stone chimneys still stood&#8212;cracked from the furnace heat and blackened with the smoke from the blaze.  Too numb to feel anything as I surveyed the destruction, my foot chanced to turn up the soot, with an odd tinkling sound.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Squatting in the coals I gently lifted the ruined frame of the Erudite glass window from the ash.  I slowly shook my head, as I looked at it.  Such a wondrous thing of beauty it had been.  Months to create&#8230;and seconds to destroy. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A sliver glint in the ash I had uncovered by moving the window caught my eye.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The arrow.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I dusted it off and looked at it.  Still perfect.  It had missed its mark, but survived the fire.  For a moment I fancied breaking it in my hands, but reason restrained me.  To destroy it would do no good.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I would keep it&#8230;for another day.<br>**********************************************************************************<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Druids presented me with Layla&#8217;s ashes for the burial shortly after my recovery.  Again, all the Jaggedpine Treefolk gathered in the Glade.  It was a short, but elegant ceremony, performed by the High druid.  The druid did all the speaking.  I could not.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I had never heard of such a creature as the one that lived in my dreams now, but I related the details to Master Sureshot as best I could.  He gave my his condolences and told me he would inquire about what manner of beast this might be.  Other than that, he was supportive.  I could live in the bunkhouse with the other intiaites and eat in the cabin.  He told me there would be no need to hunt, until I felt up to it.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was then that Kartum resurfaced.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Looking back on my experiences with Kartum, I can still not understand why he harbored such ill will for me.  Simple jealousy does not explain it all.  It seemed that, whatever troubled him so badly that he needed always hide in the bottle, he had blamed on me.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cheskin and I were in the cabin for the evening meal.  Tunare bless Cheskin for his staunch support in these times.  He and Maurita always had a place for me at their table.  Some nights though, Ches and I went down to the Glade and ate at the cabin.  He was always at my side.  This was one such night.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kartum&#8217;s stride was straight, but his face was flushed with wine when he entered the dining hall.  He filled his plate and seated himself across from me, glancing to his left and right and mumbling unheard greeting to the initiates beside him.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was only moments before he started on me.  His anger and courage must have been fueled by the wine.  When he spoke his voice was deliberately loud&#8212;to be certain that everyone at the table could hear.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I have heard that Eshkin has had a tragedy!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I looked at him evenly, my heart growing numb as the subject was braoched that I least wanted to hear about.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;What was he trying to do here?   I nodded and forced myself to speak, &#8220;Aye, Kartum.  That&#8217;s true.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I have heard that a monster attacked in the night&#8230;killed Layla and burned down his beautiful house!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I shook my head and again forced the words to come, &#8220;This is not new news, Kartum.  What is your point?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It was here that Cheskin stepped in, rising from the table, &#8220;Kartum, you had best excuse yourself.  You are drunk.&#8217;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;The hell I am!  I can hold my liquor with the best.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Then what is your purose here?&#8221; asked Cheskin, &#8220;Just opening wounds?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kartum took a bite from his plate and laughed, &#8220;Not at all.  I just think it&#8217;s unusual that Fortune should suddenly fail <b>poor</b> Eshkin&#8212;who seemed so favored by her before.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I carefully set down my sliverware and placed my hands on the table, &#8220;Explain that.&#8221;  I stated.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Well,&#8221; Kartum smiled and leaned back in his chair.  He had the attention of the whole room now.  &#8220;A monster&#8230;that killed your woman and <b>then</b> lit your house afire?  Sounds a bit supect to me.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The weight of Ches&#8217; hand on my shoulder made me suddenly aware that I was standing.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ches squeezed my shoulder, &#8220;Kartum, you are a fool.  You have been drinking and you are not welcome here.  I don&#8217;t care whose nephew you are, such talk is sheer spite.  We&#8217;ll have none of it here.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;But Kartum was on a roll.  He knew he was getting to me.  Such blatant flaunting of Layla&#8217;s memory&#8212;to use her to try and hurt me&#8212;he could not have picked a better subject.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I&#8217;m merely supposing, Cheskin,  that Eshkin had to get the money to build his house from somewhere.  Perhaps someone wanted it back?  Despite her bad taste in men, I&#8217;m certain Layla wasn&#8217;t earning her keep on the streets of Qeynos&#8230;at least I&#8217;m fairly certain&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My cup of water was in motion faster than I could stop my arm.  Its contents splashed into Kartum&#8217;s eyes, blinding him for a moment.  In that moment, my fingers laced themselves into his hair and pounded his face into the hard oak of the table.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sound was uncertain and the room was a haze.  I am unclear of the reactions of those around me.  All I knew was my rage to exterminate Kartum was not to be denied.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There was no hesitation, as my arms carried out actions, seemingly on their own.  Perhaps the creature had left the touch of Innoruk upon me.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I have always been a big man.  My time at the forge as a boy had conditioned me with the build of a smith from a young age.  Kartum was off-balance, bent over the table, unable to get the leverage to pull himself away as I pressed his face into the plate of food before me.  With one hand in his hair, I held the half-elf&#8217;s face to the table, and he flailed and gasped for air through the mess of food on my plate.  With the other,  I slid my table knife under his neck and sawed open his throat.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Blood erupted all over the table, the flood of it carrying away bits of bread and meat as it spread across the wood.  Kartum&#8217;s gargling cry was choked off by the blood and food.  I held his face to the table until his struggles ceased&#8230;and his body relaxed into death.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As my rage faded, I became aware of the thick silence that had fallen over the dining hall.  Some two dozen of the Jaggedpine Rangers stood staring at the grizzly spectacle before them.  There was no time to run for the druids&#8212;Kartum was obviously quite dead.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Oddly enough, I felt no remorse, as I had on the day I had battled with the gnoll.  The gnoll was, somehow&#8230;well&#8230;somehow the gnoll was just another soldier, innocent at heart, but fighting the fight he was born to fight.  Kartum was an animal.  I felt no more remorse than had I just gutted a kill.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Letting the bloody knife clatter to the tabletop, I straightened and wiped the blood from my hands with my napkin.  A strange numbness had settled on me.   &#8220;I guess I had better go tell Master Sureshot about this.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No one spoke as I walked from the room.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;What was said behind closed doors, I do not know, but it went on for several days.  I was disarmed and escorted to the bear caves, where I was ordered to stay.  Two of my comrades guarded the entrance to ensure I did not escape.  It was a token, really.  Everyone knew I would not try to leave Surefall Glade before judgement had been passed on my deed.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I did not wonder about my fate.  I had ceased to care.  My life had ended a fortnight ago.  It was only now that I would get around to dying.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I don&#8217;t know what was said between Hager Sureshot and the High Druid, but it was apparently not what I was expecting.  The next night, from the entrance to my impromptu prison, I heard whispered voices, and the tread of boots.  Into the meager light of my lantern, where I had expected the armored forms of Antonius Bayle&#8217;s guards, stepped Hager Sureshot.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;His skin was pale and there were dark circles under his eyes.  Sleep must have eluded him for some time.  &#8220;Eshkin,&#8221; he said, nodding to me.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Master Sureshot.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I have been in long deliberation with the druids and others of the Jaggedpine Rangers.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Yes, sir. I imagined that you would be.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;&#8230;and so  am quite tired of talk right now, so I will come to the point.  The business of the Jaggedpine Treefolk is not the business of Qeynos, or Antonuis Bayle.  We have made our own decisions.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Yes, sir.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Rangers do not kill rangers.  You must leave Surefall Glade.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Sir?&#8221;  It was not that I did not understand him.  I found the verdict surprising.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Kartum was a disgrace to our kind.  It was inevitable that he one day would meet such an end.  But rangers do not kill rangers.  Do you understand me?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  I nodded.  The numbness in my mind and heart was all there was.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Very well.&#8221;  He said, &#8220;This thing shall not be spoken of in Surefall.  Take your things and go.  It makes no difference where.  Just go to your bunk and get your things.  Speak to no one.  Then leave.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Aye.  I will sir.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There was a long pause.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Eshkin.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Yes sir?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Now, please.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Oh&#8230;.yes sir.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I stood, taking the lantern in my hand, and walked toward the exit to the cave.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sureshot&#8217;s voice stopped me at the entrance, &#8220;Eshkin, one more thing.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I turned to look at him, &#8220;Sir?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;His voice was low and he looked intently into my eyes as he spoke.  &#8220;I know do not want to think about&#8230;that night&#8230;or about the creature that took my form.  But I have spoken with the druids on it, and this thing has touched you.  It has marked you.  As you travel&#8230;as you go&#8230;it might be good of you to think on it.  One day you may find it important.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I nodded to him.  Not understanding what he was saying.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I did not want to understand.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;That night I looked bitterly back at the torchlit tunnel that was the entrance to Surefall Glade.  I had lived there all my life.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;But that was over now.  That life was just a bright and painful memory.  It was time for a new life.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For a time, I lived in the remote parts of Qeynos hills,  hunting and foraging for my meals and camping against the cold.  The quiet  of the wilderness demanded nothing of my mind.  I could try to forget.  I could live as an animal.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This I did for two years.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Of course, during this time, I was not without certain needs.  Clothing wears out, bowstrings break, and arrow points were always a commodity.  For this reason I had to endure the presence of people from time to time and sell my pelts in Qeynos for money to purchase that which I needed.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The pallor of my mind and the heaviness of my heart must have been fading at last.  On one of these excursions I found myself, on a lark, at Fish&#8217;s Tavern.  After almost two years, Fish Ranamer still recognized me.  We exchanged michevious grins, as he quietly changed my coin for a case of Blackburrow Stout.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The stout was a treat for me.  Having finally packed the heavy crate back to my camp in the hills, I nursed the beers, on special occasions:  Layla&#8217;s birthday, my own birthday, and sometimes when Tunare favored me with a quick and easy hunt<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I had bought twenty four beers from Fish Ranamer, each of the odd, brown clay bottles sealed in wax.  After each beer I would carefully rinse the bottle and use it later to hold water.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Several months later, I was down to eight of them.  I had not been gone from camp long when a yearling buck crossed my path.  With the day&#8217;s hunting done early, I decided to enjoy the last of the autumn warmth and simply lay by the stream with a beer.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At first I could not decide what was wrong when I opened the wooden case in my tent.  I glanced about, listening and smelling the air.  Someone had been in my tent.  The crate was not latched, as it should have been.  While I was out, someone had been in my camp.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Carefully, I unclasped the thong on my scabbard.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No sound.  Not even the birds.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Whoever had been in the tent was still nearby.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Slowly, I emerged from the tent, looking about for my uninvited visitor.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He was sitting on the log I had felled next to my fire pit, as relaxed as though it were his own camp.  It was a gnoll, the black of his fur was peppered with the white of age and his face was scarred from some long passed battle.  He wore a leather tunic and breeches, and an axe hung from a thong at his belt.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A heavy, leather bag sat on the log beside him.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He had come silently, and invisibly.   My pulse quickened and my hand fell to my sword.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He addressed me in broken common, &#8220;You&#8230;you like beerrr&#8230;.?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Uh&#8230;I&#8217;m sorry&#8230;&#8221; I said.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;His  paw gestured toward the crate beside me, &#8220;Beerr! Beerr!  You like?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This was somewhat different from the greeting I had heard from other gnolls.  &#8220;Uhh&#8230;yes.  I like beer.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It grinned.  The edges of its mouth turning up and wrinkling its snout&#8212;showing a rake of yellowed, broken canine teeth.  Out of the bag, it produced a bottle.  Deftly, he flipped the cap off of it with one thumb.  &#8220;Good beerrr it is!  Best beerr it is!&#8221;  He took a long, sloppy swig, his tongue lapping it noisily out of the bottle as he poured it all over himself.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He was drunk!  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A drunk gnoll in my camp?<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Uhh&#8230;.yes, it is good beer.  I really don&#8217;t like beer much but this is good beer.  It&#8217;s uh&#8230;it&#8217;s gnoll beer&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The gnoll slurped and lapped noisily as more beer slopped down the front of his tunic.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;&#8230;but I guess you know that.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The gnoll released a humungous belch.  &#8220;Ahh&#8230;good gnoll beerrr!  My beerr it is!  Gnasher I am!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ahhh&#8230;So this was Gnasher Furgut, the gnoll brewer!  Somehow I had envisioned him as a bit more, well&#8230;fearsome.  Younger and more sober, perhaps.  Antonius Bayle&#8217;s guards would like to find this one.  Gnasher Furgut was supposedly the brewer and vendor of Blackburrow Stout to Qeynos.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;You like my beerr!&#8221; he beamed proudly,  &#8220; It is therre in yourr little house-of-cloth!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I stood up  and let my hand fall from my sword.  He certainly didn&#8217;t  seem hostile.  If he&#8217;d wanted to kill me he could have done so without introducing himself.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Yes&#8230;.uh&#8230;your beer is very good.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gnasher grinned a cracked-tooth, yellow gnoll grin, &#8220;Then drrrink with me, you must!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Drink?  With a gnoll?  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Hmm&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Well, he certainly didn&#8217;t seem to be a <b>typical</b> gnoll.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Slowly and warily I seated mself on the log next to him and accepted the bottle from his furry paw.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Despite the age-old relationship between the rangers of Surefall and the gnolls of Blackburrow Gnasher was totally at ease.  He deftly popped the cap on another beer and, very humanly, knocked his bottle against mine in toast.  &#8220;Health!&#8221; he said, slurping his beer sloppily all over himself.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Uhh...yes.  Health,&#8221; I Replied.  &#8220;May I ask you why you have not tried to kill me?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gnasher snorted a beer-wet laugh, &#8220;Kill you, why?  You drrink my beerr!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Uhh, well, I am a human and you are gnoll.  I rather thought that was the way things worked.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Ahh&#8230;Blackburrrrow rrrulz, yes.  To hell with them!  That arrre foolz.  You arre customerrr.  Bad business to kill customerr&#8212;even for humanz.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I hadn&#8217;t thought of that.&#8221;  I admitted.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;You a Rrrangerr.  Rrangerrr rulz sayz to kill gnollz.  Why you not kill me?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I took a cautious sip of beer, &#8220;Well, you rather surprised me.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gnasher growled a chuckle and looked knowingly at me.  &#8220;You a smarrt pup.  You not like to kill.  Killing is forr foolz.  Drinking is for wizdom!  Blackburrow kill, kill, kill.  No one to drink beerr!  No one to play bonz!  No one to tell talez!  Killing is forr foolz!  Warr, warr, warr&#8230;.everrryone likez warr!  Not time for beerr!  Not time for bonz!  Bah.  Foolz they arre.  But I like beerr&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Do the commanders and shamans of Blackburrow not like&#8230;.err&#8230;do they not like your beer?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Bah!  No.  Just like to make warr.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I see.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gnasher took a long, tonguey slurp from his bottle, tilting his head back to get the last drop.  He contunued tilting back, and back&#8212;until his unconscious form rolled off the log.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Hmm.  Well this was an interesting dilemma.  What if one of the Jaggedpine Treefolk saw this?  A drunk Gnoll passed out in my camp.  I could have killed him, I suppose.  The Qeynos guards would pay well for his head.  But that would not be right&#8212;certainly not honorable, anyway.  In retrospect I&#8217;m glad I didn&#8217;t.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Instead, I draged him into my tent and let him sleep it off.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;When he awoke, he was only slightly different of temperment than before.  We revisited briefly why we had not tried to kill each other, and talked a bit more.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gnasher was an orphan of Blackburrow&#8212;immigrated from Karana for some reason, long ago.  He was tolerated, but not welcomed by his own kind&#8212;who resented both his dealings with humans, and his lack of enthusiasm for killing them.  He too lived apart from his people, in a rather nice cabin far back in the hills behind Blackburrow.  It was there that he kept his brewbarrel and gardened the special hops and berries for his beer.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I seldom visited him that summer, but regularly he would stagger into my camp drunk and entice me to join him in beers and his favorite dice game.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;After awhile I began to welcome the sound of his uncertian steps, crashing through the underbush into my camp. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He taught me how to play Bonz--a gnoll dice game, and we spent long hours at this.  However, I was never convinced I knew all the rules, as he consistently beat me.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This was one such night&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;HaHa!  One Bash, Thrree Fangs!  Beatz yourr Fourr Clawz!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I looked at the arrangement of the shiny, carved bits of bone on the log in front of me, &#8220;No it doesn&#8217;t.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;HaHa!  Yez it doez!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I shook my head.  I was never going to understand this game.  I had almost given up trying to master all the rules.  The gnolls had seemed to me, always, to be a rather dim race.  Pea-brained, in fact.  But to master a game of such deep complexity as this Bonz game, they must have a well-disguised streak of genius.  Another copper changed hands.  Gnasher beamed a snarl-toothed grin of undisguised pride each time he took a copper from me.  There was no animosity though.  I could say with reasonable certainty, that we were friends.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I think you like this game too much Gnasher.  Have you ever thought of mastering something else.  Something like checkers perhaps?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gnasher shrugged and passed me another beer.  &#8220;Bah!  Nothing is good az Bonz!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Now wait a minute.  How do you know that?  There are plently of other games out there.  Chess, Backgammon, King&#8217;s Trio, Bao; All kinds of card games too.  And all you play is Bonz?  That&#8217;s rather limited, don&#8217;t you think?  There is a lot more out there.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the first time in the months that I had known him, Gnasher scowled.  His yellow eyes were lit with a dim mix of anger and sorrow. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I know thiz.  You tell Gnasherr that the worrld iz biggerr than bonz?  You arre a pup!  Thirrty yearz and you still crringe around yourr Glade&#8212;hiding from people becauze you lost your mate?  Becauze you kill yourr enemy?  Ahh&#8230;.?  Gnasher trrick you, eh?  You don&#8217;t know I know thiz?  I know many thingz!<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I waz grreatest Raider of Splitpaw!  I have seen all Karrana and Rrathe-Lake!  I even go to Qeynos morre than you!  Dangerruz!  Have to sneak!  But eat at human tablez with human friendz!  Do not talk to me like I am an old fool!  Old may&#8212;bee but no fool!  You want to play at chezz?  You want to play at bao?  Okay&#8212;but we play forr plat!  I play all thoze gamez!  And I will kick your hairrlezz, human tail!<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I am old now!  I make beerr.  I play bonz!  Not becauz I not know otherr gamez.  I like bonz.  I like beerr.  Life too shorrt to drrink waterr and play gamez you not like!  Life iz too shorrt to hide frrom it!  You arre the fool, Eshkin!  You arre hiding.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;After his rant, Gnasher downed a few more beers and staggered back to his cabin, but his words still made me angry inside, and sad.  I thought much of Layla, and found myself crying most of the night. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As the sun rose, however, I was bathed in a calm serenity and clarity of thought.  Gnasher was absolutely right.  Was I going to give up my whole life over that night&#8212;the life that had been spared?<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There were things to see, things to do.  Important things.  No idea what they were&#8230;but they were important.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I went to Qeynos that day, loaded heavy with skins.  Lacking sleep, I stayed the night at Fish&#8217;s and set out the next morning to sell my skins.  For the first time in a long time, the press and the sound of the streets of Qeynos felt good to me.  There was something happening to me.  I felt very alive.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Having reprovisioned mysef, I set out at dusk for my camp again, but not without first stopping by Voleen&#8217;s Bakery and purchasing a few fresh pies for Gnasher, as well as some coffee and tobbacco.  It felt good to do.  I knew from talking with him that Gnasher had a taste for sweets, and I had never done my strange gnoll friend the honor of a gift before.  Considering the change that his words seem to have wrought in me over the last days, I concluded that it was appropriate.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;After a forced march back to my camp and a quick nap, I struck out with my pack for Gnasher&#8217;s cabin.  I shortly found him out back, futzing with the brewbarrel.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We stoked the fire in the hearth and boiled water for coffee.  I rolled us both some cigarettes (I had not had the money to afford the new, pre-rolled tobbacco sticks that were becoming high fashion for the Qeynos elite)<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We cut the pie and drank the coffee (Gnasher scalded his tongue, but enjoyed the novelty of fresh coffee immensely). <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Over breakfast  I told him the story of that night over two years ago, of the monster that took the form of Hager Sureshot.  I told him of its last word to me&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&#8230;Delicious&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He sat for a long moment, the smoke from his cigarette rising in lazy circles to the ceiling, staring his yellow-eyed stare at some invisible point in the distance.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Dangerrouz thing this monsterr iz.  Change shape, change voice&#8230;and lovez pain and fearr, it doez.  Strong too&#8212;to thrrow you off that high place.  You arre big for a human.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I took a drag off my cigarette, letting the buzz from the tobbacco calm the edginess that had suddenly risen in me.  &#8220;Have you ever heard of such a monster?&#8221; <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gnasher stared through the smoke into the distance, as though thinking far back into his past.  &#8220;Only in bad dreamz&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We drank our coffee in silence for a moment, Gnasher lapping especially quietly from his cup, and making only a minimal mess.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I have to kill it.&#8221;  I announced.  &#8220;I even kept the arrow.  Although, at the time I didn&#8217;t know why.  I have to kill it or I can never be truly at peace.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;You, kill it, pup?  How will you find it?<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I don&#8217;t know.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;How you kill it?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I don&#8217;t know&#8230;my bow, or my sword.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gnasher laughed, &#8220;You die like a fool then.  Everr rraid Blackburrow?  Everr fight gnollz?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I have fought a gnoll.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;NO.  Have you fought <b>in</b> Blackburrow!?  Not one-gnoll hunting.  Twenty gnollz! Fourty gnollz!  You are a pup!  You must trravel.  To fight thiz thing you must be a <b>Grreat Rraiderr!</b>&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This last bit he almost shouted&#8230;err&#8230;howled.  Gnasher certainly got emotional when he talked about raiders and raiding.  It was a gnoll thing, I suppose.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I nodded.  He was right.  I had felt it back in Qeynos.  I needed to travel.  I knew nothing of the world beyond Qeynos.  I had heard of the Barbarians of the Everfrost Peaks and even seen them in Qeynos.  And the Erudites I had also seen, but only from a great distance.  It was time to expand my hunting grounds.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I was thinking of going to hunt in the Peaks.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gnasher leaned back and smiled his snarling smile, &#8220;Bewarre, Eshkin.  The rroad is the best of beerr!  Once you set yourr pawz in motion&#8230;.might be harrd to stop!  And it will be harrderr life sometimez than you think.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I smiled, &#8220;It&#8217;s just up to the Peaks, Gnasher.  How hard could it be?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Tunare punishes arrogance.  At least my father always told me so.  Perhaps it was my jaunty remark at Gnasher&#8217;s table that had done it&#8212;or perhaps I simply left Tunare&#8217;s blessings back in Qeynos Hills, but Everfrost was not kind to me.  It was stark and beautiful&#8230;but not kind.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My first attempt at hunting one of the exotic white bears of the plains almost cost me my life.  The hide and fur of these bears was tougher than anything I had ever encountered.  My first arrow, instead of crippling the beast, only enraged it, and it came barreling at me over the frozen ground.  My second arrow stuck in its hide unnoticed.  There was not time for a third arrow.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I valiantly reached for my sword, only to find it stuck solidly in the scabbard&#8212;frozen there from the cold.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fortunately, polar bears do not climb trees.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The result was a bit humiliating.  The bear growled and roared for most of the day, beneath me.  Until a cadre&#8217; of Barbarian warriors happened by, attracted by the sound of the animal&#8217;s cries.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;They spoke to each other in their native tongue for  bit, examinaing the situation, and laughing vigorously.  Finally their leader stepped forward a bit, &#8220;Ho there, Halfling!&#8221; he called, &#8220;What are ye seekin&#8217; up there?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;They apparently found this pretty amusing.  &#8220;Nothing, really.  Just relaxing, and having a smoke.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Again they conferred and laughed, &#8220;Very well, then!  We&#8217;ll be on our way!  Good huntin&#8217;, to ya, Halfling!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Alright, Alright!&#8221;  I cleared my throat. &#8220;I am not from here.  Can you tell me how to kill this bear?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Hmm&#8230;have ya been shooting him with arrows?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Yes.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Well, don&#8217; do  that, it does na work!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Yes, I discovered that!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Well, have ya skewered &#8216;m on yer sword?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;No.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Why not?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Because it&#8217;s frozen into the scabbard!&#8221; <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As the leader turned to translate my words, several of the hunting party actually fell the ground and rolled in the snow in mirth.  For the better part of a half hour, each one of them in turn would speak in Barbarian and all the others would roll on the ground laughing.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The bear was the only one not laughing.  It looked very serious.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At last the leader of the warriors wiped the tears from his eyes and spoke again in common, &#8220;Alright, Halfling!  We&#8217;ll help ya out.  But in the the future ya ought na hunt up here.  G&#8217;back ta the hills and the vales.  This is hard land up here.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With this, the warriors abruptly produced, seemingly from nowhere, a forest of heavy swords, axes and spears and simply hacked the bear to death. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Then they strolled off into the tundra laughing to themselves in Barbarian.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I sat up in the tree for some time and rolled myself a cigarette with the last of the tobbacco that I had bought in Qeynos.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;So that is how you do it.  You just hack it apart.  Just like that&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;These Barbarians were the toughest men I had ever seen.  Was I a little out of my depth here?  Surefall and Qeynos Hills were so tame compared to Everfrost.  I started to wonder if I could make it here or not.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Things didn&#8217;t get much better form there.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Just outside Halas, I used the last of my copper to buy some blade oil&#8212;in hopes that I would not suffer the frozen sword problem again.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Adjusting my expectations, I discovered quickly that I could kill the white wolves of Everfrost&#8230;and the very small polar bear cubs.  Unfortunately, barbarians are huge people and the small pelts of the wolves brought me next to nothing from the merchants of Halas.  Even when I was able to bring down a polar bear cub, the disdain of the Barbarians was evident in the prices that they gave me on my skins.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Everfrost was a hard land, as the warrior had told me that day.  My bow was no longer sufficient to bring down game and I would frequently have to engage it in melee.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My meager savings was dwindling.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I was out of arrow points and blade oil.  But worse still, my boots were wearing thin.   Everfrost&#8217;s bitter cold I could not last without good boots.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I needed money.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To this point I had not dallied too long in the town of Halas.  The stares and hushed voices of the tall, fur-clad barbarians were warning enough.  I was not welcome here.  However, Halas now had something I needed.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It had a public forge.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Located just outside the armorer&#8217;s shop, the elders of the Six Hammers had erected a forge for any and all who wished to use it.  Presumably this was to encourage the skill of smithing among the citizens of Halas.  A town can never have too many smiths.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As it happened, Halas had very few.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I had not fully stoked the forge before a young barbarian walked up.  His face was painted in blue war paint.  He was obviously a warrior.  He looked quizically at me and then at the forge.  I stared back at him for a moment and continued firing the forge.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Ya a smithy, Halfling?&#8221; he asked.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I scowled a bit.  &#8220;Acutally, I&#8217;m a human.  Halflings are a bit shorter than me, even.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;But ya are a smithy?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Yes.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;From under the folds of his furs he produced a battle axe.  To this day I am constantly amazed at the menagerie of places that barbarians can hide the largest weapons.  It was in pitiful shape.  The head pitted and cracked and rattling loosely on its haft.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I got this off a gnoll.  Can ye touch it up?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Aye friend.  I can touch it up.  If you have some coin I&#8217;d much appreciate it though.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In short order I filed down the edges and finished them hot with stone and hammer.  Then  shimmed the head down tight.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I had not fogotten everything from a boyhood at the forge.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Before I handed it back to him I shoved it into a drift, to cool and wiped it clean with a cloth.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He took it from me eagerly and spun it over in his hands.  He was a large man.  He handled the heavy axe as though it were a child&#8217;s toy.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;His boyish face beamed as though it were one as well.  &#8220;I canna believe me eyes!  Is like it&#8217;s new!  You really are a smithy, Halfling!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Err&#8230;Human&#8230;&#8221; I protested.  My protest was interrupted as he dropped a platinum piece, thick and heavy, into my hand.  &#8220;Or Halfling&#8230;whichever is easier for you, really&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In only a few hours,  a trickle of other warriors and hunters began to flow to the forge.  By nightfall, I had a queue.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As it happens, there is almost no smithing interest in Halas--because the nearest ore mines are all the way in Highpass.  Most of the limited weapons and armor available to the Barbarians are either taken from the goblins, orcs or gnolls, or are imported from Qeynos.  Smithing weapons and armor (the highest art of a blacksmith) is just not profitable in Halas, and so, no smith of significant skill ever stays to ply his trade there&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Leaving no one to sharpen and repair the Barbarians&#8217; weapons&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Until now.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I worked into the night, and word of my presence at the long-dead public forge quickly spread through the town.  Some were indifferent to me, most were a bit threatening&#8212;men and women alike&#8212;but they all paid.  Grudgingly, they acepted my work, and filled my purse.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This was a welcome change.  At least I wasn&#8217;t wading through waist-deep snow or sleeping in trees trying to wait out angry bears.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I was down on my knees with the iron door to the coal-catch at the base of the forge open, trying to scrape the excess coke into an already overful bucket when a blur from the side caught my eye.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I consider myself very fortunate that I got my hands out of the way in time, as a Barbarian boot slammed the coal-catch shut with a resounding clang.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My face flushed with rage as, cursing, I jumped to my feet and faced down the owner of that boot.  Standing with my chest out, at my full height, I was able to look him straight in the sternum.  And his two friends were just as large as he.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;What ye doin&#8217; Halfling?  This is a Barbarian forge&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Aye,&#8221; I said, &#8220;And I am using it to repair Barbarian weapons.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Yer no welcome here&#8230;we don&#8217; need ya.  You got good Babarian gold in yer purse from swindling these folks, Halfling.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I am reputed to be naieve, to this day, but it didn&#8217;t take much to see what was happening here.  &#8220;Yes, you are right, sir.  It is good Barbarian coin.  I have charged a fair fee and my customers are happy.  I can see you are a warrior.  Perhaps you&#8217;d like a weapon touched up&#8230;free of charge&#8230;as a sample of my work&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In response, a fist pounded into the side of my head&#8212;not his&#8212;one of his friends had grown weary of my trying to diffuse a fight, and elected to get straight to the bashing.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There were three of them all much larger than me&#8212;and frankly&#8212;all better warriors than me.  I was a &#8220;Halfling&#8221;--a foreigner.  One of the many times I thudded to the ground I blearily noticed the Barbarian guard looking very engaged, pretending to lecture one of the crowd that was gathering to watch the &#8216;Halfling&#8217; take a beating.  No help from the guards.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the record, I did fight back&#8212;not very well though.  When one is a child, brawls are more like a game.  Wild punches are thrown until someone gets a bloody nose and cries &#8220;uncle&#8221;.  Grown men fight more for hate&#8217;s sake&#8230;and consequences are much more serious.  I simply hoped they wouldn&#8217;t beat me to death.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Broken ribs, broken nose&#8230;eyes tight shut agianst the blood burning in them.   I was reeling from pain and shock.  I couldn&#8217;t stand under my own power&#8230;so the three of them helped me to my feet.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Ye like our forge, d&#8217;ya, Halfling?  Why d&#8217;ya not take a closer look at it.  You&#8217;ll see it&#8217;s a Barbarian forge&#8230;&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;One huge hand twined itself into my hair and pressd my head forward, into the forge.   I could feel the rising heat through the blood and cuts&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And suddenly my eyes and ears were filled with eerie sond, and a bright blue light&#8230;in a second, my wounds vanished, and I felt the hands holding me relax.  I stumbled away from the heat, wiping the blood from my eyes.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The crowd had parted, making way for two newcomers.  From the painted marks on their faces and the staves in their hands, I knew them to be shamans&#8212;holy men of the Six Hammers, and mystics who drew their power from the spirits of their animal totems.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;One was much older than the other.  It was he who spoke now.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Moradorf, what are ye doin&#8217;?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The brute&#8217;s friends, quickly abandoned him, fading back into the crowd.  Moradorf (apparently his name) glanced back and forth quickly, realizing that something had changed.  &#8220;Master Khondoran, this halfling was swindlin&#8217; gold fer smithin&#8217; he took me gold and dinna gimme nothin!&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The old shaman stepped quietly into the ring of the crowd and looked about at the faces.  He paused at me, and his blue eyes looked deeply into mine, curiously.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Kheldan!&#8221; he called to the younger shaman, &#8220;This is a friend of yours, this halfling?&#8221;&#8217;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Aye Master, he is my friend from Qeynos&#8212;he is a blacksmith.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I looked quizically at the younger mystic.  He was younger than me, perhaps five years.   His beard and hair were a ruddy blonde, touched with white.  I had never seen him before in my life.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Or had I?  There was something&#8230;familiar about him&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Khondoran continued, &#8220;&#8230;Is he an honest halfling?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Aye, Master, he is.&#8221; Kheldan replied.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The old shaman turned back to Mordorf, &#8220;You ye have anythin&#8217; further, Moradorf?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Moradorf bowed his head, &#8220;Nay, sir.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Then I think it&#8217;s time fer ya to go home.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Aye.  Thank ye sir.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With a wave of his hand the old shaman dismissed the crowd, who quietly, and respectfully disbursed.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I was left to my own to pick up the scattered mess of my things from around the forge.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Well, almost to myself&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Are you hurt still?&#8221;  It was Kheldan.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Hmm&#8230;no, not really, just my pride.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Master Kohndoran&#8217;s healing is powerful&#8230;but it can&#8217;t help that, I fear.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I balanced my pack on the edge of the forge and tried tying it all back together.  &#8220;So&#8230;If I may ask&#8230;why did you and your master interfere with that little fight back there.  I thought all <b>halflings</b> were more or less better beaten and burned than not, in this town.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Well, it wasn&#8217;t a fair fight.  There were three of them.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I laughed bitterly.  &#8220;Well, it wouldn&#8217;t have been fair if there were just <b>one</b> of them.  You didn&#8217;t notice that he was a bit <b>bigger</b> than me?&#8221;  I looked the young barbarian up and down.  He was not big for a barbarian, but he still towered above me.  &#8220;Hmph&#8230;no I suppose you didn&#8217;t.  In any event&#8230;I&#8217;m sorry, I don&#8217;t mean to be ungrateful.  Thank you for vouching for me.  You likely saved my life.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I stopped packing my pack and looked at him again.  Even through their crude dress of skins and furs the barbarians were a striking people.  The looked rough and noble.  But there was something about this one that struck me.  He looked so familiar&#8230;it was eerie.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kheldan shifted the tip of his staff in the snow and looked about nervously.  When he spoke, his voice was hushed, &#8220;Those scars on your arms, where did you come by them?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;In a drunk wrestling match with a crocodile.&#8221;  I replied.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He scowled, looking puzzled.  I was never any good at humor.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;These scars were given to me in a fight with a monster.  The druids of Surefall Glade tell me they cannot be healed.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He nodded knowingly, &#8220;What kind of monster?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I stopped my packing and stared at him.  &#8220;Why does this interest you.  It&#8217;s something I&#8217;d rather not discuss.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In response he pulled aside his thick bear-hide cloak and lifted up his jherkin.  On his chest&#8230;from throat to navel was a deep, ragged, greusome scar.  &#8220;Tis true.  The scars the creature leaves can not be healed.  This I have had since I was an infant.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It is difficult to make one understand what I felt at this moment.  It was sadness, despair&#8230;.yet mixed with hope&#8230;.and excitement.  Suddenly, I was here with this strange mystic&#8212;this barbarian&#8212;and we were participating in some kind of rite.  Some secret brotherhod pact.  For the first time in years I flelt an instant bond form.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kheldan was a gracious host.  I stayed that night in the Shaman&#8217;s guild on a straw mat next to the huge stone hearth.  The following day, I spent a good deal of the money from the night before on resupplying myself.  New fur-lined boots, plenty of arrow points, dried provisions, blade oil and tobbacco were the order of the day.  For all the crude amenities in Halas, their tobbacco shop (a place called Dok&#8217;s) is very well-stocked and turns a thriving business.  The rough-and-tumble warriors of the North may not have the money, day-to-day to care properly for their weapons, but many a goblin and gnoll has met an untimely demise for the sake of a fine cigar.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We talked as friends and were instantly comfortable in the presence of each other.  We spoke of our families and our past and our hopes&#8230;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&#8230;And, for the first time, we spoke of the creature.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kheldan was not only Khondoran&#8217;s aprentice, he was his ward.  Twenty-five years ago, Kheldan&#8217;s family had been attacked by the monster.  Kheldan&#8217;s father, shaman of great renown, battled the creature, while his mother, placed the baby&#8217;s pram on their dog-sled and whipped the dogs away.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At least that is the theory.  No one who was old enough to remember the battle survived to tell the tale.  Khondoran used all his healing powers to save the wounded infant, and still only just succeeded.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The massive war party assembled by the Wolves of the North was not so fortunate.  Their corpses were found in mass&#8230;dismembered and scattered about the burnt wreckage of Khledan&#8217;s parents&#8217; house.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Khondoran had a name for the beast.  It was the One Without Form&#8230;.it was The Doppleganger.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We talked long about it.  For the first time, I recalled the night of Layla&#8217;s death clearly.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As we drank and ate and talked--long into the next night&#8212;smoking our tobbacco and reflecting.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;What could this creature do, if it had mind to do so?  What sorrow could it reap in Quenos?  Or in Halas?  Or in all of Norrath?<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;This night will live in my mind forever&#8230;it is the night my life  had been building to for thirty-one years.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Erudites say that a life without reflection, is a life unlived.  I have found that there is some truth to this&#8212;so I shall reflect now--on this night in Halas.  <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I beleive that going out into Everfrost, to try and earn my keep had empowered me.  I was not relegated to Surefall, or Qeynos.  I was a hunter&#8212;perhaps my technique with polar bears needed some refinement, but I was skilled.  The loss of my Layla had made me stronger than I could have been, even as her love brought me alive while she was with me.  Gnasher Furgut had taught me, also&#8230;the precious value of life and its fleeting nature.  And now my new friend Kheldan&#8230;a brother by blood, somehow&#8230;a brother in the Monster&#8230;a brother in the Doppleganger&#8212;his presence opened up a world of possibilities.  It opened up a future.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As we talked together, the way these things fit together began to become clear to me.  I thought back all the way to my thirteeth year, as a boy in Surefall, holding in my hands the enchanted bow of Tamryn Scholl.  My fascintation with the bow was not the fascination with the bow itself&#8212;it was what that bow represented to me.  It was adventure.  It was action.  It was danger in high places for a higher ideal.  It was heroism.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The candles were burning low, and the tavern was empty.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;&#8230;It can take the form of anything it chooses,&#8221; said Kheldan.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;&#8230;and the voice.&#8221; I added.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;And it feeds on sorrow&#8212;on terror.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Aye, it seems to enjoy it immensely.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There was a long pause.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I cleared my throat.  &#8220;Ahem&#8230;that&#8217;s it?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kheldan thought a moment and nodded, &#8220;Aye.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;That is not much to go on.  We need to know more.  Much more.  The monster must have a weakness&#8230;or at least a home.  Does Halas have a place of knowledge&#8230;a hall of records?  Perhaps we could look at records of untimely deaths to learn more?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Kheldan shook his head.  &#8220;We are a people of oral tradition, Eshkin.  Khondoran has already told me all he knows.  We learn to write and read your language only so we can deal with outsiders.  We have no need o&#8217; such things in Halas.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Hmm.  No wonder they called them Barbarians.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I thought for a moment.  Kheldan was feeling the same strange elation I was; I could see it in his eyes.  We were balanced on a moment of decision.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;Well,&#8221; I said at length, &#8220;Are you up for a journey?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;His slow smile was answer enough.  &#8220;To where?&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I carefully rolled and lit my last cigarette on the flame of the ebbing candle, rolling the options over in my mind.  A feeling of peace settled over me as the decision was made.  I knew that Tunare&#8217;s blessing was with me again.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#8220;I know a place that makes beautiful glass.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Beginning&#8230;<br>

