<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">The Excuses of EverQuest</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Graack  (<a href="mailto:urquon54@hotmail.com" class="credit2">urquon54@hotmail.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
	Each day a number of problems found within EverQuest are brought forward in <br>a desperate attempt to catch the eye of Verant's PR people, such as Gordon <br>Wrinn.  And each day, some of these problems are noted and addressed on the <br>various web-boards, /petitioned, or /bugged.  Some times, a misconception is <br>cleared up.  Sometimes, more information is requested.  Sometimes, we, the <br>players, are told that the issue will be fixed shortly.  And sometimes, <br>we're just given the same excuses that we've read so many times; we can <br>recite them from memory.<br><br>	One of the most blatant problems with the excuses I've seen given the <br>players is that Verant lacks the manpower to follow through thoroughly on <br>each change it makes.<br><br>Examples of this:<br><br>1)	Verant has repeatedly asked it's players that if they find a bug, to use <br>the /bug command to report the problem.  Quite often, however, I feel that <br>the bug-logs go unexamined, and are allowed to fill to an overflow such that <br>old items are automatically deleted before they are ever addressed.  I know <br>that a number of issues have been /bugged (as I have done so myself), and <br>rarely have I seen one of these issues that was not addressed through use of <br>web-boards, rather than through examination of the bug-logs.<br><br>2)	Verant has repeatedly asked it's players to use the /feedback command to <br>give their opinion of the game and certain issues that arise.  This would <br>allow Verant to have an inclination how of the players of EverQuest feel.  <br>However, again, I feel that the feedback-logs are allowed to fill to such a <br>capacity that many feedbacks are lost without having ever been examined.<br><br>Indeed, I have often seen GW post about various issues on how he sees the <br>people who post on the web-boards as representing the minority of players.  <br>And yet, he has a very valuable tool in finding the pulse of the majority <br>that he allows to go unused, and wasted.<br><br>3)	Quite often, players have been promised to have an issue looked at either <br>in the immediate future, or by some deadline.  And Verant has quite often, <br>at the last moment, told the players that they have to be more patient, and <br>wait for a further deadline.  Examples of this include Alchemy and Poison.<br><br>4)	Because of the small staff that Verant maintains, they cannot properly <br>play-test things that they put into the game.  This causes repeated changes <br>for something, once it is put in, in order to balance it within the context <br>of the game.  A good example of this is Alchemy, as it has undergone three <br>major forms now (scavenged components, expensive components, and cheap <br>components).<br><br>5)	I have heard, repeatedly stated, that "A number of employees at Verant <br>have characters of level 50 or higher, and thus have an idea and give input <br>for how items go into the game."  I find this very difficult to accept, as I <br>don't think any PC shaman in the game was happy with alchemy not working, <br>nor with either of the first two systems of alchemy that were put into the <br>game.<br><br>Additionally, I saw a post from GW in the previous week where he stated that <br>his level 50+ necromancer has over 40 days played on him.  Now, he's been <br>claiming to have a level 50 necromancer for months now, and if this is true, <br>then he certainly must have had to quit him once he achieved level 50.  My <br>shaman, at level 44, has somewhere in the area of 42 days on him.  <br>Therefore, it is my contention that while many Verant employees may have <br>level 50+ characters&#8230;.they might have not been leveled up in the same manner <br>as the PC's have had to do.<br><br><br>	Another area of great contention and excuse is that of Customer Service.  <br>Here, Verant has brought forth some very flimsy excuses to cover existing <br>problems within their CS program.<br><br>Examples of this:<br><br>1)	Because of the possibility of lying on the part of the Customer, who may <br>indeed have a very legitimate claim, Verant has instructed it's Guides and <br>GM's to automatically assume that the customer is lying UNLESS that customer <br>can prove otherwise.  Their reasoning is that they suspect many people would <br>attempt to get free items or xp-resurrections if they did not take this <br>attitude.  When given the decision between allowing the players to abuse the <br>system (I/e with false claims) or allowing the system to abuse the players <br>(I/e assume they are lying), Verant has chosen the latter course.  And while <br>this may indeed prevent cheating, I am also 100% certain that it will also <br>have the effect of chasing off many more customers than the former route <br>would have caused.<br><br>Also not that many important changes have been put into effect without any <br>attempt made to pole either the players involved, nor the populace in <br>general.  A recent example of this is the changes made to the Antonican <br>Dragons (Vox and Nagafen will teleport anyone of level 53 or greater who <br>engages them<br><br>2)	As noted above, Verant has the perfect way to find how players feel about <br>the game, and yet they don't use it, and simply state that "Only a minority <br>of the players make posts here, and thus are not representative of how the <br>players in general feel about the game."  A major flaw with this is that <br>many players (such as myself) are willing to allow others to speak for us on <br>the web-boards because we feel that we have little to add to their <br>statements.  Quite often, the players posting on the web do represent the <br>feelings of the game.  These are people who have talked to their peers while <br>playing EverQuest, and thus know that they will not offend their compatriots <br>with their postings.<br><br>3)	As noted above, Verant's PR people have made false promises to the <br>players.  In addition to this, there are times when the PR people make <br>strong statements, that the PC's who have wanted the change, assume will go <br>into effect soon.  And thus a promise to examine something with a strong <br>possibility for a change becomes to whichever group is affected, a definite <br>promise of the aforementioned change.<br><br>	What Verant lacks, to me, is communication.  They are in a service where <br>their customer base has wants and needs, and satisfaction is based upon <br>their ability to meet these needs and mitigate the wants in a balanced <br>manner.  By avoided making excuses, looking at a matter in a smart, <br>un-objective manner, and seeing how it would affect their player base as a <br>whole, Verant would have much fewer complaints to deal with, and given <br>enough time, might not even be viewed as the enemy that they are today.<br><br>Graack, Shaman of Xegony<br>"For Halas!  For MacLear!"

