<P>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The orcs came just as the rain season began in Faydark.  The blue-skinned creatures had long been residents of the Elven wood, occasionally stirring up trouble around the city of Kelethin, but rarely outside the boundaries of their camp.  The rain, however, drove the orcs to new levels of violence, as if the simplest exploitation of Karana&#8217;s power enflamed Cazic-Thule&#8217;s malice within their twisted souls.  Such outbreaks of violence were quickly stamped out by the Kelethin legionnaires and were rarely much cause for alarm.  This time, however, the rains had come to Faydwer early, just as a legion of the Crushbone Orcs were returning from an excursion along the northern coast.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; As usual, the berserk rage poured down upon the orcs as swiftly as the falling rain.  Blinded by this rage, the savage creatures swarmed south in search of their instinctive target &#8211; Kelethin.  But there was a great deal of territory between the coat and the treetop city and the orcs predictably blundered their way into further mischief.  Like a cloud of locusts, the Crushbone Orcs descended into a farmland valley owned by a gentle wood elf named Larwyn Aislein.  <BR><BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Daylan Aislein hunkered down low, examining the ground closely where his sharp, sea green eyes had picked out an animal track.  Lowering his face to the spring moss, he took a tentative sniff, causing a lock of auburn hair to fall across his eyes.  Grimacing with annoyance, Daylan flipped the offending lock back, firmly reminding himself that he needed to get it trimmed.  <I>Such things can wait,</I> Daylan conceded, taking another sniff at the minute depression in the moss.  Sure enough, he detected the telltale scent of a wolf.  His father had been right; the packs had returned to take advantage of the hole in the south pasture&#8217;s fence, where they could gain easy access to the chicken pens.  Well, that wouldn&#8217;t last for much longer.  Not only would he patch the fence, but also Daylan intended on making an example of the interloped.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Adjusting his quiver more securely onto his back, Daylan stood and head east in pursuit of the four-legged bandit.  His family had struggled long and hard to establish a foothold in the untamed wilderness of northern Faydwer, and they were not about to let the wilderness take it back.  Not while he was such a skilled archer, at least.  At the thought of his weapon of choice, Daylan raised his right hand to examine the bow his father had presented him two months earlier.  It was only a simple hunting bow, nothing like the elaborate long bow his father had kept from his days as one of Faydark&#8217;s Champions.  Still, it was Daylan&#8217;s most prized possession and he had practiced long and hard with it every day.  Now he could best even his father in an archery match. <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The wolf&#8217;s trail was still fresh, indicating that it had only just left the pasture when Daylan had passed on his patrol.  It was also moving in a straight line, so the wolf had no idea it was being tracked.  Daylan wanted it to stay this way, making his job that much easier.  He wetted a finger and raised it to test the wind direction, nodding with satisfaction when he discovered he was downwind from the wolf.  <I>I can smell you, but you won&#8217;t smell me until it&#8217;s too late.  Just the way I like it.</I><BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The ground several feet in front of him descended into a shallow chasm were a broad river had once cut across Faydwer from the Ocean of Tears to the Timorous Deep.  The river had long since dried up and the flora had reclaimed its territory, leaving a jagged scar across the eastern coast of Faydwer.  Instinct told Daylan that he should be cautious coming over the rise.  The elevated banks would serve as a blind against the wolf&#8217;s scent and the animal would have the added bonus of being able to see the hunter before he could fire off a shot.  With these thoughts in mind, Daylan lowered himself onto his stomach and slithered up to the crest.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; And there it was.  The silver furred wolf was lying in the riverbed, licking its forepaws contentedly.  There was blood on those paws, and Daylan realized that at least one of his father&#8217;s chickens had met its fate at the claws of this savage beast.  He aimed to make certain the wold didn&#8217;t kill again.  Notching an arrow to his bow, Daylan carefully took aim at the beast&#8217;s forehead, aiming slightly above the kill mark between its eyes to compensate for the arrow&#8217;s natural drop.  He breathed a soft prayer to Tunare as he created tension on the string and &#8211; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The wind shifted.  Even as Daylan was muttering an even softer curse, the wolf&#8217;s head shot up.  The young wood elf immediately tensed himself up for the inevitable attack, wondering if he would be able to draw his dagger before the wolf tore out his throat.  Then the smell caressed his nostrils, the foul stench that was overpowering his own scent from the wolf: Smoke.  Something in Faydark was burning, and fire was never a good thing among trees.  The wolf knew it too, and off it pelted, away from the smoke.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; To the east.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Which meant that the fire was in the west.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; In the direction of Daylan&#8217;s home.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Daylan leapt to his feet and dashed back along the wolf trail, his heart pounding with dread.  The smell of smoke grew stronger as he neared the south pasture, confirming his fears of the worst.  Without slowing, Daylan vaulted over the fence and continued running, his ears detecting the crackle of flames before his eyes saw them.  Daylan came to an abrupt halt, shocked at the sight of his house, consumed in a raging inferno.  The chickens were running amok through the field and from the corner of his eye, Daylan could see the splintered remains of their little house.  But he didn&#8217;t see and sign of the villains who had caused this madness, nor of his family.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Father!&#8221; Daylan shouted, his gaze darting about the field wildly as he approached the flames apprehensively, afraid he would find his family&#8217;s charred remain near the house.  &#8220;Mother!&#8221;  Thick storm clouds began to fill the mid-afternoon sky, casting a surrealistic pallor over the farm.  A sudden gust of wind blew Daylan&#8217;s rebellious forelock back across his eyes.  The young elf shuddered.  This whole situation seemed bizarre, for Daylan couldn&#8217;t comprehend anyone invoking such a vicious act upon his family.  During his entire life, the only enemies he had encountered had been wolves, who were far from capable of causing this sort of chaos.  His father had not been part of the Champions for over thirty years, and he hadn&#8217;t left any enemies behind in his passing.  He didn&#8217;t think that a complete stranger could so callously destroy all they had struggled to obtain.  &#8220;Father!&#8221; The young elf&#8217;s cries went unanswered, save for a wet snuffling sound, much like that of a pig feeding from a trough.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; But the perpetrators of this destruction weren&#8217;t harmless pigs.  A hulking creature suddenly materialized aside the burning wreckage, the flames causing its blood red eyes to gleam maliciously.  The creature made its snuffling noise again, which Daylan recognized as its laughter.  The creature was laughing at the outmatched elf that had stumbled into its trap, as blindly as a moth would be drawn into a flame.  Numb with fright, Daylan could only watch the creature&#8217;s advancement, his eyes growing larger as the creature loomed closer, allowing the elf to see the peculiar emblem on the creature&#8217;s gray tunic, the rippling muscles protruding from its blue flesh, and its razor sharp teeth.  It all added up to one possible conclusion : He was going to die, and the creature was going to make his death prolonged and painful.  Daylan squeezed his eyes shut and fervently prayed for Tunare to have mercy on him after the creature ripped him to shreds.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <I>THWACK!</I><BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Daylan&#8217;s eyes sprang open at the familiar sound of an arrow striking home.  The creature stood before him with a barbed arrow jutting from its throat.  Directly behind it stood Daylan&#8217;s father, Larwyn, lowering his longbow to regard his son warmly.  A wicked looking gash dribbled blood into his right eye, but otherwise he seemed to have born the invasion well.  The Elven ranger strode toward his son, giving the slain creature a swift kick in passing, as if to assure himself it was truly dead.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Larwyn strung his bow across his back so he could place both his hands upon Daylan&#8217;s shoulders.  &#8220;Are you all right?&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Daylan nodded, his mind whirling with shock. &#8220;I tracked the wolf, but I didn&#8217;t have time to kill it.&#8221;  It seemed like a foolish thing to say in light of the circumstances at hands, but Larwyn nodded with understanding. <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Another time then,&#8221; he murmured, his quiet voice accentuated by a sudden clap of thunder.  The elf stared up into the overcast sky pensively, then frowned at Daylan.  &#8220;This isn&#8217;t good.  It&#8217;s going to rain.&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Karana is weeping for our tragedy,&#8221; Daylan observed sagely.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Karana will weep us into our graves!  Run, lad!&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Larwyn&#8217;s barked command so startled Daylan that he spun around in confusion.  &#8220;Run?  But to where?&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Anywhere but here!  The orcs will be drawn to this fire like moths once the rain starts to fall!  Hurry, go find your mother!&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Orcs?&#8221; Daylan repeated wonderingly.  His curiosity overrode the urgency of the situation and he gaped down at the corpse.  His father had often entertained him with tales of his deeds as a ranger, back when Faydark&#8217;s Champions had waged war against the twisted spawn of Cazic-Thule, the Lord  of Fear.  It was told that the orcs had a fortress in Faydwer, somewhere along the northern ridge of the Steamfont Mountains.  Twin bonfires, giving it the appearance of an orc awaiting its prey with a gaping maw and burning eyes flanked the entrance to this fortress.  Now that Daylan had finally seen one of the creatures, he was inclined to believe that story, along with all the others that spoke of the orcs&#8217; violent nature.  It was no mystery as to why the orcs would be drawn to the flames; the fire reminded them of the protection offered by their feared stronghold.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Yes, and from the Crushbone clan as well, though what they&#8217;re doing this far into Faydark is beyond me.  I haven&#8217;t seen their ugly hides since I was a ranger with the Champions.&#8221; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Daylan inspected the emblem on the orc&#8217;s tunic.  It was a three-clawed hand gripping a femur so tightly that the bone had shattered.  The intricate design bothered Daylan, as it hinted that what he had taken for a mindless creature possessed some disturbing inklings of intelligence.  Then again, perhaps it was only their foul god&#8217;s grip on them that gave the orcs such a manipulative hold on fear. <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;What are you still doing here, Daylan?&#8221; Larwyn suddenly snapped, startling his son.  &#8220;I told you to go find your mother!&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Realizing the urgency of the situation, Daylan leapt to his feet.  But before he bolted off, he locked eyes with his father.  &#8220;What are you going to do?&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Larwyn readied his bow and regarded his son with a grim expression. &#8220;Take as many of them down as I can.&#8221;  <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <I>Before what?</I> Daylan thought, but he kept silent.  Such a question was not meant to be ventured before a battle, especially one against overwhelming odds.  <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The young elf ran into the north pasture to seek out his mother, notching an arrow to his own bow as he went.  He tried to convince himself that he had done this in order to slay the first orc who crossed his path, but in the end he had to admit his nervousness.  In truth, his small arrows would only serve to annoy the brutes before they ripped his head from his neck.  The entire scene seemed designed to induce paranoia, as well.  The approaching storm had darkened the afternoon sky, leaving the pasture faintly illuminated by the raging inferno of the Aislein home.  This light was marginal, and it was enough to confound Daylan&#8217;s infrared vision, leaving him almost blind as he floundered about the pasture.  The speckles of blood and the crumpled corpse of a lamb gave testament to the orc&#8217;s activity in this sector.  For a moment, Daylan paused and stared into the animal&#8217;s empty eyes, stunned by the savage violence performed upon it.  Its head had been wrenched around to gaze at the elf behind it.  The orcs had even taken the brutal murder a step further, ripping the lamb&#8217;s stomach open and spilling its entrails across the grass.  Pushing his revulsion aside, Daylan stepped over the corpse and continued north.  The firelight elongated his shadow into a surrealistic specter that danced before him in a herky-jerky rhythm. <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; His mother&#8217;s vegetable garden seemed more sinister now, though whether that impression was gleaned from his shadow&#8217;s eerie dance across the soil, the oppressive darkness, or the lamb and chicken corpses strewn among the rows of cabbages, Daylan wasn&#8217;t sure.  Vanessa Aislein wasn&#8217;t there, however, though she had left tracks leading away &#8211; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Daylan paused and squatted to examine the puzzling impressions in the soil, knowing they would reveal the answer to his mother&#8217;s location.  Before a freshly planted row of turnips &#8211; Vanessa&#8217;s current project &#8211; the shallow gouges caused by his mother&#8217;s knees abruptly ended.  Daylan deduced that she had immediately dropped her labor once she had seen the house erupt in flames, just as Daylan had abandoned his hunt when he had smelled the smoke.  Her shallow footprints led towards the house briefly, but then made a sharp turn away, diving into the surrounding forest.  Closely following Vanessa&#8217;s retreat were deeper impressions, a four-clawed mark which Daylan hesitantly identified as an orc print.  Vanessa had been moving fast, her fear giving her flight, but the orc&#8217;s long strides had easily carried him within attacking distance.  There was more blood on the ground just outside the tree line and a peculiar mixture of chicken feathers had fallen amidst the droplets of bright red fluid.  A discarded carcass of the feathers&#8217; owner caused Daylan to form an odd picture in his mind.  Had the malicious Crushbone Orc been hurling <I>chickens</I> at his mother, tearing gashes in her arms?  Daylan considered that to be a pointless exercise and was about to dismiss this absurd possibility &#8211; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Then he saw the other orc tracks, and he realized something new about his enemies : They hunted by the scent of blood and the chicken attacks were driving them into a frenzy.  There were now <I>five</I> sets of orc prints trailing his mother, and the blood was beginning to fall at a more alarming rate.  His heart pounding in his throat, Daylan followed the trail further into Faydark, his infravision slowly returning now that the flames were far behind.  Just as he was began walking beneath the dense foliage, he felt a pitter-patter of rain droplets upon his head.  The onset of the storm caused the young elf to reflect upon his father&#8217;s perplexing words.  He was running out of time.  Once the orcs began to head toward the flames, the trail would become hopelessly muddled, making it impossible for him to track his mother.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Just then, a familiar snuffling sound attracted his attention.  Withholding the urge to panic, Daylan dove into a nearby bush, holding perfectly still to camouflage his presence.  As soon as he was settled, the five orcs came lumbering out of the trees, snorting and pounding one another upon the back, congratulating each other on some marvelous deed.  Their blood red eyes were glowing wit a malicious form of energy and Daylan shuddered unconsciously wen an orc glowered in his direction.  He had a new reason to fear these grotesque creatures now.  He had been disgusted by their actions earlier, just as he would have been had he stumbled upon the carnage left by a pack of wolves.  But now that he saw that they were sentient creatures, he was filled with rage.  Not only did they realize they were committing heinous crimes against the peaceful farmers, but they were actually enjoying it!  Yet, even this newest realization didn&#8217;t prepare him for the orc&#8217;s reaction when they emerged from the thick canopy and felt the rain beating down upon them.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The orcs went berserk.  As one, the foul creatures raised their faces to the sky and began to howl.  It was a cry of defiance raised towards Karana for sending the offensive precipitation.  Their battle cry sounded, the pack darted out into the downpour, heading directly towards the still-burning farmhouse.  For a brief instant, Daylan considered unloading his arrow into one of the orcs&#8217; backs to distract them from his father, but he decided it would be unwise to incur the wrath of the Crushbone pack.  He was not particularly proud of his decision since in emphasized his terror of the orcs, but he firmly reminded himself that his father was a ranger.  Larwyn could take care of himself without his son running the risk of getting killed.  Besides, Daylan had his own assignment, though he had a dreadful suspicion as to what he would find in the depths of Faydark.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The rain could not penetrate the thick canopy, but the rhythmic drumming high above enhanced the eerie feeling within Daylan&#8217;s spirit.  He separated himself from the surrounding foliage and cautiously maneuvered over the where the orcs had come from, fearful that the slightest noise would bring a horde of orcs crashing down upon him.  Despite his caution, it only took a few seconds for him to backtrack the orcs&#8217; trail and discoverer the scene of horror they had left behind.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Vanessa Aislein was nailed into the bark of a wide oak tree, her arms and legs splayed like a fur hanging on a wall.  Her mouth was gaping open, forever frozen in the scream of terror she had emitted before the orcs had administered their final torture.  They had casually slit her open from navel to throat and emptied her intestines upon the ground.  The organs had then been trampled, possibly while their screaming owner watched helplessly.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Daylan stared at the scene before him in hopeless horror for a long moment.  Then, slowly, steadily, his disbelief gave way to a raw, unharnessed rage.  His vision dulled into a red-tinted landscape and an animal growl emerged from his throat as he whirled around to track his foes.  He had no more fear for the sick, twisted monsters who had done this, only an urge to find them and tear them apart as callously as they had done his mother.  The rage was far beyond anything he had ever felt towards the vermin who had harassed their farm.  There was no animal instinct involved in his mother&#8217;s death, only a lust for cruelty.  Daylan wanted to give them their cruelty back, in full.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Mother Tunare,&#8221; he snarled devoutly, &#8220;forgive me for this anger, but give me strength to vanquish these murderers!&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; In response, the sky flashed and rumbled as the storm broke over the farm.<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Though he knew the orcs had gained a substantial lead on him, Daylan managed to catch up with the monsters.  The five orcs were still charging towards the fire, their eyes intent on Larwyn taking aim before them, heedless of the danger approaching from behind.  Suddenly, one of the orcs grunted and stumbled, an arrow protruding from its shoulder blades.  The arrows were designed to take down small woodland creatures, not thick-boned monsters, so the orc was considerably more surprised than injured.  While the other four continued their relentless charge, the marked orc paused to dislodge the arrow from its back.  As a result, it was standing perfectly still when Daylan delivered a flying kick, driving the arrow deep into the orc&#8217;s spine and shoving the monster onto its face.  Now that injury had been added to insult, the Crushbone Orc clambered to his feet, eager to break the annoying wood elf in two.  <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; But the burly orc was no match for Daylan&#8217;s fury.  Before the startled monster could launch an attack of its own, Daylan slammed a right cross into its bony jaw, shattering it.  A kick to the stomach doubled the monster over, allowing Daylan to bring his joined hands down upon its neck and, as the orc fell, drive a knee into its face, shoving its snout back into its brain.  The orc flopped to the ground and died with a groan.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; By now, the other four had realized that something had gone horribly wrong, but it was far too late to stop their charge now as they were in range of Larwyn&#8217;s longbow.  An arrow in its right eye promptly dropped the lead orc, while the second took the point right in its skull.  The last two seemed hesitant to continue up the hill towards the master archer, but they were just as reluctant to face the raging elf behind them.  But the rain continued to fall, overriding their life-preserving thoughts of surrender.  Of the two left, the bulkier orc whirled around and charged towards Daylan.  Larwyn&#8217;s hastily fired arrow bounced harmlessly off the thick armor concealed beneath the remaining orc&#8217;s tunic and the monster quickly closed the distance between them.  Unimpressed, Larwyn drew his short sword and ran the monster through.  As for the other, once it was in range, Daylan punched it in the throat.  The blow collapsed the orc&#8217;s windpipe, reducing the orc to a whimpering, choking beast.  It writhed on the ground in agony, tears forming at the corners of its red eyes.  Then it lay still, dead.  <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Larwyn&#8217;s orc slid off the steel blade and plopped on the ground, its eyes scowling at the gaping wound in its chest.  Larwyn leveled his sword at the orc&#8217;s throat. &#8220;Why?&#8221; the elf demanded. &#8220;Why did you do this?&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;  The orc&#8217;s eyes rolled back into its head and its skull cracked against the ground.  &#8220;Hail Emperor Crush,&#8221; it muttered in a gravelly voice.  And then it died.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Larwyn shook his head and knelt beside the corpse, wiping his blade on its tunic.  When the sword was clean, he looked up at Daylan, squinting his eyes to see his son through the rain.  &#8220;Vanessa&#8217;s dead, isn&#8217;t she?&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The thunder rumbled as Daylan nodded grimly. &#8220;It&#8217;s not a very pretty sight.&#8221; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Orc mutilations rarely are,&#8221; the elf murmured, closing his eyes to ward off the pain. &#8220;I tried to spare her this.  That&#8217;s why I resigned from Faydark&#8217;s Champions so long ago.&#8221; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;This atrocity can not be allowed to pass without retaliation!&#8221; Daylan cried, crossing to where his father knelt.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Larwyn regarded him evenly. &#8220;And what would you suggest we do about the Crushbone Orcs to repay them?&#8221;  <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Destroy them!&#8221; Daylan snarled vengefully. &#8220;Find this Emperor Crush and slay him for his vile nature!&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;That&#8217;s not a wise idea, Daylan.  Not even the entire legion of Faydark&#8217;s Champions were to assault the Crushbone fortress.  I doubt the two of us would stand much of a chance.  Besides. . . I can&#8217;t go with you.&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;What?  Why not?&#8221; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Larwyn shook his head, saddened by Daylan&#8217;s brashness, a tragic circumstance caused by his youthfulness. &#8220;My life is <I>here</I>, Daylan,&#8221; he explained patiently. &#8220;I&#8217;ve passed my fifth century, and I&#8217;m too old to go adventuring through Faydwer again.  I&#8217;m too old to even start my life over.  I&#8217;m far too old to wage war against Crushbone.&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Then I&#8217;ll go alone!&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;And get killed without doing any significant damage to the orc population.  You handled those two fairly easily, but you had the element of surprise of your side and that berserk rage of yours can&#8217;t last forever.&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Daylan opened his mouth to argue, but he had to admit that he felt weary now that the battle was over.  A grim picture flashed into his mind, one in which he was slumped to the ground, exhausted after an intense battle in the orc camp, only to have twelve more swarm over him and systematically beat him into the ground.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Then there&#8217;s nothing we can do,&#8221; Daylan concluded glumly.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Now I didn&#8217;t say that, Daylan.  There&#8217;s always something you can do.&#8221;  Larwyn rose from the ground and walked over to the burning remains of their home.  Though the rain was still falling, the fire was still raging. &#8220;The Crushbone Orcs are like this fire, son.  It has been burning for so long and so hot that a simple rain shower can not put it out.&#8221;  He smiled at Daylan. &#8220;On your own, son, you would only be a light drizzle upon the orcs&#8217; blaze.  You either need to find more water or &#8211;&#8221; Larwyn raised his hand and stretched it towards the flames. &#8220;&#8211; or become a more effective extinguisher.&#8221; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Daylan felt the hair on the back of his neck rise as a peculiar tingling washed over him.  A soft rumbling began beneath his feet, closely followed by a minute eruption from behind the house.  As Daylan watched in shock, a patch of earth rose up and flopped over the house, extinguishing the flames in a heartbeat.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;How. . ?&#8221; Daylan began, but his voice trailed off when his father pivoted to face him.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;You will journey south, to Kelethin.  You will join Faydark&#8217;s Champions and become a ranger.  You will become one with nature and learn how to employ it in your fight against Crushbone.&#8221;	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Kelethin?  But I&#8217;ve never &#8211;&#8221;  <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Seek out Eldin Trueshot.  He is the leader of Faydark&#8217;s Champions and an old friend of mine.  He will welcome you into the guild and train you as if you were his own son.&#8221; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Yes, Father,&#8221; Daylan agreed reluctantly, bowing his head in submission. &#8220;I&#8217;m ready to go.&#8221; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &#8220;Then go.  Follow the road to Kelethin, and follow your heart beyond.&#8221; <BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; This last bit of wisdom imparted, Larwyn sank to the ground to watch the cooling embers.  Daylan stood there a moment longer, searching for something to tell his defeated father.  Discovering nothing but a profound heartache, the young wood elf sighed heavily and set out for Kelethin, in the southern edge of the Greater Faydark.	<BR>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Daylan Aislein was only nineteen years old.  

