<P>
One very fascinating aspect about writing opinionated editorials such as this one is the amazingly broad spectrum of responses you get from the readership.  One person can read an article about fly fishing and walk away thinking it was about how to tie bait to a hook, while another person can read the same piece and walk away thinking it was about boat and water safety as you fish on a lake.  While both may be essentially correct, neither is accurate.<P>Similarly, some people can read an editorial about customer service at Verant and walk away thinking it was nothing more than a well-phrased justification for poor quality, while other people can read the same editorial and walk away thinking it was a flame on Verant's inability to live up to unreasonable expectations.  I received responses from readers who were convinced I was squarely on "Verant's side," and others who saw my editorial as a blatant attack on Verant.  It just goes to show how true the old axiom is that says people will see what they want to see.  <P>(As evidence of this, I even received one very amusing letter from an individual who accused me of being Abashi himself.  I'm sorry, but the patience of Job is not a virtue I possess.  If I had Abashi's job, I'd probably be fired within a cool 24 hours.)<P>The truth is, I'm not on anybody's side.  The Bottom Line details the situation as I see it, and that's the long and the short of it.  There were some points that cut Verant several yards of slack and other points that left no room for excuses.  Like most things, it's not a black and white issue.<P>As usual, such circumstances inspire some very contemplative individuals to voice their own take on the matter.  Beyond the very positive comments I received in the message board thread (thanks a bunch to everyone who posted!), I did receive two e-mail responses I felt warranted some comment.  Both are well-written and made for enjoyable reading.<P>Our first one is from a gentleman named Fred who thought it proper to defend Verant against some of the more negative points...<P>----------<P><FONT COLOR="0000AA">You have no idea what it's like running a company that has to deal with the public <BR>at large. When 99.5% of your customers are satisfied. Unfortunately, it's the .5% <BR> that are the vocal minority. They are the ones who post on all the boards, whining <BR> because "it's unfair." And as in real life, it's always the outspoken minority who is <BR>heard, and not the satisfied majority.</FONT><P>Of that, I have no doubt.  However, don't presume I have no idea what it's like running such an institution.  I worked as one of six (yes, <U>six</U>) technical support representatives at a multi-national software development company whose latest product release was ungodly at best, and 99.5% of the customers were irate.  Can we say "Class Action Lawsuit?"  I think we can...<P><I>"And thank you so much for bringing up such unpleasant memories.  While <BR>you're at it, why don't you give me a paper cut and pour lemon juice on it?"</I><P>- Miracle Max, The Princess Bride<P><FONT COLOR="0000AA">I laugh when people say that Verant "doesn't care about their customers." To <BR>believe that is foolish and naive. Everything that they do is geared towards making <BR>the MAJORITY of the customers happy. You can't please everyone when there <BR>are 250,000 people involved in the same small universe. <P></FONT>I'm glad you concur with at least one point from the article.<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>And no one, no one, I don't care if you run one of the main EQ webpages, has an <BR>ear to even 1% of the customer base. <P>I sympathize with Verant. It's people like yourself and those silly board posters <BR>who bitch and moan and attack the company that are the root of the most of the <BR> dissatisfaction. When you take your visible position and attack something, people <BR>automatically think that you are right, and Verant is completely out to "screw" <BR>people.<P></FONT>Me?   What did I do?  I pointed out several key issues that have been the subject of player ranting of late - leaving many unmentioned, by the way.  I never said that I agreed with them or endorsed player arguments.  In fact, I defended Verant's seemingly callous attitude, citing the very same reasons you mentioned above where you shared with us what makes you laugh.  <FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>Of course, you realize that with 250,000 people subscribewd, they can't just <BR>arbitraily make changes to the fundamental game. They have to carefully weigh <BR>what they do. Fact: every time they adjust something, something else in the game <BR>goes wrong. There is an awful lot that is interdependant. They can't just rush in <BR>and change something without careful planning and testing. And just imagine how <BR>long their list of "fine-tuning is." It must be immense. And every siungle issue <BR>must be addressed in regards to class and game balance, and even how it will <BR>affect the underlying code. <P></FONT>I agree.  Such matters should be addressed with care and foresight.  To do otherwise is reckless and invites no end of trouble.<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>And, if someone whines loud enough, and they do respond by saying something <BR>like, "it's on the table," everyone assumes that it will be ready tommorrow, and <BR>when it's not, they holler louder, that "Verant is out to screw them again." I can't <BR>imagine having Gordon or Brad's job. Protected by the anonymity of the internet <BR>makes people truly rotten. If a customer acted liek that in real life to a company <BR>rep, the company would simply stop doing business with them. <P></FONT>It depends on the company.  Such generalizations are rarely true.<P>You're right about one thing, though.  The relative safety of the Internet does open the door to see people at their worst.  I sometimes wonder what would happen if half the things said in my reader response e-mails were spoken to me face-to-face.<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>And regarding the test server. It is unfortunate that the characters were wiped. Yes, <BR>it stated that at the OPENING page of the server, but still, these people contributed <BR>their time to test bugs and improvements/patches for everyone else, especially the<BR>whiners. I'd put good money that the majority of the players on the test server were <BR>altrusistic and intelligent. That being said, I agree that it may have been a little <BR>extreme "wiping the characters," but it doesn seem like Verant is retracting that <BR>stance and at least reinstating the players if not the items. Lesson learned, <BR>problem solved.<P></FONT>The Test Server is an island unto itself, both in playing EverQuest and in its administration.  I, too, am ranked among those players who were hit by the item wipe, but at least I knew the score when I created those characters.  There were many players (particularly since the opening of Kunark) who were not entirely aware of the situation on Test, and were consequently caught flat-footed when they discovered the truth of things.  Whether or not it was their own fault, it's still regrettable.  Personally, I think mistakes were made on both sides of this issue.  <FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>In conclusion, no one, not the webpages, nor Verant themselves, makes anyone <BR>play/buy Everquest. It's a product like anything else. If people are dissatisfied, then <BR>they are welcome to stop paying $9.89 a month, and move on. But I personally get<BR>exasperated when I hear or read reactionary, inflammatory material. People never <BR>see the forest for the trees in this case. <P></FONT>What you call inflammatory, many people call constructive criticism.  You seem to resent my latest contribution to the EverQuest community, but going over it, I find nothing that could be seen as anything but forthright and patently honest.  My candor may collide with your own opinion, but like Verant, I'm not out to satisfy the outspoken minority.<P>I'm not even out to satisfy the silent majority, for that matter...<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>&lt;sigh&gt; Anyway, I am a satisfied customer. I play EQ as a light hobby, and <BR>have a very good job, a great life, a wife, and a hopping social life. Maybe that <BR>gives me a different perspective than much of the customer base. Or, perhaps that <BR>is inaccurate. A better perspective than the WHINING customer base, as I in no <BR>way shape or form am privvy to the thoughts and feelings of a quarter million <BR>people. Oh wait- but then how are those handful of professional complainers any <BR>more knowledgable than me?<BR>Hmmm.....  <P></FONT>That's not for me to say, but reducing "much of the customer base" to a group of whining, social recluses is not a good way of getting your point across.  People complain when something contrary to their enlightened self-interest takes place - it has always been that way, and it always will be.  Validity takes a backstage stance to all else under such conditions where people have free reign to speak their minds.<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>For the record, Shadoe, please don't see this as ire directed completely at you. You <BR>are just as entitled to your feelings as I am. <BR><P></FONT>Why, thank you.<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>Oh yeah, re: "capitalism at iits finest." Capitalism is competition in a free market <BR>place. Verant "not caring" is not "capitalism at its finest." Capitalism at its finest <BR>would be several companies like Verant competing for the same consumer dollar. <BR>The only other kid on the block right now is Ultima Online, which isn't really <BR>competiton in the sense that it's not as active a member in the "MMRPG" <BR>community anymore. You're talking about a "monopoly." <P></FONT>One... I never said Verant didn't care.  On the contrary, I said they <I>do</I> care about their players as a community, <I>questioning</I> whether they cared for them as individuals, or even if they should.<P>Two... When did I say Verant not caring would be capitalism at its finest?  For those like you who missed it, I'll summarize: It's the freedom of the consumer to cancel his (or her) account that is capitalism at its finest.  It's increased competition that will make the bottom line serve the online gamer.  I suggest reading that part again, sir, because I simply can't fathom how any other message could come out of those two paragraphs.<P>And, no, Verant does not hold a monopoly.  The market is just very narrow at the moment.  Besides, this is <I>entertainment</I>.  People will pay for it so long as it serves their purposes to do so.  This being the case, a monopoly in this regard would really be bordering on futility.<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>Anyway, I appreciate and respect the fact that you aren't afraid to express your <BR>opinions Shadoe. <P> See you around, <BR>Fred</FONT><P>----------<P>Great Marr in a bottle... If I were shy about expressing my opinions, I'd have no right being a columnist.  Thanks for sharing your point of view, Fred!<P>Moving on to our second reader response, we'll take a closer look at a couple of the more specific issues I mentioned in the article...<P>----------<P><FONT COLOR="0000AA">Shadoe,<P>Excellent article.  I know I haven't been playing as long as you have, but<BR>I've seen the number of complaints increase in the few months that I've been<BR>here.  You can't deny it either; it really affects your opinion of the game.<BR>Even though many of these complaints are unfounded, it really skews your<BR>impression after enough time reading them.  The best thing I've done lately<BR>with regard to EQ is deciding to stop reading the message boards.  Sure, there<BR>are several valid complaints on the boards, but they're buried beneath<BR>thousands of whines and rants and *bump*s.  The sheer amounts of name <BR>calling and personal attacks on the official board makes me sick...but I digress.<P>Everquest has its problems.  It has bugs, and it will always have bugs.  It's<BR>a computer game.  Vampire will have bugs, and so will Neverwinter Nights.<BR><P></FONT>Eh, bugs are bugs.  No matter how we try to disavow such things, computers will always be riddled with them.  The real question is, will the bugs in Vampire and NeverWinter be duly fixed as they arise, or will it follow the same path Origin and Verant have adhered to in the past?... "We don't have time to fix this bug, so anyone found exploiting it will be banned."  Of course, with DMs in charge of their respective worlds, that complicates matters a bit.<P>(Okay, so it's a non-issue.  Sue me!)<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>Now, I'm not saying that that's fine; not by any means.  Verant does seem to<BR>have a nack for creating more problems than they fix.  Everquest's biggest<BR>problem, though, is it's player base.  There are 250,000 people here, and 90%<BR>of them expect preferential treatment.  It's just not goint to happen.<BR>There's no way it /can/ happen.  But people complain anyway.  And complain,<BR>and complain, and complain.<P>One problem that I really have is the complaints about Verant's 'Vision(tm)'.<BR>It rears it's ugly head in every complaint.  But I, for one, am glad that<BR>Verant has a vision of the game.  How is this any different than having a DM<BR>with a set of rules for your pen and paper campaign?  <P></FONT>It's different in the sense that a Dungeon Master's game session is a privatized arena.  I've been playing pencil and paper roleplaying games since childhood, and I've yet to see a DM charge his players admission (though I've heard about the unusual, tournament-style occasions that could technically serve as exceptions).  Quite literally, if a DM laid down a set of ground rules the players didn't like (or worse, <I>changed </I>the rules when they became inconvenient), he'd be playing the game alone.  Though commercially the same rules do apply, it's really an apples-to-oranges comparison when measured against massively multiplayer gaming.  Verant is a multimillion dollar company; Dungeon Masters are a dime a dozen.<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>Their vision dictates virtually every aspect of the game, which is /definitely/ a <BR>good thing.  Imagine the complaints if Verant hadn't given thought to their <BR>perception of their game?  Their 'Vision(tm)' is a good thing, as it allows for some<BR>understanding on their stance on many issues.<P></FONT>Allow me to play devil's advocate here, and argue the point that if Verant's Vision(tm) were as you say, then there would be nothing to take issue with.  Normally such a vision is defined in a few simple, definitive sentences.  Yet Verant has as much as admitted that their Vision(tm) is a conglomerate of mixed opinions of their team.  Such a nebulous definition leads into territories that smack to me as being greatly hypothetical in nature.  When you take any kind of foundational meaning out of your vision, what's left but a device that you can dig up every time you make an administrative judgment call?  Basically what such a vision says is "We'll do what we think is best at any and all times, end of story."<P>While that may be a valid statement when it comes to Verant's liberties with their product, it certainly isn't visionary.  I contend that Verant, in fact, has no substantial vision beyond that of their quaintly trademarked title.<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>Dont' get me wrong, I don't necessarily like the idea of paying a monthly fee<BR>to have someone tell me how the game is supposed to be played.  But it /is/<BR>their game.  If I don't like that fact, I am free to cancel my account at any<BR>time.  But, quite honestly, I don't mind it.  (And I for one would /hate/ to<BR>go to the Bahamas, but that's another story. :)  I certainly enjoy the<BR>prospect of Neverwinter Nights.  Vampire doesn't appeal to me because of the<BR>setting, but Neverwinter Nights is definitely something that I'm going to look<BR>into.  In fact, I'd love to see what you could do with a NWN server.<BR><P></FONT>As would I.  It has incredible potential.  We'll see if the folks at Bioware have what it takes to pull it off.<FONT COLOR="0000AA"><P>I agree with you about the roleplaying.  I've only been playing for a few<BR>months, but I know I wouldn't be here any more if I hadn't been roleplaying my<BR>characters.  Fighting in Everquest is /boring/ to me, and I don't see how<BR>others could do nothing but fight.  But that's my opinion, and I'm entitled to<BR>think that way.  If you want to do nothing but fight, then you are definitely<BR>free to do so, just as I'm entitled to sit around in a bar with my goblet of<BR>wine.<P>Anyway, this email has become long-winded.  Again, great article.  It's always<BR>good to step back and look at these issues from a broader perspective.  It's<BR>just unfortunate that a large percentage of the player base seems to be unable<BR>to do the same.<P>Tween</FONT><P>----------<P>Though marginal to the topic at large, I have been looking for an excuse to voice my opinions along those lines.  Thanks for giving me the opportunity, Tween!<P>That about sums it up for this edition of Shadoe's Corner.  Thanks again to all who read the article, and my gratitude to those who took the time to comment!<P>- &lt;Shadoe&gt;

