<a name="newsitem961380015,57564,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Quit Yer Whinin'</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Oakgrove Fallingleaf  (<a href="mailto:disneyvillain@home.com" class="credit2">disneyvillain@home.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Over the past month or so, I have read an increasing number of<br>complaints regarding the evil race factions on Kunark and how they make<br>it virtually impossible to function on the continent.  I play several<br>evil characters, and I have to say, "Shaddap and quit yer whinin."<br><br>First, I should remind those who are complaining that the game is not<br>meant to be easy - the fact that evil races can pretty much roam every<br>other continent in the game with little to no retribution is a testament<br>to the playability of the game as thought out by the production team. <br>It pleases me greatly, however, that Verant took the time to produce a<br>continent which won't let you race up to level 60 without some<br>forethought.<br><br>Second, the game is meant to be challenging for all levels.  Granted, we<br>all fall out of character from time to time as we spend endless hours<br>camping the same spawn for whatever flavor of magical candy we are after<br>that day.<br><br>In fact, I see the complexity of the factions on Kunark to be colorful<br>obstacles to be overcome by those who are the most ingenious.  Further,<br>I would not characterize Kunark as a region in which high-levels should<br>concentrate on levelling quickly - much of what is there is to provide a<br>variety of challenges rather than the ability to race through levels. <br>Moreso, I was glad to see the experience lowered for monsters of the<br>same caliber elsewhere in order to slow level advancement and<br>concentrate on the environment and thrill of the game.<br><br>Perhaps I am idealistic in this, and I am sure this will draw fire from<br>fellow high-levels who adventure to Kunark and feel they have no<br>stronghold there, but I don't think everything has to be equal between<br>races and classes.  The differences and complexities of faction and race<br>are just one more facet that makes this game truly an outstanding<br>MMORPG.<br><br>Oakgrove Fallingleaf

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem961379430,93126,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">A Word About Guides and GMs</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Oakgrove Fallingleaf  (<a href="mailto:disneyvillain@home.com" class="credit2">disneyvillain@home.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Here we go - a few words on those seemingly tireless individuals who<br>donate hundreds of hours of time to the game, field our praise and our<br>profanity, and strive to make our playing experience a little better. <br>As a former Senior Guide, I caught both sides of the act and hopefully<br>can offer some insight to dealing with these unusual individuals.<br><br>One of the first mistakes new players make is that they do not<br>distinguish between Guides and GMs.  Guides are NOT employees of Verant<br>or Sony, whereas GMs enjoy that status.  Guides are given special tools,<br>far more than Origin allowed their volunteer customer service reps, to<br>assist players.  Guides cannot, however, create any kind of item,<br>including cash, for a reimbursement; this is the realm of the GM. <br>Guides cannot reset zones or repop monsters - they can only kill stuck<br>monsters.  Guides can do several things - summon your corpse out of<br>lava, handle the initial stages of harassment or kill-stealing<br>incidents, investigate recurring bugs, resurrect you for bug-caused<br>deaths and give you basic instructions about the game.  GMs spend much<br>of their time performing tasks such as resetting zones, investigating<br>bugs, taking care of reimbursements, disciplining characters who abuse<br>the rules, and assisting with GM-run events.<br><br>The best way to reach a guide is through the petition system - it's the<br>easiest way for the Guide to track customer concerns and make sure<br>everyone is serviced.  This does not always happen in a timely manner -<br>just like any other organization, Guides are not always online.  Some<br>guides miss their shifts for real-world reasons.  It's unfortunate, but<br>some petitions can take 3 hour to get answered.  This is not the goal,<br>but staff limitations sometimes warrant this.  I received a number of<br>petitions from people who had petitioned before and received no response<br>- I always tried to make the time to ensure they were taken care of<br>properly.  This is an area in which players simply need to be patient.<br><br>I know that many players make use of the "who all GM" command and then<br>lament that no Gms/Guides are online and thus do not submit a petition. <br>You should keep in mind that about one third of the petitions received<br>are about harassment situations for which guides need to be invisible<br>and anonymous for investigation.  Thus, a Guide or GM may be online but<br>not visible to the player.<br><br>Also, I recall that a number of players have voiced complaints that<br>GMs/Guides favor specific groups on a server.  Initially, Guides have no<br>control over the server to which they are assigned, aside from<br>specifying their main play server.  No Guide may maintain a character on<br>ther server for which they guide to prevent the temptation to cheat. <br>Granted, there may be the occasional dishonest Guide, but these are<br>punished not only by removal from the Guide program but also by having<br>their accounts banned.<br><br>I hope I have addressed a number of areas in which players are unaware<br>of the roles of GMs and Guides.  This is a vast subject and I could go<br>on for much longer, but you would grow tired and might injure yourself<br>when your head smacked the keyboard.  If you have questions about the<br>Guide Program, I will be happy to answer them.  Feel free to e-mail me<br>at <a href="mailto:disneyvillain@home.com">disneyvillain@home.com</a>.<br><br>Oakgrove Fallingleaf

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
