<a name="newsitem960250451,762,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Joining a Quality Guild</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Jubal Kinseeker  (<a href="mailto:jubal@sok.org" class="credit2">jubal@sok.org</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.sok.org" class="credit2">Sterling Order of Knights</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
There is a few things that you can look at when determining what makes a 'Quality' guild. Most of these views are assuming that the guild has a website from which you can investigate. <br><br>One of the first things to look at is the management of the team. Without exceptional management, a guild will generally be it's worst enemy. Keeping control of any organization can be a difficult and daunting task that requires alot of work and determination. The management of the guild must be able to consistently handle trouble within the guild and eliminate it, or problems will only get worse. Situations often arise which need to be handled and dealt with appropriately. There should be some form of code of conduct that is in-line with what you expect from your fellow guild mates. It is also important that this is enforced. Management that is unwilling or unable to uphold their Mission Statement, or remove problem members will also be a liability. Reviewing the guild policies or charter can generally give a good indication of what kind of guild you are dealing with, assuming that they follow through with what their Charter states. <br><br>Another aspect to consider is community. Many guilds claim to be a 'family', but are they a dysfunctional one? How the members interact with one another is vital. Does the guild provide means to strengthen this community? Whether it be a chat room, message board, mailing list, or other means of communication. If the guild has a message board, browse it and read how their members interact. If the board is filled with hostility and angst, I would expect the guildchat to be similar. Is the message board unused or rarely posted on? This can also be a good indication of the sense of community in a guild. <br><br>Also consider what type of player you are, and whether you fit in with the guild you are looking into. As we all know, every guild has different priorities and objectives. Ask yourself what aspects of the game you consider enjoyable. Are you a role-player? power-gamer? a little of both? When looking, you should make sure that a guild can meet your needs as a player. <br><br>The most important aspect of a successful guild is their recruitment policies. Guilds should make sure that the guild and the player are compatible before allowing membership. I look down on guilds which offer open recruiting via public channels. Considering that you will spend your online time consistently with these people, you want to make sure that there is some kind of filtering process. Although this is somewhat related to the above paragraph in making sure that the guild offers what you need, it puts the responsibility of that determination on the guild management, where it should be. An alternative to this would be if the guilds have an open invite policy, but remove the undesirables quickly. I have found that slow recruitment often prevents members from being removed later. <br><br>A guild's reputation on a server often can give you an indication of what kind of people you are dealing with, and whether they follow through with their intentions. It is common that most players will think that their guild is the best and the greatest, but what do other people on the server think? Of course, your own personal experiences here should hold more weight then anything you have heard. <br><br>I am sure there are other things to consider when determining what makes a 'Quality' guild, but I think these are the most important. <br><br>Jubal Kinseeker<br>Guildmaster of the Sterling Order of Knights

