<P>
	Cobus and Berglad ran as fast as their legs could carry them. Their boots caught roots and were embedded in the soil as they ran. It was only their resolve that kept them upright. The Faydark was quite its namesake once the sun had fallen. Thankfully, both the elf and the dwarf had excellent vision at night. Unfortunately, though, vampires did not have true blood. Nor did they create any heat. An entire legion of them could be right in front of the pair, and they wouldn&#8217;t know it until they were upon them. <br><br>Lightning, however, causes much heat.<br><br>The sky seemed to be a thunderous storm right over what appeared to be the battlefield. Blast after blast rained down like vengeance from the Gods. Once they came closer, the warmth of fire engulfed them, as many corpses were still afire. Cobus reached the edge of a hill, and his vision portrayed a valiant sight. There moved a single druid, half flying, half running his way through a myriad of undead. In his wake stood burning corpses, blackened bones, and shattered vampires. Cobus was for a moment held admiring the abilities of his long time friend. The next moment he reminded himself that mana has limits. With that he charged in, with Berglad close behind him. <br><br>Cobus dashed into the fray, occupying several new reinforcements coming forth from the Lesser Faydark. His wakizashi parried every attack perfectly, as his angled blade of Morin tore through reanimated tissue. Zombie after zombie, ghoul after ghoul, Cobus continually felled his opponents. Berglad fought along side him, with mighty swings of his Ghoulsbane. A particularity tough zombie parried a blow with its forearm, losing it in the process. Still it fought on, landing two strong bashes at Berglad&#8217;s armor. The Ghoulsbane glowed bright blue, having unleashed heaven&#8217;s fury on the zombie. Flayed flesh was simply thrown from its hide, as the zombie was reduced to ashes. <br><br>A valiant call had risen from his heart. &#8220;For Brell Serilis!!&#8221;, shouted Berglad as his blade divided a ghoul into two.<br><br>Cobus had just dispatched a skeleton when another, armed with dual axes, launched toward him. Cobus was barely able to parry the flying attack as the axes came in for dual strikes. Cobus did what he could, flipping backwards and regaining his balance. Much to his surprise, the skeleton before him stood some 10 feet tall. One expected such a large creature to move lethargically. Unfortunately, this wasn&#8217;t the case, as the skeleton began to attack as quickly as before. For every slash Cobus blocked, he lost ground and stamina. He was losing this battle. His wakizashi and Morin blade rose to block a single, powerful strike, just as the other axe began it&#8217;s decent. Cobus could feel the steel entering his side, even before it happened. He let out a violent shout, as his chainmail absorbed the slash, doing nothing to the concussion. As the skeleton recoiled for another attack, it was bathed in a jet of fire from over Cobus&#8217; shoulder. Cobus quickly prayed for a blessing of short flight, as he arched over the skeleton. His blades came down strong, breaking the weakened bone into a crumble. The skeleton had been reduced to a flaming morass of bone in mere seconds. With this, the other undead became unorganized, and as vampires retreated, the flow of undead into the Faydark had lessened. Cobus surveyed the battleground, seeking stragglers or civilians. When he found nothing, he turned to locate his comrades. Aeril was tending to a wounded child, while Berglad was cleaning his blade of material it had &#8220;collected&#8221; during the fight. Cobus approached Aeril, quickly remembering the massive gash on his side. <br><br>&#8220;You fight as well as ever, Aeril&#8221;<br>&#8220;If not a bit better&#8221; added Berglad<br>Aeril finished tending to the young one, and stood to face Cobus.<br>&#8220;It seems fate is much more on my side than against it. Your timing couldn&#8217;t have been better old friends.&#8221;<br>Berglad grew red &#8220;I am not old!&#8221;<br><br>The elves chuckled. Aeril spoke &#8220;I see nothing has changed. How have you been, Cobus?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Good, to say the least anyway. We were coming to visit you when we heard of this battle. I haven&#8217;t seen anything like this since we tried to breach the castle at Mistmoore itself.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;It was quite a battle, and quite refreshing. Spending months turning a ruined tower into a place of Nature is very taxing on your mind&#8221;. Aeril had been trying to make a home for himself. He had found an old tower in Lesser Faydark that had probably been made by the scum from Mistmoore. It was so dead, so haunting. He had transformed it into a small utopia of life. It was quite a tiring, but rewarding process.<br>&#8220;Aye, ya&#8217;think we could see this tower of yours?&#8221; questioned Berglad.<br>Cobus interjected &#8220;Soon. Right now, Aeril, we need your help&#8221;<br><br>A smile came to Aeril&#8217;s face &#8220;Another crazy plan, Cobus?&#8221;<br>&#8220;I suppose it&#8217;s a bit risky, but well within reason . .&#8221;<br>	&#8220; . . . Of a crazy wood elf &#8220; finished Berglad<br>&#8220;Well, out with it. What do you have planned?&#8221;<br>Cobus retold the story of Unrest, how the council wanted someone to clear it, and of the mystical boots that could be found there.<br>&#8220;Sounds like a quest worth of completion. Is it to be just us three?&#8221;<br>Cobus smirked &#8220;Oh come now. You know I want the six of us in on it. I figured to get you first so you could provide travel&#8221;<br>Berglad grumbled &#8220;I hate teleporting. It makes me sick.&#8221;<br>&#8220;Almost as much as I hate warriors who don&#8217;t make use of plate mail vambraces. Is the maneuverability that important .  . .&#8221;<br>Aeril and Cobus laughed once more. Good old Berglad was always there to make sense of everything. Cobus coughed again in pain of from his wound. Aeril said a small prayer, and used the last of his mana to mend the broken flesh. The feeling of relief swept over Cobus, like a splash of cool water. It was good to be together once more.<br><br><br>They arrived in Kelethin by sunrise. The first thing they did was rent an inn and catch up on some much needed rest. The city of Kelethin was quite a marvel. Seated high above the ground, it was a city that lived in the air, bound to the massive trees of the Faydark. It was also a literal death trap to newcomers. Many a visitor had fallen to great injury or even death. Even with it&#8217;s subtle danger, Kelethin was gorgeous; a true achievement in elven craftsmanship. It was also well known for its hospitality. Cobus awoke midday, remembering that the day ahead was busy. Aeril would rest all day to be prepared for the teleport, while Cobus and Berglad would gather supplies and call in favors. The residents of Antonica were usually hospitable to elves, but dwarves were a bit harder to accommodate. Cobus walked to the bank, enjoying the rustle of the city. As he came to be bank, he saw none other than his archrival Sirene. As kids they had played together on often. They had both chosen the path of the ranger. Since a small competition in their early teens, they had strived to over-achieve the other. It was usually friendly, though recently it had become sour. They even argued over whom had the better equipment. Now those arguments were the definition of useless. Sure she had the fabled sword of the Ykesha, but his armor was way nicer than her . . <br><br>&#8220;Cobus&#8221;<br>The sneer in that call was like an arrow.<br>&#8220;Long time no see. Not like anything has changed&#8221;, she said, showing her obviously new greaves.<br>&#8220;And I see you have some need to wear stolen plate mail?&#8221;<br>&#8220;These leggings came off the Froglock Crusader himself, deep in the caverns of Guk!&#8221;<br>&#8220;That&#8217;s nice. Did you kill him or take them with other &#8216;methods&#8217; ?&#8221;<br>Her sword was into her hand in the flash of a heartbeat, just in time to collide with a guard&#8217;s shield. &#8220;We&#8217;ll be having none of that&#8221;.<br>Cobus could do nothing but grin. &#8220;Sorry, I couldn&#8217;t imagine what came over to me to think that the great Sirene would actually use manipulation to acquire something. Must be a passing thought.&#8221;<br>For the first time, he had actually left a confrontation with her feeling better than when he entered it. &#8220;On to the bank to get money now!&#8221; a small voice told him.<br><br><br>The three of them stood just out of the visual range of Kelethin. When a druid teleported you, you feel as though you were sent to the clouds. A massive wind made every step you took a giant one. In minutes you could cover ground that took days. A druid had to send each person to this place, one at a time. A wizard&#8217;s portal was quicker, but many preferred the experience of the walking on clouds. Aeril summoned all his energies, and prayed to Tunare to give him the key to open the pathways towards the clouds. A blue aura first enveloped Berglad, and he vanished. Cobus saw the aura around him, and as he blinked, he opened his eyes to a new world, where the sun was very bright and the clouds were surreal. Soft and misty to the touch yet stable to the foot. Aeril suddenly appeared in front of them and he gestured toward the sun. As the three of them walked, the environment amazed them. Aeril had traversed this place time and again, yet the wonders of its beauty still dazzled him. Cobus and Berglad had been before, but like anyone not totally accustomed to it, time passed before they got the feel of walking in the clouds. Just when Cobus finally started to truly enjoy the experience, they plummeted to Norrath. Once again, Cobus blinked, and opened his eyes to the Druid ruins of the Commonlands. Once his companions appeared, they set off toward Freeport.<br><br>&#8220;Damnit I hate that last part&#8221; a grumpy Berglad said.<br>&#8220;Cant ye makit a bit smoothar?&#8221;<br>&#8220;Next time you&#8217;re in a shrine to Tunare&#8221; Aeril chuckled, &#8220;Be sure to make a request&#8221;. Cobus could only hope that Beppe would be as much fun as Berglad was.<br><br><b>Please send all comments to <a href="mailto:spilla@home.com">spilla@home.com</a>.</b>

