<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Hoppin' Mad</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Brim StoneCutter  (<a href="mailto:VLDISANZA@rainbow-media.com" class="credit2">VLDISANZA@rainbow-media.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">Fates Hands (E'ci)</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
	&#8220;Stay close to me,&#8221; said the Wizard in purple.  &#8220;We don&#8217;t want to get ambushed in here, so be careful and alert.&#8221;<br><br>	The party members looked around and saw nothing that signified any danger, but they knew that if Izzi told them to be wary, then they must be wary.<br><br>	Izzi Fizzlethorpe, Erudite Wizard and High Lord of At Fates Hands, the secret society formed of Norrathian adventurers by Izzi himself.  Izzi was every bit the classic looking Erudite, his dark skin and lean features matched only by the permanent furrow in his brow from continuously trying to perplex some issue.  Izzi was a master tactician and a brilliant man.  He had shown the world that views of the Erudite Elitist Society were not his own, forsaking their snobbery and holier-than-thou attitudes for one closer to brotherhood and kindness.  He was respected in all circles, and a welcome friend and confidant.<br><br>	&#8220;What are we looking for?&#8221; asked the other wizard at Izzi&#8217;s side.  Gobo Brimfire was every bit the spitting image of his teacher and friend, Izzi, except that his robe was a sheen of a forest green rather than the metallic purple that had become Izzi&#8217;s trademark with the rest of the guild.  Gobo was an Erudite of normal proportions: tall and lanky, with a sense of grace that had been overwhelmed by the years of studying books in the Library of Erudin.  Gobo&#8217;s eyes shifted from left to right down each corridor, constantly searching for the trouble that Izzi made reference.  However, nothing stirred within the quiet walls of Guk.<br><br>	&#8220;Same thing we are always looking for,&#8221; replied the older wizard, a smile playing on his lips.<br><br>	Brim looked at his two companions and sighed.  Izzi constantly spoke in riddles and incomplete verse, always preoccupied with planning of some adventure.  Gobo was voicing the same concerns of the other party members, which at the moment was, &#8220;What are we doing here?&#8221;  <br><br>Brim Stonecutter, High Elf Enchanter from Felwithe had heard of the legendary journeys of Izzi from his cousin the Cleric who had in the past fought side by side with the Erudite.  He had spun wondrous tales of trips all over Norrath, battling many creatures that Brim had never imagined.  He had thought these to be mostly fiction until meeting with the wizard and eventually teaming up with him and his companions.  He now believed the impossible.<br><br>	Brim was often timid and shy compared to his wizard companions.  He was well known for his &#8220;sit back and examine&#8221; approach to everything, and it often took him much longer than others to make normal decisions.  His alabaster skin and thin frame also gave him the ability to easily blend in with, if not hide from, other members of his party.  As he studied the two wizards, he felt a hot and acrid wind on his shoulder, along with a slimy drip of something skittle down his blue robe.<br><br>	Brim turned and looked into the yellow-green eyes and black-toothed grin of the next member of their group.  Jarnvid <lastname> had to be the ugliest Ogre Brim had ever seen, not that he had seen many.  Jarnvid&#8217;s oversized nose and pockmarked face blended all too well with the rest of his oversized head atop his massive body.  He was easily three times the width across as Brim, and towered over the Elf like a full grown adult over a child.  <br><br>Jarnvid was a Shaman they had run across some time back and invited into their group without haste.  Despite his hungry, drooling smile and hideous looks, Jarnvid was about the best companion anyone could have.  His loyalty and honor were matched by few, and his ethics &#8211; something Brim didn&#8217;t even believe Ogres knew about &#8211; were of the highest regards for his companions.  The Ogre was a welcome addition to the group, and his simple yet matter-of-fact attitude often kept the group from becoming too serious.<br><br>Brim smiled at his oversized companion and asked, &#8220;Do you mind?  You are drooling on my robe.&#8221;<br><br>Jarnvid&#8217;s grin grew even larger and he emitted a low chuckle as he stood up even taller, nearly hitting his head on the ceiling of the corridor.  Brim smiled back and carefully brushed the drool off of his shoulder.  The Elf had once heard a story about how Ogres loved to eat the Elfin and Fairy creatures of Norrath, and when his big friend looked at him so, he often wondered if such tales were true.  He quickly shook the thought from his head and decided that if he was going to be Ogre food, it would have happened ages ago.<br><br>&#8220;Me Sorry, fren Brim,&#8221; boomed the Ogre, and Brim noticed that when Jarnvid said his name, a line of saliva always seemed to shoot into the air and land on him.  Ye gods, did the Ogre have a drooling problem.<br><br>Izzi waved the enchanter and shaman into silence as a figure crept around the corner at the end of the hall.  Brim couldn&#8217;t tell from his position in the back, but it appeared to be human formed.  Brim could see the figure gesture with a few signs and sensed Izzi sigh in relief.  &#8220;Come, it is safe,&#8221; he breathed and they walked down the corridor to the mystery person there.  As the shadows descended and Brim was able to make out the form, he too smiled and let out a sigh.<br><br>Olwen Brytangel stood crouched up against the wall at the end of the hallway, an ever-present smirk twisting from his lips.  The Half Elf Paladin gesticulated to Izzi as in a form of reverence and both their smiles grew wide.<br><br>&#8220;Sir Olwen,&#8221; dripped the honeyed words from Izzi.  He put an emphasis on the &#8220;Sir&#8221; and Brim grinned at the reference.  Olwen had reluctantly accepted the title as one of the guild officers after faithful service to the guild.  Izzi knighted so few, and even Brim was taken aback from the title given.  &#8220;It is good to see you, and in one piece.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Took you long enough, it did,&#8221; replied the Half Elf.  Brim noticed his words equaled the common dialect of most humans, and knew that Olwen probably spent a more time with humans than Elfin races, more than likely being shunned by the Elfin.  Elves tended to be like Erudites in that respect, and that was something that Brim had often frowned upon from his brothers and sisters.  He would never understand the reasoning behind their callous racial issues.<br><br>Olwen was stocky, even if he would have been full human, with a light olive skin tone that seemed to blend perfectly with the armor and tunic he wore.  His sword was currently sheathed and his shield was slung over his back, but Brim knew from prior experience with the Paladin that both could be out of their harnesses within a second and ready for battle.  Olwen was a pious and righteous individual, as all Paladins tended to be, and sometimes his faith could cloud his judgement of a situation.  However, Olwen&#8217;s war and combat skills rivaled that of the most legendary knights and warriors and Brim was proud to have him fight by his side.<br><br>Suddenly, Gobo&#8217;s head shot up and he began to look around the corridor.  &#8220;Did you hear that?&#8221; he asked and went back to surveying his immediate area.  The others took caution from the young wizard&#8217;s actions and began to ready themselves for whatever may be happening.<br><br>&#8220;Me no hear nuthin&#8217;,&#8221; grumbled Jarnvid.  &#8220;You mus be hearin&#8217; tings.&#8221;  Brim wasn&#8217;t certain if Ogres had a keen sense of hearing, but he knew that as a shaman, Jarnvid often had many abilities above and beyond that of a normal creature.<br><br>Being the only Elf in the party, Brim used his finely tuned senses to see if he could pinpoint what it was that Gobo might have heard.  He thought he could hear&#8230; something, like a scratching, but he couldn&#8217;t be sure.  It may have just been the echoes from the cavern walls off of their own boots.<br><br>Izzi, however, wasted no time.  &#8220;We move, now,&#8221; he commanded, and the party moved on down the hallway to the end.  When they reached the end, the room opened up into a hollowed out cave with something like a monument in the middle, a large torch burning in the center.  Two figures stood hunched near the torch, and Brim couldn&#8217;t make out the forms.  One of them emitted a low gurgle and pop that let Brim knew he was not up against anything he could recognize.<br><br>Izzi waved the group back into the corridor and signaled for them to go wait here.  The wizard cast an invisibility spell on himself and continued into the room towards the two figures.  Brim could see the sparkles of power from the spell fade out as he turned the corner to enter the room.  Moments later, Izzi returned and reappeared before them, his brow furrowed into that permanent thinking position as he reasoned out what he had just seen.<br><br>&#8220;Froglocks,&#8221; he began, &#8220;and lots of them.  Those two near the dais plus three more in the cavern at the other end of the room.  I could not tell for sure, but I one of them radiates the strands of power of a magic user.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Shamun,&#8221; interjected the big Ogre.  Jarnvid&#8217;s big head bobbed up and down in the affirmative to let Izzi know he was correct.  &#8220;Froggies sometime is caster froggies, an&#8217; dey have magics like Jarnvid.&#8221;  The Ogre would know, since the land of Guk was directly bordering his homeland, and Brim was sure that Jarnvid had slain his share of Froglocks.<br><br>Damn, thought Brim to himself.  Froglocks.  Never in his life did he ever think he would encounter such a menace.  He had once seen pictures of the frog-like men in the libraries back home during his studies of far off lands.  Now, not only was he in the far off land, he was about to encounter the beast from his studies first hand.  To think it was only a few short years ago.<br><br>&#8220;We&#8217;ll attack them head on, then,&#8221; Izzi surmised.  &#8220;There may be many, but they are the weaker tads of their race.  There should not be much trouble in defeating them.&#8221;<br><br>If there was one thing Brim had learned from his travels with the wizard - as well as from his cousin &#8211; when Izzi stated something wouldn&#8217;t be trouble, then he better be ready for trouble. (/ooc &#8211; Sorry Izz, but its true!  lol)<br><br>Brim blinked and looked around at his party members.  While in his thoughts, they had already begun to prepare for the battle.  Izzi and Gobo sat across from each other, cross-legged and flecks of power dashing in front of them. Jarnvid was crouched down one of his massive legs chanting something in his guttural Ogre language.  Brim&#8217;s Ogre was horrible, and he couldn&#8217;t make out any of the words used by the shaman.  Olwen had unsheathed his blade and laid it across his forearm.  The mighty blade seemed to shimmer in the half-lit hallway and the Paladin&#8217;s eyes fluttered open, then closed again.<br><br>Brim decided to ready himself and checked his spell book for the right illusion.  He found the one he was looking for and mouthed the words once to make sure he had them right.  He then closed the book and chanted in the arcane language of power and enchantments.  A green nimbus surrounded his hands and crept up his arms.  Slowly, the light flowed over his shoulders and down his chest cavity.  It finished surrounding him and ended off with a bright green pop, and Brim suddenly felt&#8230; different.<br><br>Izzi stood and looked at the form Brim had taken, and nodded at his choice.  Jarnvid swung his big head around and his eyes narrowed slightly, almost as if he could just see through the illusion, but not quite.  Brim surveyed himself and could see the form of the Earth Elemental looked satisfactory.  He also felt the form&#8217;s added strength, and welcomed it for the upcoming battle.<br><br>Brim watched the others prepare with their own magical enchantments and protections.  With all the light emitting from the spectacle, Brim was surprised that the Froglocks didn&#8217;t detect their presence much sooner.<br><br>After the group finished, Izzi signaled for silence.  He then explained that he would attract the attention of the Froglocks first, giving the rest of them time to form up.  &#8220;The two on the dais,&#8221; he began, &#8220;should be rather easy, and if we can avoid attracting the attention of the other three down the other hall, then we will survive with little or no damage.&#8221;<br>The other four nodded in agreement and then headed out, following Izzi to the room.  Olwen followed directly behind him, with Brim and Gobo next and Jarnvid to follow up in the rear.  Izzi motioned for a halt just before they entered into the room and frowned at what he saw next.  Of the three that were down the other corridor on the other side of the open area, two of them came into the room and up to the dais.  The third was no where to be found.<br><br>Izzi swore under his breath and Brim began to worry.  He looked to his other party members and could see the concern on their faces as well.  Izzi&#8217;s brows furrowed into their seemingly constant thinking state and he tried to reason out what to do next.  It became so quiet in the hall that Brim heard Jarnvid scratch at his oversized bottom.  He shook his head, but couldn&#8217;t help grin at the image that came up with the sound.<br><br>Izzi snapped out of his planning and motioned for Brim to come forward.  The enchanter had a feeling this would happen.  &#8220;All right, Brim,&#8221; encouraged Izzi, &#8220;it is all up to you now.  We need you to keep these over grown tadpoles suspended while we take them down one at a time.  Are you up for the challenge, friend?&#8221;<br><br>Brim took a deep breath.  He knew his limitations when it came to spell casting, but never had the Elf encountered a Froglock before.  Now he was faced with four of them and perhaps more coming.  &#8220;I do not know,&#8221; was the only answer Brim could summon.  The rest of the party members shuffled and sighed dejectedly at Brim&#8217;s disconcerting answer.<br><br>Izzi grabbed the enchanter by the shoulders and looked into his eyes.  &#8220;You must try, or we cannot survive otherwise,&#8221; he admitted.  Brim broke eye contact with the wizard and looked down at the floor.  He hated to be the one to lead the force into battle.  Once before, when he was younger and more hotheaded, he had tried a bravado move of attacking a creature head on, only to realize that if his Cleric cousin was not there to instantly heal him, he would have died.  Since then, he had adopted the more reserved and more careful approach to his adventuring, and it had kept him alive long enough to get here.  And now it looked like he was about to jeopardize that which he had been so cautious over.  <br><br>Brim stopped his musing, looked at the wizard and replied, &#8220;All right, if I must, then I will try.&#8221;<br><br>The Elf stepped out of the hallway and into the room, the rest of his party members behind him.  He reached down deep into the source of his magic and began to form the image of the spell in his mind.  He then sought the minds of the four Froglocks before him, each mind as individual as a snowflake, but similar in construction.  He could sense their primitive thoughts and was happy to learn that each of the minds before him could not resist the force of his mesmerize spell.  Brim waved his hands in the air and formed the illusion of mind control.  A purple and blue ball of power appeared at his will and he gathered the necessary energies for the spell.  He was amazed that none of the creatures looked up from whatever they were doing on the dais.<br><br>With a final wave of his hands, the enchanter sent the mind spell reeling towards the targets.  Three of the Froglocks stood frozen in place, but Brim felt his spell crumble like an egg on stone against the fourth.  The creature blinked in surprise, its large amphibious eyes locking on the enchanter.  It was Brim&#8217;s turn to blink in surprise as the Froglock let out a horrific sounding &#8220;Frrroooaaakkk!&#8221; and began to advance on him.<br><br>Impossible!  The creature had no where near the capabilities to resist the force of that spell.  Yet for some reason, the spell crumbled like stale bread.  Next, it whirled around and began to croak and pop in some odd, yet familiar language.  It was spell casting!  The Froglock Shaman!  No wonder his spell had no effect; the creature probably had some magical resistance spell cast upon itself.  A light blue and misted swirl of power crackled from the Froglock Shaman&#8217;s fingertips and began to grow into a powerful blast of energy.  Brim could hear his friends begin their own incantations, but they would not beat the Froglock to the punch.<br><br>The Shaman threw its hands forward and a frost beam erupted forward and slammed against Brim&#8217;s magical shields.  The effect actually knocked him back and he nearly lost his balance from the blast.  The Elf regained his composure and turned in time to see the Froglock Shaman erupt into a shower of sparks and fire.  Brim laughed to himself.  The creature could not withstand the effects of the two wizards and a shaman&#8217;s spells.  The Froglock sagged to the floor, a mass of charred, smoking flesh.<br><br>At the same moment, two of the other mesmerized Froglocks broke the enchantment and went rushing towards the source of that enchantment.  Brim searched his memory for a quick spell and thought of the perfect one.  He held his hands up, palms forward, and rattled off a quick verse.  Colored light erupted from the enchanter&#8217;s palms, blinding and temporarily stunning both of the Froglocks.  In seconds, Olwen was on one of the blinded creatures, effectively slashing and cutting it down in three deft movements.  Jarnvid went to the second and crushed it&#8217;s skull in an over-handed blow with the tremendous maul he had aptly named Gatorsmash.  <br><br>The wizards turned the last Froglock into a charred mess before it even broke the Enchanter&#8217;s first spell.  The battle was over as quick as it had begun.  Jarnvid trudged over to the nearest Froglock and picked it up by the legs.  The limp corpse of the creature hung like a child&#8217;s doll in the massive Ogre&#8217;s hands.  With little effort, he tore off one of its legs and took a bite out of the limb.  The crunch sent shivers through the rest of the party, and Jarnvid let out a satisfied, &#8220;Mmmmm,&#8221; followed by, &#8220;me luv froggy legs.  Dey gud when fresh.&#8221;<br><br>Brim resisted the urge to wretch, and he saw Gobo place his hand over his mouth looking rather pale.  The Ogre finished his meal and let out a thunderous belch.  Flecks of meat flapped from his lips and when he finished, he dropped the now clean leg bone and wiped his mouth on his arm.  &#8220;Ahhhh,&#8221; he sighed contentedly.  The group reformed and assessed their situation.<br><br>&#8220;All right, my friends,&#8221; Izzi began.  &#8220;Very well done.  But remember, these were only young Froglocks, and the older beasts will tear us to shreds if we are not careful.&#8221;  Brim noticed several of the companions nod at the statement, knowing that he was probably the only one who had never encountered the beasts before.  Once again, Brim was reminded of his inexperience around such veterans.<br><br>Gobo was peering down the hallway where the fifth Froglock was before, but he was unable to see anything down the dark corridor.  &#8220;Dark as the inside of a Hill Giant&#8217;s&#8230;&#8221; started the young wizard, but he thought better of his statement and cut himself off.  Brim grinned and rattled off his Ultravision spell that had always come in handy for his human friends when it got dark.  Gobo smiled at Brim and nodded his thanks.  &#8220;It would seem that the fifth creature has left the area, it would be safe to pursue.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Then let us move quickly,&#8221; replied Olwen. &#8220;We wouldn&#8217;t want this little event alerting the rest of the clan.&#8221;  With that Brim definitely agreed, and they moved on down the dark corridor to the next part of the cavern.  Brim was taking grand notice of the intricate carvings on the walls hat depicted great scenes, almost as if they were telling a story.  He stopped in front of one primitive looking scene trying to decipher what it may be.  Several green colored beings &#8211; obviously Froglocks &#8211; were standing around a pillar of fire, apparently in worship.<br><br>&#8220;The Coming of Great Power,&#8221; Izzi read from the picture.<br>Brim stared at the wizard and asked, &#8220;You can read this?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Not really,&#8221; he admitted, &#8220;but the general idea is there.  I have studied primitive clan cultures of Norrathian species and they often use these hieroglyphics to tell stories of great happenings in their society.  This looks to be like the telling of a volcano erupting.&#8221;<br><br>Brim puzzled around the idea of a great event happening in the Froglock culture that would cause them to draw pictures on a wall, and a volcano would definitely be one of them.  &#8220;But the closest volcanic activity resides in Lavastorm, a land quite far from here,&#8221; responded Brim.  &#8220;How would they know of such an event?&#8221;<br><br>His response surprisingly came from Olwen.  &#8220;Do not presume, young enchanter, that the Froglocks were not once of the land you refer to as Lavastorm.  They are an old species on Norrath, and have much history within the lands.&#8221;<br><br>Brim crossed one arm over the other and tapped a finger on his chin in thought.  The idea that the Froglocks were that old of a society went against many of the teachings he had back in Felwithe.  Of course, since he had met with his current friends, many of the teachings he had received prior to leaving his homeland were now as silly as children&#8217;s tales, once again proving that no education was as good as a life experience.<br><br>&#8220;Let&#8217;s move,&#8221; interrupted Gobo.  &#8220;I would hate to be caught in this dark space with a horde of Froglocks at my back.&#8221;<br>&#8220;Agreed,&#8221; said Izzi.  &#8220;We must keep moving.&#8221;<br><br>They continued to the end of the hall and came around a corner into another large area.  This time the space was more like a pit, but there were stairs carved into the walls.  On the outer edge of the room on each side was a dark doorway.  At the bottom of the pit were another three Froglocks, dancing and chanting around another one of the daises like the one they encountered earlier.  The creature in the middle held an extended gold colored rod with a jagged top.  It wore a robe-like garment and between each set of chants would bang the rod on the ground for an emphatic effect to the chant.  Brim could swear he saw a blue image waver on top of the icon resting in the middle of the dais, but after shaking his head and blinking a few times saw nothing.<br><br>&#8220;Perfect,&#8221; gasped Izzi in what seemed like delight.  &#8220;That is what we came for.  I had not thought it would be so easy an item to attain, but there it is.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;We do not have it yet,&#8221; corrected the younger mage.<br>&#8220;We shall, my friend, you shall see.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Nuff talk, me hungry!&#8221; bellowed Jarnvid and he rushed into the room and stood at the edge of the open pit hefting his mighty maul into the air and whooping a deadly Ogre war cry.  The Froglocks were surprised only for a second before the one holding the rod gestured to the Ogre and garbled something unintelligible to his acolytes.  Both creatures crouched and then leapt incredibly high into the air and landed on either side of the Shaman.  They turned and started to move in slowly on the Ogre, obviously thinking the two would outnumber his one.<br><br>  The rest of the party poured into the pit area and went to the aid of their friend.  Brim noticed a red and purple nexus of power gather around Izzi.  It looked to Brim like Izzi was about to roast the two advancing on Jarnvid, but noticed that the wizard had another target in mind.<br><br>Gobo also started to wave his hands in a spiraling motion and circular flames appeared in the air in front of him.  Olwen had already reached the side of Jarnvid and now the two were back to back and prepared to take on the advancing Froglocks.  Izzi&#8217;s spell went off and Brim could feel the enormous force behind the magical attack, so much that it actually made a whoosh as it flew towards its intended target.  With blinding speed, the Froglock still in the pit spun the Golden Rod in a wide arc and deflected most of the magical attack.  Izzi blinked in surprise and Brim couldn&#8217;t help but gape.  A low gurgle emitted from the Froglock in the pit and he began to advance forward on the wizard.<br><br>Olwen and Jarnvid were trying to make quick work of the other two beasts, but these were undoubtedly tougher than the last bunch.  Brim saw Olwen misstep and take a blow across the shoulder.  The enchanter gathered some of his own magic and cast protective fire barrier around the Paladin.  The flames harmlessly enveloped him and the Froglock shied away from the increasing heat of the flames. In a movement like a blur, Olwen spun and lopped the creature&#8217;s head right from its shoulders.  He turned and grinned at Brim in the fashion that showed his gratitude.<br><br>Gobo managed to get off his spell and a spiral column of flame shot towards the second Froglock, slamming full force into the side of the beast.  It shook its head and turned on the young wizard.  Jarnvid seized the moment and dealt a crushing blow to its back with the full force of his maul.  Brim could hear the snap of the creature&#8217;s spine and see its eyes glaze over in death even before it crumpled to the ground in a heap.  Jarnvid&#8217;s black and yellow grin was enough to make even Brim smile.  Then he heard the explosion.<br><br>Brim turned to see Izzi standing a few yards from the last Froglock, his arms crossed defensively in front of him.  The creature twirled the Golden Rod and an eerie dark purple bubble of power formed and edged its way slowly towards Izzi.  The wizard somehow seemed to anticipate the attack and brought his crossed arms down in a chopping motion.  The dark bubble split in half twice and disintegrated.  The Froglock let out a rumble of a croak advanced on the Wizard, the Golden Rod held like a spear.  Brim desperately tried to think up a charm that would work on a Froglock, but could not come up with anything.  Instead he rattled of a quick spell designed to hamper the speed of an opponent. The Froglock turned towards Brim, moving like he was pushing through water.  Olwen easily walked up to the creature and plunged his sword into its skull.  It shuddered once and slumped to the group in a useless heap.<br><br>Once again, the battle went smoothly, if not as easy as their first.  Izzi walked directly over to the fallen Froglock holding the Golden Rod and kicked it onto its back.  &#8220;Brim,&#8221; he called, &#8220;come and take this from him.  If what I read about it is true, the Rod is a magical item that cannot pass between the living once possessed.&#8221;<br><br>Brim nodded and walked over to the corpse.  He had heard stories of magic items on Norrath that were enchanted so that they may not be passed from one to another, but rather formed a magical bond with the owner until its death.   Apparently this beast was the former owner of this item, and now it was to become his.<br><br>&#8220;I want you to hang on to that for now, &#8220;said Izzi.  Like I have a choice Brim thought to himself.  &#8220;I read in an ancient tome that it is one half of an ancient weapon designed to bond with the magical properties of an enchanter.  It was known as the Rod of Insidious Glamour, but was destroyed and the pieces were never found.  I learned of this one&#8217;s whereabouts from our big friend Jarnvid over there.&#8221;<br><br>At the mention of his name, Jarnvid gave a toothy grin and said, &#8220;Me watch froggies do dat sing an&#8217; dance an&#8217; me tell Izz &#8216;bout dem.  He say we come gets dem froggies, so me waited ta eat dem.  Now me have lunch.&#8221;  And the big Ogre did just that, eating another pair of Froglock legs while the team planned their next move.<br><br>Izzi filled them in on some of the history of the Caverns of Guk, explaining some of the believed origins of the Froglocks, and how it is believed they came to find these caverns in the first place.  Brim listened intently to the history lesson, the whole time wondering if there was anything the Wizard didn&#8217;t know about.  He seemed to have a vast knowledge of Norrath&#8217;s history and creatures, as well as speculation and factual information on all accounts.  Brim was starting to understand why his cousin liked and respected the Wizard so much and had insisted that he study with the scholar. <br><br>&#8220;Izzi,&#8221; Interrupted Olwen from the other side of the room.  &#8220;I do not mean to be rude and disturb your lesson, but the less time we stay there, the better I will feel.&#8221;  The Paladin&#8217;s eyes shifted from left to right to accentuate his unease.<br><br>Izzi only nodded and walked to the doorway on the left and motioned for the others to follow.  They walked single file down long and dark corridors for what seemed like hours.  Sometime later, when Brim&#8217;s thoughts began to drift off, the nearly crashed into Gobo, who had stopped directly in front of him.  He peered around the young wizard and saw that Izzi had found another room, this one had a more eerie presence about it.  Brim couldn&#8217;t put his finger on it, but something was definitely not right.  Izzi motioned for silence and waved everyone to follow.  Reluctantly, the others complied.<br><br>They entered into a room that resembled other caverns in Guk, but this one was very different.  The walls had a glowing sheen that seemed to ooze rather than radiate light.  There were large web-like structures along the ceiling connecting to long columns of rock that jutted out of the floor like teeth.  Brim noticed quite a few stray bones lying on the floor, some of them seemed quite large.  Jarnvid reached out and pulled on one of the stray webs attached to a stone column.  Izzi saw the Ogre reach for it and yelled &#8220;NO!&#8221; but not before he pulled on the web and gave the wizard a quizzical look.<br><br>Something large and black dropped from the ceiling, knocking into Brim and tossing him aside easily.  He rolled over just in time to see a spider almost as large as Jarnvid advancing on him.  The creature was easily eight feet across its leg span and its menacing glare fixed on the enchanter.  Brim tried to scurry backwards, but the spider was quick and was on him instantly.  The spider sank its fangs deep into the Elf&#8217;s leg, and Brim felt burning sensations shoot up his leg, a fire of unspeakable pain.  His scream echoed throughout the walls of Guk.<br><br>Poison! He thought to himself. Spiders were known to be poisonous arachnids, but hardly enough to do any damage to a full sized Elf.  Except this was no ordinary spider.  Brim managed to roll over and scurry along the floor, trying to claw his way from the beast.  Brim heard the unsheathing of a blade and a large thud, but was having a hard time focusing his vision.  He then felt more than saw a magic blast of power explode only a few feet from him and knew that Izzi had unleashed a full force attack on the beast.  Another burst of power followed right behind his, and this time Brim could sense the power radiate from Gobo.<br><br>A tremendous squeal emitted from the spider and the sound of clashing steel.  Olwen was making his advance on the beast but from his grunting Brim could tell he wasn&#8217;t getting very far.  He tried to shake the blurring vision and stand, but was only just able to sit up.  This monster&#8217;s poison was strong, and it was infecting him fast.<br><br>A guttural sound followed by another wave of magic and Brim knew that the Ogre had just cast one of his own spells on the spider.  Brim could hear the magical buzzing of the insect spell the shaman cast and the spider squealed anew, the sound penetrating Brim&#8217;s head and making him even more lightheaded.  Brim heard a final clang followed by a gurgling squeal and knew that Olwen had scored the final deathblow on the spider.  He grinned, but was beginning to think he did so because the lightheadedness was effecting him.<br><br>Brim heard some talking, but had trouble making out the words.  &#8220;&#8230;help him quickly&#8230;  poisoned.&#8221;  That sounded like it may have been Izzi, or Gobo, but Brim couldn&#8217;t make out the fuzzy sounding voice too clearly.  Two extremely large hands lifted him like a helpless newborn and set him up against a rock.  Brim felt close to blacking out, but convinced himself that he needed to stay awake.  A low guttural chant and an eerie green light exuded in front of him.  Brim could remember hearing something like it once before, but he was uncertain where.<br><br>Suddenly Brim felt a rush of energy surge through him, hot then cold, then hot again.  He started to sweat and then shiver and felt he would shake so hard he may fall apart.  A voice near him said he should be all right, but Brim wasn&#8217;t so sure.  He slumped to the ground, his vision returning slowly.  Another wave of power washed over him, this time warming and comforting.  Brim recognized the healing spell drift over him and his strength returned anew.  His eyes fluttered open, and he jerked up, not even realizing he had them close.  When his eyes came into focus, he was face to face with Jarnvid&#8217;s huge yellow and black toothed grin.<br><br>Resisting his urge to jump in fear, Brim shook his head to clear out the last of the dizziness.  Slowly, he stood up and noticed all of his friends standing around him and looking intently to see if he was all right.  &#8220;Thank you, my big friend,&#8221; he said to the Ogre.  &#8220;I owe you a debt of gratitude.&#8221;<br><br>The big Ogre shook his head and frowned.  &#8220;No, fren Brim.  We is frens an&#8217; frens help each udder.  You no need tank Jarnvid for ting he do frum frenship.&#8221;<br><br>Brim couldn&#8217;t help but smile, and noticed the others smiling as well.  Jarnvid didn&#8217;t have a way with words, but he definitely was honest and got his point across.  Something that too few people did these days, and Brim welcomed the honesty.  He extended his hand and clasped that of the Ogre, only grimacing slightly from the powerful grip and vigorous shake he received in return.<br><br>&#8220;Well, I think our friend Brim will recover,&#8221; said Izzi, &#8220;so let us get moving.  We are almost to our destination.&#8221;<br><br>Brim fixed his robes, now stained with some of his blood and the venom injected by the spider.  He went to a nearby puddle and carefully washed off the excess venom.  He also noticed that he had lost his illusion of the Earth Elemental, but decided not to renew it and conserve his energies.  He then rejoined the others and they continued into the hallway and on to the next oversized cavern.<br><br>They all entered into an open area that was hard to distinguish from many of the other areas they had been in so far, the walls having the same look as many other rooms.  The only difference Brim noted was a painting of dead Froglocks on the far wall to the left next to an opening to another corridor.  Izzi was studying the drawing, his finger rhythmically tapping his chin in thought.<br><br>Izzi turned to his companions and had a worried look on his face.  This concerned Brim since he had never witnessed the wizard in such a state. He noticed his companions with a similar concern and knew it obviously meant some sort of great danger.  The enchanter was about to ask what he had discovered, but Gobo beat him to the punch.<br><br>&#8220;A graveyard of some sort?&#8221; he pondered.  The others looked at Izzi and saw the confirmation in his eyes.  Brim wondered why a graveyard had worried the wizard so.<br><br>As if the wizard had read his mind, he spoke, &#8220;Ordinarily graveyards would not concern me in the slightest.&#8221;  He paced across the floor and his fingers massaged his temples.  Brim could tell he was remembering some long ago studied information.  The wizard went on.  &#8220;However, in this case, I believe we have trouble.  Froglocks are a very superstitious species.  Some of them believe they are meant to be immortal, others believe they are reincarnated and brought back in a new life.  Different clans pose different beliefs.  This symbol,&#8221; he gestured to the drawing to his right, &#8220;is representative of the Zok Clan.  They are known necromancers and are feared greatly by the other clans with much reason.  I have a bad feeling that&#8230;&#8221;<br><br>As if the words had sparked the action, a low and eerie croak came from one of the hallways.  A wind burst through the room bringing the chill and stink of death with it.  Each of the party members backed up a step or two, eyes wide at the noise that emanated from within the corridor.  Something made a hiss and sounded as if it was slithering down the hall.  It let loose another gurgling croak and stepped into the room.  What they witnessed was nothing like what they expected.<br><br>The Froglock&#8217;s skin was a darker green, almost gray, than a normal Froglock.  Parts of its flesh were torn away or missing all together, exposing many bones.  Its skull looked as though it had been caved in at one point, and one of its eyes had a nasty gash in it where it oozed some type of yellow puss.  Each party member stared is disbelief and he even heard Olwen mutter, &#8220;&#8230;Mother of All&#8230;&#8221;<br><br>The Undead creature reared its head back in challenge and let out a mighty &#8220;Frrroooaaakk!&#8221;  It then sprang forward towards its nearest target, namely Gobo.  The young wizard started to bring up a spell, but the Froglock reached him and easily swatted him aside.  Gobo flew into the wall behind him and slumped down unconscious.  Jarnvid threw his hammer up into the air issuing his own challenge and the Froglock stopped in his tracks and turned towards the Ogre.<br><br>Jarnvid waved his arms in a peculiar motion and they ignited with a misty blue light.  The light grew and grew, and soon enveloped his entire body.  He then threw his arms out to the side and then flung both of them forward.  Large pellets of hail scattered across the Froglock, and though they could be seen hitting his body, the beast seemed to hardly notice the fist-sized balls of ice.  Brim could swear that the creature was actually smiling.<br><br>Brim sought the monster&#8217;s mind and wove his hands into the pattern to bring down its magical resistance.  It did little, and the creature started its advance on Jarnvid.  The Ogre began another spell, but the Froglock sprang forward at blurring speed and stuck the Ogre in his huge gut.  He doubled over in pain, clutching his stomach and gasping for air.<br><br>Another burst of power exploded across the Froglock&#8217;s back and sent him sprawling into the nearest wall.  Brim turned and saw the residual fluxes of power emanating from Izzi&#8217;s fingers.  Brim was certain that same blast might have felled a Hill Giant.  Brim looked back over to the Froglock and saw it spring back to its feet.  The creature gave a low croak, obviously angry and preparing to launch itself at the wizard.  Just as it was about to leap into action a bloodthirsty war cry pierced the room as Olwen sprang into action.<br><br>Olwen collided with the Froglock, hacking at it with the ferocity of an animal.  The beast retaliated with a blow of its own which Olwen easily absorbed on his shield.  The paladin swept around and feinted stabbing low at the beasts&#8217; gut, then spun his sword into a massive over-handed swing.  The beast was fooled and Olwen&#8217;s sword struck home, embedding deep in the Froglock&#8217;s shoulder.  He ripped the sword from the creature&#8217;s shoulder and black ooze seeped from the new wound.  The Undead creature only stared at its new slash and turned its gaze back to Olwen, who was beginning to pant with his effort to keep the beast at bay.<br><br>Brim tried to think of something he could do, and then had an idea.  He reached into his pack and pulled out two miniscule little daggers, knives too small for combat.  He held them in his open palm and waved his other hand over them, beginning his incantation.  Yellow sparks flew from his fingertips and the daggers spun out of his hands, landing on the floor.  The daggers were glowing and began to grow.  They then changed shape until a sword and shield were lying on the ground.  Another chant from the Elf, and the weapons lifted from the ground, waiting to spring into action at the enchanter&#8217;s command.  Brim hated the part that came next.<br><br>Olwen was holding his own with the Froglock, but looked to be getting tired (Brim could imagine the sword and shield he was wielding must be heavy).  The Elf pulled out his own dagger and crept up behind the beast, attempting to take a stab at him.  The Undead menace must have seen Brim coming because in one deft motion the beast spun and gave a crushing blow to the enchanter&#8217;s temple.  The punch knocked Brim back, dazed and barely holding on to consciousness.  Brim&#8217;s pet vaulted into action.  In it&#8217;s own hollow voice the pet shouted, &#8220;Taunting attacker, Master,&#8221; and the floating sword and shield became a dizzying flash of steel, hacking and slicing at the Froglock.  The beast&#8217;s surprise quickly turned to anger as it tried to fight off an attacker it could not see.  It swung at the enchanted pet, sometimes landing a blow on the shield, sometimes passing through empty air.  Brim&#8217;s pet was failing fast, but for what happened next, it was worth the distraction.<br><br>Olwen, seeing the distraction, took his opportunity while he had the chance.  He hefted his mighty sword in both hands and it seemed to take on an eerie bluish purple glow.  Brim felt the power of the sword begging to be used.  His eyes widened in surprise at the sudden surge from the blade.  He had felt the same surge of power from his cousin when he was battling with his Cleric cousin against the Undead that occasionally plagued the forests of Faydwer.  Brim suddenly remembered that the sword Olwen used was no ordinary sword.  It was enchanted with powerful spells against Undead creatures.  Brim had heard the paladin refer to it as Ghoulbane, a perfect name for such a powerful weapon.<br><br>Olwen swung his mighty blade overhead and let it fall into the creature&#8217;s neck.  The sword erupted into a fiery blue and purple blast of energy and sliced deeply into its spine.  The Undead Froglock grasped the sword, which had sunken as far in as its chest, shuddered once and fell to its knees.  Olwen placed his boot on its back and ripped his blade free with a clang of metal.  The beast collapsed forward and after a few twitches finally ceased moving.  Olwen sagged and leaned heavily against the nearest wall panting with exertion.<br><br>Brim clung to the growing bruise on his head and closed his eyes to the massive headache forming.  Izzi was helping Gobo, who had just regained consciousness and was sitting up with his hands cradling his head.  Jarnvid climbed to his feet and shook off the remaining effects of the blow to the gut.  &#8220;Dat Froggie hurt Jarnvid!&#8221; he exclaimed.<br><br>&#8220;Yes,&#8221; agreed Izzi, &#8220;He was tough, but we defeated him.  Very good word Sir Olwen.&#8221;  The grin flashed to Olwen from the wizard was warm and full of thanks.<br><br>&#8220;&#8217;Twas my pleasure, Sir Wizard,&#8221; replied Olwen, and he bowed graciously.  Brim tried to hide his grin, but felt the need to laugh more than anything.  &#8220;And you, Enchanter,&#8221; and the tone of his voice was full of respect, &#8220;that was quite a trick with that distraction.  It helped keep the beast from me long enough to strike the killing blow.  Good thinking.&#8221;  The paladin walked up to Brim and gave him a good solid pat on the back.  The enchanter nearly fell forward from the force of the blow.  That gave them all a good laugh.  <br><br>Until the heard the grumble.<br>At once, all five companions turned towards the hallway.  More of the scraping and croaking came from the corridor, and the same eerie chill followed.  This time, however, it sounded like a whole group of Froglocks, and most likely more of the Zol clan.  Olwen turned to Izzi and hissed, &#8220;Get us out of here, now!&#8221;<br><br>The wizard had already begun his chanting and that familiar nexus of power began to grow around him.  At the same time four more Undead Froglocks emerged from the hallway and roared a croak of anger at the party.  The five members of At Fates Hands gathered around the wizard and watched as the monsters started to advance on them.  Izzi&#8217;s hands came down and Brim saw the shimmering portal of blazing energy envelope him just before the Froglocks were upon them.<br><br>*****<br><br>The Greater Faydark&#8230;  Brim blinked as he was mystically dropped off in the Forest of the Elves, happy to be home and in a safe place.  He looked up and saw the giant spires built centuries ago by ancient wizards for use as a focal point for teleportation.  Brim looked around at his friends and saw they were all safe and sounds, and he breathed a sigh of relief.  Jarnvid was glancing around nervously, and Brim was reminded that he was in a land where Ogres were seldom seen and almost never welcome.<br><br>Izzi noticed his discomfort and assured him, &#8220;Fear not my large friend, you are safe with us.  No one here in the Faydark will harm you in our company.&#8221;  The Ogre nodded, but he did not seem to be at ease.<br><br>Gobo looked around and asked, &#8220;The Faydark?&#8221; Why are we here Izzi?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;He has come to see us,&#8221; came the reply from the trees.<br><br>The group members turned towards the sound of the voice and saw several figures emerge from the woods, broad swords brandished and at the ready.  From the look of their weapons and armor, these were the mighty High Elf Paladins of Felwithe.  They were an impressive bunch, a mix of males and females all appeared to have their combat gear on.  Brim had remembered encountering them many times, and even having a few friends within their guild.  The leader, however, was none other than General Jyleel himself.<br><br>&#8220;Good to see you again, Sir Wizard,&#8221; boomed the General.  His voice was strangely low for a High Elf, and his muscled frame was nearly twice that of the frail Brim.  On closer examination, the General resembled Olwen in stature.  If Brim hadn&#8217;t known any better, he&#8217;d have though the two were cousins.<br><br>&#8220;And you General,&#8221; responded Izzi.  &#8220;I take it that you await our news?&#8221;<br>&#8220;I do, yes, and I can see from the look of your ragged and shaken adventurers it is not good news that I will here.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;None too good I am afraid.  The Zol Knights are surfacing again.&#8221;<br>At the mention of the name, the General&#8217;s face darkened into apparent rage.  &#8220;Zol Knights,&#8221; he spat, &#8220;are unholy monsters.  They could not possibly have resurfaced.  My men made sure their taint was wiped clean from Norrath years ago.&#8221;<br><br>Izzi gave no reply, only stoically looked the General in the eyes and the High Elf let out a lengthy sigh and said, &#8220;But I know you not to be a liar, Sir Wizard, and you have been a great service to the Elves of Felwithe.  I will take a detachment into the caverns of Guk and route them out once again, for good.  Thank you, again, all of you for your service.&#8221;<br><br>The general bowed to each one of the companions, even Jarnvid, who he only glowered at dubiously.  Jarnvid gave the General a toothy grin, and Brim saw several of the Paladins betray a smile in return.  Even Jyleel&#8217;s mouth twisted into a small grin before he spoke his final words, &#8220;Fare thee well, comrades.  May you live to have many adventures.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;We will General.  Our blessings to you.&#8221;<br><br>As the Elves sprinted off back into the forest, Izzi turned to his companions and asked with a mischievous grin, &#8220;So, what shall we do next, my friends?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Let&#8217;s head to Freeport,&#8221; responded Olwen.  &#8220;I know the best bar just outside the Eastern gate&#8230;&#8221;<br><br><br>fin

