Blair gazed intently at nothingness,  his mind digesting the latest developments at Crushbone.  Blair&#8217;s skill in the art of Necromancy was unparalleled by anyone in Neriak.  As a side effect,  Blair aged much quicker than his fellow Dark Elves.  Although Blair was only twelve years old,  he resembled an elf in his early twenties.   Because Blair found that the power of Necromancy flowed naturally in his veins,  he dedicated more and more time to the art of melee combat.  In the past few months,  Blair&#8217;s skill with a sword rivaled the best of warriors Neriak had to offer.  The capture of young Darien Sleighhill had come earlier than expected.   In Blair&#8217;s opinion,  the defenses of Freeport had not been weakened enough.   The Trolls and Ogres would suffer much heavier casualties than expected during the second phase of Lord Nafagen&#8217;s plan.   <br><br>&#8220;The Trolls and Ogres will be severely weakened.&#8221;  Blair noted to his fellow Dark Elves.  &#8220;It may not be wise to proceed at this point.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Would you like to be the one to inform Lord Nafagen that we have failed to execute his plan,   Lord D&#8217;eewlay?&#8221;  snarled Krast Ka&#8217;Pappan,  a skilled shadow knight.<br><br>&#8220;Mind who you speak to!&#8221;  snapped Tralon D&#8217;eewlay.   Although Tralon and Aerual D&#8217;eewlay were Blair&#8217;s parents and were well respected Necromancers in Neriak,  they knew better than to cross their son.  Fortunately for Krast Ka&#8217;Pappan,   Blair was feeling merciful this day<br><br>&#8220;I never said that we have failed,  Lord Ka&#8217;Pappan.   Lord Nafagen&#8217;s plan simply needs to be adjusted.  I will speak with him alone.   All of you,  leave my presence.&#8221;<br><br>The Dark Elves left single file out of the Lodge of the Dead.   Blair sat alone.   What would he tell Lord Nafagen?   Taking a deep breath,  Blair prepared to contact the Dragon Lord.<br><br>Darien Sleighhill felt the mana flow through his veins as he continued to heal Eralyn.  The cell the orc placed the two elves in was damp and bleak.  It had no windows and little chance of escape.  Escape was not the immediate concern on Darien&#8217;s mind at the moment however.  Slowly but surely,  Eralyn&#8217;s life force continued to strengthen.  Had Eralyn&#8217;s wounds been more severe,  Darien could not have helped her.  Slowly,  Eralyn began to regain consciousness.<br><br>&#8220;Where am I?&#8221;  Eralyn groaned.  &#8220;What is happening?&#8221;<br><br>Eralyn struggled to get on her feet, and instinctively clutched at her ribs and winced in pain.<br><br>&#8220;Do not try to move.  You are badly wounded.&#8221;  Darien said with concern.  &#8220;We are in Crushbone and in a lot of trouble.  Do you remember anything?&#8221;<br><br> Eralyn closed her eyes and tried to think.<br><br>&#8220;I remember being attacked by an orc.  You helped me,  then you were hurt.   No more&#8230;&#8221;   Eralyn gasped through the pain.  &#8220;What do we do now?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I don&#8217;t know.&#8221;  Darien answered truthfully.<br><br>&#8220;I&#8217;m scared Darien.&#8221;  Eralyn whispered.<br><br>Darien wanted to tell Eralyn that everything would be alright.   That they would be home soon for supper,  or that this was all just a bad dream.   Unfortunately,  it was not a dream.  It was all too real.  Darien would not lie to Eralyn and tell her everything would be okay when he didn&#8217;t know what was in store for them<br><br>&#8220;So am I.&#8221;  Darien finally replied.<br><br>	Lord Nafagen listened with keen ears as Lord D&#8217;eewlay informed him on the latest of news in Faydark.    Lord Nafagen&#8217;s plan to conquer the Eastern portion of Norrath hit its first obstacle in what seemed like a flawless plan.    Lord Nafagen had to exercise all of his self-control to keep from lashing out at the Dark Elf.   Lord D&#8217;eewlay wondered himself if it was so wise for him to travel to the dragon&#8217;s lair in person.  Perhaps he should have used magical communication.<br><br>&#8220;Lord D&#8217;eewlay.  You were a fool to trust those incompetent Crushbone Orcs.&#8221;  Lord Nafagen growled.<br><br>&#8220;They have their uses,  my lord.&#8221;  Blair said in the most humblest of tones.  Even the mighty Necromancer could not stand toe to toe versus the great wyrm Nafagen alone.   <br><br>&#8220;We must attack now then.&#8221;  Lord Nafagen concluded.  &#8220;The trolls and ogres will just have to fight harder to conquer Freeport.  Prepare to ransom off the Sleighhill boy.&#8221;<br><br>Lord D&#8217;eewlay  gazed upon the dragon for a moment, his mind racing.   There had to be a way to keep their army stronger for their invasion of Faydwer.<br><br>&#8220;With all due respect,  mighty Lord Nafagen.  May I suggest an alternative course of action?&#8221;  Blair asked.<br><br>The Dragon lord listened as Blair D&#8217;eewlay outlined his new sinister plan on how to reach Faydark with their forces intact.<br><br>	Jeyna Sleighhill sat by the fire in her chambers alone.   Darien was late for dinner yet again.  Jeyna had decided to give her son an earful when he returned home.  Any minute now,  Darien would come running through the door,  a happy playful mess as he always did.   Any minute now&#8230;  Jeyna had told herself that for the last hour,  and there was no sign of Darien.   Darien&#8217;s dinner was long cold now.  Suddenly,  there was a knock on the Sleighhill door.  It wasn&#8217;t like Darien to knock.  Jeyna rose from her chair and answered the door,  fully expecting Darien to be standing on the other side.<br><br>&#8220;Young elfling,  you better have a good explanation&#8230;&#8221;  Jeyna started.   At the door was an elven messenger.  <br><br>&#8220;Lady Sleighhill.  An emergency session of the council has been called.   You presence is required.&#8221;  The messenger said.  Jeyna&#8217;s heart sank as she somehow felt some terrible misfortune had befallen her son.   She immediately rushed out of her house with speed and made her way to the council room.<br><br>	The mood in the council room was gloomy as Ambassador D&#8217;vinn  listed off his demands in exchange for the release of Darien Sleighhill.   Included in those demands were two million platinum to be forwarded to Neriak,  and the withdrawal of all elven forces in Freeport.   As the telecommunications portal closed,  the council was more silent as it has ever been in a millennium.   The silence was to be broken by the quiet sobs of Jeyna Sleighhill.<br><br>Meanwhile,  back in Crushbone,  D&#8217;vinn was very satisfied with what had just occurred.   He knew very well that the elves would not give into his demands.   He was counting on that.   In fact,  he was hoping more reinforcements would be sent to Freeport.  He sat in his chair and turned to Darien Sleighhill,  who was being restrained by two orc legionnaires.<br><br>&#8220;Soon,  my young friend.  The elven council will fall,  and all your people will die.  If you are fortunate enough,  you will live to see the beginnings of the new order.&#8221;  D&#8217;vinn remarked.<br><br>&#8220;You fiend.   My mother will never give into your demands.  Your plan,  whatever it is will fail.&#8221;  Darien spat back.<br><br>Ambassador D&#8217;vinn rose from his chair,  and swiftly delivered a backhand across the face of Darien.   Darien fell to the ground.   <br><br>&#8220;Stop it!&#8221;  Eralyn screamed.   She too,  was restrained by two orc legionaries.<br><br>D&#8217;vinn went over to Eralyn,  and backhanded her as well.  She fell to the ground and began to cry<br><br>Darien noticed this and the anger grew in him.  It seemed to him in the last few days that Eralyn had given up all hope.  Darien knew that D&#8217;vinn had no intention of releasing them.   He could not wait for his mother to come rescue him.   Darien looked around,  the legionnaires were laughing.  D&#8217;vinn was not paying attention,  now was his chance.  With one quick motion,  he lunged for the sheath of a legionnaire and stole his sword.  He quickly slashed the legionnaire across the midsection,  spilling his intestines.   D&#8217;vinn turned around just in time to see this.<br><br>&#8220;Stop him!&#8221;  D&#8217;vinn screamed.<br><br>The remaining three legionnaires closed in on young Darien,  who maintained a defensive position.   Darien had his back to a wall.  On the wall was the single lantern that provided light to the room they were in.  Darien turned around and struck the lantern with all his might.  The room became pitch black.  The only ones who could now see were the elves in the room.  Darien quickly made his way to Eralyn and grabbed her by the arm<br><br>&#8220;Come on!&#8221;  Darien urged.<br><br>Darien pulled Eralyn to her feet and they bolted for the door.   Only one thing stood in their way,   D'vinn.   Darien slashed at D&#8217;vinn,  who dodged the attack.  D&#8217;vinn countered by attempting to pierce Darien with his dagger,  but Darien saw the counter coming and parried the attack.   Eralyn then intervened by giving D&#8217;vinn a swift kick in the groin,  and D&#8217;vinn dropped like a sack of potatoes to the ground.   Darien and Eralyn bolted out the door and searched for a way out of Crushbone,  leaving D&#8217;vinn and the orcs behind in a pitch black room of total chaos.

