<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Rare Spawns</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Jace Von Varius  (<a href="mailto:jace_von_varius@yahoo.com" class="credit2">jace_von_varius@yahoo.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2"></a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
<center><b><a href="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?mes=5620110">Discuss and Debate This Article</a></b></center><br><br>Rare Spawns. <br><br>Those single two words have sparked issues of incredible size. Play-nice rules, E-Bay, and many other problems have cropped up simply because some spawns (Fishbone Earring, JBoots, Erudin Library Book) are far too rare for their own good. Why is this? No one here wants to wait 8 hours before a part of a needless quest pops. No one wants to deal with people who time their kills. So why are some spawns and items so rare? <br><br>Verant, would it really hurt the game SO MUCH if all the 50+ characters were able to collect a pair of JBoots, and a Fishbone Earring? Instead of these headaches (and for those of us that cannot play 36+ hours straight...), why not put these items in another quest, or put the item in another spawn and raise the difficulty? Why not have these wonderful items available on some merchant in a high level of, say, the Plane of Sky? The current quest for the JBoots is good (except for needing SOW to receive it from the guy in the FIRST place...), so just put one in for the other things. <br><br>Items like the Fishbone Earring are supposed to be really valuable, right? That's why you keep them with such a long spawn type, right? Well here's a thought- put 'em on a GOD or a DRAGON! I could easily see someone really high (50+) in Prexus' hierarchy having a Fishbone Earring. <br><br>Some items are just stupid, the way their spawns are. The page in the Erudin Book, for example. With the time this spawn takes, you might as well just have a separate quest to get the one page! Hell, that would be BETTER! <br><br>But still, the main point of my editorial is thus- why do the rare spawns have to be so rare? Is there no alternative?<br><br><center><b><a href="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?mes=5620110">Discuss and Debate This Article</b></a></center>

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem957568061,3411,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Play Nice Exchange</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Selvas  (<a href="mailto:aseca@rt66.com" class="credit2">aseca@rt66.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
<center><b><a href="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?mes=5582033">Respond & Debate this Article</b></a></center><br><P><br>Dear Fellow Gamers:<br><p>I submit the following e-mail exchanges with Verant as an editorial<br>comment regarding Verant's "play nice" policy, and its overall player interaction<br>policies. I believe the NATURE of the responses (i.e., delays, delegation,<br>inadequate reply, etc.) says something significant about Verant. After<br>setting aside my original annoyances and frustrations, however, I was fascinated<br>by the realization that the game HAS taken on a life of its own, and that<br>even the nasty turns are consistent with the evolution of a fantasy world<br>which the "creators" likely CANNOT truly control any more (although they<br><u>could</u> admittedly nerf or bureaucratize it to death).<br><p><u>Original E-mail sent to cfolz@verant.com on 4/16/2000, cc to eqmail@verant.com</u>:<br><p>Greetings:<br><p>The cfolz email address was reluctantly given to me by a Guide when<br>I stated that I wished to have an address to direct further communication<br>regarding the referenced attachment. I trust that I was not simply given<br>GM Seign's address as a ploy to misdirect my complaint. In any event, I<br>have cc'd eqmail, and I SPECIFICALLY REQUEST that a copy of this e-mail<br>and its attachment be forwarded to Gordon Wrinn, Internet Relations Manager<br>for Verant Interactive, Inc.<br><p>I have no objection to GM Seign receiving a copy of this e-mail, and<br>presume it will be shown to him for his response. As is reasonable, however,<br>I insist on a reply from someone higher in the EQ hierarchy, since this<br>complaint is directed at his failure to apply an EQ rule.<br><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>April 16, 2000<br><p>John Smedley, President<br><br>Verant Interactve, Inc.<br><br>8958 Terman Court<br><br>San Diego, CA 92121<br><p>Re: Everquest/ your "play nice" policy, a spawn dispute and your "Seign"<br>GM on Rodcet Nife<br><p>Gentlemen:<br><p>I play on Rodcet Nife as "Selvas." In recent months, I had been watching<br>developments in increased kill stealing and game abuse violations with<br>concern and consternation. I was therefore preliminarily pleased to see<br>that you were attempting to address the problem with your new "play nice"<br>policy (the "play nice" label, by the way, was a peculiar piece of self-sabotage,<br>since it evokes kindergarten images and most likely has insulted game players<br>into a default negative stance). The producer letter description of the<br>need, however, was well articulated, because you only have to browse the<br>editorial and message pages of the various excellent EQ sites to see that<br>self-serving groups and even whole guilds HAVE virtually taken over unique<br>spawn sites to the detriment of non-member players. Individual abuses and<br>harassments have increased without question.<br><p>It was with some interest in your new policy, therefore, that I invoked<br>your "resolution" process on Friday night. Here was the situation:<br><p>-- For some months, I have been checking the Dyllin Starshine spawn<br>in HH, for the Book of Vanear page drop. This is a highly camped spot and<br>is rarely free, with a respawn of about 6-8 hours. At various times, I<br>had waited until boredom or other commitments had taken me elsewhere.<br><p>-- On Friday night, I found the spawn clear at about midnight, and proceeded<br>to wait, not knowing when Dyllin could next be expected.<br><p>-- Approximately one hour later, a halfling druid by the name of Haeen<br>appeared, and insisted that I should leave and that the spawn belonged<br>to him, because he had been there earlier and had "timed" the spawn. I<br>explained, assuming that he had been there earlier, that he had lost his<br>spot by leaving, and that I would not relinquish it back to him. He then<br>implied that his spell-casting would enable him to take the spawn away<br>from me, and he proceeded to try to "inspect" my equipment repeatedly without<br>permission.<br><p>-- Please note that this druid was green to me as a 26 Cleric, and I<br>believe I could have simply waited for the spawn and outblasted and outmeleed<br>him. But NO....he was an irritating and arrogant little smear whose behavior<br>was, I believed, directly and clearly contrary to the newly announced rules.<br>I therefore decided to invoke these rules rather than rely on MY superior<br>position, and rather than get into an odious pvp encounter. I petitioned<br>a GM.<br><p>-- After some time, but before the spawn appeared, GM Seign gated in.<br>I explained that Haeen was claiming the spawn because he had "timed" it,<br>and Seign initially conceded that returning to a "timed" spawn does not<br>give a player priority if someone else is already there. Seign then proceeded<br>to ask "who was here first?" Haeen claimed he was, but admitted that he<br>had left "to kill some blues and run errands." I advised Seign that I had<br>been there for about an hour with no other players present, which Haeen<br>disputed and said had been only "20 minutes." Haeen also admitted to Seign<br>that he had returned at this time because he had "timed" Dyllin to appear,<br>and that he was entitled to the spawn because other players had kill-stolen<br>the spawn from him before. Haeen also was very clear about how he hadn't<br>reported this supposed kill-stealing because didn't like or agree with<br>the "play nice" policy.<br><p>-- So, the indisputable facts were:<br><br>1) I had been at the site for at least 20 minutes(Haeen's admission),<br>and as long as an hour(my recollection), with no other player present;<br><br>2) Haeen might have been at the site earlier, but had left. There was<br>no way of verifying when he had been there or for how long.<br><br>3) Haeen's main claim to priority at the site was that he had "timed"<br>the next spawn.<br><p>-- You must understand my shock, therefore, when Seign the announced<br>that he could not determine who was there "first", and would settle the<br>dispute with having us do a dice roll.<br><p>-- I advised Seign that this was unacceptable and unprincipled, since<br>he had enough evidence to make a ruling, not cop out. When he insisted<br>that this was the only "fair" thing he could do, I told him that I would<br>not participate in the dice roll, and I left. I did not feel that this<br>spawn was so important that I should have to ratify Seign's peculiar solution<br>by participating in it. I have no idea what happened to the spawn, but<br>I assume that the strident little druid got his wish.<br><p>-- In further conversation with Seign, he insisted that the "only fair"<br>thing he could do was to use the dice roll. I eventually asked him to preserve<br>a full copy of the encounter, so that others could review it fresh. It<br>wasn't until after I logged off that I realized I could have saved it myself,<br>as a series of screen shots.<br><p>The problem, as I see it, is this:<br><p>-- You have a policy in which you wish to enhance player satisfaction<br>by encouraging fair play and discouraging intimidating, territorial and<br>possessive behavior. Among other things, exclusive campings and "reservations"<br>are not permissible.<br><br>-- To assist in this policy, you have set up your GMs and guides to<br>apply these rules of fair play and to sanction bad behavior, if warranted.<br><br>-- It is clear that a player may not assert "possession" of a spawn<br>site after he has abandoned it.<br><br>-- It is equally clear that "timing" a spawn does not entitle a player<br>to "possession" of a site after he has abandoned it - this is simply a<br>rational corollary of the rule.<br><br>-- It is clear that I was the only player on site when the other player<br>with his "timing" claim appeared.<br><br>-- Seign chose to ignore the fact that Haeen had abandoned the site,<br>and that I had been waiting alone for the spawn for some time.<br><br>-- IF EQ policy IS to decide ALL of these issues with a dice roll,<br>as suggested by Seign and his guides (who were, by the way, oddly reluctant<br>to give me a name or address to whom I could direct this further communication),<br>then EQ should make that announcement in a new producer letter so that<br>players are not misled into believing that they can expect fair rulings<br>instead of random results.<br><br>-- It seems to me, however, that EQ may actually intend and prefer<br>to provide just and fair resolutions when possible. In that light, please<br>examine what happens when dice rolls always settle disputes:<br><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The "bad guys" don't CARE. They're in it to manipulate<br>the system. "Why can't we all just get along" and "you guys should go out<br>and settle it between yourselves" are the refrains they MOST like to hear.<br>When the judge then leaves, the bad guy smirks...he has won.<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1) the good guys don't KS or spawn steal. They generally<br>apologize and leave when they realize they have inadvertantly intruded<br>on someone else's kill. The bad guys therefore rarely have their sites<br>disputed when they get there first.<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2) When there exists enough evidence to make a ruling,<br>but the GM refuses to do so because of inexperience or discomfort with<br>the responsibility, the bad guy wins. Consider: the bad guy's legitimate<br>camps will not be disputed by the good guy...but when the good guy's legitimate<br>camps are disputed by the bad guy, he (or she) get a 50% statistical chance<br>of beating the good guy out of his spot with a dice roll. It doesn't take<br>a mathematics wizard to realize that dice rolls work VERY nicely to the<br>advantage of the bad guy. The bad guy wins again.<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3) the bad guys generally have no compunction about<br>lying. For this reason, GMs should inquire about testimony fron other players.<br>Nevertheless, many situations will boil down to unresolvable evidence (can't<br>tell who is lying) Those probably only can be resolved with a dice roll.<br>The bad guy wins again, but this is the ONLY scenario that can't be helped<br>at first. However...GM staff should be keeping a player complaint file<br>to see if one or the other of those players is consistently a party to<br>complaints. After a certain threshold, EQ should have a pretty good idea<br>that such a player is manipulating this built-in uncertainty.<br><p>So...what are you going to do? The larger issue is whether EQ intends<br>to do the right thing...or the easy, convenient thing. You have created<br>a wonderful game which is indeed developing into a "society," but there<br>are snakes in this paradise which must be dealt with. The Game is evolving<br>at an amazing rate, and may become something quite surprising and important<br>....if it survives. You people have quite an interesting responsiblity<br>AND opportunity here. Do not discount the importance of your treatment<br>of this issue (which might be defined as the Administration and Application<br>of Justice on EQ). You have only to read the multiple postings at the various<br>sites on the reasons for dissatisfaction, to understand the potential impact.<br>I would presume that your direct "feedback" file also has a plethora of<br>aggravated complaints on these issues.<br><p>On my more personal isuue...what are you going to do? I believe there<br>is really no reasonable question as to what the result should have been<br>-- unless EQ wishes to announce that "timing" spawns bumps waiting players<br>as a priority. I was so frustrated and frankly infuriated by your GM's<br>"solution", after I voluntarily elected to abide by and apply EQ's new<br>rules, that I almost terminated my membership on the spot. There is no<br>correction of the specific spawn problem now possible, since it involved<br>no-drop items, but I believe that I deserve an apology from both Verant<br>and Seign, that Haeen should be advised of what the correct ruling should<br>have been, and that Seign should be admonished to do his job correctly<br>and trained to make that possible.<br><p>Please understand that in addition to my complaint, this letter is intended<br>as a heartfelt plea for EQ to correct a continuing and serious problem<br>which likely will have very bad long-term repercussions for the viability<br>of a game that I dearly love... if not corrected.<br><p>As final constructive criticism, allow me to point out that this is<br>potentially an extremely complex game because of its online player interfaces,<br>and that future expansions, additions, tweakings and interactions will<br>make it more so. The judging of disputes is NOT a casual matter, which<br>everyone is capable of doing competently. Both talent and training in dispute<br>resolution is generally required, especially if you do not wish affected<br>parties to leave these encounters feeling thoroughly cheated, and resentful<br>of EQ. So...wouldn't it be interesting to have some sort of player-ratified<br>court system in EQ? Just a thought. I believe you could tap much player<br>experience to aid in such a venture. I myself, as I pointed out to your<br>GM, have quite a bit of backgound in this subject area.<br><p>The bottom line for me is that much as I love this game, I do not need<br>to participate in a virtual world where the aggravations I face in the<br>Real World are duplicated or exacerbated. I need to know that EQ will resolve<br>this issue. Please provide me with a reply at your earliest opportunity.<br><p>Sincerely,<br><br>"Selvas" on Rodcet Nife<br><p><u>E-mail to cfolz@verant.com on 4/18/2000, cc to eqmail@verant.com:</u><br><p>Mr. Folz--<br><p>I would appreciate receiving an acknowledgement that you received my<br>letter of 4/16/2000, and that a copy has been forwarded to your Mr. Wrinn<br>for his attention.<br><p>Selvas on Rodcet Nife<br><p><u>E-mail to jsmedley@verant.com on 4/19/2000, cc to gwrinn@verant.com</u>:<br><p>Mr. Smedley--<br><p>I have tried since Saturday the 16th to receive at least some acknowledgement<br>of receipt of my letter to Verant...with no response. I also originally<br>asked that my letter be forwarded to Mr. Wrinn's attention...no response.<br>I am beginning to wonder if my complaint has been lost or intentionally<br>misdirected by others in the Verant sequence. My original e-mail on this<br>was to a cfolz -- the only further contact that Rodcet Nife guides would<br>(reluctantly) give me.<br><p>As you can see from my attached letter, I have some serious concerns<br>about your GM's and guides' understandings and enforcements of Verant's<br>game policies. I and quite a number of other players are awaiting a response<br>to this letter with some interest.<br><p>Sincerely,<br><br>Selvas on Rodcet Nife<br><br>&nbsp;<br><p><u>E-mail received on 4/26/2000 from lcarrick@verant.com:</u><br><p>As Head GM for Verant's Customer Service program, I am in charge of<br>all the server GMs. I do not believe I received your original message,<br>but if you wish, you may send it to me directly. Thank you,<br><p>C. Lynn Carrick<br><br>Head Game Master<br><br>Verant Interactive<br><br>lcarrick@verant.com<br><br>&nbsp;<br><p><u>E-mail to lcarrick@verant.com on 4/26/2000:</u><br><p>GM Carrick--<br><p>I have posted e-mails to Mssrs. Smedley and Wrinn about this issue,<br>and yours is the only response I have yet received, of _any_ sort. You<br>are welcome to a copy of my original letter, and it is attached. I make<br>here two observations, not noted by me previously, based upon my surfing<br>of the various EQ websites and e-mail discussions with fellow game players<br>during my absence from game playing these past two weeks:<br><p>1) The new GM Seign does not generally enjoy a good reputation among<br>other game players -- his decisions are by and large considered to be arbitrary<br>and unprincipled, and it is believed that his guides are following his<br>example. My only experience with him, however, is in this one issue, and<br>I obviously was less than impressed. Traikis was held in much higher regard.<br><p>2) It seems to me that Verant staff have ignored comments or complaints<br>that haven't been publicly posted. If true, this is very poor PR. For me,<br>it has been 12 days since my problem occurred and I attempted to bring<br>it to someone's attention for response. In the meantime, there have been<br>dozens of response postings by Mr. Wrinn about issues of much lesser importance.<br>I expect to be posting my letter and questions about Verant's non-responsiveness<br>within the next couple of days, unless I receive a substantive and fair<br>reply very soon.<br><p>Nevertheless, thank you for your inquiry.<br><p>Selvas, on Rodcet Nife<br><br>&nbsp;<br><p><u>E-mail received on 4/27/2000 from lcarrick@verant.com:</u><br><p>Since I received your first email, GM Seign was released from our program.<br>As he is<br><br>no longer on Rodcet Nife, I imagine your problem is fairly well resolved.<br>If not,<br><br>feel free to contact me at your convenience. I'm afraid I did not open<br>your<br><br>attachment - could you please re-send it in the body of your email,<br>if there is more<br><br>that I should address?<br><p>Thank you,<br><br>C. Lynn Carrick<br><br>Head Game Master<br><br>Verant Interactive<br><br>lcarrick@verant.com<br><br>&nbsp;<br><p><u>E-mail to lcarrick@verant.com on 4/27/2000:</u><br><br>&nbsp;<br><p>I am not quite sure why you are having difficulty opening a standard<br>WordPerfect attachment, and I continue to be puzzled as to why Mr. Smedley<br>and Mr. Wrinn have not seen fit to provide me with a reply, but Seign's<br>departure does _nothing_ to answer my concerns, unless you are telling<br>me that he was let go for violation of the rules I cited, and you provide<br>me with a more detailed response regarding the corrections contemplated<br>overall. In any event, here is yet another copy of my letter:<br><br>&nbsp;<br><p><u>E-mail from lcarrick@verant.com on 4/28/2000:</u><br><p>I have no difficulty whatsoever opening attachments, but I choose not<br>to do so for virus protection reasons. Mr. Smedley and Mr. Wrinn receive<br>so much email in a day's time that selected issues are handed to those<br>who are in the most logical position to answer them. Although you have<br>a very good understanding of the rules, it seems there was one slight misconception<br>in the incident you described. Please let me explain. The "Play Nice Policies"<br>were, in fact, intended to prevent any player from claiming title to any<br>spawn, and when there is a contested spawn, the GM is directed to advise<br>all parties to share it in rotation, using a random roll to decide who<br>goes first, if it has been determined that the players can not or will<br>not reach an agreement on their own. The facts that one player arrived<br>first or second, or spent any length of time at a spot are irrelevant.<br>If you have any further questions about the policies, feel free to send<br>them along via email.<br><p>Regarding Seign's release, I do not feel it is appropriate to publicize<br>such matters, and will only say that his qualifications turned out to be<br>mismatched with our needs for the GM position.<br><p>Thank you,<br><br>C. Lynn Carrick<br><br>Head Game Master<br><br>Verant Interactive<br><br>lcarrick@verant.com<br><br>&nbsp;<br><p><u>E-mail to lcarrick@verant.com on 4/29/2000:</u><br><p>GM Carrick:<br><p>Your response has indeed clarified a number of issues with which I was<br>concerned, and has given me a much better understanding of Verant's gameplayer<br>relations. My observations and conclusions are as follows, which I shall<br>pass on to fellow players who have expressed interest in the matter:<br><p>-- Verant, though you, has essentially blown off my detailed assessment<br>of the problems that exist with your "play nice" policy. Saying that I<br>misunderstood, that the involved GM is now gone, and that you will not<br>comment on the reason for his departure is blatant abrogation of responsibility...but<br>IS consistent.<br><p>-- If indeed I have misunderstood Verant<font face="WP TypographicSymbols">=</font>s<br>policy, then I believe this is because it was unintelligible and confusing<br>to start with. More important, however, is that as "Head GM," with apparent<br>authority to make such statements, you have now clarified "play nice" so<br>that everyone should understand the following--<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -There IS NO first-come, first-served fairness rule,<br>implied or otherwise;<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - It DOESN'T MATTER how long a player has been waiting<br>for a difficult spawn in ANY circumstance;<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; - The FIRST player to attack a mob "gets" it, according<br>to "play nice." So if a more powerful player wants <u>any</u> mob, he can<br>simply step in and attack first, regardless of who else is around, or how<br>long they've waited. VERANT THEREFORE SUPPORTS THE PREEMPTIVE STRIKE AND<br>FREE-FOR-ALL APPROACH TO SPAWN OWNERSHIP.<br><p>As I explained in my earlier letter, this means that a player with no<br>interest in fairness issues may simply appear at a spawn site and take<br>a newly spawned mob with no fear of impunity. If he is smart, he won't<br>announce his intentions, and your administrative dice-roller will not be<br>called. Once he HAS the mob, there is no foul, no fault, according to your<br>rules. Too bad for the patient questor who has waited for two hours, or<br>two days.<br><p>It is irritating for me to realize that I have been so naive. I really<br>thought that Verant seriously wanted to fix this problem, when in fact<br>it is apparent that Verant only wanted players to THINK they wanted to<br>do so. My mistake was obviously in paying too much attention to the administrative/bureaucratic<br>noise of Verant's policy-makers, rather than to the game itself...I looked<br>for rational and needed answers in the wrong place.<br><p>I will continue to play according to my principles of fairness ... that<br>is my inclination and the role I choose in the game. I will, however, ignore<br>the "play nice" policy as any meaningful codification of fairness. It is<br>now quite understandable to me why many players and guilds prefer to pursue<br>vigilante "justice," since it would frankly be irrational for any player<br>to do anything but keep his own counsel in these matters.<br><p>It occurs to me that in a larger role-playing context, GMs and Verant<br>administrators should be treated as randomly behaving, unpredictable petty<br>gods of the game...and therefore should largely be ignored and avoided,<br>when possible...and whose actions must be suffered with and tolerated when<br>not.<br><p>As for Mr. Smedley and Mr. Wrinn being too busy to "answer all posts,"<br>I simply observe that there have been literally dozens of posts by them<br>about relatively minor issues, including a number of vanity posts regarding<br>Mr. Wrinn's game playing prowess and preferences, in contrast with the<br>more substantive matters raised by me. I recognize, however, that minor<br>gods have always been known to relish flattery and to dislike having mere<br>mortals try to hold them accountable for their acts. In a peculiar and<br>perhaps predictable way, the unfolding dynamics of the game, even in its<br>irritating aspects, demonstrates that the game has taken on a life of its<br>own. Interesting.<br><p>Thank you again for your courtesy in finally providing me with a response.<br><p>Sincerely,<br><br>Selvas-- Cleric on Rodcet Nife<br><P><br><center><b><a href="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?mes=5582033">Respond & Debate this Article</b></a></center>

