<span class="credit2">John  (<a href="mailto:jthiatt@earthlink.net" class="credit2">jthiatt@earthlink.net</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
The far northern reaches of Permafrost pose a challenge to even the hardiest and most experienced travelers. Crevasses and drop holes slick with ice and covered in a thin blanket of snow routinely swallow the unwary before the dreaded dire wolfs and great white arctic bears ever have a chance to pick up a scent of their passing. Snowstorms and straight winds blowing in from the frigid Western Sea freeze exposed skins in moments or can bury entire caravans in just a few short hours. Understandably, few ever brave these dangers. But here in harmony with the snow and ice is where Barbarians prosper. Here is where the Clan of the White Bear makes their home.<br><br>The lodges of the White Bear People stood empty; no fires burned low to warm the people, no sounds were lifted by the gentle breeze blowing in from the north. The people, shrouded in a mood of somber expectation, slowly made their way to the center of their winter base camp. This was the focal point of the community where feasts were held, holy days observed, and when necessary trials were held. Even the camp dogs, vicious and ever alert to danger, sensing the people&#8217;s sobriety, milled quietly around the tents they had claimed as their own with hardly a whimper or growl.<br><br>In the center of the camp, lit by gas lamps fueled with whale oil and seal fat, stood the six Clan Elders, holy shamans hard and serious in this time of judgement. When the people had gathered, Aolis, Garggenstakken of the White Bear Clan [literally translated as He-Who-Leads-In-Plenty-And-Want] opened the gathering with the formal introduction of the Six.<br><br>&#8220;By Hammer and Blood, we meet under open sky. In the name of Truth and Justice, we seek guidance from the Tribunal of Six. Let the claimant come forward.&#8221;<br><br>A huge young man, a solid seven feet tall and pushing 300 lbs., strode forcefully into the lamplight. His face was a study of the rugged northern male &#8211; blue eyes and a strong face wreathed in a thick mane of long golden hair. Although flanked by two older men, whose experience and competence showed in their every move, the large barbarian youth was clearly used to commanding them and many more just like them.<br><br>&#8220;Who come before us seeking Justice from the Six?&#8221; asked Aolis.<br>&#8220;I, Eolric, of the Eagle Claw Clan, seek justice from the Six.&#8221;<br>&#8220;And will you abide by our decision as revealed by the Six and keep peace no matter the decree&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I will,&#8221; answered Eolric.<br>&#8220;State your claim, Eolric.&#8221;<br><br>Eolric straightened his back looming to his full seven feet and paused as if to collect his thoughts. Without doubt, this made him look the consummate heroic warrior: young, brash, and yet controlled under pressure. A canny observer might have also seen it as a means to harness his anger and indignation. Aolis inwardly smiled in understanding.<br><br>&#8220;I have traveled many leagues through the dead of winter risking much to the dangers of the Plains. I came in time for Wintersheight to feast with you and honor the joint rule of Marr and the Six. I came bearing gifts with my wife, Hallywin, and my father, Waol, son of Borgynn and Harvenstakken [He-Who-Leads-In-Strife] of the Eagle Claw People, with a full honor guard of seasoned warriors. I came to honor the alliance between our clans, as agreed during the festival of Wintersrest.<br><br>I came in good faith, and yet I and the Eagle Claw Clan were met with betrayal and dishonor. Jamki, step forward and relate your tale.&#8221;<br>One of the men standing behind Eolric took one step forward to stand at Eolric&#8217;s left shoulder. At close to six and a half feet tall, he would make a formidable opponent and yet beside his young leader he seemed small and uncomfortable with his role in so solemn a proceeding.<br><br>&#8220;I, uh, excuse me,&#8221; he said clearing his throat. &#8220;It was two nights ago, Elders, after the feast and well past the high moon. Me and Kellen were grooming our dogs and drinking up the last of our mead. Everyone else was pretty much asleep or at least in their lodges and tents. I had to, uh, wet the snow so to speak when I saw Hallywin and your man Tamurlane down behind some rocks. They were, uh, otherwise engaged, Elder, and didn&#8217;t notice me.&#8221;<br><br>Eolric&#8217;s face tightened almost imperceptibly, but his knuckles as they gripped the hilt of his sheathed two-hander would have made a white ptarmigan look dirty.<br><br>&#8220;Well, I forgot all about needing to pee, Elder, and I went straightaway to get you.&#8221;<br>&#8220;Why did not you not go to Eolric, Jamkin? Is he not your commander?&#8221; asked Aolis.<br><br>&#8220;Well, uh, we was afraid he might kill your man, sir,&#8221; replied Jamkin. &#8220;Didn&#8217;t think that would do on a holy day. Just thinkin&#8217; of him you see. Thought it&#8217;d be better if you handle things right off.&#8221;<br>&#8220;I see.&#8221;<br><br>The six shamans sat quietly digesting what they were told and <br>revealing nothing in their faces. The crowd had grown impossibly quiet, not even the creaking of boiled leather or the whispering of cloth to indicate any movement at all.<br><br>Jamkin, obviously relieved the questioning was over and so easily done, stepped back to stand behind Eolric. Eolric, pausing for a few moments for the facts to be processed by everyone present, resumed the hearing by stating his charge.<br><br>&#8220;It is commonly held among all our people that adultery deserves death, Elders. Tamurlane slept with my wife. He brought dishonor to me. He flaunted the law of the People. I ask for my due. Give Tamurlane to Marr and let this matter be decided by combat.&#8221;<br>&#8220;No!&#8221; screamed a woman from well behind the assembled people. &#8220;That is not what happened.&#8221;<br><br>The crowd stirred not at all. Aolis, taking pride in their devotion to the Six, gazed for a moment upon the crowd and then he called for the woman to be brought forward.<br><br>Hallywin, despite being haggard and worn from her two days of anxious confinement, boldly strode between two honor guards to stand proudly before the Elders and her husband. She was breathtaking even in her state. Tall and strong, she embodied the stereotypical Northern warrior maiden and then put the stereotype to shame. Without waiting for formal leave, she spoke.<br><br>&#8220;Tamurlane did not dishonor anyone. He did not know who I was or who I was married to.  I guess I could have made it plain, but I really wasn&#8217;t interested in wasting much time in small talk. And since we are on the subject, why don&#8217;t you ask Eolric where he spent that evening. I tell you this, jealousy drives this hearing, not dishonor. And if my husband had shown the least degree of faithfulness in our marr&#8230;&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;That is enough, Hallywin,&#8221; stated Eolric quietly but with a firmness that gave pause to everyone who had heard.<br>Aolis&#8217; eyebrows rose a degree.<br><br>&#8220;In light of the lady&#8217;s statements, do you stand by your charge, Eolric?&#8221; asked Aolis knowing the answer before it was said.<br>&#8220;I do.&#8221;<br><br>Aolis sighed to himself, careful to display nothing of his thoughts. Inwardly, he berated himself. Why hadn&#8217;t he seen this or something like it happening long ago? Tamurlane had been a loose cannon since he came into the Elders&#8217; care 12 years ago. He remembered that day well. Bruised and barely conscious due to a beating by his father, may the Six shower justice upon him, it was doubtful whether the boy would even make it. His father, a violent drunk but an incomparable warrior, had a long history of abusing his family. Ultimately, after almost killing Tamurlane, he lost his life to the Six in sacrifice and penance decided in a hearing much like the one Aolis was now presiding over. His mother left to return to her Clan. She never made it. Rumors of suicide abounded. Publicly, she died in an orc raid.<br>Tamurlane was given to Woodson, now an Elder and standing to his right, to nurse back to health. In the weeks after the beating, as his talent for manipulating the life force of Norrath, manna, became apparent, Woodson took over his training.<br><br>Should they have cut their losses sooner? Tamurlane showed such potential, his gift for working spells and healings was almost savant in its nature. But he was soft inside. Completely unwilling to make even the most minor of decisions and unable to open himself up to guidance from the Six as necessary to pass judgements, he labored in seeming futility without hope of becoming a full-fledged shaman of the people. Furthermore, the boy had taken to drinking excessively just like his father. At least he didn&#8217;t have that tough, old bastard&#8217;s temper. Soft, thought Aolis. Soft and lazy. The only things he seemed to apply himself to at all were sleeping with any woman willing and drinking too much.<br><br>&#8220;Bring Tamurlane forward,&#8221; Aolis said bringing himself back to the task at hand.<br><br>Tamurlane was escorted under guard from one of the small sweat lodges constructed near the site of the hearing to stand before the Elders. He had been alternating between the heat of the sweat lodge and the cold of sleeping on bare snow covered ground for the past two days in an effort by the Elders to purify him for this hearing. Truth told, he felt tired and worn, but not the least bit pure.<br><br>&#8220;You have heard the charges laid against you by Eolric, son of Borgynn, and the statements made by his wife, Hollywin?&#8221; asked Aolis.<br>&#8220;I have.&#8221;<br>&#8220;And what say you to these charges?&#8221;<br>&#8220;I don&#8217;t know.&#8221;<br><br>Aolos almost spluttered in disbelief. Years of training and countless hours spent schooling himself in the disciplines of the Six were the only things that kept him seemingly implacable. Even so, his eyes widened slightly. Tamurlane&#8217;s face broke into a very small smile. He had spent the last two days trying to piece together what had happened to no avail.<br><br>If he knew she was married, she could claim he seduced or even raped her. This would surely get him death, but for her punishment would probably only amount to months of confinement and a loss of her position as a Hunt Leader. <br><br>If she claimed their coupling was consensual, exile or death would occur. The Elders of the Eagle Claw Clan would decide her fate. His would be decided right then, and would probably mean a battle to the death with Eolric. Whose death was not in question. A half-trained shaman wouldn&#8217;t stand the chance of a snowflake in sunlight if pitted against that giant of man. And he could only be a couple of years older than Tamurlane&#8217;s seventeen. <br><br>But for her to say he had no knowledge of her identity at all? Something wasn&#8217;t quite right in her marriage to Eolric or else she was more honest than any person he had ever met. Looking at the distaste in her eyes as she looked up her husband indicated to Tamurlane that it wasn&#8217;t the latter.<br><br>&#8220;I don&#8217;t know,&#8221; he repeated. &#8220;The only parts of that night I can remember I don&#8217;t think Eolric wants me to repeat.&#8221;<br>Now Aolis did sigh in spite of his position and duties. Eolric had a vein on his temple that swelled to the size of an elven forearm.<br>&#8220;I want you dead, child,&#8221; Eolric growled at Tamurlane and took a step in his direction.<br><br>&#8220;Hold, &#8220; said Aolis stopping Eolric before he had taken the second. &#8220;Do not despoil this sacred hearing. Show some respect for the Six.<br><br>&#8220;We have heard enough. Stand fast and we will return with our judgement.&#8221;<br><br>With that, Aolis and the other five Elders, holy representatives of the Six on Norrath, retired to a large sweat lodge to decide the facts and pass judgement. The two hours passed slowly, a palpable feeling of anxiety intermingling amongst all present. Still, not a sound was heard and the People of the White Bear stood absolutely still as directed.<br><br>Tamurlane couldn&#8217;t decide if he was worried or not. Even at his age, death was not a stranger. How often had he known his father would not stop a beating before killing him? The worthless piece of dung always did, obviously, but the last one was damn close. How often had he thought of his mother&#8217;s death? How did it happen, or did that really matter? How often had he himself brought himself to the brink of death doing something stupid on the plains or the northern shores? Maybe death would be welcome. He definitely needed a drink.<br><br>Minutes turned into an hour which then turned into two, and finally the Elders emerged. Aolis made it short.<br><br>&#8220;We know three things not revealed during the hearing. One, Tamurlane spent the last fortnight gathering lichens for us on the northern shores. That he still does this nearly two years past what is proper reflects poorly on us, his teachers, and should bring shame upon him. He did return in time for the feast, but it was not until nearly high moon according to the perimeter guards, and so he was not present for formal introductions.<br><br>&#8220;Two, Tamurlane feels little shame for his poor judgement or lack of initiative. Simply put, he has never lied to protect himself or his reputation. Nor did the Six reveal to us any dishonesty on his part. <br>&#8220;This in and of it itself does not exonerate Tamurlane nor implicate Hallywin; however, the third truth we know, as revealed to us by the Six, is that Jamkin&#8217;s testimony is incomplete. Jamkin, do you wish to revise your testimony or shall you face the judgement of the Six?&#8221;<br>Jamkin blanched, and looked upon Eolric with eyes opened wide.<br>&#8220;Jamkin, &#8220; Aolis prodded, &#8220;speak openly and honor Truth. What did you not say?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I, uh, that is, well, sir &#8211;When I came upon your man and Hallywin, they were &#8211; uh, pretty far along in the whole, uh. Anyway, well, you see, sir, Tamurlane was kind of, uh, chanting a woman&#8217;s name over and over. Only it wasn&#8217;t Hallywin&#8217;s name, sir.&#8221;<br><br>Obviously, Eolric knew nothing of this. His man had held back; justifiably afraid, as far as Aolis could tell, of his young commander&#8217;s temper. Even with this truth revealed, though, Eolric just looked angrier.<br><br>&#8220;You mean he dishonored me and my Clan and he did not even know her name?&#8221; growled Eolric between gritted teeth. His grip tightened around the hilt of his great sword and his arm began to shake with barely controlled rage.<br><br>&#8220;Mm-hmm. We suspected something of this nature. In light of this new testimony, would you like to revise your charges, Eolric?&#8221; asked Aolis.<br><br>&#8220;I do not. I honor the Six, but I pray to Marr. I want his head. Do you grant me this?&#8221;<br>&#8220;No, Eolric, not this day.<br><br>&#8220;Let those assembled witness our judgement in silence. We, the Elders of the White Bear Clan, dutiful servants of the Six and the leaders of our people in plenty and want find the following: Tamurlane, while exercising poor judgement and once again comporting himself in a way unbefitting his station, broke no laws in coupling with Hallywin. Tamurlane acted in ignorance of her identity and position as supported by both witnesses, Jamki and Hallywin. <br><br>&#8220;Furthermore, while matters of honor and war can be settled in the blood of Marr, matters of justice, particularly when applied to an initiate shaman must be, decided by a sacred tribunal made up of clan elders. You will abide our decision, Eolric, upon pain of war between our clans and disfavor in the eyes of the Six.<br>&#8220;That said, we further find that Tamurlane has tried our patience and our hospitality long enough. You are exiled Tamurlane. You will be gone by week&#8217;s end. You are not welcome in the White Bear lodges any longer.&#8221;<br><br>They met him nearly 8 miles from the winter lodge of the White Bear Clan: Aolis and another shaman whom Tamurlane had heard of but never met, an adventurer named Stormhawk. Tamurlane had been walking the broken plain for nearly three hours, and was startled to see anyone he knew waiting for him. Besides Eolric, of course. The look on Aolis&#8217; face was grim indeed. Without preamble, Aolis spoke.<br>&#8220;The decision was not unanimous young one. One voted for Eolric and the rule of Marr.&#8221;<br>&#8220;And you came to tell me this why, Elder? You despise me so much as to make the pain of going that much harder, or are you just upset that you didn&#8217;t see Eolric take my head?&#8221;<br>&#8220;Watch your tongue, cub,&#8221; said Stormhawk stepping forward.<br>Aolis just smiled. &#8220;You don&#8217;t feel pain at leaving, young one, and I wasn&#8217;t the one who voted for your death. That was Woodson, your mentor.&#8221;<br><br>The shock of this statement left Tamurlane visibly shaken.<br>&#8220;His vote was marred by emotion obviously and as such was declared invalid, but I think it says much about you, doesn&#8217;t it?&#8220; continued Aolis. &#8220; Actually I came here to make you an offer. The Six need a representative to serve the Temple of Marr in Freeport. It is dangerous, but you can continue your studies and, if you deign to listen to the Six, you might even become a man. Do you wish to go?&#8221;<br>&#8220;Why do you offer me this, old man? No, don&#8217;t tell me. I have much potential, is that it?&#8221; Tamurlane snorted in disbelief. He had heard that his whole life, and hadn&#8217;t seen that it had done him much good.<br>&#8220;Indeed, you do. But potential means nothing if it is never realized. You need to be a man before you will ever become a shaman, or a warrior, or anything besides a rutting drunken animal. If you choose to try, leave with Stormhawk. If you do not, do not. It makes no difference to me. I offer you a chance. As far as I am concerned, it is your last.&#8221;<br><br>With that, Aolis turned to leave, but barely ten feet gone he turned to face Tamurlane once more.<br><br>&#8220;Those who deserve to sit in judgement are often the most reluctant to do so. If you can tell me how this applies to you, come back to see me. Fare well, Tamurlane. May you find what you are seeking.&#8221;

