<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Smashing the Stereotype</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Chialde Tal'Dranneth  (<a href="mailto:daymon_kelley@interfor.com" class="credit2">daymon_kelley@interfor.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Smashing the stereotype:  A brief insight in to the mind of an<br>established Player Killer.<br><br>Not all Player Killers fit in to the "kewl d00d" mold so readily<br>attached to them.  This brief essay is not an attempt to change your<br>gaming philosophy.  The following text is intended only to give you some<br>insight in to my own philosophy and perhaps to show that not all Player<br>Killers are the mindless children that most would have you believe them<br>to be.<br><br>Let me first introduce myself,  out of game context.  My name is Daymon<br>and I am a 26-year-old male residing in Vancouver, Canada.  I am<br>gainfully employed as a Project Manager responsible for the computer<br>business systems of a large forestry company.  I have had a computer<br>since 1982 and have been part of the online community since the first<br>300 BPS modem available for a Commodore 64.  I am by no means a social<br>deviant. I have many friends,  family and a girlfriend of nearly 2 years<br>now.  I sincerely love all of these people and would not trade them for<br>anything. I consider myself to be a stand up and trust worthy<br>individual.  I am fascinated with medieval times and many of my software<br>purchases reflect this.  <br><br>My experience with online gaming began with Diku MUDs many years ago.<br>From there I began playing West Coast Creation's Major MUD up until the<br>release of Ultima Online.  I continued to play Ultima Online on and off<br>until the release of EverQuest.  When EverQuest was released I<br>immediately canceled my UO account in favor of the newer,  flashier game<br>of the future!  I'd like to point out here that I never found Ultima<br>Online to be stable enough to provide a solid gaming experience.  Many<br>times after being disconnected I would log back in to find one or more<br>players standing around my ghostly image shouting something to the<br>effect of  "Stupid PK I owned you".   This more than any other one<br>factor made me leave Ultima Online. I have never played Quake and for<br>the most part have no interest in these first person shooter type games.<br><br><br>I have always been a PK,  in every game I have ever played.  I have<br>never played an "anti PK" or played by any other gaming philosophy.<br>Many of my "crimes against humanity",  mostly perpetrated in Ultima<br>Online, have been documented on the Internet (do a search for "WarChild<br>of KoT" if you are interested).  Most of these published experiences,<br>although resulting in the other player's death,  have been positive for<br>all parties involved.  <br><br>I am probably not what most would consider to be a "strong" Role Player.<br>I play for the challenge,  companionship and excitement of the game.<br>This is not to say that role-playing does not encompass these same<br>qualities. I do my very best to not impede others in their role-playing.<br>I do not try and change the way they wish to play the game and<br>appreciate being given the same consideration.  Online games are<br>different things to different people.  So long as one group is not<br>actively trying to stifle the gaming experience of another, I believe<br>there is room for co-existence.  The cooperation of all gaming groups is<br>however required for this and is easier said than done.<br><br>My Primary Character,  Chialde Tal'Dranneth of Rallos Zek is a level 44<br>Dark Elf Wizard.  She can be found quite often in the Karanas.  While<br>Wizard's are probably not the best choice for a PVP character,  I find<br>it suits my play style nicely.  The other two characters I play are<br>Chield Wardancer,  level 20 Ranger of Rallos Zek and Warchialde,  level<br>20 Shaman of Tallon Zek.  All of these characters have a reputation for<br>player killing.  All of these characters will always be Player Killers.<br><br>I have never been accused of exploiting.  I have never been banned or<br>suspended from ANY game.  I have never engaged in PVP for the sole<br>purpose of ruining somebody else's gaming experience.  I live by my own<br>code of conduct that includes,  but is not limited to,  the following<br>ideals:<br><br>* I do not hunt zone boundaries for my prey.  <br>* I will always let my target dispatch any MOB or NPC they may be<br>fighting before engaging them in PVP. <br>* I will accept almost any duel offered to me.<br>* I will not engage in a shouting match nor will I single out any<br>player, or group of players,  for having a different philosophy than my<br>own.  <br>* I will engage you in PVP when the opportunity arises.<br>* If you lose connection while fighting me,  and I notice,  I will<br>disengage combat immediately until you return (I returned a Rubicite<br>Breast Plate just the other day to a player whom I unknowingly killed<br>while he was link dead).<br>* I do not hunt naked.  In fact,  I wear many valuable and highly<br>desired items. <br>* I will not "pull the plug" in a zone to escape a death.  I will<br>try and wait out any victim who does this as I believe it is not in the<br>spirit of the game.  Zone boundaries are part of the game's mechanics,<br>not a "home free" area to run to.  <br>* I will not corpse or bind camp. <br>* I will not bind rush. If I am defeated,  I will retrieve my<br>corpse and leave.  After all,  to the victor go the spoils!  <br>* I do not care if I get any "loot" from a victim.  EverQuest,  to<br>me,  is not about accumulating the most items possible.  Quite often I<br>will sell back any item I take from somebody at a price far below the<br>item's market value. <br>* I will keep my word, once given.<br>* I will endeavor to play fairly at all times.<br>* I have never nor will ever utter the phrase "I owned j00!"<br>* I will treat everybody with the same basic level of respect<br>deserving to all human beings.  Treat me badly and I'll simply ignore<br>you.<br><br>Without re-hashing and old,  tired argument,  I will simply state that<br>in my opinion Player Killing IS a component of PVP.  Anybody who plays<br>on the PVP servers should expect this type of activity to occur.  If a<br>player wants a controlled PVP environment,  there are some 20 odd other<br>servers that cater to this.  You can duel,  chose to activate your PVP<br>switch or fight in an arena on any of the essentially non-PVP based<br>servers.  By playing on Rallos,  Tallon or Vallon Zek,  you are in<br>effect consenting to be involved in unscheduled,  unregulated player vs.<br>player activity.  I very much dislike somebody joining this environment<br>to attempt and change it.  In it's most simple form:  I do not come to<br>Non-PVP servers attempting to make them PVP servers.  Please do not come<br>to my PVP server and attempt to make it anything other than what it is.<br><br>In closing,  I would like to re-iterate that this is not intended to<br>sway anybody's gaming philosophy.  This is not an attempt to justify my<br>actions to myself or anybody else.  I don't feel I need to.  I do not<br>consider myself to be a "kewl d00d",   "power gamer"or exploiter.  The<br>next time somebody takes your life in EverQuest,  before you shout out<br>"stupid power gaming kewl d00d pk!" or spam them with tells of how much<br>they suck and how dead you will make them,  ask yourself this;  "Does<br>this person really fit the stereotype I am attaching them to?".  You<br>might find some people out there that surprises you.  I know I<br>constantly do.<br><br>Please feel free to contact me in game on any of my characters.  I will<br>be pleased to have an intelligent discussion with you on a whole host of<br>interesting topics!  <br><br>Chialde Tal'Dranneth - Officer of Darkenbane,  Player Killer and intelligent human being

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem956347642,99345,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">The /Con System</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Jaxsion KneeCrusher  (<a href="mailto:quaffpup@edge.net" class="credit2">quaffpup@edge.net</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="N/A" class="credit2">Dragonfire Guild</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Most of us living within Norrath have known for a LONG time that<br>the /con system is messed up and heavily favors casters. After thinking<br>long and hard about it (and getting madder every time I log on); and<br>after hearing Verant's latest explanation of how it is "supposed" to<br>work, I have come up with the following idea regarding the /con system<br>and it's future.<br><br>First, a little background on the /con system. According to the game<br>manual when EverQuest first opened up to the public and for the last<br>year of our lives, we have been told the following statistics applied to<br>the /con system:<br><br>Green: You should be able to kill it easy. So easy in fact, you get NO<br>experience when you kill it except in rare HIGH GREEN cases.<br><br>Blue: You should be able to kill it if you are full health and mana<br>and though you will take damage, odds are you will emerge the victor<br>easily.<br><br>White: A fair fight. It could go either way, depending on your stats and<br>the mood of the gods at that moment<br><br>Yellow: You, on your own, should NOT be able to kill this NPC, except in<br>rare circumstances, adn if you do, you will be VERY low on HP and<br>probably NO mana left.<br><br>RED: YOU will NOT be able to kill this on your own. In fact, in most<br>cases you are going to die very fast.<br><br>Within each class above there are "low" and "high" cons that affect<br>the class a little. For instance you will be able to kill a "low" blue<br>/con easier than a "high" blue /con.<br><br>The only problem without the /con system above is that it simply does not work<br>at levels above 15 or so....sometimes lower, if you are a melee<br>or (in some cases) a hybrid class. If you have played the game for more<br>than 12 or 13 levels, you begin to notice that the "Blue" /cons can and<br>probably will kick yer butt and "White /cons are almost certain death.<br>However, pure casters and druids have little trouble soloing "White" and<br>even "Yellow" cons all the way up the Level slider.<br>Before I go any further, let me tell you that I play both a Level<br>24 Wizard and a Level 24 Warrior.....exact OPPOSITES in the class range.<br>Both of these characters are VERY well outfitted for their levels, both<br>are maxed out in their skills for the level, and both have VERY good<br>stats. Both characters fight in Mistmoore, mainly in the courtyard. My<br>wizard can SOLO the mob's there all day long, however there is NO WAY my<br>warrior can survive the courtyard solo for any period of time....he<br>simply cannot take the damage. The problem with this is that the mobs<br>there /con THE SAME to both of my characters.<br>Let me say also that I know that casters are designed to be more<br>powerful to some degree than straight melee because of their spells. I<br>HAVE NO PROBLEM WITH THAT. My problem is that the /con system is SOLELY<br>based on level.<br><br>Verant has come out in the past few weeks and tried to further<br>define how the /con system works. It is a pitiful attempt to gloss over<br>what so many melee players have been griping about for so long.<br>According to Verant, the /con system, AS YOU GET HIGHER in level,<br>(supposedly) assumes that you are GROUPED and that the /con you are<br>seeing is meant to reflect it being attacked by a GROUP. Hogwash.<br>Lets take their assumption that the /con reflects a group. The blue<br>initiate familair that /cons low to high blue to my warrior means that<br>my warrior is going to need a group to take it out. It usually does<br>require more than 1 melee person attacking it to kill it effectively.<br>Now, assuming I have 4 people in my party, we have to split a low to<br>high blue con experience 4 ways. That is a lot of killing to level up.<br>However, THAT SAME initiate familair that requires 4 melee class people<br>to kill it effectively, can be DESTROYED EASILY by my level 24<br>Wizzie.....with NO damage done to him. So now, my Wizzie gets the FULL<br>experience value for the kill because he soloed it. My wizzie is going<br>to level A LOT faster than my warrior is, which in fact, he does. Is<br>there any wonder there are so many casters in the realm as compared to<br>melee or hybrid classes? No, it is easy to see that the game caters to<br>the casters.<br><br>Now for my solution to fix the con system? Simple. If a mob<br>/conning blue to a melee class at certain level (say 24, for example)<br>requires several melee class people to kill it effectively, then that<br>same NPC should /con GREEN to the same level caster. Or to reverse the<br>case, a "high" blue /con to a solo caster should /con White or even<br>"low" yellow to the same level melee classes. This would balance out<br>more evenly the experience gained by all in the game. It simply makes NO<br>SENSE why my caster can SOLO yellow /cons while my Warrior gets his<br>brains beaten in by a "high" blue /con. Even if the crap Verant is<br>feeding us is correct about the /con reflecting a group con, then<br>explain WHY my caster is STILL able to solo it.<br><br>Seeing how the /con system is based solely on level, it would seem<br>to me to be easy to implement my suggestion. Simply correct the<br>databases on the NPC's to reflect 1 to 2 levels higher on the /con scale<br>to melee and most hybrid classes (Druids seem to be a hybrid class that<br>can solo practically as good as casters). That way, experience will be<br>more equally shared by all, seeing as that you RARELY find 20+ melee<br>characters soloing, but it is quite a COMMON site to see level 20+<br>Caster characters soloing. Now, you ask, "What if the caster is in a<br>group of melee classes and they NPC is blue to the caster and white to<br>the melee classes? Won't the caster take less experience than the melee<br>guys for the same kill?" Yes, but that could be worked out as well, like<br>taking for instance the AVERAGE level of the group and awarding the<br>experience accordingly. It would have to be worked on yes, but it could<br>be done.<br><br>Finally, for all who would flame me for this opinion, I understand<br>BOTH sides here, Casters wanting the power and Melee classes upset by<br>the /con system because I PLAY both types. However, I understand that<br>there is a problem and would have no qualms about having this happen. I<br>would still be able to solo NPC's with my Caster, but my Warrior, who,<br>having to group to effectively kill the same mob, would get his<br>experience upped to reflect the fact that the NPC is harder to kill by<br>melee classes.<br><br>I have talked to MANY people in game about the /con system and most<br>agree that something should be done. Not surprisingly the majority of<br>people who seem to like the /con system the way it is happens to be<br>either a Druid or a PURE Caster. Hmmmmmmm, I wonder why that is :)<br><br>Jaxsion KneeCrusher<br>24th Season Servant of Rallos ZEK<br>Warrior Champion of Rivervale<br>Dragonfire Guild<br>Veeshan

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem956347337,20629,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">The Corruption of EverQuest</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Drakmire the Forgotten  (<a href="mailto:drakmire@hotmail.com" class="credit2">drakmire@hotmail.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="(http://crimsonspire.com" class="credit2">Knights of the Crimson Spire</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Greetings fellow players and ex-players alike.  Today, I wish to speak on the subject of what EverQuest has become, the adulterated form of what the original principle was.  <br><br>	To begin with, EverQuest is meant to be the graphical representation of a fantasy setting, putting images to life where previously, imagination had to be employed.  The idea behind it was a fantasy setting, a role-playing environment, where the real world would be kept to a minimum, and to the respective channels if at all possible. It caters most to those who wish to enjoy the game, and less to those who seeks the instant thrill. If I am wrong about this, then you need read no further.<br><br>	My personal experience extends back only to the 4th phase of the Beta testing.  At that time, there was that certain mystique about it which allowed every new monster, each turn of the corner a new and unexpected thrill which all novices experience (or at least I hope so.) This is nothing new, this is simply the thrill of discovery, but even then, it still seemed in-character, it still seemed as a fantasy.<br><br>	Growing up, however, one <u>must</u> abandon some aspects of role-playing in order to succeed, lest that player never accomplish anything.  What I mean is the people shouting for "Can I get a SOW please?" or perhaps auctioning "WTB: SMR, GBS, and GEB." To understand anything of what goes on in the world, that player must abandon their ignorance.<br><br>	Normally most people consider the banishment of ignorance, of any form, a good thing.  But consider it this way: to take the first steps in learning, one also learns more about the game as it is outside of a role-playing environment.  Now, I'm not so naive as to think that there will never be people around who never break someone's fantasy, nor will everyone respect each other enough to see a role-player and avoid ooc around him/her.  I do, however, believe that there is no other way to progress in EverQuest, neither by levels nor social standing, unless one takes an active part in dismantling the mechanics of how the game works, so that the maximum effect can be wrought.  This inevitably has the effect of reducing a person's fun, which, according to Verant, is the driving factor behind Customer Service: if the majority of customers aren't happy, then something is wrong.<br><br>	As a character matures, the player behind it learns more and more of the world, creating mental maps of the areas, and with this, spawn areas, drops, roamer pathing, and all the other technical information needed to hunt there. There is something very wrong about knowing everything about a zone, knowing every major spawn, the major items contained within, the levels to hunt there.  There is no more factor of the unexpected. There is nothing that Verant can do to help this, and once they realize this inherant flaw, they <i>might</i> be able to work alongside players in a conscious effort to extend EverQuest's lifespan. Until then, they must employ Internet-Relations specialists such as once-Guide Gordon Wrinn to find out what the vocal minority wants in the game, constantly changing the way external mechanics work in an effort to promote "balance" through second or third-hand experience, rather than the designers and development team seeing and experiencing the problems for themselves.<br><br>	Take for instance, the Alter Planes.  In the Planes of Fear and Hate, a tactic known as "breaking" must be used before the plane can be "done," meaning that effective team tactics must be used if that group plans to continue hunting there.  Reasonable enough.  Now take the information that to break the plane, a large majority of the hunting party needs to know the mechanics of the game: pathing problems, damage percentages, agro status, etc.  In fact, this is true among most every place where there is a constant spawn, Unrest, Kedge, both Upper and Lower Guk, Solusek's Eye, and the other dungeons.  This is the corruption of which I speak.  Why should a player be required to know external game calculations when the setting is supposedly in-character? To ruin someone's fantasy with numbers and spawn information is the failure of what I and others originally played EverQuest for.  We wanted to be able to get away from the "real world" and have fun in this fantasy realm.  Now the question is no longer "By Marr...what powers does that nefarious sight hold that it can slay our friends with but a gesture?" but "Omg, how the hell did Sirren just wipe the entire zone pop in less than 2 seconds??" <br><br>	There are some exceptions, but not many.  The Plane of the Sky has not been fully "done" yet, as the monsters it contains are meant for post-expansion players.  When a higher level island has been breached, it is heralded as a great triumph, but I fear that this is the last of its kind.  Even with the impending lands of Kunark about to provide new areas and opportunities, there will no longer be the awed hush as a new monster which is not aggressive walks by, but rather the question to the group, "Got mana for one more?"

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem956347106,16625,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">EverQuest: The Religion</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Brambel Thistletoe  (<a href="mailto:kerion@bellatlantic.net" class="credit2">kerion@bellatlantic.net</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Recently I began to ask myself a question. What in the world could make sensible <br>people turn into swearing, babbling, blabbering fools, frothing at the mouth at the drop of <br>a hat. What could possibly ignite the fires of hate in a person so strongly that they post <br>whole newsgroup messages consisting of "F*** YOU VERANT!" After thinking on it <br>for several moments (it honestly didn't take long), I came up with one answer: <br>EverQuest.<br><br>I started playing EverQuest over a year ago, just weeks after it hit the store <br>shelves. At first, no one was this passionate about the game. It was still a game. Unknown <br>to all of us of course was The Addiction&#8482; (this is much like The Vision&#8482;, but is not <br>advertised by Verant). The Addiction&#8482; is blind, much like justice and can afflict anyone <br>who dares put the EverQuest CD in his or her CD-Rom drive. As the title of my article <br>states, I find this Addiction&#8482; to be akin to a religion. The Addiction&#8482; can drive a person <br>into a religious furor if the Addiction&#8482; is not fed.<br><br>Now, I will be the first to admit I have been caught up in the furor myself. <br>Unfortunately for me, I am usually in the defense of Verant (because I feel they have <br>made an excellent product). I always wondered to myself after the matter had blown over, <br>how I could get caught up in the same boiling anger as hundreds of other players. I have <br>always considered myself a reasonable person, intelligent, fair and never quick to jump to <br>conclusions. It seems though that when EverQuest is the topic, my mind goes into a state <br>of panic and all the rationale I have is blown out the window. It is my personal belief that <br>this is the case with over 90% of the "trolls" and "flamers" on the message boards. <br>Behind that keyboard they are a rational, intelligent person who has gone into a fit of <br>anger over an Addiction&#8482;, just like a zealot would over his or her religion.<br><br>I sometimes wonder how a game could inspire this kind of passion in people. I <br>mean, in reality what is EverQuest? A series of binary strings interpreted by your <br>computer to put a nice 3D rendered picture on your screen. It is simply streams of data, <br>nothing more, nothing less. How can intangible streams of data make peoples stomachs <br>churn and their hearts boil to the brim with hate and anger? Simple: Immersion. People <br>get completely immersed in EverQuest and the world of Norrath. The people, the sites, <br>the sounds, the interaction. No matter what you think of Verant or EverQuest you have to <br>admit it is one of the most immersive worlds ever created. It simply draws you in and <br>won't let you go. To illustrate what I mean. Last Saturday I sat down in front of my <br>computer with the intention of playing for two hours then going outside for some fresh <br>air. I logged in as Brambel, summoned some food and headed to Lake Rathetear for some <br>hunting. When I looked up at the clock over eleven hours had passed. I had lost all track <br>of time, it was now dark outside, my stomach was rumbling. I had not eaten, taken a <br>drink or so much as moved from that chair in eleven hours. Some may laugh and call me <br>a junkie, but I know some of you reading this have done the exact same thing.<br>	<br>With the Ruins of Kunark opening up in about three days, we have to ask <br>ourselves: What impact is this game having on my life? How is it affecting me, especially <br>if the affect is adverse? I for one have begun to scare myself with the amount of time I <br>spend in Norrath. I live two separate lives. I get up and go to work everyday, earning my <br>pay, doing my job and putting food on my table. When I go home, I live a separate life. I <br>am a halfling Druid named Brambel  Thistletoe, not a software developer named <br>Matthew. Even as much as the extent of my Addiction&#8482; scares me, I have no intention <br>of cutting back on my play. Perhaps I should, perhaps I should question why I let this <br>game rule parts of my life. Perhaps we all should?<br><br>Brambel Thistletoe

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem956167236,24679,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Unwritten Rules Follow-up</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Serenedena Caamora  (<a href="mailto:N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
I read with interest the editorial you posted entitled &#8220;<a href="http://www2.eqvault.com/lore/admin/viewnews.cgi?newsid956081020,81624,">EverQuest Ettiquite and Unwritten Rules</a>&#8221; written by Ungoliant SpiderSoul. I read this with interest, mostly because I feel that there certainly is a lack of common courtesy among players in EQ lately. Unfortunately, it is &#8220;common&#8221; courtesy most in that it should be innate among players, not because it exists in abundance. To a lesser extent, I was interested due to the fact that I also play on the Karana server. This server is extremely overcrowded, and when operating in such close quarters it becomes so much more important to show each other the respect that they deserve.<br><br>The article, in and of itself, is inaccurately titled. It should have been titled &#8220;A powergamer&#8217;s perspective on farming items efficiently - and the arguments you need to use to justify your actions&#8221;. For the most part, these &#8220;unwritten rules&#8221; are simply justifications to keep other players from what you feel is yours. I will address one of these specifically.<br><br>&#8220;* If a player or group is at a small spawn or camp, and has obviously been <br>there a while, it is an unwritten rule that they own that spawn. They most <br>likely have spent enourmous efforts (and possibly lives) to set the spawn at <br>the camp, and they deserve to keep it. One may think that they have a fair <br>share there too, but this is not the case. You put no effort in helping <br>split or set the spawn, why should you reap the benefits? Any high level <br>player can tell you this&#8221;<br><br>This is inaccurate. You may feel this is an &#8220;unwritten rule&#8221;, but in actuality, the <b>written rule</b> is that you do not &#8220;own the spawn&#8221;. Any other player has as much right to the spawns in Norrath as you do. Note that this does <b>not</b> necessarily mean that you must yield and allow them to take it immediately. Something as simple as stating that you will advise them when you are vacating within a reasonable amount of time is all that is usually necessary. By your &#8220;unwritten rule&#8221; a large guild could hold popular spawns such as the &#8220;Golden Effreeti Boots&#8221; in Solusek B, or the Yakesha in Lower Guk, for weeks. The result of this kind of attitude is that by controlling the supply of such popular items, the prices would rise exponentially, and people who have a right to such items (and are an appropriate level) are unable to attain them. This is simply unfair. Also, the statement that they put no effort in splitting the spawn equates to no right to benefits is inaccurate. You are excluding them from the spawn, thereby not allowing them to put effort into controlling it. The argument is circular, and excludes people from enjoyment of the game. Most people who play EverQuest <b>want</b> to put <b>lots</b> of effort into acquiring items for their characters. That is what makes the game fun. People who want to sit at a camp and supply the items to lower level guild members (i.e. - power gaming guilds) or their own low level characters (twinks) are trying to sidestep this effort.<br><br>His other &#8220;unwritten rules&#8221; follow from a similar flawed logic, that the right of an individual is more than the rights of the Norrath Society as a whole. It is a question of balance. People need to be respectful of those among them in Norrath. The document written by Ungoliant is a recipe of disrespect and self-importance.<br><br>I offer the following alternate set of &#8220;unwritten rules of Norrath&#8221;. They are short, simple, and easy to remember. Like everything that is really &#8220;common sense&#8221; they are general and applicable to many situations. Unlike the previous set, they are written to allow people unfamiliar with the game to integrate within Norrath and enjoy the experience in utmost.<UL>1.	When dealing with another player, always remember that although you may be interacting in an RP way with another &#8220;person&#8221; in Norrath, there is a real human being with real human feelings behind them. You probably do not know this person, but treat them as though you do. If they ask for something that is unreasonable, explain why (i.e. - out of mana, can&#8217;t afford it, in a hurry). If they ask for help, try to aid them. Yes, some of us have been playing this game for over a year now, many haven&#8217;t, and the world of Norrath is a confusing place.<br><br>2.	Share share share. If you have room in your group, and someone wants to join and is an appropriate level, let them. If you are full, tell them you&#8217;ll let them know when there is room. If you are afraid of &#8220;xp dilution&#8221; you are probably overpowered enough anyway, and another person will not significantly downgrade your experience further.<br><br>3.	Remember that Everquest is a &#8220;Multiplayer&#8221; game and that you are in a simulated society. I found that many of the attitudes presented in the previous document place the person believing these unwritten rules in a position where they feel superior to their fellow players. You are no more or less important than anyone else. If you want to play a game where you do not have to interact with other people, play a single player game for a bit. If you find yourself annoyed with forced interaction with others perhaps Everquest isn&#8217;t the best game for you. Power gamers have as much right to the spoils of Norrath as anyone else, but they do not have any more.<br><br>4.	If you attempt to interact with someone who is rude or unhelpful, simply move on. Realize that you are gaining much more than they are from the game, that the game is not about madly leveling, it is about having a good time.</UL>If you try to remember these simple rules at all times while you move throughout Norrath, you will find your experience significantly more enjoyable.<br><br>Serenedena Caamora<br>50th Shaman<br>Officer of The Silver Blades<br>Karana Server

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem956081020,81624,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">EverQuest Ettiquite and Unwritten Rules</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Ungoliant SpiderSoul  (<a href="mailto:tulkein@hotmail.com" class="credit2">tulkein@hotmail.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Recently, I have started a new character and have come across a disturbing <br>trend amongst new players - They have no respect for unwritten rules. It <br>could be because no one has ever explained them, but nevertheless I feel it <br>is my duty to try to explain them: <br><br>* If a player in anonymous, they most likely have good reason. They do not <br>want to be bothered! Do not hound them for "buffs" or "TPs".<br><br>* When searching for a specific service, it is common curtesy for a player <br>to not /shout aimlessly for "need SOW plz" or "Can someone TP me to NK <br>plzez?". It only takes a few seconds to do a /who search for a player with a <br>specific service. Most people will be more than happy to grant a service if <br>you are more personal. Most people will NOT answer a random /shout.<br><br>* If a player or group is at a small spawn or camp, and has obviously been <br>there a while, it is an unwritten rule that they own that spawn. They most <br>likely have spent enourmous efforts (and possibly lives) to set the spawn at <br>the camp, and they deserve to keep it. One may think that they have a fair <br>share there too, but this is not the case. You put no effort in helping <br>split or set the spawn, why should you reap the benefits? Any high level <br>player can tell you this.<br><br>* It is good practice to read what is /auction'ed or /ooc'ed. It is just <br>troublesome (and downright rude and annoying) to ask "How much?" for <br>something that was clearly stated as being bought. The same holds for /ooc <br>or /shout conversations. If you don't know what you are talking about, don't <br>say anything. Doing so only makes you look bad.<br><br>* If you feel that your class/race/diety/position/faction standing/etc. is <br>not as good as anothers, and you don't like it, do not complain. You chose <br>the position you are/were in, deal with it. If you do not like it, choose <br>another. Whining and complaining only hurts, it doesn't help. If you feel <br>that a class is "better than yours", why are you complaining? Their <br>advantages will help you.<br><br>* The above statement holds true for twinks, too. If a person has better <br>equipment than you, what gives you the right to complain? Most likely they <br>have a higher level character who earned it. Others might have gotten lucky. <br>A twinked player is only a benefit, being able to cast more efficently, take <br>more hits, etc. A self-twinked player most likely knows a lot more tactics <br>than a non-twinked player of the same level, and can put them to use by <br>making a fight go more efficently. More efficent fights = less death and <br>more experience.<br><br>* If a player doesn't want to group, he doesn't want to group! Some players <br>function well solo, others are antisocial and do not like to group. Still <br>others just want some time alone. If they say no, don't complain...just find <br>somebody else.<br><br>* And finally, and most importantly, LIFE ISN'T FAIR! If you think something <br>shouldn't be that way, don't complain, just suck it up, deal with it, and <br>adapt. Complainers cause more problems than solutions, and when a person's <br>abilities are nerfed, who do you think they are going to be mad at? <br>(Exception: If there is harrassment or another extreme case, you shouldn't <br>have to take it.)<br><br>Maybe this seems a little harsh, but people must learn the proverbial ropes <br>=). Thank you for your time and I hope to hear from you soon.<br><br>Ungoliant SpiderSoul<br>Karana Server

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem956005462,29000,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">The Risk of PvP</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Brega  (<a href="mailto:thomasha@psa.psafe.navy.mil" class="credit2">thomasha@psa.psafe.navy.mil</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">Vallon Zek</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
The EQ Staff has not elaborated on the "studies" that have led them to<br>believe that the majority of the players that now play EQ PVP would not go<br>for a PVP XP loss system (contrary to the Risk Poll, posted on the EQ-PvP<br>forum). However, they did open the door for a poll, and if they actually<br>need this information to make a decision, I would like to suggest a way to<br>do a poll ONLY on the PVP servers.<br><br>Insert the poll question only on the PVP servers, AFTER the server selection<br>screen, but before the character enters the world. That way, one would<br>actually have to log onto a PVP server, or have a character on one of the<br>PVP servers, to respond to the poll. Of course, one could create a character<br>on a PVP server just for the purpose of participating in the poll, but at<br>least that person would have some interest in PVP to be willing to do that. <br>The results of this poll would not only show what the majority of PVP<br>players prefer, but would show which servers currently prefer which methods.<br>Then decide to change all servers to the same system, or implement different<br>systems on different servers, depending on the outcome of the poll, and<br>allow character transfers.<br><br>The EQ Staffer (Gordon) mentioned in another post that they felt that xp<br>loss is the best system for EQ PVP. I agree. EQ's game mechanics are already<br>engineered almost exclusively around xp gain/loss. Why should PVP be any<br>different? I have faith in Verants "vision" of EQ, and feel that if EQ<br>believes that xp loss/gain in EQ PVP is the superior system, then EQ should<br>implement their vision of PVP, and not necessarily what the players may feel<br>is most popular.<br><br>I have had many conversations with people regarding the pros and cons of EQ<br>PVP. IF I can get the person to disregard what they have grown accustomed to<br>regarding the current system(s), they usually see the benefits and<br>superiority of an XP based system. I usually argue that xp loss should be a<br>fraction (25%) of the amount lost to an NPC, because the likelihood of being<br>defeated by a PC is much greater than being defeated by an NPC. <br>Most people on PVP servers play casters. This is fact. Many PVP casters have<br>grown accustomed to not wearing their prized gear most of the time (if<br>anything at all), and only wearing what they are comfortable losing when<br>there is even a remote risk of a PVP confrontation. These people have for the<br>most part eliminated risk from themselves, and thus the thought of losing xp<br>to a PK is unsettling. They are accustomed to shouldering little or no risk.<br>It SHOULD NOT be possible to eliminate all risk from yourself in a PVP<br>environment. Many casters' vision of risk is someone else risk, not theirs.<br>Melee's don't have this luxury, and don't know the feeling of never being at<br>risk. However, most meleer's DO know the feeling of risking to those who<br>don't risk anything, and I can say from first hand experience that I DONT<br>LIKE IT! It needs to change. Visit any major PvP confrontation on Valon<br>Zek, and what you see is 99% Naked combatants (or no drop, or inferior<br>equip) participating in battles. It's not a "healthy" PvP environment at<br>all. Naked PvP, combined with Power Bagging pretty much summarize the<br>typical battle.<br><br>Coin only eliminates the majority of the risk from most people, but still<br>allows people to eliminate ALL risk from themselves (What they've implemented<br>on Talon Zek). It is still a flawed system, but marginally superior to item<br>loot. If a server switch occurs, I will leave VZ. But not because I'm<br>endorsing ZERO RISK, but because Item Loot is grossly inherently flawed as<br>it has been implemented on Valon and Ralos Zek.<br><br>It will be very hard to implement an XP based PVP system, considering that<br>for almost a year now many people have been able to play with very minimal risk<br>to themselves. Many have profited greatly from the current system, and have<br>lost very little. Some, particularly those that are used to being able to<br>take without risking, will have a hard time adjusting to being at risk. On<br>the other hand, players that have played "straight up", "non naked" will<br>rejoice at the change. In the long run the PVP servers will be much<br>healthier with an XP based system. <br><br>EQ doesn't really need the information garnered from a poll, nor do they<br>need to go with the system they "feel" to be the most popular. XP gain/loss<br>is the system preferred by EQ Staffer with the power to make a change<br>(Gordon) and is the system that provides equitable fair risk for all and<br>that's issue that should be paramount in pvp game designers minds. Please,<br>relieve us all of the "Naked, No Risk Item Ganking World" we pvp'er endure<br>now, and replace it with one of Equitable Risk and Fairness.<br><br>Brega, 41 Troll SK of Vallon Zek

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
