<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Conflicts</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Jamie Thweatt  (<a href="mailto:Jamie.Thweatt@KLINE.com" class="credit2">Jamie.Thweatt@KLINE.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
The warm breeze blowing through the Commonlands gave no comfort to Khonshu as he stood watch over the empty Orc camp with his companions. A great peril was at hand & Quellious gave no clue as to the hour that it would arrive. At the urging of Puab Klosk, Grandmaster of the Ashen Order, Khonshu accompanied his friends Pandawen & Halyn, a paladin & cleric respectively & representatives of the Temple of Mithaniel Marr, Sian, a Half-Elvish paladin of Pandawen&#8217;s faith, and Eirik, a Wood Elf ranger acquaintance, to the edges of the Commonlands near Kithicor. From Puab&#8217;s rather disturbed tone, the matter was grave indeed. <br><br>&#8220;Pandawen,&#8221; Khonshu said, &#8220;You&#8217;ve been uncharacteristically tight-lipped throughout this watch. What exactly are we looking out for?&#8221; <br><br>Pandawen smiled. &#8220;No fooling you, my friend. I suppose I&#8217;d better fill you in on why we&#8217;re out her on our little surveillance mission. Three days ago, a caravan bound for Freeport came under attack by a rather heavily armed band of orcs. The merchants & other members of the caravan were slaughtered to the last soul.&#8220; <br><br>&#8220;What makes the matter more frightening,&#8221; Halyn added, &#8221;is that we found this amongst the bodies at the site.&#8221; Halyn reached into her backpack, produced a morning star & handed it to the ranger. &#8220;What say you to that, Eirik?&#8221; <br><br>Eirik studied the weapon & a look of astonishment slowly crept over his face. &#8220;Clearly, this is a weapon of orcish design, but it bears the markings of the clan Crushbone..&#8221; <br><br>The cloud of dread slowly spread to the further reaches of Khonshu&#8217;s heart. &#8220;Are you telling me that there is a possibility that the Deathfist & the Crushbone are forming an alliance?&#8221; <br><br>&#8220;Yes!&#8221; Sian spat out. &#8220;Are you afraid to face them? I&#8217;ve heard that the fists of the Ashen are sturdier than their resolve! You pacifists are no better than the godless Silent Fist&#8230; &#8221; <br><br>&#8220;Don&#8217;t make the mistake of confusing calm with a lack of courage, Sian!&#8221; Pandawen shouted, visibly angered by the enflaming remarks of his fellow paladin. &#8220;I&#8217;ve fought alongside Khonshu in many campaigns against the Deathfist & other enemies of Marr. His grasp of his art meets or exceeds any warrior&#8217;s sword arm. Best not to insult concepts you don&#8217;t understand. To insult the Ashen is to relinquish this mortal coil.&#8221; <br><br>&#8220;That&#8217;s quite enough, my friend,&#8221; Khonshu calmly replied. &#8220;Sian is entitled to his opinion. Should the time for a skirmish arrive, I will prove my prowess. Hopefully to his satisfaction.&#8221; Halyn beamed a smile at her friend, but took a rather icy tone as she turned to face Sian. <br><br>&#8220;At any rate, we don&#8217;t need any dissention in our ranks. We&#8217;ll have enough problems if we&#8217;re forced to fight. The Deathfist & Crushbone tribes hate each other almost as much as they do every other race. Anything that unifies them is a powerful force to be reckoned with.&#8221; <br><br>Day gave way to nightfall & their vigilance was rewarded. <br><br>After what seemed to be an eternity, Eirik noticed torchlight in the valley. The Deathfist were returning from another raid. The camp suddenly filled with the shouts of war cries & screams of victory. Pandawen quickly assessed the situation & formulated a strategy. <br><br>&#8220;We aren&#8217;t here to start a fight, merely gather information. Khonshu, you & Eirik are best suited for a clandestine entry of the camp. Find out what you can. If there is any trouble, we shall provide support.&#8221; <br><br>Eirik smiled. &#8220;Seems fair enough, although I think that we could handle that lot. I only count seven in that war party.&#8221; Like ghosts, the monk & the ranger melted into the dimly lit landscape. <br><br>Khonshu crept closer to the tents on the outskirts of the camp, being careful to avoid being noticed. Below the shouts of the orcs, the monks heard a rather intense exchange of words whispering on the wind. He slowly made his way to one of the larger tents & cut a small eyehole in the fabric with the edge of one of his wolf-stars. There in the tent sat what appeared to be a Deathfist legionnaire conversing in a rather heated tone with another blue-skinned orc. &#8220;Crushbone,&#8221; Khonshu thought to himself & silently thanked Quellious that he decided to pay attention during Ran&#8217;un&#8217;s tutorials on the Orcish language. <br><br>&#8220;Bah!! They may be your masters, Barak Sol, but they are not my own. While Shin Ree is appreciative of the weapons, that doesn&#8217;t mean that we accept their rule. Our offer still stands; safe passage for the Crushbone to Antonica after Freeport falls to the Deathfist in exchange for further weapons shipments.&#8221; <br><br>&#8220;How dare you say that they are our masters! They are merely benefactors with a vested interest in an entrenched Crushbone presence in this region. The Deathfist can either benefit from it or be victims of it!&#8221; <br><br>Khonshu heard the faint crackle of magical energy. Someone was coming to pay the duo a visit. As Khonshu strained to make out the figures, he heard cries of alarm from the outskirts of the camp. Much to his chagrin, he saw his companion, Sian, engaging the advanced guards with Pandawen & Halyn in tow.<br>It was obvious that Sian had taken it upon himself to attack the orcs & settle matters directly. <br><br>&#8220;Reckless Half-Elf,&#8221; the monk muttered to himself. The war cries brought the two orcs from the tent to aid their fellows against the advancing warriors. As Khonshu emerged from the shadows, he heard the familiar hiss of sheaf arrows hurtling through the air. Eirik would support the others while he confronted Barak Sol. <br><br>&#8220;Barak Sol of the Crushbone. I, Khonshu of the Ashen, would ask you to surrender. There is little sense in one of us dying this day.&#8221; The orc snarled, relishing the thought of spilling the young monk&#8217;s blood. <br><br>&#8220;Ashen, eh? I&#8217;ve killed many of your kind, human. The Shadow Wolf won&#8217;t save you from my axe!&#8221; <br><br>Barak Sol lashed out suddenly; his battle-axe cleaving the air dangerously close to Khonshu. The monk shouted & unleashed a swift, staggering blow. If Barak hadn&#8217;t known better, he&#8217;d have sworn that the monk&#8217;s hands were made of iron. The orc spat out a tooth in disgust & pressed his attack. Despite the furious exchange of strikes & feints, the two warriors were locked in an evenly matched battle of skill and ferocity. Around them rung the chime of steel on steel and the cries of the dying orcs. Seizing an advantage, the monk spun & lashed out with a savage kick; staggering his larger foe. Barak replied by swinging his axe in a deadly arc, grazing Khonshu&#8217;s chest & drawing blood. The monk skillfully ducked Barak&#8217;s second swing & hit the hapless orc in the armpit. The sudden burst of pain caused Barak to drop his axe. As Barak reached for his broadsword, Khonshu struck him squarely in the throat; the monk&#8217;s outstretched fingers piercing Barak&#8217;s flesh & sinking deeply into the orc&#8217;s windpipe. <br><br>The Crushbone warrior&#8217;s dying gasp gurgled in his throat as he fell. Khonshu paused to briefly lament the unfortunate loss of life when a mysterious force behind him stirred him into action. Wheeling around to face the new threat, Khonshu caught a brief glimpse of his new foes. There in the entranceway of the tent stood a shadow elf clad in the trappings of a necromancer & an Erudite clad in black armor.. Skeletal warriors armed with swords flanked both figures & the eyes of the undead glowed with hellish red motes of light. Neither of the pair introduced themselves, but the shadow elf smiled briefly & spoke. <br><br>&#8220;You should stay out of matters that aren&#8217;t your concern, monk. You should also keep a better eye on your friends.&#8221; <br><br>With that, the necromancer chanted an invocation. His hands crackled with a sickening greenish glow and a bolt of black lightning streaked from his open palm unerringly towards its target. Khonshu watched in horror as the enervation hit Eirik squarely between the shoulder blades. The ranger uttered a silent scream and slumped to the ground: Eirik had no knowledge of nor did he see the nihilistic force that struck him down. The necromancer cast another spell & the pair vanished as quickly as they had appeared. Pandawen & his faith-mates made short work of the remaining orcs, only to find their Elvish companion&#8217;s lifeless body lying still in the bloodstained grass in the camp. Khonshu&#8217;s eyes blazed with cold fury, but the monk said nothing. <br><br>Sian could sense the animosity rising against him in the aftermath of the terrible battle & quickly rose to his own defense. &#8220;I suppose Eirik&#8217;s death is my fault. We saw that blue skinned murderer entering the tent from our vantage point & that was proof enough of Crushbone&#8217;s alliance with the Deathfist.&#8221; <br><br>&#8220;As you have seen,&#8221; Khonshu sternly replied, &#8221;Eirik was struck down by a shadow elf necromancer accompanied by an Erudite Shadow Knight. Thanks to your reckless action, neither Eirik nor myself could gain enough information to discern whether or not the pair acted as individuals or if Neriak & Paineel are somehow involved in this. Saving you from yourself cost Eirik his life & we are no closer to the truth than we were when we started.&#8221; <br><br>&#8220;By Marr, I don&#8217;t believe I like your tone, Ashen.&#8221; Sian reached for his sword, only to be confronted by Pandawen. <br><br>&#8220;The Ashen is correct, brother. We can&#8217;t assume that their appearance here equates to Paineel & Neriak&#8217;s involvement in this & to accuse them would be to invite war. The orc&#8217;s body more than confirms the temple&#8217;s suspicions, but now we aren&#8217;t sure if the orcs are co-conspirators or merely pawns of a greater threat.&#8221; Halyn wiped the gore from her mace & knelt silently next to the fallen elf, weeping the entire time. Her face was a contorted visage of rage & sorrow. Sian was honestly puzzled by his companion&#8217;s reactions to his deed. How dare they take the side of a monk over a fellow member of the faith! The temple would surely hail him as a true harbinger of Mithaniel Marr&#8217;s greater glory. <br><br>As the rain began to fall, Khonshu slowly averted his eyes from Sian & the Ashen became lost in his own thoughts. Was the orc alliance the true threat or merely an advance for more insidious dark force? Emperor Crush could just as easily be an unwitting Neriak pawn as the Deathfist. The concept of Erudite sorcery aiding the shadow elves didn&#8217;t make matters better, nor did the fact that it was a possibility that neither Neriak nor Paineel were involved. The conspiracy could be a plot of an as of yet unseen foe, waiting for the opportunity to sink its fangs into Freeport&#8217;s throat & drink its lifeblood. <br><br>The only thing the companions could do was bury their dead friend, report the details to their superiors, & pray that they would have a second chance to successfully confront the dire force that slowly stirred in Norrath. Although his exterior was calm, an old shadow elf saying echoed in Khonshu&#8217;s sub-conscious, sending waves of trepidation through his mind: <br><br>&#8220;You cannot see the eyes of Innorruk until he comes for you.&#8221;

<!-- End Content -->
