<a name="newsitem954886415,64290,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Fate of a Boy</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Blair  (<a href="mailto:kma@julian.uwo.ca" class="credit2">kma@julian.uwo.ca</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
CHAPTER 1<br><br>	Seron Sleighhill stepped onto the docks in Freeport, followed by his wife, Jeyna.  In Jeyna&#8217;s arms was the couple&#8217;s infant son, Darien.   Seron was a warrior hailing from the Wood Elf City of Kaladim, while Jeyna was a cleric trained in the High Elf City of Felwithe.  Seron gazed at the setting sun and smelled the salty air of Freeport.   Young Darien stirred in his mother&#8217;s arms and showed signs of waking up.   Lovingly,  Jeyna slowly swayed her son back and forth in her arms while humming a comforting tune.   Seron put an arm around his wife&#8217;s shoulders and gazed into the city of Freeport,  a city bustling with activity and alive with action.   Jeyna looked into the brown eyes of her wood elven husband, and saw the fiery spirit of a warrior.  This concerned Jeyna deeply.<br><br>&#8220;Seron,  perhaps this was not such a good idea to bring young Darien here.    I mean,  you know about the dark side of this city.  It is not safe here for a child.  Why not raise him within the safe confines of Felwithe?&#8221;<br><br>Seron turned to face his wife and looked deep into her clear blue eyes.   <br><br>&#8220;Nonsense, my dear.   Darien will have the strength of his father, and the wisdom and intelligence of his mother.  He will be a great warrior someday, and perhaps,  will lead a great assault on the Teir&#8217;dal and finish them once and for all!&#8221;<br><br>Seron turned his focus onto his infant son.   Darien continued to sleep in his mother&#8217;s arms,  his dark brown eyes closed and his brown hair swaying ever so slightly in the wind.   &#8220;This boy is strong&#8221;  he thought.   &#8220;I knew it the instant he was born.  There is something very special about him.&#8221;<br><br>Jeyna knew that somewhere nearby,  the forces are darkness were watching them,  stalking them,  even as they stood on the pier.   She didn&#8217;t really understand why her husband desired to bring her infant son to such a place.   They would be much safer back home in Felwithe,  with the Elven Guards to protect them against any danger.<br><br>&#8220;My dear,  after you deal with the customs paperwork,  take Darien to our new home in North Freeport.   I must go meet with my old friend Barnabus now.    I will be back later tonight.&#8221;  said Seron.<br><br>&#8220;Alright.  Be careful Seron.&#8221;  said a concerned Jeyna<br><br>After giving his wife and son a goodbye kiss,   Seron entered the city of Freeport.<br><br>	Seron walked through the doors of Tassel&#8217;s Tavern and saw Barnabus sitting alone at the bar,  slowly sipping an ale.   Barnabus was a dwarf of incredible strength, with a long brown beard and a scar, which ran along the left eye.   It was not unusual to see Barnabus with a drink in his hand, although the fellow never seemed to be drunk.   That dwarf could hold his alcohol!  Seron approached the dwarf and greeted him with a hearty handshake.<br><br>&#8220;Seron!  M&#8217;boy!   It has been too long!&#8221;  exclaimed Barnabus  &#8220;How are the wife and child?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;They are well,  old friend.&#8221;  answered Seron.  &#8220;And how are you?   Plenty of wine and women,  and usual?&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Ah,  my friend.  I am getting much too old for that sort of behaviour&#8230;.  Although I do enjoy a good wine now and then.&#8221;  laughed Barnabus.  &#8220;So,  what brings you to Freeport?  Tis not the safest place for young Darien to be,  my friend.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Alas,  Jeyna has already voiced that concern.  But I believe that training in Freeport will make young Darien stronger in the long run.   When he gets a little older&#8230; I will take him to West Freeport to hunt.&#8221;  said  Seron.<br><br>&#8220;Why not train him over on the Faydwer Continent?   I hear the fight against the Crushbone Orcs is going well.&#8221;  countered Barnabus.<br><br>&#8220;I could do that.  But I want Darien to look into the eyes of the true evil.  I want him to confront the Teir&#8217;dal.   I want him to look into the eyes of the sons and daughters of Innoruuk and know that such evil does exist in Norrath.   He must understand that the Dark Elves really do exist, and are not just evil characters in children&#8217;s stories.&#8221;  <br><br>&#8220;Aye,  I can understand that,  my friend.  Speaking of the Teir&#8217;dal,   there have been reports of them terrorizing the inhabitants of East Commons.&#8221;  said Barnabus.  &#8220;They usually attack at night,  and I was going over to East Commons myself to see if the reports are true.  Would you like to come with me?  It will be just like old times.&#8221;<br><br>Seron looked deep into the eyes of his old friend.    Age did not dim the old dwarven warrior&#8217;s fighting spirit.   That much was evident to Seron.    However,  Seron wondered if Barnabus was still physically able to confront the Dark Elves.<br><br>&#8220;Barnabus,  you should leave the fighting to the next generation,  my friend.  You have done more than your share of fighting in your day.&#8221;  voiced a concerned Seron.<br><br>Barnabus laughed a hearty dwarven laugh.<br><br>&#8220;Nonsense!    I have plenty of fighting days ahead of me!   Any Teir&#8217;dal that dares confront me will taste the steel of my blade!   Just as their fathers before them did.  <br><br>Seron shook his head.  There was no extinguishing Barnabus&#8217; fighting spirit.   <br><br>&#8220;Alright,  I will come with you.   It will be just like old times,  my friend.&#8221;  said Seron.<br><br>Barnabus roared with laughter.  &#8220;That&#8217;s the spirit M&#8217;boy!   Come!  Let us have one more drink, and we will be off!&#8221;  <br><br>Seron opened his backpack as Barnabus drank, and equipped his sword and shield.<br><br>	Jeyna Sleighhill sat in her chair and stared out of her window.   Night had begun to settle on the human city of Freeport,  yet the city continued to bustle with activity.   The house, which the Sleighhills had bought with their hard-earned platinum, was small, but comfortable.     In the distance,   Jeyna could see the Temple of Mithaniel Marr in all of its majesty.    Jeyna began to shiver,  it would be a cold night tonight.   She got up and placed another log on the crackling fire.    Seated near the warm fire was the Sleighhill&#8217;s infant son, Darien.    Darien had just been fed, and was quite content to sit and stare at the fireplace.    Jeyna glanced out the window once more and wondered where her husband was.   Deep down inside,  Jeyna knew exactly where he was.     He was with Barnabus,  off seeking another adventure.    It would not be the first time that Seron&#8217;s fiery warrior spirit overrode his parental and family duties.   Jeyna sighed.<br><br>&#8220;Oh Darien,  why does you father insist on keeping us up all night worrying about him?&#8221;  Jeyna asked her infant son.<br><br>Darien replied merely by staring curiously at his mother.      Jeyna returned to her seat and continued to stare out the window.<br><br>As their glistening armour shined in the pale moonlight,  Seron Sleighhill and Barnabus walked quietly along the path in East Commons towards Nektulos forest and the city of Neriak.  According to the rumours that Barnabus had heard,  the attacks were occurring in the hills region of East Commons,  near the passage to Nektulos.   In the distance,  Seron could hear the chatter of numerous fire beetles and the flapping wings of a large Griffin.    Seron scanned the hills for any type of movement, and saw none.   However,  he could feel an evil presence nearby.   <br><br>&#8220;They are out there somewhere.  I can feel it.&#8221;  commented Seron<br><br>&#8220;Aye.  I know.&#8221;   replied  Barnabus.   &#8220;Keep your eyes and ears open.  It will soon be time.&#8221;<br><br>	They stalked their prey as quietly as possible.    Aided by invisibility magic,   Tralon and Aerual D&#8217;eewlay carefully monitored the dwarf and elf duel that had wandered carelessly into their commonlands.   Along with the couple was their five-year-old son,  Blair.    Tralon and Aerual were extremely pleased with their son.  At five years of age,  young Blair had already mastered several first rank necromancer spells.   For the first time in his life,  Blair saw the enemy.    Tralon and Aerual motioned for their son to keep quiet,  as they organized their bone chips.    Quietly,  under the cover of darkness,  the necromancer couple began to summon a pair of skeletal warriors.<br><br>	Seron Sleighhill thought he saw motion out of the corner of his eye.   He stopped dead in his tracks.<br><br>&#8220;What is it?   Do you see something?&#8221;  asked Barnabus.<br><br>&#8220;Maybe.    I do not know&#8230;.&#8221;  replied Seron.     <br><br>Seron drew his sword and walked slowly in the direction in which he saw something move.   Suddenly,   a pair of skeletal hands grabbed Seron&#8217;s ankles from below.<br><br>&#8220;Seron!  Look out!&#8221;   cried Barnabus.<br><br>Barnabus ran to his friend,   only to be hit by a blast of poison magic.    Barnabus flew fifteen feet in the air and landed in a nearby bush.    From the shadows,  emerged Tralon and Aerual D&#8217;eewlay.    Barnabus slowly rose to his feet and withdrew his sledgehammer.  Seron remained rooted to the ground by the necromancer couple&#8217;s undead minion.   <br><br>&#8220;Look at what we have here,  my dear.   Wood Elf filth and a dwarven D&#8217;raakhatal.&#8221;  said Tralon D&#8217;eewlay.  <br><br>&#8220;Dark Elf slime,   why don&#8217;t you speak common and say that again?&#8221;   challenged Barnabus.   The fact that the dwarf was called a name that he didn&#8217;t understand enraged him.<br><br>&#8220;Oh,  my short, and soon to be deceased friend&#8230;   we will speak common if it makes your inevitable death more comfortable for you,  if you wish.&#8221;  replied Aerual.   <br><br>In the hills,  a safe distance away,   young Blair D&#8217;eewlay watched the encounter.<br><br>&#8220;You two are the ones who will soon die.&#8221;   said Seron,  who was still rooted to the ground.<br><br>&#8220;Is that so?&#8221;  replied Tralon.   Without warning,  a second skeleton emerged from the soil next to Tralon.   Tralon simply pointed to Seron.   With a hideous cackle,  the skeletal warrior began to pummel Seron.   <br><br>&#8220;Seron!&#8221;  cried Barnabus.    Barnabus ran to engage the skeleton.  He brought his sledgehammer down on the skeleton&#8217;s arm and shattered it with one blow.    Aerual raised her hand and the skeleton that had a grasp on Seron&#8217;s ankles released him.   Seron dropped to the ground a bloody mess.   He struggled to get back to his feet.   With one arm remaining,  Tralon&#8217;s skeletal pet returned to him.   The skeleton that had a hold on Seron&#8217;s ankles rose from the soil and took his place next to Aerual.   <br><br>&#8220;As you can see,  my foolish friends.  You cannot defeat the Teir&#8217;dal.  It is foolish to even try to oppose the sons and daughters of Innoruuk.&#8221;  said Aerual.   &#8220;Blair.   Blair.  Come here,  my son.&#8221;<br><br>From the shadows emerged young Blair D&#8217;eewlay,  his red eyes focused directly on his foes.  <br><br>&#8220;Now Blair,  just as we practiced.&#8221;  said Tralon D&#8217;eewlay.<br><br>With a single nod,   Blair began to cast a spell on Seron Sleighhill.   Seron gasped for air,  as he could feel the life being drained from his body.    <br><br>&#8220;Stop it!&#8221;  screamed Barnabus.     Barnabus charged at Blair.   Calmly,  Aerual D&#8217;eewlay began to chant her own mystic words.   Suddenly,  Barnabus felt as if two Sand Giants had wrapped themselves around his ankles.    He could now barely move.<br><br>&#8220;My dwarven friend.   How dare you try to deprive my son of the pleasure of his very first kill.&#8221;   said Tralon.<br><br>Barnabus felt very cold.   He could not move.   There was not much that he could do,  except to watch his friend Seron die,  and to await death himself.     Young Blair continued to cast on Seron,  slowly draining away his life.   Finally,  Seron&#8217;s lifeless body collapsed to the ground.   <br><br>&#8220;No!!!!!!&#8221;   cried Barnabus.<br><br>&#8220;Worry not,  my short friend.  You will be joining your friend shortly.&#8221;   said Aerual.<br><br>Mana pulsed through the veins of Tralon and Aerual D&#8217;eewlay.    Barnabus could see a pale green aura surround the necromancer couple.   Suddenly,  Barnabus felt very hot.   He looked at his hands,  and he could see his skin boiling.   Barnabus broke into a heavy sweat and dropped to his knees.  He could not run,  he could not hide.  All he could do is await death.  <br><br>&#8220;What is going on out there!&#8221;  came a voice from the distance<br><br>Tralon turned in the direction of the voice and saw its source.   It was Innkeep Harold. Tralon cursed in his dark language.<br><br>&#8220;Harold!   Bah!   Blair.  Time to go.&#8221;  said Tralon.<br><br>&#8220;But Father.  He is not dead yet.&#8221;   complained Blair.<br><br>&#8220;Do not argue with your father!&#8221;  said Aerual.    &#8220;It is time to go.  NOW.&#8221;  <br><br>With that,  the three Dark Elves disappeared into the shadows in the direction of Neriak.   Barnabus struggled to his feet and watched them melt away into the shadows.   Barnabus moved slowly to his fallen friend.  He checked his pulse,  there was none.   <br><br>&#8220;Are you all right?&#8221;  asked Innkeep Harold.<br><br>Barnabus did not reply.   Instead,  he picked up the body of his fallen friend and began to make his way back to Freeport.   &#8220;How was he going to explain this to Jeyna Sleighhill?&#8221;  he wondered.   Darien Sleighhill no longer had a father.<br><br>End of Chapter 1<br><br>Send Comments to kma@julian.uwo.ca for any suggestions,  comments, etc.<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>

