Part 1<br>    <br>    "Ye know, it's a wonder I haven't killed ye yet, ye senseless idiot."  Bulkroth spat the words irritably at his companion, who trudged along wearily ahead of him.  The other dwarf didn't bother to turn around, but the fairly audible grumbling that emanated from his short, stocky figure indicated that he was no more pleased with Bulkroth than Bulkroth was pleased with him.  <br><br>Taking his relative silence as an invitation to press even further, Bulkroth continues his assault.  "Take us straight to Kelethin."  He mocked, using his best imitation of Kragbarth's deep-throated voice.  "Damned elves.  If we ever actually get there, I'm throwing you straight off the edge."  Kragbarth refused to be nettled by the comment.  Reaching out in front of him, he grabbed a thick, springy branch that protruded out into the heavily overgrown "path" the two dwarves were slogging along.  This he held tightly onto for a few feet, until he himself was quite clear of it.  Then, without the <br>slightest twinge of remorse, he released the branch, sending it catapulting straight into Bulkroth's burly, armored chest.   An audible clang reverberated throughout the deep woods as the branch crashed into the dwarf's thick, metal breastplate, followed by an almost as audible thud as the dwarf crashed into the ground.  The resulting torrent of curses sent most of the birds within a half-mile radius soaring out of the trees for safety, and probably both alerted and scared off any enemy that had the misfortune of being in the same vicinity as the two dour dwarves.  Kragbarth didn't even turn his head back towards his unpleasant companion; the fiery, red-bearded <br>dwarf simply trudged on, leaving his muddy cousin sputtering on the forest floor.<br><br>    After several minutes of relative silence, Bulkroth managed to catch up with the leading dwarf, and fell in step with notably less complaint.  "Where do ye suppose we are?"  He asked gruffly, brushing aside some cobwebs from his ruddy forehead with the back of his mailed hand.  After a few seconds, Kragbarth responded.<br><br>    "Ye got me.  It's a big woods.  Not that we really got anything to worry about."  Bulkroth grumbled at this answer.<br><br>    "Aye, so long as we don't starve.  Can't eat these Brell-be-damned leaves."  The dwarf's stomach added it's own grumbling, accentuating his point.<br><br>    "Quit yer whining." Kragbarth responded sharply to the chorus of grumbles emanating from his companion. "I've got a good bag fulla fishcakes in the pack, bought 'em off that elf we saw yesterday."   Bulkroth shot him a filthy glance.<br><br>    "You know full well I hate fishcakes."  He kicked at a root with his thick, iron-shod boot.  "Besides, we saw that elf two days ago, not yesterday.  Fishcakes barely stay fresh fer two hours, let alone two days." Kragbarth still refrained from looking at his companion.<br><br>    "Then eat yer Brell-be-damned leaves, ye Brell-be-damned idiot."  The red-bearded dwarf swept aside a patch of briars, and trudged along a path that was no longer the slightest bit visible.  A few more minutes passed quietly, broken only by the grumbling of Bulkroth's stomach.  Eventually, Kragbarth felt a rough tap on his armored shoulder.  "Aye?"  He tossed the word over his back, not bothering to glance backwards.  Bulkroth spoke softly; his gruff voice was barely audible above the clumping of their heavy boots.<br><br>    "Can I have a fishcake, lad?"  Kragbarth's grim visage split with a slow smile.<br><br>    "Be my guest."  He responded, carefully controlling his voice.  "They're in yer pack.  I didn't wanna carry em, the things smell terrible!"<br><br>    The Mighty Faydark was deep in shadows well before the sun fully set, the great trees shutting out the last warm rays, and chilling those left outdoors to the bone, even though the sky was still tinged with color, and the breath of summer was still in the air.  Bulkroth stared up into that sky, watching the magnificent reds and oranges recede into a fading, deep purple through the leaves of the mighty trees.  Crickets and cicadas were beginning to awaken throughout the wood, filling the darkening Faydark with the chorus of nighttime in the summer.  The dwarf looked over at his companion across the small clearing, catching sight of the warm glow of fireflies flickering in <br>and out of the trees.  Kragbarth was leaning heavily against a thick tree trunk, draining a waterskin that smelled suspiciously like beer.  The red-bearded dwarf met his cousin's glance, and lowered the flask.  "Nice night, eh?"  He asked, the first words the two had spoken for some time.  Bulkroth turned his gaze back up into the sky.<br><br>    "Aye, that it is."  He responded, and paused a moment, pulling in a deep breath of evening air.  "Maybe we should camp right here, tonight.  We've walked a long way already, I think we earned it."  Kragbarth glanced around the clearing, weighing the matter in his mind.<br><br>    "Don't suppose we're likely to find a nicer spot tonight <br>anyways."  He responded.  "I'm good fer camp, so long as yer takin' first watch."  Bulkroth sighed heavily, tossing his pack upon the ground.<br><br>    "Aye, no problem."  He agreed, without removing his gaze from the deep sky.  "Go cook us some dinner."  Kragbarth set about gathering some small firewood.    <br><br>"Warm fishcakes?"  He asked, glancing over at his cousin.  Bulkroth <br>shrugged.  Kragbarth dumped the wood in the center of the clearing and dug into his pack.  Triumphantly, he dragged out a small, wrapped bundle.  Bulkroth looked over at the package with interest.  "Picked up something else off that elf, too."  Kragbarth tore open the carefully folded package with his dagger, and thrust his nose into the contents, sniffing sharply.  "Couple good slabs of wolf meat."  He held the package up for Bulkroth to see.  "The elf salted 'em, they're still good as ever.  I'll cook 'em up real nice for us.  I even got some beer stowed in one of those flasks."  He jerked his <br>thumb in the direction of the waterskins, spilling out of one of the packs.  Bulkroth smiled knowingly at the gesture.  Kragbarth grinned at his weary companion.  "Tonight we feast!"<br><br>    The sky was clear and cold, allowing the light of the pale moon to illuminate the thick treetops of the great forest.  Yet, on the ground, the heavy shadows of those same trees absorbed all celestial light, leaving it's inhabitants in a night as black as pitch, a darkness that they were all too used to.  Bulkroth huddled tighter into the worn blanket draped across his broad shoulders, absently hacking at a chunk of unused firewood with his dagger as he waited out his watch.  It was a cold night, even though September had only just begun to wane, and the dwarf was not the slightest bit surprised to see faint tendrils of his breath condense in the air before him, lightly dispersing in the cool, gentle breeze that wafted through the <br>wood.  <br><br>The night was quiet, although the insects still chirped and Kragbarth occasionally burst forth with an explosive snore.  Bulkroth lifted his dagger from the block of wood and picked at one of his teeth, scraping free a straggling piece of food.  Dinner had been excellent.  Although he hated to admit it to his face, Kragbarth was one hell of a cook.  Few people could turn a slab of wolf meat into a delicacy the way the fiery dwarf could.  In fact, he could cook nearly as well as Bulkroth could brew, given the proper facilities, of course, and that was no small feat.  Kragbarth had long ago <br>given up denying the fact that his cousin easily made the best beer he had ever tasted, realizing at last that by acknowledging his companion's skill, more beer was to be had.  Bulkroth smiled at the thought of his cousin's grudging compliments.  Yeah, when the two of them finally settled down with their own inn, no competition would even stand a chance.<br><br>    Bulkroth's eyes roved over to the still form of his cousin and companion.  Kragbarth's ruddy features were dimly illuminated in the dying light from the glowing embers of their cook fire, the fiery ashes accenting further the flame red beard that grew in a tangled mess from his strong jaw.  His dented breastplate gleamed slightly from beneath his ragged cloak and the equally ragged blanket he was wrapped in.  The shiny, three-horned helm that he wore with such pride rested directly next to his sleeping figure, right alongside <br>the mighty warhammer that was his heirloom, and weapon of choice.  Bulkroth's eyes rested on that hammer, and he subconsciously fingered the heavy battleaxe that lay across his thick knees.  Kragbarth's hammer was one of the most fearsome weapons he had ever seen.  <br><br>Although it seemed unimpressive lying cold and dark next to the sleeping warrior, Bulkroth had seen his cousin wield the mighty weapon in combat countless hundreds of times.  Every single one of those times, Bulkroth had not ceased to be impressed.  The thick steel head of the weapon was unadorned, save for a single, chiseled <br>rune blazoned along its left side.  When Kragbarth traced his finger through that rune, the hammer erupted with life, crackling with internal magics all its own.  It was a fearsome sight to see.  Not that Bulkroth's own axe was any less fearsome.  Certainly it was prettier to look at, the shining silvery steel seeming to glow with the barely visible rays of the white moon, and the soft, carefully laid grip caressing the rough palm that held it.  Yet, in truth, it was the wielder, rather than the weapon, that held the difference <br>in battle, as the two dwarves had found out many times over.  Both dwarves were easily worthy of their weapons, as countless enemies had found out, although often without the chance to do so many times over.  Thinking of this, Bulkroth smiled inwardly, easing his armored bulk back against a tree trunk, and fell to memories of the duo's fiercest battles.<br><br>    So wrapped up in his thoughts was he that Bulkroth missed the first signs of approaching danger almost until it was too late.  With a jerk of his head he pulled himself back to the present, and felt a tense shiver run down his spine.  Clambering to his feet, as silently as an armored dwarf can, he pricked his ears to his surroundings, quickly kicking out the last glowing embers of the campfire.  The insects had stopped chirping, the forest was dead silent, unnaturally silent.  Straining his ears, Bulkroth tried desperately to pick up a recognizable sound.  For several long seconds the dread silence echoed through the mighty Faydark, until finally Bulkroth's ears picked up what they were searching for.  A faint, rapid crunching <br>slithered through the dark trees.  Faint, yet increasing in volume every passing second.  The crunching was unmistakable; footsteps, running footsteps, a sound the dwarf had heard often enough.  Yet, with the rapidly approaching footsteps came a growing, chill sense of dread, a feeling that grew on the dwarf inexplicably, filling him with an uneasy fear that he could not explain.  Without looking down, Bulkroth kicked softly at his companion, arousing the sleeping dwarf, who was on his feet in a matter of seconds, balancing his hammer in one hand, rubbing sleep from his deep-set eyes with the other.  He looked at Bulkroth questioningly.<br><br>    "What is it?" He mouthed silently.  Bulkroth shrugged, both in answer to the inquiry and in an attempt to shake away the discomforting fear.  He glanced over at Kragbarth; by the uneasy look on his cousin's face, he was experiencing the same inexplicable feeling.  Bulkroth tightened is grip on his battleaxe, hoping to grind out the shaking in his hands.  Kragbarth reached down with fingers that trembled ever so slightly, snatched up his helm by one of the horns, and dropped it onto his head.  The footfalls were <br>clearly audible now.  Someone, or something, was crashing through the woods, headed straight in their direction.  The two dwarves crouched down amongst the shadows of the tree trunks, straining their eyes for a glimpse of this newcomer.<br><br>    They did not have to wait long.  Moments later, dark branches began to swing and small limbs cracked off, beaten down by a tall, ragged figure, racing blindly through the foliage at an incredible pace.  Just as the figure would have stepped into the dwarfs tiny clearing, one of its feet became entangled in some sparse underbrush, and the creature crashed to the ground with a groan, rolling into the clearing, in plain view of the hidden dwarves. <br><br> Bulkroth looked over at his cousin.  Kragbarth stood up.  The figure in the clearing was struggling to his feet.  Kragbarth caught sight of pointed ears, saw the flash of large, luminous eyes, set in a thin face.  As bloody and ragged as this figure was, it was unmistakably recognizable.  Kragbarth spoke one word to his concealed cousin.<br>   <br> "Elf."  At the sound of the voice, the elf swung around in the direction of the shadowed warrior.  Kragbarth found an arrow leveled at his throat.  He held up his hand, palm towards the newcomer.  "Hold, elf."  He spoke the elven tongue crudely, but the effect was astonishing.  The elf looked hard at him for a second more, then, turning aside his bow, he crumpled to the ground, panting heavily.  He looked in Kragbarth's direction.<br>    <br>"Run, dwarves."  He spoke the common tongue, and his words encompassed both Kragbarth and Bulkroth.  His sharp eyes had not missed the crouched dwarf.  Kragbarth stepped forward, extending a hand to the prone elf.<br>   <br> "From what, lad?  I'm not prone to running at just anything."  The dwarf hoisted the panting elf to his feet, supporting his slender form on his stocky shoulders.  His words were bold, but his eyes gave away the growing fear the two dwarves continued to experience, a fear that obviously grew upon the elf as well.  The elf looked at him strangely, a wild look in his large eyes.  Then his gaze trailed past the dwarf, staring into the woods, and his <br>eyes widened in terror.<br>   <br> "No!  Too late!"  The elf whispered these last words.  Kragbarth stared at him, not comprehending what was said.  Then he felt the hair rise on the back of his neck.  The elf continued to stare dumbly over his shoulder.  Bulkroth bellowed an earsplitting shout from his place amongst the tree trunks.<br>   <br> "DUCK!"  Kragbarth bowled himself over forwards, dragging the lanky elf down with him.  The air above his head sang as the shimmering, silvery blade sliced through the place where his head had been, only instants before.  He rolled onto his back, leveling his hammer, in an attempt to get a glimpse of his attacker.  What hovered before him froze his heart, and his rough face mirrored the terror-filled visage of the elf at his side.  As dark as the night was, the hellish figure confronting the prostrate dwarf was blacker, its torn, rotting black robes billowing out around it with a numbingly cold <br>wind that seemed to emanate from within.  The smell of rotting flesh filled Kragbarth's nostrils, yet his nose didn't even wrinkle, he simply stared into the ghastly visage of the monster before him.  The creature's face had long since decayed, leaving a dark, hideous skull, grinning like a tortured demon from the plane of fear.  The empty eye sockets glowed with an unholy light, and these endless depths held Kragbarth's eyes, froze him in dumb terror.  In it's bony, rotting hands it held a long, glimmering, vicious scythe, and <br>slowly it raised this weapon, preparing a blow that would slice the dwarf's head clean off his body.  Still, Kragbarth could only stare.  The scythe rose higher and higher, then stopped.  With a blood chilling, moaning laugh, the hellish creature brought down the wicked blade.  <br><br>It never made contact.  With a howl, Bulkroth hurled himself bodily at the unholy apparition, crashing into it with bone-cracking force, and disrupting the swing meant to behead his cousin.  The creature was swept to the ground underneath the armored dwarf, yet as they hit, it was Bulkroth who screamed, not the apparition. <br> <br>Yet, this was not an ordinary scream.  The bellow of agony that poured from Bulkroth's mouth was inhuman, filled with terror and pain, as if the dwarfs very soul were being pierced.  That scream shocked Kragbarth back to life.  Gritting his teeth, he dragged his stubby finger through the groove of the rune on his hammer, and swung the weapon high over his head.  The dark steel begin to glow sullenly, then with a crackle, explosive lightning erupted around it, coursing through the veins of both the metal and it's wielder. <br><br>Snarling, Kragbarth charged the apparition, which was now atop Bulkroth, it's fleshless hands wrapped tightly around the writhing dwarf's neck.  Kragbarth swung his crackling hammer, catching the demonic beast soundly in the torso area, sweeping it off of his companion, and giving Kragbarth the satisfaction of feeling bones splinter beneath the black robes.  Yet, the dwarf watched with a horrid fascination as the creature picked itself up, swinging it's <br>enormous scythe in a wide arc in his direction.  Cursing, Kragbarth fell back, his mind racing.  Bulkroth still lie writhing upon the ground, clutching at his throat.  His skin was all blue.  Kragbarth wiped cold sweat from his forehead, the scythe was huge, far too long to allow him to get close enough to score a hit without first being cut open by the shimmering blade.  The apparition advanced upon him very slowly, swinging the scythe in slow, lethal arcs, making the air sing with the sound of hissing metal.  Kragbarth's mind was blank.  He would have to charge this thing and pray to get a good shot off before the thing tore him apart.  Muttering a quick prayer to Brell under his breath, he cocked his warhammer, facing the hellish visage with the cool calm of a warrior who knows he's going to die.  The <br>rotting creature seemed to smile in anticipation.  Kragbarth swallowed a cold lump in his throat.  Then, at that very moment, a muffled "twang" sounded throughout the small clearing, followed by a soft "thwack."  The apparition reared back its ghastly, hooded head, and in less than a second, flames licked up its robe, swiftly transforming the creature into a demonic inferno.  With a hellish scream, it swung around, whipping the scythe in a murderous assault upon its attacker.  <br><br>The moment the creature turned, Kragbarth charged, and with every once of strength in his compact body, smote the head of the decaying monster with his blazing hammer.  The skull shattered beneath the blow, and energy coursed through the flaming apparitions ghastly body.  <br><br>The robes crumpled into a smoldering heap upon the ground, and the enormous scythe fell to the earth with a clatter.  Panting, Kragbarth looked up from the corpse.  There stood the ragged elf, bow in hand, staring at the guttering mass lying upon the ground at his feet.  From the back of the ungodly apparition protruded the charred shaft of an arrow.  Kragbarth muttered a quick thanks to whatever god was watching over him.  The elf continued to stare at the crumpled corpse with a blank expression on his thin face, although the apparition was obviously incapacitated, and the chill fear had lifted from the clearing with it's relative death.  Kragbarth opened his mouth to speak, but he was cut off by a low groan, feebly drifting from <br>Bulkroth's prone form.  Momentarily forgetting the elf, Kragbarth clumped over to his cousin's side, and dropped to his knees, shaking the unconscious dwarf gently.  Color was slowly returning to Bulkroth's face, and his eyes rolled slowly open.  <br><br>With a weak cough, Bulkroth managed to revive himself, hoisting himself up feebly upon one elbow, and looking at his companion with <br>a sickly triumphant expression.    "Boy lad, do you owe me one now!"  He wheezed the words, but they were clearly audible.  Kragbarth looked down at him, and was silent for a few moments.  Bulkroth waited patiently, a weak smirk upon his pale face.  <br><br>Kragbarth patted him roughly on the shoulder.<br><br>    "Aye, next round's on me."<br>                                    -end, part 1-<br><br>-Hope you enjoyed it!

