<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=-1>Okay, I've had enough.  The player-killing situation on Rallos Zek has become intolerable, and it's about time someone came out with a true-to-life guide on what it means to be a player-killer, and the impact it's going to have on the lifestyle you've chosen for your character.<P>Now, before all you mindless yahoos out there (you know who you are) decide to skip the rest of this article and click on my e-mail address below to send me nastygrams, let me say up front that I'm <I>not</I> here to flame player-killers for their choices.  If I were against PK as a play style, I wouldn't be playing on Rallos Zek, okay?  I fully expect to fall victim to the occasional marauding vagabond out to get my barbed shoulder pads or savant's cap.  It's a part of life on the Rallos Zek server, and I never cry foul unless I was somehow helpless to defend myself (i.e. link dead or similarly stuck due to a flaw in the game).  In fact, if I believe that the battle was fought fairly and the victor had performed well, I will go out of my way to congratulate them in /tell.<P>So if you're all set and ready to send me a scathing letter about how I should go play on a "care bear" server, you can save your breath because your efforts will be wasted, and it'll only serve to make you look all the more hose-brained when I post your e-mail in the reader responses.<P>What I'm talking about is the typical player-killer attitude, pure and simple.  Player Killers (read: those who run around killing every other character they can for no better reason than for fun and profit) need a serious attitude adjustment.  They spew the same old tired rhetoric every time I log on Rallos, and I'm sick of it.  <P><B>Rhetoric 1: "If you don't want to be PKed, play on a blue server!"</B><P>Rallos would be <U>empty</U>.  Nobody likes to be killed by another player and have an item stolen that they either quested for weeks to obtain, or paid out the nose to purchase.  Nobody!<P>I'll agree that if they didn't want that item stolen, then they should have taken the proper precautions against it.  The best advice I can give is to make sure you always have enough container slots to bag your items and make regular trips to the bank often.  <I>Never</I> carry more cash around with you than you can afford to lose!<P>But anyway, back to the issue.  Not everyone on the PvP server is there to share your Quake attitude, bud, nor should they be forced to share that vision any more than you should be forced to share theirs.  <P>Personally, I enjoy playing on Rallos Zek because of several factors.  <P>For one thing, your achievements mean a <I>lot</I> more than on a normal server.  High-level characters are held in much greater esteem by those beneath them -- even by green cons.  I, for one, strive to obtain such an image with my own characters.<P>Another thing I like about Rallos Zek is that gestures of kindness are far more meaningful to people.  When I come across a valid con (blue, even, or yellow) resting on the ground with only half a bubble left, and I cast a greater heal spell on them with my cleric, it means so much more than if I had done it on a blue server.  I've made a friend for life, because they know I could just as easily have whapped them a few times, ending their union with that grotesque mask they're wearing.  <P>And finally, if someone's being an impudent prick, they're more likely to be placed in a position where they are made to put their money where their mouth is.  It really bugs me that someone my level on a normal server can shoot their mouth off, and I'm powerless to retaliate with anything other than the /ignore switch.<P>Those are the things I get out of playing on Rallos, and it's why the greater percentage of my characters resides on that server.  I don't share the attitude that it should be one big bloodbath, and that's my privilege.  So, lay off telling me I should play somewhere else, because you're dead wrong.<P><B>Rhetoric 2: "I'm playing my role as an evil character!" or "I hate Dark Elves.  I'm just fulfilling my role like any decent High Elf!"</B><P>That is the most enormous pile of BS I have ever seen shoveled in EverQuest, and considering some of the nerfs Verant's put in place, that's saying a <I>lot</I>.<P>I have played this game since beta (well over a year), and I can honestly say I have never -- not <I>once</I> -- been PKed by someone actually playing their role.  Zero.  Zip.  Nada.  I think if it ever took place, I'd probably fall out of my chair in a coma.<P>Pin back your ears and listen, people.  Simply killing someone because their race/class is at odds with yours is <I>not</I> roleplaying!  Roleplaying means acting in-character.  During a fight, would it be so hard to say "I slay you by the hate of Innoruuk," or "Remove your sorry Teir'Dal hide from my sight, or I'll remove it for you!"<P><I>That</I> is roleplaying.<P>One of the most absurd things I've heard is when a PKer says, "What are you getting all upset about?  I'm just roleplaying!"  If you were a real roleplayer, buddy, you'd recognize that it makes sense your victim would be irate at what you just did to them.  What <I>really</I> would be out-of-character is for them to just shrug it off, like you want.<P>Roleplaying, my butt...<P><B>Rhetoric 3: "Everyone on this server is a PK!"</B><P>Ridiculous.  The term "PK" is reserved for people who kill wantonly, regardless of race/class/deity.  It's murder for lack of reason beyond that of gaining personal wealth.  I'm here to tell you, the clear majority of the people playing on Rallos Zek are <I>not</I> PK.<P>Vengeance is another matter.  When someone slays you and you retaliate by hunting them down in return, then all is kosher in my opinion.  Yes, technically once you kill a player you can be labeled a "player-killer" in the strictest sense of the term, but certainly not under the criteria I've detailed above.  This holds true for anti-PK guilds that valiantly help protect others and go out of their way to seek out and destroy notorious player-killers out there.<P><B>Rhetoric 4: "I was once a PK, but I stopped."</B><P>This statement sparked off one of the most enormous debates I've ever seen in the game.  A known player-killer was shouting that he had given up his evil ways and was playing it straight from now on, and asked for everyone's forgiveness.<P>Utter crap, and I'll tell you why.<P>First off, never believe anyone who says this.  I don't care if it's the truth or not; anyone who would behave in such a manner in the first place is in no way deserving of my trust, and will never convince me of their newly discovered benevolence.  Period.<P>"But, Shadoe!  What about forgiveness?  Shouldn't we extend the benefit of the doubt, and give this person a chance to redeem himself?"<P>The answer is simple: NO!  Redemption is earned, and simply asking for forgiveness does not cut it, people.  How many people has that person victimized to earn their notoriety as a player-killer?  How much platinum, and how many items have that person stolen and sold for a 100% profit margin?  How many of the items he currently uses were bought using that money?  You want redemption?  Then <I><U>give</U> <U>it</U> <U>back!</U></I>  All of it, and leave no stone unturned!<P>Of course, what I'm suggesting is impossible.  Many of the victims have already given up and moved on at this point.  Even if they haven't, it's ridiculous to expect to remember every single person you've killed, every item you took from them, and then have the resources to repay them all in full.  I don't care how high a level you are -- it can't be done.<P>The only other option that comes anywhere close to redemption is to scrag the PK character you're playing and start over with a new one as a gesture of your sincerity, and the depth of the guilt you feel.  This is typically when player-killers show their true colors.  "No way!  I'm level 34!  You seriously expect me to start over?  Screw you!"  Bingo.  You're not sorry, so don't insult my intelligence.  You're going to continue with this character, playing "honestly" using wealth obtained at the expense of others, and you think that qualifies you for my forgiveness?  <P>Think again.  You're a PK.  You always will be in my eyes.<P><B>Rhetoric 5: "Five on one?  That's no fair, man!  Leave me alone!  I'm petitioning you all for harassment!"</B>  (Usually shouted by a PKer when he's managed to piss off so many people that they decided to team up on him.)<P>My response is always the same: "Go for it."  Chances are very good that he had already been killing me repeatedly and refused to lay off.  <I>That</I> is harassment, my friends, and the arrival of a guide or GM could only be a good thing.<P>It amazes me how most player-killers get when the tables are turned on them.  When the going gets rough, the PKer gets whiney.  If you can't take it, don't dish it out.<P>And a single death by a group of five victims isn't nearly enough.  If he killed all five people three times each, then I say he has <I>at least</I> 15 deaths of his own coming.  I say "at least," since he's probably already stashed their cash and belongings away in the bank, where they have no hope of recovery.<P><B>Rhetoric 6: "Dammit, this is the PK server!  I have a right to PK if I want to, so live with it!"</B><P>I saved this one for last, because this is one issue they're very right about.  Yes, Rallos Zek was created for the purposes of player-versus-player combat.  If they are able take you down in some way, they are certainly free to do so.<P>But remember, this isn't a rant about player-killing.  It's a rant about the typical player-killer attitude.<P>So, you claim the right to player-kill?  Fair enough.  But you better be prepared to suffer the consequences.  So, allow me to clue you in on a few rights everyone else has.  <P>If you kill someone, you're seriously going to make them angry.  And when people are angry they get vocal about it.  Expect them to start calling you every name in the book in shouts, ooc, auctions, guildsay, and any other means they can dream up.  That's their right.<P>While they're doing that, they are going to warn others in the zone about you by shouting that you're a PKer.  Not only is that their right, but I personally see it as their <I>duty</I>.<P>Kill enough people, and they're going to get organized and kick your butt all over the zone.  Leave the zone, and they will likely follow.  The only way to avoid being hounded is to log out, which makes everybody happy.  That's their right.<P>No matter what you say or how you justify it, the truth is your actions are an affront to most people's sense of honor and justice.  Entire guilds were founded because of how true this is.  These people <I>will</I> seek you out and they <I>will</I> kill you on sight when they find you.  As a general rule, people will view your actions as deplorable, and will have nothing to do with you.  I don't care if it's in the game context or not, expect to be labeled a bad person and don't act surprised when you discover that people don't like you.  It's their right.  <P>Those are the caveats to being a player-killer, and if you refuse to accept any of them as being the standard quid-pro-quo, then you're a <I>stupid</I> player-killer on top of it all.  <P>- &lt;Shadoe&gt;<BR><A HREF="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</A></FONT>

