Forgive me Reader, for I have sinned. It has been three months since my last dissension. The alluring call of Norrath taunts me at night and on the weekends. Try as I might, its evil temptations enthrall me until I fall victim to my own weak mortal desires and perform the "double-click, snore, click, escape, escape, escape... escape, click, [password]" ritual of loading EverQuest. My carnal massively multi-player urges become satisfied for a brief time, yet remain insatiable in the extreme. I beseech you... I need help. I have no life. Forgive me, for I am an online sinner junky dweeboid. <P>Actually, a number of things have pulled me away from writing this next article. Not only am I embarking on an unprecedented move to the world of authoring fiction (jibes and snide comments welcome), but the EQ issues of late haven't exactly rung my bell. Not that there haven't been good issues to write about... far from it. But they've either been commented to death already by far better writers, or they've been so petty that I didn't want it to appear as though I was grandstanding in the whole mountain/molehill conundrum just to get a new article cranked out. <P>As it stands, many things have happened lately that I would have loved to comment on. And that's all they would have been, too - comments. To cite one prominent example, this entire debate on the rogue pickpocket skill is something I have extremely strong feelings about, and no amount of bold-faced "assurances" from Verant will convince me that it hasn't been altered. But this is just one of many examples I could give, and I don't wish to argue the matter here. <P>So, enough idle chit chat.  Just this morning, I read a posting where our esteemed Abashi addressed a user concern that totally blew me away.  Sitting here speechless, I can only show it to you and let you come to your own conclusion before I begin my rant...<P>----------<P><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">User:</FONT> Okay first of all I just looked on my EQ box thats been sitting under my computer desk since EQ came out and its says for ages 13+, now tell me what 13 year old kid needs to be staring at female characters with cleavage? <P><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Abashi:</FONT><B> I don&#8217;t think that the amount of cleavage in the game is excessive at all. It&#8217;s certainly no more, and in many cases less, than the average MTV video or Sports Illustrated Swimsuit issue. The PG-13 movie rating allows for brief nudity, which we have none of here, unless you count the rear view of a troll. </B><P><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">User:</FONT> First point: Female Characters need to be toned down or age limit needs to be upped. Second Point..Recently I've read on forums something totally ridiculous like EQ Cybersex.. I thought this was supposed to be a game where you went up in lvls and got equipment by killing stuff? or is eq cybersex some sort of kinky quest? I mean come on verant you need to put some major attention into this especially when a 13 year old boy can pay 1000pp for to have another female character have EQCybersex with him, I read that on a forum... what do you think? <P><FONT COLOR="#0000FF">Abashi:</FONT><B> We certainly don&#8217;t have anything to do with those sites, and we really have neither the ability nor authority to police the content that people put on their private sites. If this stuff takes place in game, and someone raises the issue with our GM staff, then certainly we can step in.<P>Personally I think that it&#8217;s the responsibilities of parents to decide what content is acceptable for their children. <P>-Gordon </B><P>----------<P>Now that you have read all that, I have now regained the power of speech and am fully prepared to give you my take, without commercial interruption, on this sensitive subject.  Here goes...<P><I>GIVE ME A FRIGGIN' BREAK!!!</I><P>Thank you.  I just had to get that out of my system.<P>Female characters with cleavage.  Yes, friends, that is what is wrong with EverQuest, and must be immediately addressed by Verant.  Otherwise the core morals of over 170,000 people will come crumbling down around us.  That is the real issue, Verant!  Nevermind the senseless violence where 13-year-olds are taught to march into the homes of various creatures, wantonly killing for no better reason than to "level" or obtain that Shiny Brass Shield.  No, it's the half-naked chicks that are corrupting the youth of the world.<P>Sanity Check #1: Are the females in EverQuest dressed inappropriately for young audiences?<P>My Answer: I'm not going to sit here and profess to hold the moral ground to tell you what is best for your kids.  Neither should the user above, and certainly neither should Verant.  Abashi said it best; the parents are responsible for that decision, and nobody else.<P>Sanity Check #2: Are the females in EverQuest dressed inappropriately for combat?<P>My Answer: In most cases, definitely!  Has anyone ever taken a good, close look at the female Wood Elf in leather?  (C'mon, admit it, you sick bastard!)  Will someone please explain to me exactly what the tunic is designed to protect?  Certainly not her virtue.  Don't even get me started on the ringmail...<P>Nevertheless, the art of titillation is a delicate one, and it's an art that fully transcends the notion of making EverQuest reflect reality.  In the real world, would a female enter combat dressed like 80% of the women depicted in Norrath?  Of course not.  The idea is absurd.  But the fact remains, Norrath is an advocate of "high fantasy," (or so they tell me) and high fantasy is notorious for its curvaceous and provocative women.  It's a fact of life.  If there is any doubt to this, take a look at the works of art created by <A HREF="http://www.larryelmore.com">Larry Elmore</A> and EverQuest's own <A HREF="http://www.keithparkinson.com">Keith Parkinson</A>.  Unarguably beautiful works of fantasy art, largely involving healthy, attractive women.<P>Sanity Check #3: Are the <I>males</I> of EverQuest dressed inappropriately?<P>My Answer: This isn't a question to be answered so much as to allow me to make a point.  Whenever a woman is scantily clad, it's always perceived as a moral outrage.  Yet, when men show off their physique in a similar fashion, everything's kosher.  It amazes me how political correctness focuses so much on the female while ignoring the double-standards of males.  <P>To wit, the barbarian males.  In their unladen form, they wear kilts and boots.  That's it.  Nothing else.  Zippo!  Verant would have us believe that these Scottish wannabes are hardy enough to survive for longer than five minutes in the harsh and freezing wastelands of Everfrost without any better protection against the elements.  <I>Right!</I>  At least the females have <I>something</I> more to cover themselves with -- albeit just barely.<P>Is this any more believable than a female warrior charging into the valley of death wearing nothing more than a thong and halter top?  Obviously not.  But which do we choose to focus on, and which do we choose to dismiss?  To quote Dan Quayle, "I don't get it!"<P>Sanity Check #4: Is EQ cybersex some sort of kinky quest?<P>My Answer: I can't believe someone has the blind ignorance to even ask this question.  It tells me that this person has never once played EverQuest (at least not to any respectable lengths) and clearly has no clue what his/her kid is up to on the Internet or anywhere else.<P>EverQuest <I>is</I> about leveling and getting equipment by killing stuff -- in many ways this is painfully true, especially for roleplayers like myself.  To my knowledge, there are no quests that could be termed sexually unsuitable or improper.  Not once have I seen emotes or scenes in EverQuest that depict sexual acts or situations even the slightest bit risque.<P>That's on Verant's side.  What the players choose to say or do is a different matter.  But like Abashi said, if a problem arises because of it and someone complains to a guide or game master, they will take the appropriate measures to correct it.<P>To further beat this dead horse, the notion of paying 1000 platinum for cybersex in EverQuest hits me as being plainly ridiculous.  I find it laughable that someone would blow that much virtual cash for something they can find on just about any IRC network for free.  Not only that, but the game mechanics simply don't foster that kind of behavior.  Shoot, you can't even lie down in bed <I>alone</I>, much less with another person.  (Well, technically if you both feigned death you could pull it off, but that's really stretching things and to be honest, really kind of sick!)<P>It amazes me what people will believe and what people choose to attack.  The miniscule amount of sexual content in EverQuest makes TV shows with "suggestive content" seem downright vulgar by comparison, if you ask me.<P>A word of advice to you sir and/or madam who made the post above.  Start focusing on talking to your kid about morals, about the dangers of the Internet and what to expect.  For heaven's sake make sure your child understands your stance on what they choose to do when such morally dubious situations arise, and don't kid yourself -- they <I>will</I> arise at some point.  Above all, stop trying to impose the responsibility for your kid's upbringing on Verant Interactive.  They have better things to do, like fixing that annoying looting bug!<P>- &lt;Shadoe&gt;<br><a href="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</a>

<!-- End Content -->
