<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Aurum  (<a href="mailto:aurum@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">aurum@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
The effects an online auctioning site can have on an MMORPG are amazing.  For instance, the online auction web site known as eBayallows a person to bid and buy an EQ account, allowing the individual to bypass months of playing time spent accumulating experience, equipment and money.  Thus giving the individual a huge advantage over other players. <P>Should there be an attempt, or more of an attempt made, to ban the auction of EverQuest accounts on all online auctioning sites?  Is therea brilliant plan  just waiting to be discovered that would allow the accounts to be banned?   Would it be a waste of time?   Or should people have the right to auction accounts?  This is theissue we'll be debating on the <a href="http://vnboards.ign.com/board.asp?brd=5047">Player View Forum</a>. <P>The following are excerpts from a thread of emails from one devoted player in his quest to ban the auctions of all EQ accounts on eBay:<UL>After reading about eBay's VeRO system on the EverQuest board, I decided tomake use of it. VeRO is an eBay program under which licence holders(and third parties) may notify eBay of items for sale includingnon-transferrable or unowned intellectual property for the most part. Ifound the eBay page and send them a notification, then mailed JohnSmedley of Verant this:<BLOCKQUOTE>To: John Smedley <br>From: Chris Warren<br>Re: Violation of EverQuest Intellectual Property Rights and User Termsof Service Agreement Notification.<P>Dear Sir:<P>The following has been reported to Ebay (<a href="http://www.ebay.com">www.ebay.com</a>) under theirVerified Rights Owner (VeRO(tm)) program. Since the actions describedbelow are a violation of both Verant's intellectual property rights andthe EverQuest User Terms of Service agreement, I am copying to you acopy of the notification. Mr. Brad McQuaid has made it clear that yourcompany is interested in stopping the actions described below, so Ihoping this information, especially that of the existence of the EbayVeRO program will come in very useful in protecting your intellectualproperty.<P>Chris Warren<br>EverQuest user<P>(Begin forwarded item)<P>Reported item: Every "EverQuest" account and/or game item for sale.<P>This breaks the "Everquest" user agreement, giving sole intellectualproperty rights to Verant Interactive for all accounts and game items,and prohibiting the transfer or sale thereof (with exception made to aminor child).<P>According to Brad McQuaid, Vice President of Verant Interactive, "itexpressly forbidden as per our licensing agreement and we've also postedmessages reminding our players of the problems associated with suchtransactions."<P>A copy of this message is being forwarded to John Smedley, President/CEOof Verant Interactive.</BLOCKQUOTE><P>eBay sent me a little form letter saying they were investigating thematter immediately, and within a few hours, I got this:<BLOCKQUOTE>Subject: Re: Computer software (KMM7554794C0KM)<br>Date: Thu, 30 Dec 1999 13:50:00 -0800<br>From: eBay Customer Support<br>To: warren12@prodigy.net <P>Hello,<P>We would like to explain eBay's policy with respect to reports likeyours. eBay is not in a position to make judgments about theauthenticity or authorized nature of auction items, except in the mostextreme circumstances. This may mean that we cannot remove the itemabout which you contacted us. In some cases, we refer the information tothe owner of the rights (copyright, trademark, etc.) involved, if weknow who they are and how to contact them. Although you may be extremelyknowledgeable about these types of items, we often cannot remove itemsupon the representations of third parties whose credentials we cannotverify, unless of course the alleged infringement is obvious on itsface. That is why we strongly urge you to notify the rights holder ofthe suspected infringement and encourage them to join our VerifiedRights Owners (VeRO) Program (formerly called Legal Buddy Program). Thisprogram enables them to request the ending of allegedly infringingauctions.<P>We appreciate your vigilance in helping us to keep inappropriateauctions off eBay. If we can be of any further assistance, please let usknow.<P><P>Regards,<P>Yuri<br>eBay Customer Support</BLOCKQUOTE><P>I decided to have one more stab at it and responded to eBay, Smedley,and the 989 address with the following:<P><BLOCKQUOTE><P>From: Chris Warren <br>To: Ebay Customer Support<br> cc: John Smedley<br>cc: EverQuest <P>Dear sirs:<P>In an attempt to make clear the nature of the violation, I here includethe relevant sections of the "EverQuest" User Agreement and SoftwareLicense, which all users of the indicated items must agree to beforeusing the auctionable items indicated. You indicated you could not"remove items upon the representations of third parties whosecredentials we cannot verify, unless of course the alleged infringementis obvious on its face." Paragraph eight clearly identifies intellectualproperty status to these items, and paragraphs one, seven, and fifteenall denote non-transferrability.<P>I am copying John Smedley of Verant Interactive, developer and licenseholder of this software, as well as the indicated address for 989Studios, publisher of this title on this message, as you have indicateda need for a contact to the rights holder and I urge you to come intocontact with each other on an issue both of you have indicatedwillingness to address.<P>This will be my last involvement in the matter, thank you for yourprompt replies.<P>Chris Warren<br>EverQuest user<br>eBay user<P>[begin quoted material from EverQuest]<P>USER AGREEMENT AND SOFTWARE LICENSE<P>THIS AGREEMENT DESCRIBES THE TERMS ON WHICH 989 STUDIOS, A DIVISION OFSONY COMPUTER ENTERTAINMENT AMERICA INC. OFFERS YOU ACCESS TO AN ACCOUNT(THE "ACCOUNT") TO PLAY THE EVERQUEST ONLINE FANTASY ROLE PLAYINGCOMPUTER GAME (THE "GAME"). BY PRESSING THE "I ACCEPT" BUTTON, YOUACCEPT THE TERMS AND CONDITIONS BELOW. BY PRESSING THE "DECLINE" BUTTON,YOU DECLINE OUR OFFER, IN WHICH CASE YOU SHOULD CONTACT YOUR RETAILERREGARDING ITS RETURN POLICY FORTHE EVERQUEST CD-ROM. If you have any questions regarding these termsand conditions, please contact customer service ateverquest@989studios.com.<P>1. Accounts are available only to adults or, in their discretion, theirminor child. If you are a minor, your parent(s) or guardian(s) mustcomplete the registration process, in which case they will take fullresponsibility for all obligations under this Agreement. By clicking the"I Accept" button and providing us with a credit card number, yourepresent that you are an adult and are either accepting this Agreementon behalf of yourself or your child. You may not transfer or share yourAccount with anyone, except that if you are a parent or guardian, youmay permit one child to use the Account instead of you (in which caseyou may not use that Account). You are liable for all activitiesconducted through the Account, and parents or guardians are liable forthe activities of their child. Corporations and other entities are noteligible to procure Accounts.<P>2. To play the Game, you must (a) purchase the EVERQUEST game CD-ROM(the "CD-ROM"), which includes software required for the Game (the"Software")<P>[irrelevant material deleted]<P>7. Subject to the terms of this Agreement, we hereby grant to you anon-exclusive license to use the Software solely in connection withplaying the Game via an authorized and fully-paid Account. You may notcopy (except to make one necessary back-up copy), distribute, rent,lease, loan, modify or create derivative works, adapt, translate,perform, display, sublicense or transfer the Software. You may not copyany of the written materials accompanying the CD-ROM. You may notreverse engineer, disassemble or decompile the Software except to theextent that this restriction is expressly prohibited by applicable law.The Software may contain license management software that restricts youruse of the Software.<P>8. We and our suppliers shall retain ownership of all intellectualproperty rights relating to or residing in the CD-ROM, the Software andthe Game. The Software is a "commercial item."<P></BLOCKQUOTE></UL>

