<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Shadow Knights </SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Amanujaku   (<a href="mailto:N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Let me start off by saying that I am impressed with the quality and game balance that already exists in a game as big and complex as EverQuest. Believe me I know the difficulties in creating RPGs as I work in the industry on these things myself. My hat is off to the people in the trenches that actually out this thing onto the shelves and into our lives (or what&#8217;s left of them 8) ). <br><br>However, this is a rant on the Shadow Knight class. I have been playing my SK for quite some time now, 18days and some hours, and have reached 22nd level. Most of this time was quite fun and a good deal of it was role playing as much as it was &#8220;hack and slash&#8221;. For those of you who don&#8217;t know what as Shadow Knight plays like, it&#8217;s like this: Take all the good necromancer spells, and all the good fighter abilities&#8230; and remove them, what you have left is a SK. Oh, and throw in that 99% of the time a SK is an evil race and is killed on sight and you pretty much get the experience. I have personally approached it as a challenge and a role playing opportunity, and for the most part, have enjoyed playing my character (which is what it is all about) but have come across more than a few complaints from other SK players as well as myself. I will break the major ones down. <br><br>Spell selection: The SK spell selection is rather weak. For a class that is supposed to be a offensive class, there is no direct damage spells until you get ward at 22 (which I will get into later) and only one buff until level 22 , and it&#8217;s protection from cold (has anyone ever used this spell?). Paladins at least get healing, and buffs at the start. Siphon strength, engulfing darkness are your only decent spells for a long time. When you finally do get spells like ward, you find out that it does a whopping 41 dmg, give me a break. I can do 38 a hit with my BBC and I often get double attack, so what is the point? I have mixed feelings about vampiric embrace. It is the only healing spell we get, and it must be used in combat and only heals 12 HP at a time when you hit. When it only works randomly on top of that, it makes for a very non-reliable heal source. Monsters tend to smack me for anywhere from 15 to 50+ per hit. A 12hp heal only in combat is not that great, but better than nothing. &#8220;But what about your pet&#8221; you ask. That is my next point <br><br>Your pet: SK pets are one half the level of the caster when he/she gets the spell. So, a 22nd level Shadow Knight gets his new pet spell that summons a level 11-13 Skeleton. They have almost no hit points so they cannot tank for you, they often miss when attacking (so would have I at 11th level taking a swing at a monster 16 levels higher than me) and you often summon a weak on that cannot even hit magical creatures. At best my Skel serves as a warriors kick to me. All this for the low low price of sharing XP with it. Which is my next point <br><br>XP: Shadow Knights go up slow, and I mean slow, even for a hybrid class. I&#8217;ve watched my party members pass me with much disdain. Rather depressing actually. <br><br>Harm touch: Harm touch is a good idea in concept, but not in practice. At my level 22 I can do 221 damage with a press of a hotkey, once a day, in theory this is very good. In practice, once a day I can do SOME damage, because many things actually resist the Harm touch damage. When you do full damage 221 damage is not that big of a deal at higher levels because the mob has ridiculous amounts of Hp to begin with. A mage can cook off a spell that does 170 damage many times in a combat that is only limited by how much mana he/she has at my same level. <br><br>How I would change the Shadow Knight class to &#8220;better balance&#8221; it. <br><br>Spells: Add a few direct damage spells and a few buffs, nothing crazy, you don&#8217;t want to take away from the Necro class too much. Also, now this is reaching a bit, a bind spell. As a evil race SK (which I am) it is nearly impossible to travel safely. The only people that are really effected by racial hatred are the dark elves, trolls and the ogres (conveniently the same races that make the majority of the SK players). You take a look at the paladin class, their spell selection includes heals, great buffs, a things like remove disease etc. not a bad spell selection for a hybrid that is supposed to by my equivalent opposite. <br><br>Pets: Either make them more powerful, which may be too much, or, make it so the SK pet does not take XP from you. I already go up slower than all classes, why punish me for using one of my supposed &#8220;main&#8221; perks? <br><br>Harm touch: Make it so things can&#8217;t resist it at least. I don&#8217;t see lay on hands failing. You&#8217;d have quite a few ticked off paladins if you did that. <br><br>It is just frustrating not getting the two weapon wield, bad spells, resistible and/or useless special abilities AND go up slow in XP. On the plus side, SKs are great for role playing, especially Dark elves I have found especially fun. But in everyone of us there is a power gamer, and no one wants their character to suck as it were, so that is my little rant <br><br>Again, EverQuest is by far the best game of its kind out there, and I have enjoyed MANY hours playing it. I have more than got my moneys worth out of it and I would recommend it to anyone. <br><br>-Amanujaku Jujin&#8217;Po 

