<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Beginner's Manual</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Shadoe  (<a href="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Here's the way the manual should read from my own perspective.  It would provide a far better starting point for new players than the one currently released by Verant.<P>----------<P>Welcome to EverQuest!<P>If you are reading this, it's very likely that you have already purchased EverQuest.  If such is the case, we will simply thank you and not bore you will a line of droll about how you are about to embark on a fantastic journey in a richly detailed world, and how your purchase has helped us avoid abject poverty whereby we would have ended up selling used office furniture on the street corners of San Diego.  <P>If not, you are probably mooching off a friend's manual as you consider purchasing it.  If such is the case, realize that by merely reading this manual, you are now subject to all the rules and policies of Verant Interactive, 989 Studios, and basically the entire Sony Corporate empire.  This includes junk mail, trade shows, mandatory seminars, home inspections, drug tests, piracy raids, strip searches, compulsory organ donor status, prostate exams (where applicable) and an unconditional waiver of civil and/or constitutional rights.<P>Welcome aboard!<P><BR><BR><U>INSTALLATION</U><P>Who are we kidding?  If you can't figure out the installation process after 4 years of Windows 95, you probably don't have enough brain matter to be playing EverQuest in the first place.  If you find yourself confused, we strongly encourage you to apply to become an <I>Asheron's Call</I> beta tester.<P>And since over 89% of the people who call our technical support line have never seen the inside of this manual, we figure we'll cut our overhead costs by saving ourselves the trouble of going into detail in this section.  (The remaining 11% are quickly referred to Microsoft Technical Support at 1-888-SCRU-YOU.)<P>But never let it be said we are a bunch of heartless bastards.  Here's a list of common problems people have while installing EverQuest, and their solutions:<P><UL><LI><I>I put the CD in the drive, but nothing happens!</I><BR>Make sure the CD is placed right-side up.  (That's the side with the little words and pictures on it.)<P><LI><I>I put the CD in the drive correctly, but still nothing happens!</I><BR>Turn the computer on.  Yes, the monitor too.  No, the keyboard and mouse do not need to be turned on; they have no power switches.  No, we don't know why the monitor does, and they don't, just accept this fact of life and move on.<P><LI><I>I turned the power on, but all I see is a little picture of a computer with a smile.</I><BR>Put all the items back into the EverQuest box, and give it to a friend who owns a <I>PC</I> computer.  Afterward, you are obligated to whine and carry on about how EverQuest is not supported on the Mac.  (We're sure that last part is stipulated somewhere in the Macintosh owner's manual.)<P><LI><I>I entered my Station name and password, but it says it can't connect to the login server.</I><BR>Hey!  That happens way after installation is finished.  Quit jumping ahead!<P><LI><I>It's asking me if I want to install DirectX.  What is DirectX, and do I need it?</I><BR>Okay, look... always click "Yes" to this prompt whenever you get it.  It's a very low-risk means of investing in Microsoft futures, and there's every possibility you will never be able to play EverQuest or any future game if you click "No."<P><LI><I>Why won't the program let me install EverQuest onto my zip disk?</I><BR>Please slap yourself silly until you have trouble speaking.  After you're done doing that, do it again until your brain is purged of all such irrational behavior.<P></UL><P><BR><BR><U>RUNNING EVERQUEST</U><P>Double-click the EQ shield icon on your desktop.  That's one of many ways to get started.<P>The EverQuest Patch program will run, and check to see if there are any currently working features in your copy of EverQuest that need to be broken.  This may take a while, so we recommend launching a web browser and looking at pictures of naked members of the opposite sex while you wait.<P>What happens next confuses most users the first time they experience it.  Your screen may flicker and jump for the next two to fifteen minutes as the EverQuest software tries out every screen mode your computer supports.  We're perfectly aware that EverQuest is the only game in existence that feels the need to do this, but since you're not on our payroll, your opinion about our programming technique doesn't matter.<P>Once this enumeration process is over, you will be presented with a lengthy dissertation in legalese about how we now own you and your progeny of no less than twelve generations.  As EverQuest is a constantly evolving game, we demand that you read this user agreement from beginning to end every single time you run EverQuest, just in case we decide to change it on you.  Once you have finally completed the agreement, you will undoubtedly need to find yourself something to eat and drink, as the human body cannot go for extended periods of time without sustenance.  (Official 989 Studios User Agreement Intravenous Nourishment Kits(tm) are sold seperately, available at an HMO near you.)<P>Afterwards, click the "Accept" button.  Neither Sony nor its principal stockholders are responsible for the consequences to humanity should anyone ever click the "Decline" button.  You have been warned.<P>Next comes a parade of logos of various companies who are involved in receiving a cut of your monthly payments.  You will soon come to know these institutions well, as it is impossible to run EverQuest without at least catching a glimpse of each logo.  (We require all Verant employees to kiss the screen as each one pops up.)  As time passes, you will come to accept your fate, in that there is nothing you can do about this.  In the months to come, you will often enjoy the irony as they represent the very same narcissistic egotists who are keeping you from logging in as quickly as possible after being disconnected during a close fight.<P>Lastly comes the cinematic introduction to the world of Norrath, along with a brief narrative about its history.  Though awe-inspiring at first, you will tire of it quickly as it too is shown every time you run EverQuest.  Like the logos before it, you may rid yourself of it at any time by pressing the Esc key.  Let it be known, however, that you will never be considered a true EverQuest fan if you do.  (Don't even THINK about deleting it off your hard drive.  We would have to hurt you!)<P><BR><BR><U>CREATING A CHARACTER</U><P>Making a character in EverQuest is fast and simple, covered in only thirty-six easy steps!<P>Step 1: Choose a Race<BR>Picking a race is mind-numbingly easy.  Any race at all will do just fine, so freely choose whichever one you like.  All you have to keep in mind that it is pivotal to your physical appearance, starting location, beginning stats, class selections, deity selections and basically how you play the whole entire game on a purely nebulous level.  <P>Step 2: Choose a Sex<BR>Both sexes are equal as far as character abilities go.  However, if you want other players to give you all sorts of free stuff, we strongly suggest you go with the female.  Also keep in mind that if you are a male player, you are free to play a female character without fear of ridicule by the other players.  Rest assured they have absolutely no way of knowing your true identity, so it is unlikely they will come to your home, camp out on your front lawn drinking beer and calling you a panty-wearing sissy boy.  If you are female, on the other hand, we're afraid you simply *must* play a female character, as every other female player out there demands it.  Sorry, but it is out of our hands.<P>Step 3: Choose a Class<BR>Depending on your race, you have many classes to pick from including bard, cleric, druid, enchanter, magician, monk, necromancer, Dick Van Patton, paladin, ranger, rogue, shadow knight, shaman, warrior and Wizard.  (We apologize for the inconvenience, but the "Westwood Studios Receptionist" class was discontinued due to an imbalance issue with negative charisma stats.  Also, the class-specific "useful information spell" kept fizzling, so the class had to be eliminated in the final release.  The litigation continues.)<P>Step 4: Buff Your Stats<BR>You have a set number of points to distribute among all of your preset character stats.  These include strength, stamina, agility, dexterity, wisdom, intelligence and charisma.  Keep in mind that any changes you make here are marginal unless you go totally bazonkers and put it all in one statistic.<P>Step 5: Choose a Name<BR>No, this is not a place to type <I>your</I> name.  You must make up a name for your character that fits within the high fantasy setting Norrath provides.  Keep in mind that the totally infallible name filter we have in place will catch any and all dewdish, wise ass names in order to keep our roleplayers happy.  Don't even try creating an out-of-context name, as we have given our solemn oath to our players that we will enforce our filter policy with an iron fist at all costs!  To date, not a single even remotely unsuitable name has made it past our filter, so don't expect it to start with you!<P>Step 6: Choose a Deity<BR>This is just some piddly thing we threw in so roleplayers will have their precious little pantheon of gods to worship.  Just pick one and forget about it, as it impacts your gameplay about as much as Al Gore impacted the office of Vice President.<P>Step 7: Choose a Starting Location<BR>By and large, you will have only one suitable location to start in, so you might as wellclick the button to continue.  Hey, when I was your age, we'd be thankful (that's right, <I>thankful</I>) if we got even <I>one</I> starting location!<P>Step 8: Click and Pray<BR>This screen gives a short synopsis for roleplayers, describing what kind of character they've chosen to play.  Once again, pay it no mind; it won't affect how fast you level.  You just click the button again and pray the name you picked isn't already taken.<P>Step 9: Choose Another Name<BR>Since so much time has passed and literally hundreds of thousands of players have created characters before you, it is highly unlikely that you have chosen a unique name -- even if you used the random name generator we've provided.  Since all the cool names are already taken, try picking a wimpy one (like "Buechler") and follow steps 6 thru 8 until you've completed all thirty-six steps.<P><BR><BR><U>PLAYING THE GAME</U><P>Immediately upon entering EverQuest for the first time, it is absolutely essential that every player somehow accidentally loses their guild note.  Save yourself the trauma of dying and having it vanish before your eyes by simply destroying it yourself using the "Destroy" button below your character portrait.  Trust us, you will be much happier.<P>While you're at it, use the same technique to destroy the Discord Book in your inventory.  Unlike the precious guild note, the infernal book will reappear in your inventory again and again when you are killed below level 4.  This is not a bug, but purely intended by the design team.<P>Another critical event you must experience at least once is walking up to an NPC and targeting it you begin to type the message you wish to impart.  Inevitably you hit the "A" key for the first time in your sentence and quickly realize the importance of pressing the "Enter" key before typing ANY message in EverQuest.  Try it, and you will see the light.<P>It is also overtly necessary that every new player /shout an endless stream of innane questions across the entire zone (IN ALL CAPS, IF POSSIBLE).  You can ask any series of questions you like, be it in an in-game issue or about refinancing your home.  We guarantee that between the /shouts cursing you down, you will receive cryptic answers riddled with acronyms you've never heard before in your life.  Don't panic; this is a natural part of being a newbie.  Simply /shout back, asking what each and every acronym means.<P>Movement is simple, but certainly not harmless.  Quake and Unreal players will quickly notice the handy "mouselook" feature, by which you can easily control your character's movement.  Simply right-click the mouse and move it around to get used to the feel.  Beware, however, if you should release the mouse button while standing before another player character close by.  Doing so will force you to snoop into their belongings without asking permission first, which often results in a newly furnished rectal orifice for your character -- especially if you had the misfortune of choosing Rallos Zek as your first server to play on.  This is not a bug, but purely intended by the design team.<P>Another feature you will use often (initially, at least) is the /bug and /feedback commands.  These allow you to express your thoughts and opinions directly to the design team regarding play issues and certain bugs you come across while playing EverQuest.  Few things in life are as satisfying as the feeling you get when you type in and send your first feeback message.  As you send in more feedback and bug messages, please don't concern yourself with the increased sensation that every time you click the "Send" button, you're sending your message into a black void of neverending emptiness.  This transition is ordinary, and will alleviate over time as your cynicism takes over and you decide to use /petition to report your feelings to the guides instead.<P>When sallying forth to your first adventure in EverQuest, it is vital that you first take note of where the local city guards are, as you will be needing their services often.  Don't think you won't.  You will also notice that some guards tend to patrol the adventuring areas.  These wandering guards' sole purpose is to stand back in the shadows, wait for you to expend all your energies in whacking your opponent down to a sliver of health, and then rush out and steal the final blow, effectively laying waste to your efforts.  This is not a bug, but purely intended by the design team.<P>While playing EverQuest, it is important to keep in mind that it <I>is</I> a richly diverse world.  Everyone you see around you is proud of the diversity Norrath has to offer.  So if you feel the need to create a non-agressive character such as a homebody merchant or strictly pacifistic healer of Tunare, keep repeating to yourself how "Norrath is a richly diverse world full of infinite possibilities, Norrath is a richly diverse world full of infinite possibilities," because no matter how limited you may <I>feel</I> at times, it will always be the truth.

