<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Tallon Zek Aftermath </SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Aurum  (<a href="mailto:aurum@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">aurum@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Today as many of you know, the Tallon Zek Race War server was launched for a brief amount of time before over 5,000 EverQuest players swarmed the server and forced Verant to take it down.Within this article you'll find five comments from EverQuest players like yourselves.  We've also setup a <a href="http://boards.vaultnetwork.com/wwwthreads.pl?action=list&Board=playerviews">Forum</a> to discuss this issue.  Each of the following player comments have slightly different views.  Do you agree with them?  Do you disagree with them?  Express your opinions by clicking <a href="http://boards.vaultnetwork.com/wwwthreads.pl?action=list&Board=playerviews">here</a>.  -Aurum    <P><UL><LI><A href="#one">Player Comments #1</a><LI><A href="#two">Player Comments #2</a><LI><A href="#three">Player Comments #3</a><LI><A href="#four">Player Comments #4</a><LI><A href="#five">Player Comments #5</a></UL><b><a name="one">Player Comments #1</a></b> - Louis' Perspective<P><BLOCKQUOTE><I>The general-channels filled with angry TZers who do not understand Verant. As the GM's tried to "explain" why they did what they did, they only infuritaed about 4 General-Chat channels worth of TZers. After waiting for a month, then waiting for two weeks of "delays".. It finally comes, and then plop. Just about -everyone- (Except Verant) knew it was going to be like this. Anyway, every attempt to explain their position only infuriated the crowds until the proverbial crap hit the proverbial fan. Pandamonium. All three general-channels turned into constant spam. Just pure spam (using history). Guides came, moderated the channel, and attempted to calm the situation. As soon as it was unmoderated, immediate and massive spam. GMs came, threatening to start booting people, as soon as they unmoderated, more and more spam. Utter and complete revolt against Verant. While I -never- condone pure spam for the sake of spam, I believe the public has spoken. They are -not- satisfied with what they are paying for. When I left general-chat, there were 4 channels of people just spamming, and one channel (The TZ channel) that wasn't being spammed. Guides had all but given up.</I></BLOCKQUOTE><b><a name="two">Player Comments #2</a></b> - Tailchaser's View<P><BLOCKQUOTE><I>Just wanted to share my views on this whole TZ mess. Hopefully,this'll get posted up for conversation. =><P>First and foremost: Everyone who flooded, spammed, and screamed inthe Chat Server needs to just calm down. People were gettingnigh hysterical, claiming that they had cancelled all their plans forthe week just so they could play on TZ. There is a point, folks, whereyou just need to stop and realize that EQ is a game. Nothing more.<P>Secondly: It was argued that keeping TZ running with a player capwould be a solution until the new server arrived. This would not solveanything, come next week - the players who weren't able to log in to TZwould scream twice as loud since it's not fair to them, and the playerswho WERE able to play would throw a frothing, raving fit when the capdid some off, since any existing characters would HAVE to be wiped toprevent an obscene balance problem.<P>Thirdly: Yes, there was a great deal of immature yelling on the partof the player base when TZ went locked, then came down. Yes, people aregetting way out of control about it. Within reason, though, they have aright to be upset - between taking polls, watching interest peak, andmonitoring website comments, Verant should have been prepared for thelaunch of TZ. Saying that having 5000 players log in is "unexpected"shows nothing but bad planning, plain and simple, on Verant's part.<P>Fourthly: A somewhat minor note. I personally saw two Guides, inthe chat rooms, openly insulting and taunting the players. This is just-completely- unacceptable. I won't name them here, but rest assured Ihave reported them to Verant. These guides locked a chat channel downto Moderated status, then made comments along the lines of, "Time forthe babies to calm down", and "All the little kids need to go back totheir Nintendos". As official representatives of Verant, 989, and Sony,the Guides are in a very public position. Acting abusing and uncaringtowards paying clients is nothing but inflammatory.<P>All in all, I can see the issue from both sides. Verant wasn't readyfor the demand the players put on the machine, and the players weregetting far too upset about a bloody computer game, for goodness sake. I can only hope that both parties will learn from this in the future -Verant needs to begin over- rather than under-estimating the stress thatthe player base will put on new servers, and the player base needs tostep back and calm down a little.<P>-Tailchaser</I></BLOCKQUOTE><P><b><a name="three">Player Comments #3</a></b> - The Tallon Zek Dilemma <BLOCKQUOTE><i>Ok I realize some of you are really pissed at Verant for this whole thing, I am too in a way. Yes, they should have taken into account the fact that the TZ chat was always packed, and that there were surveys up the yin-yang about people going to play and similar things. Ok, now on the part people don't get.<P>Now yes you pay for this game, and yes you want Verant to put the server up, whether with a player amount cap or not, but there are a few things you have to realize about a game server and the companies who run them.<P>1. The server is a computer, just like the one you have, it has restrictions and similar problems like your computer. A game server is one that is tweaked to hell to accommodate so many players, the EQ servers being a perfect example. A computer, server side or not can only be stressed so much that it will bog down playability so much as to hamper the players experience. <P>2. Telling Verant they are idiots isn't gonna help your cause out that much. Believe me, they already have your money, so not like its gonna matter too much how much you petition with strong hostile intents, people arent gonna respond to that. In the real world, you are more likely to get a response, good or not if you are kind to the person you are complaining to. Be nice to Smed, Fippy and the rest of them, and maybe they will help you out. Otherwise your little attempts at childish petitions aren't gonna help them to crank out the server any faster.<P>3. One week is all it will take. Or at least that's the minimum. They did of course give you the server at their given ETA, so maybe they will give you the both of them at the same time within the week, that is of course if like I said before, you don't petition like crazy.<P>4. Maturity is a big part of this game, and although most of you are probably adults, but I have seen some really childish rants from people whom I thought were smarter than that. Yelling at Smed and spamming him like hell isnt gonna get you on his good side, or anyone elses for that matter. Just try to act like you would if your grandparents came over in chat, it makes for a much friendlier environment.<P>Think of this as Christmas Eve for a Week, and when it finally hits that 12 midnight tone on the old grandfather clock, maybe you will double your presents for X-Mas, with a choice of servers, there will be greater playability. <P>Anyways, if you feel like spamming my mailbox to hell, go right ahead, im not gonna stop you. I just hope you take some of my opinions into consideration the next time you see Smed and the rest in chat, and think twice before telling him off.<P>The great and Venerable FuzzBusta<Br>Spam me if you want at Kenada666@aol.com </I></BLOCKQUOTE><B><a name="four">Player Comments #4</a></b> - Talgorin's Rant<BLOCKQUOTE><I>Tallon Zek was launches at about 7:30pm, and went down at 9:30pm. Therewas no reason. They then announced it would not return for a week. Smedthen explained why they did it in the general chat:<br>1) If they put a 2000 person limit, people would complain that Verantsucks because it was limited etc. <br>2) Open it to all. This would cause zone crashing etc. <br>3) Close it until a new server arrives.<P>After this, many people were confused and started shouting out numbers,but Smed explained that Verant was going to make the choices and pick#3. Now, the part i really do not understand is #1. Now when there is5,000 people all wanting to play TZ and cannot get in, well that's 5,000mad customers. If it were limited, 2,000 of them would be playing, whilethe other 3,000 waited. <P>Although if it was limited, I am sure manypeople would not choose to wait anyway and Verant would have VERY fewcomplaints. Now #2, if it was open to all, I am sure the max number ofpeople would not even exceed 4,000. Opening it on a Friday night withall the anticipation was not smart. If a simple news message stated thatthere could be problems with that many people on, and if you do not wishto experience then, simple don't log into it.<P>Next, after many complaints, Smed got an idea to turn the testserver into a RW 2 server and just turn the new server back into a TestServer. Now this was a very good plan, i mean Test Server can wait aweek. Smed came back and told us all that we are all going to have towait a week so no new server. I do not see how Verant can possiblyassume that opening the server limited or to all could POSSIBLE comeclose to amount of frustration that people are feeling right now. AfterSmed left, for over 1 hour a constant stream of spam flooded the chatwindow in protest of their decision. So, I ask you Verant, if you say wedeserve better, why not give us what we want to make us happy?<P>Talgorin<Br>Angry Tallon Zek player</I></BLOCKQUOTE><b><a name="five">Player Comments #5</a></b> - Juktu's Observations<BLOCKQUOTE><I>Over 5000 people logged into Tallon Zek this evening. There were so many people that there was nothing to hunt to level. Due to the overwhelming number of players, they shut the server down until they can put more than 1 team pvp server up. This angered many people as the chat channels were bogged down with grumbling and sometimes harsh and vulgar remarks. "Why didn't you think to put up more than 1 server when you knew there would be this many people wanting to play?" was the most asked question. At least one thing is clear... the server has the capacity to physically support 5,000 players although it lags and bogs out and is difficult to log in. <P>In one way Verant should view this as a success in that their servers can support many people.  In another way they should learn that when a pole is taken and 5,000 people respond, they should be prepared. <P>First hand witness: <br>Juktu</I></BLOCKQUOTE>

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem931071600,3460,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">The Catalyst, Part 3</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Jordan Thomas   (<a href="mailto:N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
&#8220;Neriak is an enigma. Finding opportunity in the home of the Teir&#8217;dal is simple. Everyone has a hidden agenda, and a need for covert aid. But one must tread carefully there, because the motives of the dark elves often involve disposal of the ally in question.&#8221; <br>-From Shades of Gray, the memoirs of Modus Operandi <br><br><br>Catalyst sat in his black stone room, on a hard bed. Through his slit-like windows, the purple glow of Neriak seeped in, just barely. He stared, silent. Catalyst was Teir&#8217;dal, a dark elf. But he was not born of their community, such as it was. Catalyst was owned, much like the goblin slaves, even if never abused. House Zu&#8217;karr claimed him, but never graced him with a real name. Burning in a distant somewhere, he felt rage for that. But it was muted, somehow absent from the now. All that remained in his head was the music, the dark music. It had always been there, an unending farewell song for whatever was lost to him. <br><br>Two days ago, he had been told why House Zu&#8217;karr bothered to support him. His holder, Aniyal, revealed to him that he would be the agent of change for Neriak, the gamble that would conquer the surface world. She had whispered in his ear that he would become the scourge of hundreds, perhaps thousands of elves. And she had hinted at a reward - the ultimate reward. An identity. <br><br>Catalyst stood, disgusted. He knew she was tempting him for no reason other than simple cruelty. Aniyal never brought happiness. She was a torturer, and Catalyst was her toy. At her orders, he had done&#8230; unspeakable things to captured prisoners. He was compelled from within. <br><br>Once, he tried to resist. Not out of pity - Catalyst never felt anything for anyone. But he wanted a will of his own, so he had attempted to stand against her. Aniyal had actually smiled. Her hand made the slightest of movements, and he was wracked from within. It felt as if she was literally stripping at his life with her sharpened fingernails. He had vomited and convulsed for the better part of an hour. Aniyal stood, watching and smiling, the entire time. By the time it was over, Catalyst had begged to resume the mutilation of her astonished victim. <br><br>He didn&#8217;t understand the hold she had on him. His few attempts to discern his origins had met with tight lips and enigmatic, condescending smiles from the other Zu&#8217;karr nobles. But he was, perhaps, more a slave than those that toiled in the mines below. He couldn&#8217;t even take his own life with a heavy pick or a leap from a chasm, like the workers often did. Whenever he brought one of his blades close to his neck or wrists, the twisting began again, and he was forced to the ground. <br><br>A sharp clack of the iron doorknocker outside. Echoes. He waited a moment, and then came the voice. <br><br>&#8220;It is I, my manse&#8217;toru. Open your door to me. I know you understand the consequences of further delay.&#8221; <br><br>There it was. Her voice, like a silken scarf on a stiletto. It hissed, it soothed, it threatened. Catalyst opened the door, less than willingly. Aniyal stood there, with her beautiful, insidious smile. She was so cold, appraising him like a jewel or a weapon. He grunted. <br><br>&#8220;It is time, pet. The moment of your enlightenment is at hand. You will at last be taught what you are the catalyst of,&#8221; she stated, and smiled as if he should thank her. <br><br>&#8220;Yes, my mistress,&#8221; Catalyst muttered. The words were ripped from him. Without a word, Aniyal turned on her heel and walked elegantly down the marble hall. As the echoes from her footsteps deepened, Catalyst sighed and then left his room to follow her. He knew the price of disobedience. <br><br>He walked with Aniyal through the upper chambers in a daze, barely aware of his surroundings, and certainly without any interest. Soon however, his bones chilled as he realized that they approached the entrance to the kaisa, the house dungeon. Marble walls became rough granite as the stairs spiraled down, down, down. Into the blackness. <br><br>All Teir&#8217;dal elves could see in even the deepest shadow, but something about the kaisa made it claustrophobic and forever concealing. It was as if the constant pain inflicted here created a kind of sinister fog. Catalyst hugged his arms about himself, and followed Aniyal carefully, now. The priestess did not even shiver. He was sure she was enjoying his reaction. The silence of the halls above had melded, seamlessly, into the screams of the prisoners. The wailing of the damned. Catalyst tried to block it out, to little avail. The shrieks even drowned out the somber melody in his head, and that scared him. <br><br>Soon, they approached a worked-mithril door. Aniyal stopped, and turned to face him. <br><br>&#8220;Come, Catalyst. Let me proudly introduce you to your destiny,&#8221; she purred. With another of her horrible, alluring smiles, she turned and traced a pattern on the door. Her elegant blue-black hands whipped around the engraved work on the mighty portal, and an audible click resounded in the hall. To Catalyst&#8217;s surprise, a secreted door swung silently open in the stone wall nearby. The mithril door did not budge. <br><br>&#8220;Appearances can be deceiving in the kaisa,&#8221; Aniyal murmured. Catalyst merely nodded, and followed her into the revealed chamber. Once inside, he froze, gaping. The circular room was far larger than he would have imagined, and ten crimson-robed Teir&#8217;dal stood, facing him. The symbol of Zu&#8217;karr was embroidered in black upon their vestments, and their eyes bored into him. He knew that look. He was manse&#8217;toru, a tool which has yet to be used. <br><br>But it was the room&#8217;s centerpiece that had him staring in horror. On a long, crooked bed of metal lay what looked like an eviscerated dwarf. All its tendons were strung to hooks on the outer rim of the grim table, and the belly was open to the ceiling. But it moved. Somehow, the poor creature was still alive. The head was covered in a hood of black silk, but the eyes showed clearly his agony and rage. <br><br>The clerics, in their robes of blood red, began to move toward Catalyst. Numbed, he was distantly aware of their hands gripping him from many angles, surging him toward the mutilated dwarf. He was being connected to some sort of harness, hanging limply above the table. From somewhere he could not discern, Aniyal appeared, carrying a tall, smoked-glass jar. <br><br>&#8220;This is a phylactery, my manse&#8217;toru. Do you see what lives inside? It is you,&#8221; she chuckled, holding the object close for him to see. Inside, a twisting band of blue energy raged and splashed against the walls of its prison. Catalyst could feel it there, wanting to be free. It was him. He was close enough now to feel the rage and pain and love and hate and - <br><br>&#8220;This is your essence, child. You were separated from it a long while ago, when you came into our care. It adorns our sacred temple now; a decoration of sorts. It is a symbol of what you are, and what you will be. It is time for your use to become clear, soulless one.&#8221; Aniyal took the jar away, and once again Catalyst felt the loss, heard the funeral melody in his skull. Everything was gray&#8230; <br><br>The hands across his back pushed him down close, eye-to-eye with the dwarf. The butchered figure began to convulse. The black silk mask became a blur as its head whipped back and forth wildly, inhumanly fast. Soon, a sound poured forth from its lips. It was like a hundred thousand banshees screaming in rage, all in unison. Somehow, in the midst of the shimmering image, Catalyst could still see its eyes. Terrible, terrible eyes. The Hatred in the chamber was tangible. You could smell it. <br><br>The mask snapped free. Blood from the bruises and cuts beneath slung haphazardly about, as the unearthly seizure continued. The scream built, until all the priests in the room covered their ears to block it out. Despite the fact that he now hung free over the table, Catalyst could not move. The howl kept him rooted in place. <br><br>A bright white poured forth from the torn face of the dwarf below him, and filled his mind. Bands of electric prime energy snaked all about him, as the unholy transfer began. Catalyst was being force-fed someone else&#8217;s tortured soul, and he could feel it all, clearly. Every muscle strained, every bone popped, every tendon stretched. Catalyst blinked. <br><br>My forefathers, my people, my kin shall be avenged! <br><br>The Mairil Elder stood before him on the hill - betrayer, betrayer, betrayer - The High Elf. His people were being torn apart, but the Elf stood and watched. The bastard could call upon the Elven legions to aid us, but he stood and watched. The Teir&#8217;dal were everywhere, cutting his dwarves apart like lambs, but the Elf stood and watched. The blood of his kindred - <br><br>We shall be avenged! Hate! Hate! Hate! <br><br>Vengeance! <br><br>Catalyst blinked. <br><br>One dwarf alone. He stood in front of every elf, all elves. Axe in hand, axe in hand. Killing blade under his fingers. He stood before every elf, axe in hand, and - <br><br>He would stand before every elf, axe in hand and - <br><br>Catalyst blinked. With a final spasm, he collapsed onto the bloodied, tortured dwarf. Somehow his bonds had snapped. He heard the rattle of long-overdue death in the throat of the poor creature under him. The clerics stood all around the table, watching his every twitch. He lurched off the table, and vomited. His head spun, and he held his hands to his face. Something had changed. The music was gone, the twilight music. The emptiness was filled somehow, and the loss abated. <br><br>In its place was something else. 

