<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Rogues</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Kevin "Akak" Hall  (<a href="mailto:N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
This letter is intended for any EQ players who have berated those of us playing rogues for complaining about the status of our broken skills. Judging from the number of posts on various message boards which have advised rogues to simply "shut up and play" because every class, not just the rogue, has inherent weakness, I think the problem with the rogue is completely misunderstood.<P>I will not discuss, in detail, the broken rogue skills. I will instead explain that we rogues are simply asking for our skills to be implemented. We are not asking for better melee skills. We are not asking for spells. We are not asking for more hit points. We are not asking to be better soloists. We are simply asking for the skills that have been advertised and promised to us to be implemented and fixed. The fact that several players have played a rogue to Level 50 has nothing to do with the fact that our class is desperately in need of repair. NO OTHER CLASS in EverQuest has these many useless, broken skills.<P>Since this concept seems to be so difficult for many to understand (especially to those playing the overpowered, out of balance classes) that I will try and illustrate with an example.<P>Imagine if you will, that the next patch required caster's to use components for their most powerful spells. On the first day after the patch, a wizard heads into HighHold Pass and sits on the big rock at the orc entrance for a night of kill stealing. The orcs attack and a party jumps into the melee. From the safety of his rock, the wizard begins to cast his most powerful direct damage spell onto the party's orc but gets a message saying, "You do not have the proper components for that spell." After his initial shock and dismay, he begins to cast another DD spell and gets the same message. Now in a complete state of rage, the wizard does a few /shouts, /tells, and /petitions and discovers that his most powerful spells now require a special component. A little more research on his part reveals something more maddening: the components for the spells are not yet implemented in the game. Soon thereafter, the message boards are alive with rants, petitions, and protests from the hundreds of magic users on every server. Verant's Brad McQuaid posts on the official EQ page that the spell components are "coming soon." Weeks go by, then months. Still, those components, which seem ridiculously easy to code into the game, are not implemented.<P>That, my adventuring friends, is the current state of the rogue.<P>So before you admonish your local rogue for whining, consider these issues:<UL><LI>We have pick locks but there are fewer than 10 locks in the entire world.<LI>We have sense traps but there is not, as far as we know, a functioning trap in the entire world.<LI>We have disarm traps but, as I said above, there are no traps.<LI>We have Apply Poison but there is no available poison and the poison that is available doesn't work properly.<LI>We have Make Poison but that skill has yet to be implemented.<LI>We have Sneak, but it does not render us invisible and is much less effective than low level druid, ranger, and MU spells. This is not the "Master of stealth" that was advertised.<LI>We have Hide but it does not remove us from a monster's "hate list" and we cannot move while hidden. Again, several other classes are overwhelmingly stealthier than the Masters of Stealth.</UL>I'm sure that if your class had as many (or even one!) broken skills, you'd attempt to get those skills fixed just as the rogues are trying to do.<P>Thank you for listening.<P>Kevin "Akak" Hall<br>16th Level Rogue on Povar Server

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem930121200,84007,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Training</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Rillien Sillsarrion  (<a href="mailto:rillien@ktis.net" class="credit2">rillien@ktis.net</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Training is one of the most talked about, most annoying, most common &#8220;occurrences&#8221; within EverQuest.  It comes in a few different flavors, some accidental while others are not so.  I&#8217;ve had the luxury of being a participant of every type of train I&#8217;ll mention here, and in a few cases I was the one instigating it.<P>The first type of train is what I&#8217;ll call the &#8220;Dungeon Train&#8221;.  It&#8217;s arguably the best known, and most feared, of any of the trains.  It&#8217;s when the arrogant adventurer goes a little too deep into the dungeon, or other zone, and encounters the mob that would mean his death.  He then makes the great escape back to the entrance, and brings with him every mob in the area.  The results of a train can be, and are oftentimes, deadly.  This type of train is typically started on accident, as the creator gets in over his head.<P>Another form of the train is one that I doubt most people even consider &#8220;training&#8221; in the traditional sense.  It consists of a member of your current group acting as a decoy; thus I&#8217;ll call it the &#8220;Decoy Train&#8221;.  To pull this type of train off, your group awaits around the corner or over the hill or anywhere else out of sight of the mob.  The creator heads in, gets the mobs attention, and pulls it back to the awaiting group.  This is done to avoid the risk of other mobs spawning and creating a very dangerous situation for the party involved.  It&#8217;s a controlled train; one accomplished with a little planning and, hopefully, no panic.<P>The last form of train is, thankfully, a relatively rare one (at least in my experience).  It&#8217;s when a player trains a high level NPC to a group of unsuspecting, or unprepared, players.  I&#8217;ll call this one a &#8220;Switch Train&#8221;, as it involves getting the NPC to switch from attacking you, to the players you wish to be killed.  This is considered an exploit by some, I&#8217;m sure.  And, arguably, it is.  Essentially, you avoid the PK switch that Verant has so thoughtfully provided.<P>But what if there was just cause for such a train to be started?  The Dark Elves of Neriak recently had just cause, when a group of players assaulted their city in a planned player event on the Mithaniel Marr server.  The Dark Elves had to defend their city, so they resorted to the only method the game allowed&#8230;training.<P><center><b>&#8220;I was disappointed at the lack of GM participation, and the amount of training from Dark Elf RP'ers. I understand that from a RP'ing stand point that they needed to defend their city, but training was a poor way to go about doing it.&#8221;  - EQVault News Archive (Week of May 30, 1999) &#8220;Neriak Invasion Report&#8221; Post</b></center><P>So, where does the thin line that defines right and wrong lay?  That&#8217;s a question that&#8217;s not so easily answered, as I found out recently.  Previously, I was of the mindset that I would never make an attempt to hamper another player&#8217;s fun.  However, my character is of the mindset that he would do anything for his beliefs&#8230;fight for them&#8230;die for them&#8230;and as I found out, train for them.<P>Recently when a group of players, in the form of a dark elf and an ogre, attacked my home of Surefall Glade I was forced to make a decision.  Do I give up the belief that I shouldn&#8217;t harm another player...or that I should protect my home and my friends?  The decision was based in character.  I hold nothing against the two players&#8230;they were attacking Surefall because they seen it as fun, and perhaps in character.  However, in game&#8230;my character took great offense to their presence.  While he was too weak to do something himself, the nearby ranger guildmaster wasn&#8217;t.  He made short work of the ogre, with the dark elf managing an escape.  Problem solved&#8230;although making a few enemies in the process.<P>The next night, they were back.  And upon issuing a request that they leave or suffer the fate of death, and receiving a no, I did it again.  I was protecting my home after all, wasn&#8217;t I?  This time however, someone was watching.  After my death at the hands of Hager (the two others didn&#8217;t die), I discovered a GM had witnessed the whole event.<P>A discussion took place, with the GM asking my reasons as to training Hager.  It was simple, to me.  They attacked my home, I was defending it in the only way I could&#8230;by calling for help.  I was issued an official warning, and told that if it continued my account would come under review.  The matter seemed settled. According to the GM, ruining another player&#8217;s fun would not be tolerated.  So I pressed the matter further.  What about them coming into MY home and attacking it&#8217;s inhabitants and ruining MY fun.  The GM grew silent.  &#8220;I re-read the manual,&#8221; she said. &#8220;I was wrong.  You&#8217;re allowed to protect your home from any unwanted guests.  The warning has been revoked.&#8221;<P>To say I was surprised is an understatement.  It did, however, settle the matter.  Upon hearing this, the two players went on their way (after killing me in a few duels that I foolishly accepted).  The GM was sure to tell me, &#8220;While you can defend your home. Remember that if you travel to Neriak, they can do the same.&#8221;  I replied, &#8220;I would hope so. In fact, I would expect it.&#8221;<P>The line seems to be a thin one, training in a certain fashion is most definitely frowned upon.  But yet in another, it&#8217;s justified.  I&#8217;ve been the victim of many a Dungeon Train, as well as the unfortunate starter.  I&#8217;ve had the pleasure to play part in a &#8220;Decoy Train&#8221;, and even seen one or two go badly.  The Switch Train, however, was something I thought I&#8217;d only be a victim of&#8230;but my first encounter had me being the creator.  When the situation arises, which side of the line will you be on?  Even at this point, I&#8217;m not sure which side I sit on&#8230;<P>-Rillien Sillsarrion 

