<a name="newsitem929430000,10610,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">It Could Happen To You </SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Felicity Hunter  (<a href="mailto:N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
<UL><I>Your new &#8216;99 Mustang convertible is humming like a very large and virile honeybee with less than 20,000 miles under its fan belt. You take meticulous care of it; the engine actually gleams when you open the hood.  You wake up one morning and it&#8217;s been repossessed. After a few phone calls a clerical error is discovered and you&#8217;re asked to be patient, they&#8217;ll take care of everything. A month later a &#8217;72 Volkswagen Beetle is delivered to your doorstep. There is a ding in the side door and the right front fender is a color that never existed in nature. &#8220;Wait,&#8221; you say, &#8220;this isn&#8217;t my car&#8221;.<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&#8220;We can take it back if you like.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&#8220;No, I want the &#8217;99 Mustang I paid for.&#8221; You&#8217;re confused, angry, and a little hurt. Your major organs feel like they&#8217;re trying to change places.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&#8220;This will get you where you&#8217;re going, they say. It has four wheels. Two doors. Seatbelts. It turns when you move the steering wheel. The lighter even works.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&#8220;But I paid for a brand new Mustang,&#8221; you reply. &#8220;I want a Mustang.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&#8220;We&#8217;re sorry,&#8221; they say. &#8220;Take it or leave it. <P>&#8220;You&#8217;re in our world now.&#8221;</I></UL>That sounds pretty stupid doesn&#8217;t it? Nothing like that could ever happen. There are laws, right? The lamentable news is no. It happens all the time, and if there are laws they&#8217;re vague and open to considerable interpretation. As you are probably aware of by now this isn&#8217;t the story of a Mustang owner, who fortunately signed a contract stating how much was paid and precisely what for down to the parenthetical VIN number and particular shade of red. The bank that tried to cheat that contract would fast find itself under a stern and sweaty investigation. This is about EverQuest&#8217;s confusing, and at times appalling, methods of handling us as customers. <P><b>The Setting</b><P>Almost two months ago an enchantress working hard to catch up with her former peers is searching for new hunting grounds, a change of scenery. Mistmoore looks intriguing. The sacrificial dagger would make a nice addition to her collection of belongings and a number of her friends are there. She&#8217;s heard experience is good there too. Perfect. She enters the zone, soon finds a good group of reliable hunters, and sets about learning the ropes. True to form, a &#8220;train&#8221; starts, driving most of the people, including, and perhaps especially, the enchantress, from the zone. The usual complaining ensues; typical post-trauma group talk. Then they all head back in.<P>Something goes wrong.<P><b>The Damsel in Distress</b><P><a href="/display.cgi?/lore/playerviews/images/falling1.jpg"><img src="/lore/playerviews/images/falling1_thumb.jpg" width=150 height=113 alt="Falling.." align="right" border=0></a>The enchantress exits Lesser Faydark through the zone to Mistmoore and enters the Twilight Zone. She is falling. The text tells her she&#8217;s in Lesser Faydark. She can still hear her companions talking. Her companions can see her. She can see them too, in a way. They are all falling in that strange colorless limbo that exists &#8220;Beneath the world,&#8221; re-spawning to a &#8220;safe spot&#8221;, and falling again. To everyone else, she has zoned into Mistmoore with no equipment and is standing among intermittent combat, unable to see or act.<P>At first she thinks, &#8220;Oops, I died.&#8221; No, her spells are still memorized. She has the same ninety percent health that she zoned with, and no experience has been lost. Besides, she&#8217;s bound in Greater Faydark near Crushbone. Her second thought is &#8220;How the heck do I get out of here?&#8221; Gating doesn&#8217;t work. She tries exiting the zone with guidance from her companions (who can still see her standing, in her skivvies, in the zone). No, she&#8217;s not interacting with the zone border at all. Maybe re-log?<P>Nope. Nothing works until, almost an hour later, after a series of strange messages, she mysteriously zones and appears in Greater Faydark with one bubble of health on the opposite end of the zone from where she was bound. Odd? You bet.<P><a href="/display.cgi?/lore/playerviews/images/falling2.jpg"><img src="/lore/playerviews/images/falling2_thumb.jpg" width=150 height=113 alt="Falling.." align="right" border=0></a>The story gets really strange from here. She petitions the problem and waits an hour or so with no response before typing <I>/who all gm</I> and sending a tell to the only one logged in at the time. The guide who answers is extremely helpful, courteous, and sympathetic. He takes down the information and promises an intervention. Two weeks pass.<P>She petitions again and receives a response in just under four hours, this time from an honest to goodness GM. The story is given again and she receives another promise of action. A week passes before she petitions again. Another guide. He takes down the information once more and tells her he will refer it to the next available GM. The following day, she sends a tell to the GM on duty who is courteous but not very hopeful that anything will be done soon if at all. The enchantress is patient and says as much. The next day, the GM appears with news. The enchantress has been approved for reimbursement. She only had to stay offline for the next day and a half and she would be restored to her position almost a month previous, before the bug occurred.<P><b>The Evil Overlords</b><P>Woah, wait a minute. Is a month of lost experience worth receiving 3,000 or more platinum in items she never should have lost to begin with, most of which had been replaced by now thanks to help from friends and a considerable investment of time and effort? No.<P>This patient enchantress is starting to feel like the guy in the Mustang now and writes a letter to the people who she feels can actually do something about it, Smedley (did you know Smedley comes up as &#8220;Smelly&#8221; in the spell checker?) and McQuaid. After all, they spend time on the message boards to directly address issues that arise. Surely they care, at least a little, about their customer&#8217;s treatment?<P>She is referred to a Mr. Butler, the Captain Chaos of Customer Service at Verant Interactive who replies with an option she was never offered and notified that this is the only way lost items are ever replaced. A leg up kit. It occurs to this enchantress that &#8220;leg-up&#8221; is what dogs do to fire hydrants and trees, not what customer service managers should be doing with the people who pay their bills.<P>A brief email war follows, ending in a nasty little volley between our heroine and Captain Chaos in which he tells her he will have no further discussion with her on the subject. My way or the highway. Take it or leave it. <I>You&#8217;re in our world now</I>.<P><b>The Truth</b><P>Chances are you have either experienced a similar situation or know someone who has. I personally know six people who can cite a similar story, some with happier endings than others. One of them received compensation in full from a GM who handed out items according to a list that was provided. Another level 20 warrior received full shiny steel plate as compensation for a bug that cost him his bronze and banded ensemble (yikes!). Most, however, receive a plastic smile (made in Taiwan), a clammy handshake, and an offer to be supplied in full with a marvelous new collection of equipment &#8220;suitable for your race, class, and level.&#8221; One hapless soul was even threatened with banishment for &#8220;harassing&#8221; the customer service people about his unfortunate incident.<P>Some instances are understandable, a death in lava for instance. Most people have been warned. Most people have a healthy fear of lava as a result. Most people stay away from it, and those who don&#8217;t know and understand the risks. The little trick at the Mistmoore zone, I discovered, is a known bug. A fault in the software. Verant is aware of it. Have there been any warnings? Has there been any indication that Verant is taking action to repair it? Are they making an effort to compensate the people who encounter their little glitch? No, no, and a vehement no.<P>The truth is, we have all paid to take part in EverQuest. It is not a privilege. Nobody is doing any of us a favor by answering a petition or an emailed request for action on a given problem, though most of the people on the far side of the modem seem to think of it that way. <P>It&#8217;s easy to call EverQuest one of the best games ever made. The programmers and designers deserve considerable credit for pulling off a software-engineering feat of this scale. But it falls, or more to the point fails, when it comes to interaction with the people who made it possible for this game to be made, the people who play it every day.<P><b>The Solution</b><P>The simplest solution would be to infuse a bit of common courtesy into the staff. In all that time, said enchantress was never even given an explanation of what a leg-up kit is, even after asking. She had to get that information from people who had received theirs, all of whom I may add were furious at being given the official booby prize. These kits consist of &#8220;equipment suitable to your race, class, and level.&#8221; This means a 26th level rogue receives a dagger and a set of chain mail to replace a collection of banded, snakeskin, a variety of magical items, a hard won dragoon dirk and an equally costly coral trident, not to mention all the items in his inventory, enough to nearly fill 4 backpacks.<P>Another fair step would be at least an appearance of effort instead of Verant&#8217;s policy of brushing players under the carpet at every opportunity. In all the time our enchantress took to get her equipment back, the only people who actually tried to help were the GMs, who are basically powerless in most cases that don&#8217;t involve buggy corpse locations, name changes, and answering questions with the canned &#8220;sorry you were screwed, I&#8217;ll see what I can do.&#8221; Customer Service, who has had so many problems with full equipment losses due to server side glitches that they have actually made a flat (and, might I add, totally inadequate) <I>policy</I> governing it, merely replied with &#8220;here&#8217;s your Volkswagen, have a nice day.&#8221;<P>Most people are reasonable if they feel they&#8217;re being treated like a person and not just a ghost in the machine. When the backhanded manipulation is so blatant it is harder for people to generate any form of goodwill toward the company or the product. The current communal mood is laid bare when you tell someone that you have to deal with Verant on any issue. &#8220;Good luck, you&#8217;ll need it.&#8221;<P>Verant&#8217;s real position? In the case of lost items, they can see what you had before you lost your belongings and they can see what you were left with afterward even if they can&#8217;t see the actual event itself. I spoke with a database designer on the subject and he told me, in so many words, that if they have any kind of backup or save feature for so many people it&#8217;s database driven, and unless the people managing it are terminally stupid, accessing it is a matter of minutes, perhaps an hour. Not days, not months. Verant can track a player as was evidenced by the original offer to restore a character from a month old backup. Verant can also create items at will (which should be obvious - what designer wouldn&#8217;t include that ability as part and parcel of a project of this scope?). So what&#8217;s the problem? Why then, instead of this leg-up kit, isn&#8217;t there a procedure for legitimate recovery?<P>Pure and simple apathy. Takes too much time. You&#8217;re not worth the effort. Take what we offer and shut up. There will be no further discussion.<P>You&#8217;re in our world now.

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem928652400,91866,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Designer's Perspective: Druids</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
