<P>
Since I got a TON of e-mail this morning all about the Druid, I am going to write one response to all of them. Please don&#8217;t feel slighted that I didn&#8217;t do my usual thing of responding personally to every e-mail - unfortunately, I still have lots of work to do during the day other than talking spell theory with people.<br>OK - I guess it is the Druid&#8217;s turn to cry "We&#8217;re not powerful enough." Every other class is doing it, so why not the Druid. Actually, this is not fair on my part. Only a few of the e-mail&#8217;s that I got were mindless rants. Most were very specific, polite, and pointing to specific points. To these people, I say thank you. Let me take a moment to talk about class balance.<br><br>No one character class in EverQuest can do everything, or be good at everything. Despite what games you may recently have been weaned on, there are no Tank-Mages in EverQuest. None. What this means is that your character will not be able to do certain things that other characters can. It means that people will be better then you in some areas. It also means that no matter how lowly your character is, you can do things that other people can not. <br><br>When put together well, this is called class balance. <br><br>No matter what we do, people will complain that their class is not powerful enough and that other classes are too powerful. Look in an editorial section of Dragon Magazine. As my co-worker Ryan P. often says, people are still complaining that classes in AD&D are not balanced. AD&D has being going strong for over a quarter of a century, yet people are still complaining. One of the reasons that they do this is that each class has a specialty - something that they are good at. Each class also has things that they are not good at.<br><br>Again, class balance.<br><br>This argument is here to tell you that there will be things about your class that you do not like, that you think should be made stronger. Other classes have the same arguments. I had a great discussion at E3 with four people - one played a Wizard, one a Magician, one a Necromancer and one an Enchanter. We were talking magic theory, and each one was surprised that other classes thought that the class they were playing was more powerful than their own. Necromancers were jealous of Wizard&#8217;s direct damage, Wizards were jealous of Magician Pets, Magicians were jealous of Enchanter Mesmerize, Enchanters were jealous of Necromancers life draining. A lively debate ensued.<br><br>Accept as a fact that the class you pick will always be a bit less powerful than you think it should be, and that your friend&#8217;s classes will be a bit more powerful. Believe me when I say that they think the same.<br><br>Now, to address some specific concerns.<br><br>Treeform killed. Oh come on. So you can&#8217;t move as a tree now. Moving as a tree always destroyed the illusion of it, and didn&#8217;t protect you any once you moved. So now you can&#8217;t move (which did you no good), but you get better healing when you stand around as a tree. This is "killing the spell?"<br><br>Direct Damage. Druids are complaining that their direct damage does not have the variety (fire, cold, magic, etc.) of a Wizard&#8217;s. True. Druids do get the second best mana to damage ratio in the game (after the Wizard). Almost all of the Druids damage spells are fire based. Outdoors, Druids also get lightning spell which do some good area of effect damage (and run off a slightly better mana to damage ratio, because they can only be used outdoors). Lightning saves verses magic. The lack of completely versatile direct damage is one of the meta-game reasons that Druids are not as powerful as Wizards. Don&#8217;t get me wrong, however. In 90% of the areas, Druids deal out direct damage better then every class but one.<br><br>So we have a class that can hit people with fire anywhere, and lightning outdoors, all for good damage.<br><br>Now, Druids are unique in that they are the only class with good direct damage that also gets DOT (damage over time) spells. Druids get a DOT spell every other spell circle, starting with Stinging Swarm at level 14. Stinging swarm also saves verses magic. As is common knowledge, DOT spells do better damage than direct damage spells on a mana to damage ratio, with the drawback that they don&#8217;t do all of their damage in one package. Necromancers and Shamans recently had their DOT&#8217;s examined, and tuned to meet our ever evolving world. Rest assured that Druid DOT&#8217;s will receive the same attention.<br><br>This being said, it is hard to see how anybody can reasonably complain about Druid&#8217;s damage dealing capacity. <br><br>Now, somebody mentioned that Druid DOT&#8217;s are resisted just as much as Enchanter DOT&#8217;s. This is not true. Enchanters and Druids use different types of DOT&#8217;s. Enchanter&#8217;s DOTs are resisted more because they do things in addition to damage. Because of this, Enchanters get a spell that can lowers a target&#8217;s resistance to magic. Druid&#8217;s DOTs do straight damage - and are therefore resisted just like regular damage spells - i.e. very rarely.<br><br>Damage Shields. Druids and Magicians are the only classes that get good damage shields. A few other classes tinker with them, but nobody matches up to a Druid or a Magician. The one big thing to remember about damage shields is that their damage is almost never resisted. If you put up a 12 point damage shield on your warrior, that is 12 points of damage that the monster takes every time they hit the Warrior. This may not be outrageous damage, but, as the Warrior can tell you, he tends to get hit a lot. Add up one minute worth of melee, being modest and saying 20 hits, and that is 240 points of non-resisted damage for the price of 80 mana (shield of brambles, level 29 spell). If your Warrior happens to be fighting 2 monsters, this spell really can get outrageous.<br><br>Healing. Druids (and Shamans) tie for the second best healers in EQ. They do not match up to the Cleric, but they are still extremely viable as healer. They get the spell Greater Healing (which has a 2-1 ratio of mana to healing done), as well as Regeneration spells, which the Cleric does not get. This follows the DOT theme, doing a reversed DOT as a means of healing their companions.<br><br>This being said, Druids are not Clerics.<br><br>Rooting. Druids get some of the best Root spells in the game (hitting their theme as masters of movement). Their Root spells deal damage, as well as holding the creature in place. No other class (with the exception of Rangers) gets this.<br><br>Unlike some other classes, Druids can do indirect magic. In a dungeon where the creatures are resistant to fire, they can still use their DOT spells, using their healing spells and use their damage shields. Druids are also one of only two classes that can use Teleport Magic - this alone makes them welcome additions to most parties. Druids have the ability to switch tactics, and to fill many roles in a party. A Druid who can not pull their own in any party is a Druid who does not know how to use her spells well.<br><br>Appearance. A lot of Druids complain that they only get to wear leather armor, or have the leather armor look. Well, this isn&#8217;t exactly a spell issue, but&#8230; Sorry. Druids don&#8217;t wear metal armor. That leaves leather. You do, however, get to change into that nifty wolf form and run around.<br><br>Just a quick rundown on Druid powers.<br><br>Movement - Spirit of Wolf, Root, Party Teleport.<br><br>Direct Damage - Very good mana to damage ratio.<br><br>DOT - Good DOT&#8217;s that are hard to save against, and save vs. something other than fire. The damage from these spells really add up over time.<br><br>Healing - The second best healing in the game.<br><br>Damage Shields - Up there with the Magician for the best Damage Shields in the game.<br><br>Charm - The ability to Charm animals<br><br>Buffing - Not mentioned in my writings above, but solid Armor Class and HP buffs, both self only and ones that can be cast on others. <br><br>Rooting - Possibly the best Root spells in the game, since they deal damage as well as rooting the creature. <br><br>Druids have a wide range of powers - of all the classes in EverQuest, they are the most likely to be considered Tank-Mages. The have healing, firepower, personal armor spells and a wide variety of miscellaneous powers. Now, Druids are most certainly not Tank-Mages - as previously stated, no class in EverQuest is. They are, however, an extremely well rounded class. So well rounded that they lack the specialty of many other classes focus on. Druids are similar to Bards in that they do many things very well, but are not specialists in one. If you want to be a direct damage specialist, you take a Wizard. If you want a healing specialist, you take a Cleric. If you want a good summoner, you take a Magician or a Necromancer. Want to be a good Buffer - take a Shaman. Want to be pretty good at all of that, deal very nice damage, and have excellent movement spells to boot? Play a Druid.<br><br>Druids are not going to be changed in any significant way. I will, however, look over some of the high level spells. There were some very valid concerns voiced, and these issues will be addressed once I have done an analysis of the numbers. Just to emphasize though, I feel very strongly that mid to low level Druids are very good. I will specifically be looking at high level Druids.<br><br>Thanks for the feedback - especially to those of you who know how to present it in a calm, rational way.<br><br>Geoffrey C. Zatkin<br>Arch-Magi of Norrath<br>Game Designer for Verant Interactive 

