<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">A Look at EverQuest</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Mahrin Skel  (<a href="mailto:mahrinskel@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">mahrinskel@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
SCENE: 3/4 isometric overhead of a small hut<br>ACTION: Enter Mahrin Skel, Grandmaster Tinkerer, stage Left. He picks up a pile of 50 ore from behind him, sets it down in front of him, walks a few steps, repeats. Reaches stage Center next to the hut, pauses.<br><br>DIALOGUE MAHRIN: "Halfway to Trinsic! Should only take another 30 minutes."<br><br>SOUND: Rapid hammering from inside hut<br><br>ACTION: Pile of ore disappears<br><br>DIALOGUE MAHRIN: "Hey! That was mine, give it back!"<br><br>DIALOGUE S00PER DEWDSLAYER: "Corp Por"<br><br>DIALOGUE MAHRIN: "OOOOooooOOOOooooOOOOooooOOOO!"<br><br>Okay, we all know where we've been, and if you weren't at least considering getting the hell out of there, you wouldn't be reading this. The $64,000 question is: Where are you going to go?<br><br>Up until now, the answer to that question has been: Nowhere. Ultima Online may not have been much, but it was, basicly, the only game in town. But now we have a glimmer of hope, a Light at the end of the tunnel: EverQuest. Some lucky few (including yours truly) have been in that world for months, scouting the territory but unable to send back reports because of the Non-Disclosure Agreement. The only un-official word coming out has been from people who didn't like it and were willing to ignore that document, and the occasional glowing review by media who were mostly spoon-fed the EverQuest experience. Until now. I had no special privileges, plenty of time, and a serious desire to get in and shake things up, see where the loose screws were.<br><br>What is the good, and the bad, and even the ugly, of Norrath? We'll start with the good:<br><br>1) If you don't want to be at war with your fellow players, you don't have to be. The "switch" is there, and it works. Turn it on and go to war, or leave it off and never have to live paranoid again.<br><br>2) The world is *huge*. Not "PR release" huge, but "real-time get in there and run like hell for hours and hours" huge. Knowing *exactly* what I am doing and where I am going, taking all the shortcuts and using a spell that makes me run twice as fast as normal, it still takes me well over an hour to run across Antonica (the main continent). Without that spell, twice as long. And there are two other (much smaller) continents in the game, and two more to be added later, and "Planes" of elementals and undead, and obvious entrances to other areas that are currently blocked off. After nearly 3 months, I have yet to get to all of the zones, and certainly have not fully explored more than 1/4 (and I probably missed things even in those).<br><br>3) The game has real depth. Each class is distinct, with its own strengths and weaknesses, as is each race. There *are* craft skills that will let you make things that simply can't be found or purchased from NPC's, but no pretense is made that those are all you need and they aren't a no-risk route to incredible wealth. There are 100 distinct creature bodies, most coming in multiple sizes and wearing multiple "skins". There are a wide variety of weapons, and deciding which one you want is not a simple matter of asking which is "Best". There are *600* player castable spells. There are 12 different starting cities, 1 city you cannot start in, dozens of "outdoor" zones, and 12 dungeons (some with multiple zones). And each is different, with it's own features, creatures, predators and prey (although some have aspects in common, there are plenty of differences even there). Actually, the line between "dungeon" and "city" is a little blurred, there are "dungeons" where you can go in and do business with the denizens and perform quests for them, if you haven't done anything to make them angry.<br><br>4) There is a highly complex backstory, that can be discovered and that process of discovery can enhance your character, as well as your gaming experience. Norrath has a history, and many of the NPC's you see are part of that history and the current state of the world.<br><br>That's the good parts of Norrath. The Bad:<br><br>1) Balancing measures meant to keep some classes from being far more popular than others mean that it may be difficult to keep a group of friends together. Certain classes, especially "Hybrids" like Paladins and Rangers need far more XP for the same levels, which means they will fall behind and eventually will no longer be able to effectively group with their friends.<br><br>2) Grouping is very nearly mandatory. As you get higher in level, it becomes more and more difficult to kill anything by yourself that will give you experience points. Some class/race combinations simply *cannot* advance solo past a certain point.<br><br>3) It is nearly impossible to give yourself a unique "look". Technical limitations and design decisions mean that only so many player "skins" could be accomodated, and a significant change in appearance is pretty much reserved for higher-level characters. You will very quickly find other players who look *exactly* like you do.<br><br>The Ugly:<br><br>1) "The problem with Online Games, is Online Gamers." They can't kill you, but the jerks out there will still find ways to annoy you. "Vulching" your kills, saying rude and crude things, blocking narrow passages, arranging for mobs to attack you when you're weakened, jerks are still jerks, and not every way that they can try and ruin your gaming experience can be done away with programmatically.<br><br>That's all for ugly, but it will be quite bad enough. Don't fool yourself into thinking that EverQuest is somehow magically going to be filled with bright, cheery people, always willing to lend a hand, and *always* doing so in perfect role-playing fashion. People will still be rude and inconsiderate, people will still powergame with no concern at all for roleplay, people will still mock you for speaking Olde Englishe.<br><br>Promised but not yet delivered:<br><br>1) Guild functions. We have been told that in-game player run guilds will be supported, but we have seen no sign of that yet.<br><br>2) "Houses". Feedback from 989 has been inconsistent. There are places where you can buy a house key, but it goes to nothing and does nothing. It has "Rent" of 0 copper a month, currently, and indications from 989 indicate that these will go to the (currently empty) rooms scattered around the cities, and will be both very expensive and limited in number to those that are already in the game.<br><br>3) PvP. It's in there, but nobody has been using it, so it hasn't even begun to be balanced. 989 says that they will balance PvE (Player versus Environment) first, then PvP.<br><br>4) Smoother quest performance. Right now, in spite of 989 promises that quests would not require playing "Guess my Magic Word" with NPC's, they by and large do. Not any worse than any RPG that allowed "Plain Speech" interaction, but not much better, either.<br><br>Norrath is a fun, large, and highly complex world, where you can spend hours upon hours exploring and interacting. It is *not* the Promised Land, and no online game ever will be. Nevertheless, it *is* the best example of the genre, ever, with many of the things we hoped for from UO, but never got. 989 Studios has done their best to make RPG'er dreams a reality, and their best is stunning.<br><br>--Mahrin Skel

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem925887600,18093,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Balance of the Classes</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Nelwan Firestorm  (<a href="mailto:N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Hail, fellow Norrathians! For quite some time now, an heated debate had been raging on. I am talking about the the issues concerning the balance of the classes in EverQuest. Everyone who didn&#8217;t played a lot of classes to high levels, and that&#8217;s most on Norrath&#8217;s population, feels that the class he played is inferior in many ways to the other classes. Although EverQuest&#8217;s development team stated several times that the &#8216;grass is always greener&#8217; syndrome was normal in any class-based games, many people still complain about their classes. I&#8217;ve always been an optimist, and my goals are modest. I want to prove to the entire world that the classes are well balanced and that every of them are fully playable. Of course the system isn&#8217;t perfect. Of course some things have to be tweaked, but compared to Ultima Online&#8217;s tank mages/archers or to Diablo&#8217;s Sorcerer, EverQuest&#8217;s class system is close to perfect. <br>I do not claim that without reasons, and these will come in due time. Some people really think that their class is &#8216;broken&#8217; or that it lacks something important, and they think that they are right, no matter what other people says. Why? First, because most players compare their class like this: they play with someone of the same level for a while, see what he can do in certain circumstances, see what he can&#8217;t do in those circumstances and immediately think; &#8220;Geez, this class sucks!&#8221; What is wrong in that? Well first, the player compares his own level of skill playing the class to the skill of a stranger playing his own class. People don&#8217;t think about it, but often the other guy might just play his class better than you play yours. <br><br>Second, all classes have a few points in terms of level where they are weaker than other classes, and that&#8217;s perfectly normal, no class is strong at every level. The problem is that if you compare your class to another when you are at a &#8216;bad&#8217; level, when the other class is at a &#8216;good&#8217; level, the opinion you get of these classes can be pretty messed up. This is particularly true to two kinds of people: those who played every class up to a relatively low-average level, like 15-16, and for the anticipators, those who read everything available on the internet, especially spell lists, and made their opinion of balance without having effectively played any class to a decent level, thinking that they would find the best class that way. The first kind of people will probably have a false idea of his class possibilities at higher levels and will end up pretty angry. The second category will most of the time end up playing druids and rangers, and will also get angry once they&#8217;ll figure that they aren&#8217;t playing a god class after all. <br><br>Last, but not least, there is what people class the grass is always greener syndrome: the fact that in certain circumstances there is always going to be someone stronger than you are. Some people just cannot get used to the idea. But it is easy to understand after all! You chose to play a role, a class, and accept its strengths AND its weaknesses. You simply have to choose what your heart tells you should play. Forget all these statistics, all the tables you&#8217;ve seen on EQlizer, all the spell lists that keeps telling you: &#8220;Play a druid, play a druid! Hey&#8230; I told you to play a druid!&#8221; when you know you only want to be a high elf paladin. Then you&#8217;ll be ready to choose what class you can beat the most fun out of. <br><br>Now to be more earth-to-earth, I know it isn&#8217;t always that easy. Some people have class-specific concerns that make, according to them, their class unplayable. Most of the time, this isn&#8217;t really the problem. Many players just do not like what their class is so they ask for more thinking that playing a god class will compensate for the fact they don&#8217;t like what the class can truly do. Other players do not even realize what their class is supposed to do and think that it isn&#8217;t very effective after all, simply because they do not play it the way it should be played. An example would be a mage misusing his pet and completely ignoring his damage shields, that would say that the wizard is better than him because his spells does more damage. <br><br>Sometimes, it would also be wiser to remember that this game is a PvE game, not a PvP one. Comparing your cleric to the druid grouping with you isn&#8217;t always the best choice. There are many things he will never be able to do even if it seems at the first glance that he is way more useful than you are. Always remember to consider your usefulness to your party and versus the world of Norrath before considering the differences between your class and the other class. <br><br>Of course nothing is perfect&#8230; EverQuest&#8217;s class system may be the best available but it isn&#8217;t the best it can be. A few problems would be the fact that warriors are much weaker than other tank classes at higher levels, the fact that many rogue skills doesn&#8217;t work properly, and maybe the fact that necromancers and shadow knights do not get enough to compensate for the great difficulties their factions causes them. But these are only minor problems that can be easily fixed, and none of these classes are broken or completely unplayable. Generally the balance of the classes is great. Druids, shamans or rangers aren&#8217;t overpowered like most people think the balance between the 4 pure mage types is in fact awesome and unequalled in my honest opinion. The strongest parties are always balanced parties, no matter what some people may claim. That is what I call balance in a game. <br><br>To conclude, I would like to make a wish. Play the class you like the most without bothering with its statistics. Do not waste your time comparing your class with the class of your friends. Do not recklessly flame the development team claiming how your class is unbalanced. If everyone does that, it&#8217;ll already be a large step forward! And most importantly, have fun! Because no matter how much we like the game, no matter how much time we invest in it, remember that, after all, it&#8217;s still a game! <br><br>Nelwan Firestorm, <br>Magician of Karana. 

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem925887600,48134,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">EQMUD - The Next Generation</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Oghma  (<a href="mailto:oghma@bv.net" class="credit2">oghma@bv.net</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://eqx.simplenet.com" class="credit2">EverQuest Express</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
The MUDding experience has been mentioned quite a few times, both as partof the EQ development teams&#8217; inspiration and in posts, chats, and articles. I realize that while many players are familiar with MUDs, I am surprisedby the amount of players that don&#8217;t.  In writing for <a href="http://www.eqx.simplenet.com" target="_blank">EverQuest Express</a>, I often get requestsfor good MUDs to play, so that the players can have a fix of something<i>close</i> to EQ before they can play in the beta.  This is an intriguingpoint - how close to a MUD will EQ be?  Also, how different? </p><p>The basic definition of a MUD from the <a href="http://www.imagica.net/mudfaq.htm" target="_blank">MUD FAQ</a> 	"A MUD (Multiple User Dimension, Multiple User Dungeon, or Multiple UserDialogue) is a computer program which users can log into and explore. Eachuser takes control of a computerized persona/avatar/incarnation/ character.You can walk around, chat with other characters, explore dangerousmonster-infested areas, solve puzzles, and even create your very own rooms,descriptions and items. "</p>	<p>That sounds pretty identical to EverQuest, doesn&#8217;t it?  What it doesn&#8217;taddress is that MUDs, in general, are text-based games (there are a fewgraphical ones out there), whereas EQ will be graphical and text.  We&#8217;veall seen the screen shots which show a text window in the middle bottomquarter of the screen, and the text looks an awful lot like a MUD&#8217;s textscroll during combat.  The EQ graphical interface leads to distinctdifferences in game-play, which I&#8217;ll address from the perspective of a MUDveteran.</p>		<p>In a MUD, a character moves from room to room in an area, even thoughsometimes the "room" has a description as "A long stretch of prairie" or "AWindy Mountain peak".  When you enter a room with a monster, you would typethe command to "kill x" and the fight starts.   You will usually have acommand (called wimpy) to flee if your hit points get too low, and youreturn to the room you left from if you "wimpy" (some MUDs allow you to seta direction).  They key here is that each room is a distinct separate "cell".EQ will let you see monsters from a distance, and auto-attack as youapproach them.  The idea of a distinct cell is no longer there.  I used tobe able to camp outside a mob&#8217;s room, run in, attack, get damaged, wimpyout, and them heal for a bit, run in, attack, and repeat until the mobdies.  I can&#8217;t see, for instance, there being a viable way to "wimpy" inEQ.  Which direction would you run?  The monster is not in a distinct"cell" so could follow you all over.</p><p>Also, in a MUD ALL your information is textual.  This leads to some prettyamazing screen scrolls, especially in MUDs with complex combat systems.  Ihave tried to get some friends into MUDs, and they&#8217;ve all said "How can youread all that?".  I reply that after a while you know what is important towatch, but it still is a lot of information to absorb.  Room descriptionssometimes go into long paragraphs, so that a simple run north of four orfive rooms scrolled  two full pages of material.  I remember having toreally watch myself when I was coding rooms, because every noun I added toa room had to have a separate description line, so that that particularroom would be appropriately interactive.</p><p>EQ has no room descriptions, you just look.  Your screen is filled witheye candy that sets a mood and informs you about your surroundings.  Musicand sound are also going to enhance the experience.  There is textualcombat, but it looks much less demanding to interpret, according to some ofthe screen shots.  None of these massive screen scrolls. </p><p>From a builders standpoint, there is one important difference.  MUDs aremostly designed by computer professionals in their spare time.  A cadre ofprogrammers, some good, some sloppy, some untrained (as I was), design theMUD and write the room descriptions, combat system, guilds, and whateverelse the MUD contains.  Often these groups of programmers create highlyimaginative worlds, with complex class systems and spell systems.  Theyare, however, done in their spare time.  I&#8217;ve worked on a MUD for a yearand then left, due to lack of interest, or a job move, or whatever.  Also,most of the programmers are spread all over the country, and never "see"each other except for online.   Game servers are often begged or borrowedand no admin has a direct, real-life access to the server.</p><p>EQ has computer professionals, too, but they are paid to create Norrath.Their full-time job is EverQuest (is there a job opening for me?<g>), theywork in the same building, have access to the servers, and there are abunch of them.  From what 989 has said, also, many of the programmers haveextensive experience with MUDs, so 989 may have quite the cream of the crop.</p>	<p>What else is the same?  Player interaction.  One of the crucialattractions of both MUDs and EQ is that when you play, you play with manyothers, and the social aspect makes it more complex and entertaining than astand alone.  It also can make it more frustrating.  (Remember UO d00dz?) Ialmost hesitate to bring up this point, since it&#8217;s been done to death inthe posts and editorials and chat discussions, but here it is:  MUD&#8217;s havealready tested the player-killing aspect of online role-playing gamesextensively. There have been MUDs since the late 70&#8217;s, some of which wereall PK, some non-PK, and some a little of both, and it has already worked.I&#8217;ve played and gm&#8217;ed MUDs of all types, and there are minor he said/shesaid issues, which have more to do with bad manners than game design, butfew of the doom and gloom make or break issues that players are concernedabout.  I think that the MUD experience of the 989 staff will show us thatthe PvP "switch" is a well thought out and implemented way of ensure thatboth PK&#8217;s and non-PK&#8217;s can interact side by side.</p>	<p>EQ seems to be the true "next generation" (pardon the over-used term) ofMUDs.  It looks as if the mud players of the 80s and 90s are now creatingwhat was the dream of every MUDder of that generation: a  graphical,immersive environment using the best aspects of the text based MUDs.  Whilethe computer gaming industry of the 90s trumpeted the arrival ofmultiple-player online games in the late 90&#8217;s, they have already quietlybeen played for more than a decade.  It is this extensive MUD backgroundthat will address the major online gaming issues that other games with astand alone background have missed.  As with any MUD, or any online gamefor that matter, however, it is up to us, the players, to make theenvironment they made for us, and that we paid for, an enjoyable one.</p><p>-Oghma

