<P>
Okay, so it's happened to every writer at least once.  He or she takes their sweet time in their research, they study their subject material at length, cover all the bases, they even start writing their article and *BAM*... Some other writer comes out with an article on the exact same topic, covering all the same points you planned on covering, and to add injury to insult, their article was so poignant and well-written that you can plainly see it makes <I>your</I> article stink like Lake Michigan.  Or at least it <I>would</I> have, had you been granted the dignity of actually finishing it.<P>That very thing happened to me when Bauhaus wrote an excellent recount of his experiences on the +PvP server titled "<A HREF="http://eqx.simplenet.com/Issue68/rallos.htm">Two Weeks in Rallos Zek</A>."  When I first read it, my heart sank clear to China.  The wind totally left my sails when I saw that not only did "Speedy Gonzales" beat me to the punch, but every point the article brings up falls squarely in the bounds I was going to make.  This, more than anything, is what contributed to my writer's block over the last three weeks.<P>For anyone who has already formed their preconceptions about the +PvP-only server (and you <I>know</I> who you are!), I would strongly recommend reading that article and taking it as gospel no less seriously than The Bible or Bill Gate's bestseller, <I>"How to Own the Internet on Less Than 640K."</I><P>So kudos to you, Bauhaus, and congratulations for writing a truly accurate and excellent article... you two-timing, thunder-stealing JERK!!!  :P<P>Instead I'll write about something else that touches on the topic of life on Rallos Zek, and I'll save my thunder for when I take Bauhaus's article back in time one week before it was released, and then pipe up with cries of plagiarism at just the right moment.  <P>So today I'm going to discuss my own escapades of doing my part in bringing the life of roleplaying to what is predominantly viewed as a powergamer's domain.  I won't blow a lot of recycled wind up your skirt and tell you how surprised I was that people weren't killing each other left and right (which is true), or how I had totally forgotten I was even <I>on</I> Rallos Zek at one point, and was reminded of this essential fact by getting whacked by someone who was obviously looking for some poor fool who didn't keep a cautious eye on their own hit point level.<P>Nor would I ever stoop so low as to tell you all these things while in the same breath stating I won't be telling you all these things.  That would make for poor writing practice, and such a display of despicable - even cowardly - journalism would never be tolerated by the EQ Vault staff.<P>Instead, I'll tell you about two characters my wife and I have been dying to play together since Phase 4, and what we've discovered about the existence of roleplaying on Rallos Zek.  We play two woodelf twins named Denna and Dharia who typically hang out in Greater Faydark  and its surrounding regions.  This inseperable (insufferable?) duo enjoy nothing more out of life than gold, flirting with High Elves, gold, drinking themselves senseless at Tovanial's Venom, and gold -- in that order and then some.<P>Needless to say, these two are not without their due collection of allies among the populace.  Not only that, but the chemistry we've given their repertoire has initiated more fun bouts of roleplaying than I can count.  I'm amazed at how many players on Rallos Zek want so much to roleplay, if only someone would give them a reason to.<P>Denna and Dharia are experts at this.  Trust me, if a character ever catches their favor, he (or she) goes away with a smile on their face.  But of course, all this roleplaying comes at a price.  You see, our "heroines" prefer to spend much of their time passing out in taverns over and above going out and killing things.  Consequently, their levels are disappointing for having played them three long weeks.  Not to mention the fact that a coupling of two same-class characters is the tactical equivalent of naming your new yacht "Titanic."<P>Be that as it may, it's who they are.  It's who they were born to be, and they're perfectly happy with their lifestyle, accepting the perks and pitfalls that come with it.  My wife and I have had an absolute <I>blast</I> playing these two -- I dare say they're our favorite characters.  So we figure levels will come with time; maybe a <I>long</I> time, but it will happen eventually.  The point is we're having fun and we're sharing the fun with everyone around us who cares to indulge themselves in something different from the rampant bloodletting you normally see.  It can be very refreshing for a change, and it's something I never thought I'd discover on Rallos Zek.<P>That's not to say Denna and Dharia don't experience the thrill of the hunt.  Far from it!  When they're not entertaining some well-to-do friend(s) in Tovanial's, they can be found chasing down just about any purse-toting NPC they can find.  Their prowess together in battle isn't something to be taken lightly, as it's what's kept them fed during their needier times.<P>As such, they will <I>rarely</I> turn down the offer of a drink at the local tavern.  It's what they live for!  With these two, it's always feast or famine.  Having squandered their latest period of feast, right now they're sleeping off their revelry in some filthy back alley in Ak'Anon.<P>So what's the bottom line?  Well, the truth of the matter is I entered the +PvP-only world with an aire of smugness, fully believing I would spend the next few hours proving how Rallos wasn't for me.  Now I'm dining on a certain corn-loving carrion eater, because I'm finding myself drawn to that server more and more as I play on it.  <P>This is doubly true now that I've experimented with a +PvP character on a "normal" server who keeps getting whacked by other +PvP characters just because they finally found someone they can kill!  To make matters worse on the flip-side, the normal servers just seem too "safe" for -PvP characters anymore.  I find myself robbed of the excitement and sense of real danger in the wilderness I've grown accustomed to on Rallos.  Plus, if some young upstart gets too cheeky on a normal server, the best you can do to put him in his place is challenge him to a duel and pray to the gods that he's stupid enough to accept it.<P>And then there's roleplaying.  Ever since Fennin Ro was christened the "roleplay" server, it's been busier than Jack Kevorkian's spin doctor.  I'll contend that by playing Denna and Dharia to their fullest extent, we (my wife and I) have seen more roleplaying on Rallos Zek in the last few weeks than we've <I>ever</I> seen on Fennin Ro!  May God have mercy on my soul for saying it, but it's the truth.<P>So if you're playing on Rallos and happen to come across our pair of pretentious party-animals, throw yourself into character and join them in a drink or twelve.  Just keep in mind that while these two are amourous and fun-loving, they are definitely not to be trusted when the chips are down.  They are, after all, a pair of egocentric and self-serving thieves...<P>-&lt;Shadoe&gt;<P>P.S. By the way, these are our favorite characters to play, and we always play them in-context.  So if you happen to come across us, please don't make me regret posting this article by mentioning it, or how you "know who we really are," or ask us who's playing which character (nothing will get you /ignored by us faster).  I thoroughly enjoy playing Denna and Dharia with my wife, and I'd really hate to see that fun spoiled by so many out-of-character comments.  So please do us -- and yourself -- a favor and have fun with these two characters in game-context.  You may not reach the next level quite as fast, but you won't regret it!  :)

