<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Shadoe  (<a href="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
You know, I don't make it a habit of writing more than one article per week, and I want everyone to know that it's not something I do lightly now. I have far too many pressing matters to deal with in my life to make writing articles anything more than a hobby for me, and a loose one at that. But once in a while an issue comes along that makes a writer say to himself, "this just can't wait." The issue I write about in this article has a profound impact for me, and I'm hoping I'll be able to portray that to you now. What is it about the "massively multiplayer game" that sets it apart from any other kind of computer game out there? If we all put our heads together, no doubt we'll come up with a list that could reach all the way from Erudin to Felwithe and then some. But what is it about online gaming in general that gives us our unique fix for entertainment that no other genre can provide? Of course, the answer is clear: player interaction. No longer must we rely on preprogrammed automatons to convince ourselves that we are not alone in a pretentious digital world through which some predetermined destiny unfolds. Our artificial friends still have a place in performing the consistent, mundane tasks. Beyond that, the world we visit - be it Norrath or whatever future worlds are to come - is ripe with a thousand other players, each with the capacity to interact dynamically with you and each other! Technologically, we made this leap a couple of years ago, and by now it's become second nature to us as we've raised the bar of what to expect from the industry. But indulge me for a moment and take a step back to see what it is we're really doing. Force yourself to remember how you felt when you were first introduced to massively multiplayer gaming. Experience, once again, awe at the miracle of what is being accomplished. This miracle isn't merely a means of entertainment. Through allowing people to experience shared dangers and hardships, risks and triumphs together, it has opened a whole new means for people to meet, build bridges of friendship, and form bonds that far outweigh any value the game holds in itself. By that, I mean everything that happens in-game is so superficial, compared to what we can gain from it in real life. So you have a level 50 necromancer who can wipe just about anyone else off the face of the planet and still have time for lunch at Crow's. So you're the head of a guild consisting of 250+ people. So you've gained power and notoriety such that you've become a household name. So you "hold the death sentence on twelve systems..." Where will those accomplishments be once the game is over? As good a game as EverQuest is, I'm here to tell ya it ain't gonna be around forever, folks. Sure there will be sequels as progress continues turning its heavy wheels, but no matter how hard you try, you can't recapture the old days. That is, except through nostalgia, and nostalgia is made ten times better when it's remembered with a friend. That is precisely what I'm getting at, and I'll tell you why it's suddenly so important to me. The server outages over the past weekend have given me leave to really take a look at where I am and what's happening around me. I suddenly found myself in the midst of a group of tremendously good friends whose comradeship was making my angst just that much easier to cope with, and I them. As kneebitingly frustrating as the blackout had been, I realized that not only is it going to be fleeting in the long-term, but these friends and I are more likely going to remember the time we spent together during the outages more than the outages themselves. In fact, the outages have introduced me to a couple of new friends I met along the way, who I'm hoping to become better acquainted with. Then it occurred to me through events that took place shortly thereafter how important this revelation really is to me. The value of the friendships I've gained hit me in a rush as I came to grips about how small and insignificant the EQ universe itself really is when compared to what I've gained from playing it... and even not playing it, in some cases! What I've gained, I can very well keep with me for the rest of my life. It's given me vision to see the ulterior, tangible rewards that EverQuest has to offer, and not merely the rewards of sitting down and getting that last bubble filled to level 8. Now I see how many good and decent friends I've made through gaming over the years, and how highly I value their friendship. Now I see how many doors gaming has opened for me in my life. They're countless, and I wouldn't give them up for anything. I think next time I enter Norrath, it will be with a little different perspective than merely 3D. So now I suggest you take a look at your own approach to EverQuest, and take a look at the Big Picture. Is EverQuest merely a $10/month distraction from your day-to-day life -- something to use as a vice to escape a disappointing reality? Or are you using it to gain something greater by far? Most importantly, where will you be once the party is over and the inevitable day arrives when the gods see fit to flip the power switch off on Norrath? - Shadoe 

