<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Shadoe  (<a href="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
[Author's Note: This little annecdote details the <I>SUM</I> of my online adventures last weekend (March 20-21, 1999 -- first weekend following the EverQuest release.)]   <P>  Darion crouched low behind the brush, the droning sounds of battle in the distance.  The sound had become all too familiar to him, having been a common participant in helping to rid the gates of Qeynos from the vermin that so often plagued the sparsely populated orchard to the north.  Northern Qeynos <I>always</I> seemed a mass of man-against-vermin of late, day or night.  The gnoll Darkpaw clan alone, with their occasional raids, were enough to cause the city guards headache without having to deal with the relentless klicknik infestation night after night.  This particular night, Darion fully intended to join the ranks of those who had the fighting savvy to deal with the klickniks once and for all.  Tonight he would succeed in killing his first klicknik drone, or die trying.  <P>  The mild breeze cooled the sweat on Darion's brow as he patiently waited in hiding to spy his prey.  Minutes wore on as he sat his lonely vigil on the area he knew the klickniks frequented every night, never questioning his faith that eventually one hapless drone would come marching by as if it owned the place.  Occasionally he'd glance above and watch the moon creep its way across the sky, noting the time as it slips away.  <P>  Then he heard it; the tell-tale "click-click" of the large, beetle-like creatures that have caused so much trouble.  Darion perked as he came to his feet and glanced around, searching for the source of the sound.  There it was, glowing in the darkness like its brethren the fire beetles, creeping along the ground.  Its manner was fluid - almost <I>elegant</I> - in the way it moved with a sense of purpose.  Such sentient behavior in a lower life-form gave Darion the creeps as he silently drew his sword from the scabbard at his side.  In moments he would run his sword through that carapace, and rid the world of this freak of nature.  <P>  With the agility of a cat, Darion pounced on the overgrown <I>bug</I> with a yell.  Now out of the relative safety of hiding, he repeatedly whacked on the creature's hard exoskeleton with his blade as if in a panic to kill the creature before it could react.  Such foolishness was rewarded by the drone turning and immediately hacking at Darion's legs, inflicting blow after blow with its mandibles.  Darion ignored the pain as he pressed his advantage with slashes of his own.  The fight was an even match, it could go either way, yet his impetus was weakening ever so slightly with every blow he delivered.  Thoughts raced through his mind as he wondered if he would actually survive this small fracas.  <P>  Suddenly his target vanished before his eyes!  Gone, without a sign that it had ever been there in the first place, aside from the bleeding cashes in his legs.  Darion shook his head with a jerk, as if to clear his mind of some devilish hallucination.  Sadly the drone was still absent when he opened his eyes, baffling his mind such that he began to wonder about his sanity.  Gazing around, he was shocked to see other creatures in the orchard around him disappearing, one by one.  Bats, snakes, even his fellow humans were being whisked away by some unknown force!  Darion's pulse raced as he feared for his very existence... was he next?  What foul curse could author such a wicked fate?  What was happening to his otherwise normal world?!  <P>  Then suddenly, all went dark about him.  He glanced around frantically, yet with a grim certainty of realizing it was indeed his turn to vanish from the world of Norrath and discover the realities of what lay beyond.  Unsure of the cold, dimensionless void he felt around him, Darion waited for a sign from the gods or fate or whatever force had brought him here -- something that could explain what has so suddenly deprived him of all he has ever known, and why.  <P>  Out of the impenetrable darkness emerged three glowing words, hovering before him... <BR>  "SERVER NOT RESPONDING."  <P>  "What the-?" was all he had time to say before he found himself standing once again in an isolated, marble room with columns and candelebras surrounding him.  Beyond, he could see shallow steps ascending to windows opening out to a twighlight sky, dusted with translucent wisps of cloud cover.  All remained silent except for the sounds he himself made.  <P>  Now Darion stands in the center of the room, alone for all intents and purposes.  What this place is, or how he got here remains a mystery.  No apparent means of leaving this room presents itself, so Darion has no choice but to remain here until someone comes to get him.  In the mean time perhaps he'll try out a few combat moves to keep himself in shape, preparing for the time when he will return to Norrath.  Nothing is forever, and he believes that his incarceration here will be fleeting in the grand scheme of things.  He has faith that some day he will be released.  Oh yes... some day soon.  

