<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Bigotry in the Roleplayer's World Readers Response</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Shadoe  (<a href="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Color me shocked! Not only did the number of reader responses from the </FONT><A HREF="http://www.eqvault.net/features/shadoe/racial.shtml"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>"Bigotry" article</FONT></A><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2> far surpass the P.v.P. article by a HUGE margin, but <I>every single one </I>was eloquent, insightful, and complimentary. This means, of course, I'm forced to write something completely scandalous next time. I hope you all fully realize this! *g*</P>  <P>This also means I have to sift through all these excellent submissions, and pick only a handful to post here. So, rather than take up all of Vault Network's disk space with me resting on my laurels, let me say right now how glad I am you guys took the time to write in saying how much you enjoyed this article. It means about as much to me as dinner meant to Orson Wells, and that comes from right my cholesterol-filled heart. Really, thank you! </P>  <P>So I've decided to post submissions that either bring something new to the topic of roleplaying bigotry, covering other areas I failed to bring up in the article. This narrows things down only <I>slightly</I>, so I'll still not be able to post every single letter like this I received (<I>sorry, but I cannae change the laws of physics, cap'n!</I>). </P>  <P>To kick off this long road, here's a letter from someone who has made it habit to cover his bases when it comes to roleplaying rude characters... </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>I always make sure that I preface rude IN CHARACTER comments with a<BR>  previous explanatory OOC comment (using /ooc). I play a goodish gnomish<BR>  magician who hates necromancers. </P>  <P>Necros always ask me to create food and water for them (since they<BR>  cannot use most shops). I always reply with a very rude and aggressive<BR>  comment towards necros, but I ALWAYS preface it with an /OOC comment<BR>  that what I'm about to say is not personal, but is simply my required IN<BR>  CHARACTER reaction.</P>  <P>Most people either tell me i'm a jerk or simply walk aways as soon as I<BR>  say I won't help. I've never had anyone else RP back. At least I think<BR>  it's a better way so at least I know I've tried to let them know it's<BR>  not personal.</P>  <P>Best, Aaron "Moryian" </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  <P>Take it from me, this is good advice. Playing my female necromancer has become a lot smoother since I started to make sure people understood that I'm <I>roleplaying</I> her rudeness. </P>  <P>I will take a moment to point out that there remain a lot of people (myself included) who switch off the /ooc and /shout messages in their chat filter options, so many of them won't get your message. It may be a good idea to type "ooc:" in normal speech and let them know about it that way, too, if they don't respond to your /ooc right away. </P>  <P>Anyway, good work, Aaron! </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>Shadoe, </P>  <P>I must agree with you on the roleplay issue. I have been a rpgamer since the D&amp;D rule's were just two paperback books the size of a TV Guide!! Although I have not had the pleasure of playing EQ yet, I have been following the talk and the sites that discuss EQ. Roleplay is not about being "politically correct" it's about becoming something else.. You have the option to choose how well you are liked or disliked based on what race you pick(I personally would not choose a dark-elf recluse!!) but that is your choice, don't take it personally, it's just a game!!! Those of us who understand and want the roleplay factor in our gaming must take the time to explain it to those who are not in that frame of mind... who knows you just might help someone become a rpgamer!! Keep up the good work Shadoe!!! Dark-elf recluse... you must be crazy!!! :) </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  <P>Heh... I've been accused of being crazy far more times than I've been accused of being Shadoe Stevens (which basically amounts to the same thing). No, I'm not Mr. Stevens, though he <I>is</I> the reason I decided to change the "w" to an "e" in my own alias back in '89. </P>  <P>And you're right, to many people, playing a Dark-Elf recluse would be insanity. I admit, it's been an uphill battle for my character (she's only level 5 now, after all this time). </P>  <P>But I'll let you in on a little secret of mine. For me, the enjoyment of roleplaying transcends the need for boosting my character's skills through their ability to group with others. True, it's nice to have a high-level character to roleplay with. Nevertheless, it's my contention that I've had more fun interacting and roleplaying this character with others than I ever did with my straight-laced, higher-level, conformist characters. Big-time! And having fun is really what we're after when we log into EverQuest, right? So what if it takes longer to boost my character's level? That just means I'll appreciate it more once I get there. It will also allow me the latitude to add haughtiness to her repertoire, since fewer people will be able to defeat her in a duel. It's just a pity I'll have to wait until after release to accomplish this, after starting her over from scratch. *sigh* </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>Man, you are an excellent writer. Very nice article. It really made me<BR>  stop and think. I try to role-play, and some people get upset because they<BR>  think it's e the player talking. Well, after reading your article, I<BR>  realize that I too sometime become aggravated thinking it's the other player<BR>  actually talking, not his character. It really made me become aware of<BR>  this. Thanks for the enjoyable reading, Keep up the good work. Oh yeah, I<BR>  don't know if you remember me, but I talked to you in one of the EQ chat<BR>  rooms called Shadoe (wait a minute, that's your name, too) anyways, my<BR>  handle was Bigfisch. Later<BR>  R. Michael </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  <P>Yep, I remember you. That was one of the many times in the early days of Phase 4 when the servers were being tweaked, and everyone (and I mean <I>EVERYONE</I>) was hanging out in the EQ chat area, waiting to reenter the game. As aggravating as outages like that can be, I enjoyed my time just milling about with everyone. </P>  <P>Anyway, you're not the only one who's caught himself taking in-character remarks personally. Even after writing this article, I've had to remind myself of this very point a number of times! The good news is I've discovered it does get easier to "make the break", as it were, the more you do it. </P>  <P>This next posting, I had to snip a bit, due to longevity. He still makes a good point in this particular paragraph, and I wanted to comment on it... </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>[...]<BR>  Anyway, to get more to the point. To change, I tried to play an<BR>  evil character. I picked the absolute most insane class in the world to try<BR>  and play a truly evil character, the Monk. My character would fit in<BR>  perfectly as one of those bad martial arts movie, smart and can fight like<BR>  no body's business. Or at least that was the original idea. The problem is<BR>  that it goes so against my personal nature, that I found it hard to be mean<BR>  to others when they helped me out. Here is a good example of one relatively<BR>  simple interchange. I was fighting a Skeleton in the Qeynos hills, when<BR>  someone started to heal me, it was a 4th level Druid giving me a helping<BR>  hand. How do you handle this situation? In this particular case I thanked<BR>  them when they started to talk to me. I tried to keep my side of the<BR>  conversation limited to one or two words at a time, showing limited or no<BR>  interest in the person. The real problem is that I don't think that is the<BR>  way I would have WANTED the character to act, but this game to some extent<BR>  dictates that you are nice to you fellow player if you want to get anywhere<BR>  because of it's PvE nature.<BR>  [...]</P>  <P>Current characters (Test Server)<BR>  Airen - Druid<BR>  Juntao - Monk</P>  <P>Final Release (Some unknown server at this time)<BR>  Indreju Thomaii - Druid </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  <P>Roleplaying the evil character is one of the most challenging tasks you can undertake with online gaming. On the surface, it seems it wouldn't be so tough, but most people realize how against their own nature it is once they try it for the first time. </P>  <P>I remember my first thief in Ultima Online. It was pretty fun being able to pull a fast one on other characters, but after a while I found myself actually feeling <I>guilty</I> for my behavior! (How's <I>that</I> for a lack of character/player separation?) Anyway, in the end I realized what I was doing, I told myself that's the way the game's played, and I ended up enjoying that character a lot more than any other I had in UO. </P>  <P>The same goes for racial hatreds, even for "non-evil" characters that should hold a natural tendency for prejudice with opposing factions. Such behavior can go vehemently against people's grain, which is a good sign for a real-world society, but it doesn't lend itself toward roleplaying bigotry in Norrath. </P>  <P>The key here lies in understanding what is fantasy, what is reality, and pointedly separating the two. </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>[...]<BR>  I believe the area that it is the most difficult for players to roleplay<BR>  is limits and stupidity. This will be amplified in online games. As<BR>  you said in your article, the other Dark Elf was trying to help with his<BR>  suggestion. And from a power-game stand-point, he was probably right.<BR>  But, it would not be roleplaying. In a pen-and-paper game, you can make<BR>  these decisions, knowing that your GM (if he is good) will take this<BR>  into account. In a pen-and-paper game, you can take stupid risks with<BR>  the intention of entertaining the others in the room, knowing that you<BR>  will probably survive if you are entertaining enough. You can take more<BR>  creative spells and have fun with them, knowing the GM will probably<BR>  tailor some encounter just for you to stretch the limits of your<BR>  creativity. None of this happens online. The computer has hard-coded<BR>  rules. You are just as likely to die no matter how entertaining you<BR>  are. You just can't do as much with some spells as with others. The<BR>  computer cannot be subjective. I still find it more fun to roleplay<BR>  this way, but it is more difficult online. Because of this, fewer<BR>  people will do it.<BR>  [...] </P>  <P>--Jon-Paul Estes </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  <P>Jon-Paul makes a number of truly excellent points here when it comes to paper &amp; pencil roleplaying versus online roleplaying. I'd comment further, except anything I could say would be redundant. Good show! </P>  <P>The only thing I will touch on here, is your comment about limits and stupidity. This is a difficult roleplaying concept at the <I>best</I> of times, much less in an online roleplaying game where the powergaming mentality runs so rampant - even among roleplayers. </P>  <P>Say, for instance, that you start a High-Elf character that travels to Qeynos. Now, because you also have that Human character who started in Qeynos on another server, you the player happen to know how dangerous it is to saunter into Queen Klicnik's lair and begin making rude gestures at her. Now, roleplaying true to form means that you will play this High-Elf in Qeynos without this knowledge. They have never been to Qeynos before, and have no clue who Queen Klicnik is, much less how quickly they would become her dinner should they do anything so foolish as to saunter into Queen Klicnik's lair and make rude gestures at her. </P>  <P>The point here is that a staunch roleplayer will recognize and play this limitation of their character - that of ignorance about this danger. But how do you do that in EQ? The simple fact the player has this knowledge affects character's behavior one way or another; be it that they deliberately avoid the lair, or you pointedly make them "accidentally" discover it somehow. You be the judge.</P>  <P>And if anyone thinks this is a spoiler, please chill out. The wise player will <I>always</I> use the "/con" (consider) feature before attacking <I>anything</I> unfamiliar, and since I didn't divulge the whereabouts of Klicnik's lair, I figure it's fair play. So there! </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>Hi there, just wanted to comment on your latest editorial. I agree one<BR>  hundred percent with everything you wrote, unfortunately I doubt you will<BR>  make any headway with combating this problem. My experience has been that<BR>  most players (Especially those new to roleplay) play themselves instead of a<BR>  character. Or not much better they play nonstandard characters which in a<BR>  strange way are generally more common than the ones roleplayed as they<BR>  should be. As an example, I met up with a Dark Elf the other day who was<BR>  very friendly towards halflings. Apparently his justification for this was<BR>  that he was raised by wood elves.</P>  <P>Now maybe he deserves credit for at least coming up with an IC<BR>  rationalization for his behavior, but it seems to me if I had a penny for<BR>  all the times I have seen this sort of explanation in a multiplayer rpg, I<BR>  could retire and play games all day long.</P>  <P>Players who follow the racial histories and roleplay attitudes properly are<BR>  the real exception, instead of the norm.</P>  <P>The only thing I have ever seen that has been halfway effective at combating<BR>  the above problem is enforced roleplay reading before allowing someone to<BR>  start a character, and given the target audience for this game I doubt that<BR>  would be very well taken.</P>  <P>Ah well, I have been having a great time on the pvp+ server. I don't think<BR>  the roleplay is any better there than on the other servers, but I have a<BR>  much more entertaining time playing the scared of everything Halfling, when<BR>  most of the kids playing there will attack anyone at the drop of the hat.<BR>  Must be something in the water.</P>  <P>Jeff/Miricas</P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  <P>Jeff makes another very good point here. It makes good fantasy fodder to have a character that breaks the mold of their race/class/faction. It enables one to play the nature-loving Ogre or the unbiased Dark Elf, both of which have risen above the fallacies of their fold, and rebelled into their own set of values. Fantasy/Sci-Fi authors have made thousands of dollars on novels starring such characters, and it makes for excellent reading. </P>  <P>The question is, does it have any place in EverQuest; a world where everyone can be anything they like? In this environment, the odd-man-out character suddenly ceases to be the exception, and becomes the rule. </P>  <P>I'm going to hold off answering that question, since it's an article unto itself. I'll simply foreshadow it by saying the question is a very poignant one. Congratulations, Jeff. You've impressed me. *g* </P>  <P>Here's a letter by an old acquaintance from the last article's reader responses. I think I'll pick this one apart in my usual fashion, as he brings up several issues... </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>Hey I just read your article at the vault and I thought it might be usefull<BR>  to point something out to you. Your main intent seems to be advocating that<BR>  we all roleplay our races as the world of Norrath would have us. I think<BR>  this is great and all but I thought I'd point out to you why this is so<BR>  unlikely. Im sure you've seen some of the polls on which race/class combos<BR>  are most popular. I can't remember which site it was but one of them very<BR>  clearly pointed out that all the numbers show people are picking their chars<BR>  based on CLASS and not race. This means that a large majority of players<BR>  are picking their race based on factors that have nothing to do with<BR>  roleplaying. </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>Whoa, hold the presses for a second. Assuming the poll is correct in saying people are choosing characters based on class and not race, how does this equate to a non-roleplaying decision? I think it's a very valid thing to say "I want to roleplay a bard instead of a warrior or mage," while deciding what kind of character you are going to play. It's a question rooted in a class-based decision, and I'd contend it's every bit as valid (perhaps even <I>more</I> so) than starting with a similar racial question. </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>Due to that fact most players get used to the idea of race<BR>  simply being that thing you picked so you could start where you wanted too<BR>  and play what class you wished to play. Once they get used to this they<BR>  assume most people did the same thing (and theya are right for the most<BR>  part). The end result is of course that most people will constantly under<BR>  roleplay race in game. </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>Okay, good point here. Race is directly influential on your point of origin, and this can hamper things greatly for a player who wants to play an Elf (who must start on Faydwer), but all his friends want to be Human or Halfling or some other set of races (who must start on Antonica). This fact will greatly affect a player's choice of race to play, not based on preference, but rather on game mechanics and the ability to group with your friends. Very true. </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>People who roleplay are just going to have to grow a<BR>  community and learn to ignore everyone else who dosn't "get it" as you put<BR>  it. I know for myself as a Bard I think more of my class than I do of my<BR>  race as a half-elf. Often I find myself making comments about infernal<BR>  spellcasters and their depedencay on their foolish mana or some such thing<BR>  as that but it's less often that I roleplay racial differences. I honestly<BR>  think the only good way to solve the problem would be to greatly broaden the<BR>  classes most races could play. </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>Well, that kind of throws a monkey-wrench into the way the designers have balanced the game. But hey, it is an issue, I'll grant that. </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>To sum it all up I'll give an example. I<BR>  myself am a casual roleplayer. I don't get a kick out of just "roleplaying"<BR>  I pick something I myself would want to do and roleplay in much the same way<BR>  I would act in real life. It's an escape that way and that's what I like.<BR>  Im sure you have no problem with this but it makes the games limitation<BR>  evident when you discover that my favorite race in all of Fantasy is the<BR>  elven race but my favorite type of class would be something closest to a<BR>  monk. You see my problem very quickly. I am limited in roleplaying<BR>  because I can not roleplay what I wish. In final I suspect I'll play a Monk<BR>  starting in freeport and immediatly move to faydark. I want to play with<BR>  other people to though so I certainly can't roleplay a racist human. So Im<BR>  limited in the ways I can roleplay that situation. Obviously there are ways<BR>  to roleplay it (I plan on being a tranquil monk preaching against bigotry)<BR>  but because those ways are limited only so many people can roleplay it<BR>  before it becomes so typical that its boring. Anyways I hate being the<BR>  devil's advocate but I hope I pointed out why its going to be difficult to<BR>  get people to play out their racial hatreds in game. It sucks that such is<BR>  the case but bitching about it to Verant prolly won't help we need to widen<BR>  our eyes and accept that other people don't want to roleplay and come up<BR>  with a solution to this problem. Maybe what we realy do need is a<BR>  roleplaying server. Not one where we restrict people but one where people<BR>  know to expect roleplaying and "get it" when it happens. Sure there will be<BR>  the party poopers but in the end its the innocent people who don't "get it"<BR>  that ruin immersivness. We can always put the jerks on ignore anyways. I<BR>  hope none of this seemed hostile or flamatory it was meant as a message from<BR>  one roleplayer to another on the problems we face in making a truly great<BR>  roleplaying exp.</P>  <P>Amaron </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  <P>Well, Amaron, you bring up several good points of contention about EverQuest's design. All I can say is that the massively multiplayer industry is still early in its infancy, and we have a long way to go before we find THE system. </P>  <P>Thanks for sharing your thoughts once again! </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>hi there, </P>  <P>Great Job on your Bigotry in the Roleplayer's World article!!!! i hope it's<BR>  going to permanently be part of the eqvault AND eqss.stratics, EVERYONE<BR>  should read that article so that they understand role-playing better, so eq<BR>  doesn't become a ROLL-playing game instead of a ROLE-playing game.</P>  <P>thanks again,<BR>  Dave Rahn </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  <P>Okay, so I'm not above resting on my laurels a <I>little! </P>  </I><P>This next one will, no doubt, be of interest to the EverQuest Express folk... </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>Hello. </P>  <P>Firstly, you have very complete thoughts, even when you are doing satire.<BR>  This ia a backward compliment, I guess. Every time during your article<BR>  when I was ready to pounce, you turned another good point.</P>  <P>So, good job. </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>Thank you! It means a lot to me as a writer to hear that kind of compliment! </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>Here is why I am writing. I am with the Vale Patrol, and wrote (what I<BR>  thought was) a humorous reply to the EQX's unapologetic (almost offended)<BR>  response. The nature of the letters was merely jokingly passed as a PC<BR>  police joke.</P>  <P>It also fell to us because of a little in-joke we've been passing around<BR>  on our message board called TSKS... or Troll Shadow-Knight Sydrome... or<BR>  what Freud would call Overcompensation for... you know...</P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>Hehehe... yeah, I think I've caught on. </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>As a result, we've been tossing some fairly jokey barbs at the biglings<BR>  just as you said... playing around with the idea.<BR>  I see the humor in the punnings of Wynn and Absor (and replied with some<BR>  of my own, to which Absor had NO SENSE OF HUMOR)... it was just a good<BR>  opportunity for us to thow a barb back...</P>  <P>Oh, well. </P>  <P>Back to your article: </P>  <P>I have the same thing with my role-playing S.O. , very good show. </P>  <P>But one thing about encouraging bigotry that I try to remember: </P>  <P>Evil can be very annoying. While some might call it role-play for several<BR>  of "Neriak's Finest" to protest goodly parties luring and killing their<BR>  bridge guard, it becomes... annoying. The roleplay leaves and the vale<BR>  drops and the dOOd5 get mad... </P>  <P>The reason I'm not of the mind to convince everyone to take it to the 9's<BR>  is becuase this is a public game... and not all/most of the public do it<BR>  well. Admit it, when you find a good party and a good adventure, and you<BR>  pop into town and everyone is acting the part it is awesome! But when you<BR>  are elsware and you spot a group of DE's running Kodoaks into newbies and<BR>  chanting we're #1... it's a touch of a drag.</P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>A <I>touch</I> of a drag? I'd go all the way and say it's downright infuriating! Of course, it could be argued that that's kind of the point, right? That's the reason evil is <I>evil</I>. </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>When you fuel the flames of bigotry, I fear the kinda sportsy<BR>  jock-attitude that REALLY does not work well in MMORPGs (I'm not geek, I<BR>  fight SCA, run, ex-hockeyplayer... but I know how to separate the two<BR>  worlds). So, yup. I liked your articles and OH MY GOD! I am so sorry I<BR>  wrote this much.</P>  <P>Keep up the good work an' stuff.<BR>  Hope to see you out there. </P>  <P>Litlegothe Bittenclaw<BR>  Warrior Marshal of the Vale Patrol, and proud.</P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  <P>I'll take your example of the annoyances of evil a step further, and cite my perennial Ultima Online thief once again. He stole the key to one particularly nasty guild's house. Did this enrage them? I'm sure it did. I, for one, would be chewing glass if someone did that to me after I'd labored weeks to attain such a thing. I'd be pissed off to no ends! As a player I'd expect myself to be gracious and return the key to them, but with that character? He'd sooner boil himself with Lord British's evening lobster! It was his prize trophy as a thief, and hence he'lI never did return the key. </P>  <P>Annoying? Certainly. But that's the way the game is played. Of course, that's an in-context example of an evil deed. There are plenty of out-of-context examples I'd say are foul play, like bug exploitation and the like. When you're all upset and angry with someone for wronging you in-game, it can be very difficult to separate the two. But in order for evil roleplaying to succeed, we victims have to do our best to do so. </P>  <P>As far as your problems with EQX a few issues back go, I'm going to have to take a neutral standpoint there. As you're about to see, I'm a big fan of that weekly newsletter, and any opinions I'd have to offer would be far too biased to be fair. *wink* </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>I just read and enjoyed your article on bigotry. I am in complete<BR>  agreement with you on the issue of in-game bigotry. <BR>  [...]</P>  <P>I enjoy your writing, and hope you continue :) </P>  <P>Oghma (Tdaven) </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>I just wanted to say that I loved your latest rant on Eqvault. But of<BR>  course with me it's like preaching to the choir.</P>  <P>Keep up the good work. You bring some class to EQV.</P>  <P>Absor </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P>---------- </P>  <P>Okay, okay... so spank me if I like resting on my laurels a <I>lot!</I> But in this case, I couldn't help toot my own horn. I've been an avid reader of </FONT><A HREF="http://eqx.simplenet.com/"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>EverQuest Express </FONT></A><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>articles since Issue 10 (almost as long as I've been reading EQ Vault), and words can't describe what it means to me to receive a "well-done" letter from very with-it writers such as these guys. I busted a gut at Oghma's </FONT><A HREF=" <a href="http://www.eqx.simplenet.com/Issue37/shake.htm">http://www.eqx.simplenet.com/Issue37/shake.htm</a>"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>How to Shake Up the EverQuest Community</FONT></A><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2> article more than once (you'll be receiving my medical bills soon, Oghma). And Absor simply knows his stuff and knows how to relate it well, as made apparent by his weekly editorials. Thanks, guys! You're awesome! </P>  <P>At long last, I will leave you with some excellent guidelines for creating a character to roleplay. This was submitted by a reader who obviously knows what he's talking about when it comes to character history and overall modus operandi. It makes for an easier time to roleplay your character, especially if you are new to roleplaying in general and are looking for some good tips. </P>  <P>So, I'll sign off here and once again give my heartfelt thanks to all of you who wrote in. You're the reason I do this, and I thank you for the letters of appreciation you've sent in return! </P>  <P>- &lt;Shadoe&gt; </P>  <P>---------- </P>  </FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#000080"><P>I posted this on the EQvault newsgroup earlier... I hope you can put it<BR>  to good use...</P>  <P>Here is my first version...</P>  <P>Questions to "ask" your character during creation:</P>  <P>1. What is your primary motivation?</P>  <P>Is it greed? Is it wanderlust? Is it devotion and a show of piety to<BR>  your religion? Is it something much more complex, like a rogue who<BR>  steals money, not only due to greed, but also because his family depends<BR>  on his "extra" salary to keep themselves above the poverty level?</P>  <P>2. How "old" of a character are you going to play?</P>  <P>Most people assume that just because your skills and level are low that<BR>  your character is not quite mature and hasn't seen the world. This<BR>  doesn't have to be true. Your character could be the frustrated<BR>  housewife that lived with an abusive husband for ten years before<BR>  deciding that she is better off travelling about; making the world<BR>  respond to her needs. It could be the ancient dwarf who decides that a<BR>  return to action may be warranted; he discovers to his horror that the<BR>  years have taken a toll on him, he learns that he forgot many of his<BR>  adventuring skills andhas to start anew. Or, you can play the<BR>  stereotypical wideeyed young whelp, out in the dangerous world for the<BR>  first time.</P>  <P>3. How would I respond to certain situations?</P>  <P>Is your character a loudmouthed, unwholesomely brash warrior that makes<BR>  passes at just about anything of the oposite sex, even during battle<BR>  conditions? Are you a necromancer who is more comfortable talking the<BR>  undead than the living? Maybe you are the famous warrior monk,<BR>  Musashibo Benkei, who challenges every samurai that comes around to a<BR>  fight (and kicks their butts). Maybe you are the serene cleric who<BR>  doesn't even blink when a twenty five foot tall cyclops attempts to<BR>  smear your entire party into fish paste.</P>  <P>4. Who would I be likely to associate with?</P>  <P>Would you be that willing to stay with a shadow knight in your party if<BR>  you were a paladin? Can you put up with that ranger that keeps on<BR>  telling you that having a sacred bear head over your fireplace mantle is</P>  <P>not cool? Can you resist taking that halfling companion and taking a<BR>  nice chomp out of his side, Mr. Troll?

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
