<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">The Metro Mentality</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Sayeed  (<a href="mailto:yu219121@yorku.ca" class="credit2">yu219121@yorku.ca</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Hailhail,<br><br>Recently, Online Role Playing Game fans have heard a lot about how gigantic the new worlds of Online Role Playing Games will be. In light of this fact, it seems reasonable to some that permanent portals or other permanent "mass transport" systems will be beneficial to the ORPG experience. The purpose of this article is to take a look at what "Mass Transit" systems do and the problems which they might create.<br><br>The argument in favor of Mass Transit is that if a world takes hours to cross (many hours of character running is the claim of some), then a character who desires to, for example, meet his friends in another city, might be out of luck. Also, if there is something taking place on one side of the world, ie- a war, then players across the world who wish to also take part may not reach the appointed location in time. I call this, the feeling of players that they should be able to immediately attend events occurring across the world on time, easily meet friends in far places, or quickly reach a dungeon (or some other place) they wish to adventure in, the "Subway/Metro Mentality." It is the same reason why people use the Metro/Subway. Someone has a job or activity to do, in a certain place, and needs a method of transportation to zip over there and do it, then zip to another place to do something else, very quickly. Granted there will be some walking at the Subway Terminals and from them to the destination, but the majority of the journey is carried out almost instantaneously by use of the Subway. At first glance, this seems completely beneficial. Beneficial to what? As we are discussing ORPGs, Role Playing is the key issue here. Therefore, the question becomes, "Are Mass Transit Systems beneficial or harmful to Role Playing?"<br><br>The benefits of Mass Transit are greatly obvious. Characters who have an "appointment" to Role Play with some friends can quickly go to whichever dungeon/castle/etc. their friends happen to be in and Role Play, without the long journey in between. Afterwards, they can go wherever else they wish to go and Role Play some more. This seems completely advantageous; yet as most of us know, there ARE a few problems.<br><br>One problem relates to "Region History" (or call it storyline). For a complete Online Role Playing experience in a persistent world, it is important for regions in ORPGs to develop histories involving players. What exactly is a history in an ORPG? The history of a location is made up of the people who lived there, and what they did. Certainly, the PLACE has a little to do with it, but only where it interacts with people. Otherwise very little could be said of it. "Yeah, that mountain has been, hmmm, has been standing there for quite some time, it's very, uh, old. Hmmmmm. It has an icecap in the winter you know." If we look at history, we notice that generally the history of a location includes people who lived there for some period of time and responded to other people in the area. Here emerges the first problem caused by "Mass Transit" in an ORPG. In an ORPG World, there are no customs barriers or citizenship problems to keep people in one region, therefore if Mass Transit exists, then many different people race constantly across the world, and few call any place home for any period of time. Even a guild hall or other residence building will only be a starting point, and sometimes even they are built right next to a Mass Transit entrance. If people do choose a place to call home, it is seldom more than an origin point from which to jump around the world. When characters have no "homeland," then the history of a place will not be kept by its "people," for there won't BE many people who call that place home. Also, most of the events which make up its history will involve outsiders who were just passing through. This doesn't seem like a problem when first considered, yet look at a practical example. Before I learned magic in UO (yes, I know some people are getting sick of UO comparisons, but they apply), I was a Tamer, and I didn't know the moongate schedule. Consequently, I pretty much lived around the crossroads west of the pass west of Britain. This place was a dangerous area, and living there or in the general area for a while, I eventually got to know the heroes and villains of the crossroads. I could tell you the stories of the devious Dr. Deth and his murderous blockade gangs, or the saga of the guilds who eventually banded to fight them off. I could tell you of Baldo the Magician or Autumner the Evil or any number of people who frequented the crossroads. I could also list the Three Great Battles of the Crossroads, what happened, how they turned out, and what part I played in them. Roleplaying this, I was an old-timer of the area and told passersby of its history, and had a lot of fun interacting with others who traversed the area and lived near me. Sure, I went on hikes, and visited other places, yet because I didn't know much about the mass transport techniques, I pretty much always came back to my home. Overall, it was thoroughly enjoyable.<br><br>Another problem Mass Transit creates is what is commonly known as World-Shrinkage. When there are teleporters in a world which eliminate traveling time, then people's opinions of a world will eventually start to change. Instead of being a gigantic and exciting new continent, in their mind the world will suddenly shrink to the land surrounding the teleporters used by the character. Changing one's residence, trekking to a different part of the world, or visiting a dangerous area will no longer be epic adventures, but instead merely a few "hops" on the local Mass Transit system. Pretty soon there will be people who want more landmass, when they've barely seen the land which already exists!<br><br>A third problem is server load. True, mechanics should be secondary and if we can, we should concentrate on what players would like to be able to do, but when servers are overloaded, what we'd LIKE to do shrinks to "I'd just like to be able to walk a few steps without server lag, Thank You." The problem here has to do with advertised events, places, or even people. When a popular website announces some interesting part of the RPG experience, all of a sudden many people immediately respond, and if a date is preset for a certain event, hundreds of people might quickly drop by to see what's going on, overloading the server and ruining the event.<br><br>How Mass Transit affects the Suspension of Disbelief, which is required for properly enjoying any RPG, is another difficulty. Travelling large distances in milliseconds just doesn't help suspend anyone's disbelief that they are in a REAL world, with believable dimensions. Also, when a player becomes used to the magic involved in jumping from city to city, other magics start to seem more common and a Great Wizard conjuring up a portal to transport himself thousands of miles home starts to seem rather mundane.<br><br>Role Playing. Yes, Mass Transit does have a direct negative affect on the amount of Role Playing in an ORPG. It has to do with the many people a player meets when he's travelling from place to place on foot, or on horseback. In some Role Playing Games, side quests which reveal themselves while a character is on his journey to complete the main quest are very engaging, and provide much entertainment until the character finishes them and continues on his way. This is what great stories are made of. The journey is part of the drama, and if that part is cut out then it is equivalent to having the dramatic question posed on one page of a novel and the climax transpiring on the next. Assuming Role Playing will catch on, a very large part of the enjoyment of online games will come from the long journeys taken by different parties. Just the quest to meet up with a companion in a different area can take on a sinister (and exciting!) meaning if the trek involves journeying across a deadly vermin infested jungle! Interfering with the Epic Journeys of characters may indeed be a grave folly of ORPGs.<br><br>There are a lot of problems Mass Transit causes, but there are also problems with NOT having it. Two notable problems raised by Mass Transit fans are boredom and boredom, and both these problems and their solutions are, as you might have guessed, related.<br><br>The first boredom has to do with the adventure and passion involved in clicking a mouse. Traveling those long distances no doubt requires a fair portion of that, and all the benefits of not having Mass Transit may be negated by that one giant problem. Travel automation and being able to talk/Role Play with friends while the automation occurs is a solution, but not for extremely long journeys. The second boredom has to do with repetition. When a party has already traversed the Dastardly Jungle of Aruykhan twice, what then? Luckily, there are workarounds that deal with both issues. The most important of these is VARIETY. If a party walks from one city to another, and sees only trees, they may get bored. If a party walks from one city to another, and sees only trees and monsters, they may get bored. If a party, however, walks from one city to another, and sees trees, monsters, hidden caves, dungeons, beautifully rendered landscapes, traps, a tribe of roleplaying PC Wild-Men, the lost city of Aruynien containing the fabled jeweled Trident, an eagle swooping down on its prey, an approaching army about to invade the city they are traveling to, another party on a quest to save that same city, and a partridge in a pear tree, then it is likely that the party may not be so bored after all. VARIETY. It cannot be stressed enough how important Variety is. A world five hundred miles long and a thousand miles wide can still be boring if it is empty of all Variety except for a few scattered dungeons and some respawning monsters. A large part of Variety, assuredly, is up to the Role Playing of other players, yet rich material to work with must be provided to them and that is the job of the game designers. They must create an exciting world with much to do in between journeys, and many different paths to take to a destination once the first is explored.<br><br>The second workaround to boredom is guess what? That's right, it's VARIETY. This time, however, it is solely the variety of the player. If you've been through the Dastardly Jungle of Aruykhan to get to a city already, why not take a party this time? If you took a party last time, why not go directly through the Aruy Wild-Men camp this time? If you did that last time, why not take a totally different route, and try using the Archae Ravine as a shortcut to your destination? Most of all, why not try talking to the people you meet along the way this time, and perhaps join THEIR party and help them on THEIR quest instead of trekking through this same forest to kill the same monsters in the same dungeon as before? In the end it is our own Role Playing which will keep us interested the longest.<br><br>In conclusion, I've given you some of the advantages and disadvantages of "Mass Transit" in Online RPG's. Read through them, and all you "Metro Mentality" supporters might find out that HOW you get somewhere is sometimes just as important as WHAT you do when you're there.<br><br>'Til,<br><br>'Sayeed<br><br>AUTHOR'S OPINIONS<br><br>I hope you enjoyed or learned something from this article, now let me tell you what sort of "Mass Transit" system I personally prefer. Keep in mind that these are only my own preferences, not what is "Right" or "Wrong," but what suits ME, and may not be fact, and so you may not wish to read past this point.<br><br>As you've probably guessed, I prefer a minimum of Mass Transit in ORPGs. I understand that the upcoming ORPG worlds will be huge, but I believe that if we all stick to Role Playing properly, then each new person we meet, and every new encounter we face, will be thoroughly enjoyable. Even if it is just meeting a good Role Playing Mercenary going the opposite direction on the same road in our travels, we will be provided with new history and connections for our characters, and an engaging and entertaining Role Playing experience. <br><br>I WANT it to be hard and a long journey to meet some friends. I WANT it to be a great task to see that fabled jungle I talked so much about. I WANT it to be difficult for people to locate the nearest castle, rescue the maiden held within, and bring her safely home, and throughout my travels I want to have fun Role Playing them. Will the Great Adventure Stories of Mass Transit ORPGs be only, "He found his wife was kidnapped, jumped into the teleporter, rode up to the Dread Lord Normord's castle, killed him, found his wife, then rode back to the teleporter and got home in time for supper."? I certainly HOPE not. Do not forget, however, that players continually Role Playing is an extremely important part of keeping adventures interesting. A company which produces an ORPG cannot itself provide Role Playing Variety lasting hours upon hours. They have other things to do and other people to entertain as well, but as players, we certainly CAN do this.<br><br>However, there IS some Mass Transit which I feel is valuable to a game, and that is higher level Mage Teleportation. I think it's important for a POWERFUL mage to be able to transport himself and others long distances, in the blink of an eye. This I feel adds to the mysterious atmosphere of mages, which is so important to their profession, and will therefore add to the atmosphere of any Role Playing Game.<br><br>In the end, the enjoyment we get out of a Role Playing Game will be decided by how good are its Role Playing Gamers, so let's ROLE PLAY!<br><br>(I think I should repeat that last line a few more times, don't you?)<br><br>I welcome constructive criticisms and comments.<br><br>'Til,<br><br>'Sayeed.

