<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
I often see people posting up what their version of Role-playing is, and compare it to my own. I wonder how the writer really plays their characters, and if there is a point where they abandon the character concept to advance the character in other ways, as I do on occasion. Where is it that the line between power-gaming and role-playing gets blurred, and when is it that it no longer becomes fun? Where does a strict adherence to a role become annoying or pointless, or even a soapbox where a role-player commits the sin of the attitude "I am the high priest of role-playing, come worship at my altar", and becomes an insufferable bore? Sometimes my fellow role-players really turn me off.<br><br>When I create a role, I do consider the game mechanics and if there is a class/race combination that would be powerful, and sometimes I try to create a role around it. If my feel for the character is not strong, however, I find that the powergame aspects of the character tend to dominate my thinking, and I wind up playing a "elf mage" or "ogre warrior" and not Crunch, the ogre or Ealwyn, the elf. My feel for the character's advancement is stronger than my feel for the character's persona. I enjoy powergaming the character, but what does s/he do after I have reached the highest level?<br><br>What about the character concept of an individual who "starts out" at a high level of acheivement? We've all created a mysterious character who comes out of nowhere and dominates the surrounding populace, but no game gives us a beginning powerful character. Perhaps in Everquest we can be one of those rare individuals that goes from one server to another, and powergame up to a decent level and switch servers. But again, that's power gaming and not role-playing. Let's get to what role-playing does.<br><br>If I do have a decent concept for a character, I find that helpful in defining my actions in a game world. One of my favorite characters in AD&D was an elf fighter whose love of freedom and distaste for restriction had him wearing only leather armor. All the other fighters in the party were bulking up with banded and plate mail, and off goes Amlaith, treading lightly in his leather armor and wielding a spear. Yes, a spear. A weapon which does only 1-6 points of damage, when I had plenty of other weapons to choose from which did more damage than that. The in-game restrictions I put on that character were rough to deal with in many ways. He got hit more, and did less damage than the other fighters around him, but once he reached a decent level, and got some magical leather armor, he turned out to be a wonderful character to run. As long as he stayed in that light armor, he was Amlaith. <br><br>That one decision, staying with light armor, wound up defining that character's temperament more than anything else I had conceived for him. His distaste for restrictions made him a proud elf that wouldn't ask others for help, since he did not want to be obligated. I decided to make him a taciturn individual, who would not use two words where one could do, and thus when he spoke, it was pretty important. Everyone listened. He had little patience for fools, and would outrage the party when he wouldn't kiss up to some palace guard or lackey who was limiting access to something he felt was needed. He told them off, and the poor band of adventurers would have to placate the "arrogant fool" who Amlaith just told off. In two words or less.<br><br>I guess this means that for me to have a character, which is viable and realistic, there has to be some point where maximizing the character takes second place to who that character is. If I have a character who hates elves, he will hate elves, even if there is an elf who will give him a magic sword. He will have a hard time swallowing his distaste for that individual, just because he is an elf. It hurts him in-game to lose that magic sword, but my character would not be able to deal with receiving it from an elf. At some level, his hatred of elves defines that character so much that he will lose out because of it. This is why characters in fantasy novels often capture our imagination. We know what we would do in those situations, and we watch as the character makes the same mistakes, and finally cheer when s/he overcomes that obstacle.<br><br>Isn't that true of who we are? Don't we all have some way of behaving that gets in our way, yet we continue to do it, again and again. All our friends know it, and some are close enough to tell us about it, yet we still persist in doing it. It is only when we attain a deeper understanding of ourselves that we are able to move past it. That spiritual step of self-enlightenment, if you will, that makes us a better person. Or at least one step easier to deal with :) .<br><br>My love of a character comes from just that, the obstacles that the character has overcome. Whether they are in-game obstacles, or obstacles that I have created to challenge myself, those obstacles are what give me pride in my character's accomplishments. As I take pride in personal obstacles that I overcome, so I take pride in a characters' personal triumphs.<br><br>I guess role-playing, for me, means writing a story with my characters actions that I would be proud to tell. A story where there are obstacles to overcome, whether personal or from the environment, and my character triumphs, despite adversity. Whether it includes powergaming, or roleplaying, or something in between.<br><br>- Oghma

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem920448000,27068,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Player Killing: Have You Ruined Someone's Day?</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Lou Capuano  (<a href="mailto:GoingNova@banet.net" class="credit2">GoingNova@banet.net</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
As an avid role player, I can see the initial thought of fighting against other players as adding spice and flavor to the gaming experience. The image of traveling on a road, between towns with a friend, and getting waylaid by four or five bandits, as we fight for survival sounds exciting. The battle goes on, as we fight for our possessions, and life. Sometimes, we manage to defeat our attackers, causing them to flee, other times they prove too much, and we fall victim to the scoundrels, losing both our lives and possessions. <br><br>This somewhat romantic view of Player Killing, if it existed, would indeed add spice and flavor to a game. However, what is more often the case is that while you are attacking a monster with half your hit points gone or as a newbie you are attacked by a gang of Pkers. The problem generally is the player getting attacked has almost no chance of survival at all, often never getting the chance to defend him/herself. Pkers keep the average player, and especially the new player, watching himself like an animal in a forest filled with crazed hunters! This takes away from the enjoyment of what the game itself actually has to offer. <br><br>I know that the player is only playing a game, but have you ever stopped and thought about the time spent playing this game? The eight hours spent on a day off, or the four hours after a hard days work? Does anyone ever think about the fact that some of us play this game as an escape from the real world, and use it to unwind and have FUN at the end of a hard days work? What fun is it to spend 2 hours exploring in a dungeon, only to be killed either when you exit or as you are attacking a monster? Where is the fun in that? What flavor are you adding to the player who you are robbing of two hours of REAL TIME? It's like scrimping and saving for a new car, only to have some cretin key it in a parking lot at the mall! <br><br>The majority of player killers are cowards. They have no desire to "Role-play" a villain, they are just lazy, and chose the easier way of earning money and experience: they pray on those weaker then themselves. They often hunt in packs, and slaughter their pray, with little or no danger to themselves. As soon as any real danger to them is mounted (for example, a group of experienced high level characters goes on a PK hunt), they run like rabbits from a fox. They usually devote hundreds of hours a month to a game, and therefore are very high level. I do not have hundreds of hours a month to spare, should I be punished for this? At point is also somewhat of a moral issue. I understand that we are talking about a game, but when a person is PKed, they often become very upset. They have worked hard to gain their possessions, and to lose them all in a moment can be devastating. These emotions, these feelings are real! How many people try these online games once or twice, only to be discouraged and never play again. What kind of person gets ENJOYMENT from other peoples misery? Have we become so callous that we can simply say "Well, too bad, if you can't defend yourself don't play!"? Is this fair??? <br><br>I am ECSTATIC over Sony's decision to include a PvP switch on EverQuest. It will allow those of you who enjoy being hunted and hunting other players the freedom to do so, and hey, more power to you! Knock yourselves out! But, more importantly, it will allow those who welcome the chance to play an online game, without having to worry about being harassed by some teenager on summer vacation, who is angry because he just got grounded by his mom, and is out to vent his frustrations on the world, especially ADULTS, the opportunity to do so. I have my own frustrations thank you, and I would prefer to vent them on the game, not someone else! I welcome any and all comments at: GoingNova@banet.net. I respect everyone's view, so I ask that you only send RESPECTFUL replies (meaning, no name calling and or cursing). You do not have to agree with what I say, but please respect my opinion. <br><br>-Lou Capuano 

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem920448000,59884,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">PowerGaming and Role Playing</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Sayeed  (<a href="mailto:zaidsayeed@hotmail.com" class="credit2">zaidsayeed@hotmail.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Hailhail,<br><br>Possibly the most ferocious debate in the Online RPG community relates to PowerGaming and Role Playing. These two juxtaposed factions appear to be the antithesis of one another, and so their supporters' virulent flaming contests litter the message boards of Online Role Playing Game (ORPG) fan sites, each faction attempting to completely disprove and therefore annihilate it's "opponent." As in most cases, however, the two sides are not, in actuality, opposites, and indeed one would be devalued considerably without the other. The purpose of this article is to show how PowerGaming affects ORPG's and how Role Players may associate with purist PowerGamers.<br><br>The true ORPG, whether set in a Medieval, Contemporary, or Futuristic setting, is designed for a very clear purpose. To transport players into an exciting new world, allow them to change and progress in that world, and allow them to enjoy simulated adventures there which they are not able to experience in Real Life. In short, ORPG's are designed to give players a new life. Whether modeled after famous characters in novels, or created from their own deeply hidden desires, players develop new personas whose decisions and ambitions they fully control. This is where PowerGaming, "Gaming for Power," is an important part in the character development of most Role Players. <br><br>To understand this, one must first comprehend the phrase "Gaming for Power." In a Medieval world, "Power" might come in the form of gold, magical ability, melee weapon skill, missile weapon skill, or any other article which provides influence over other players. Therefore, PowerGaming in a Medieval world would mean "Gaming for articles which provide influence over other players." According to certain Role Playing Guru's, this philosophy is inappropriate and misplaced in a Role Playing setting. Those gurus are, in a sense, correct, yet at the same time they are also very incorrect. To illustrate this, let us examine a common Role which one might adopt in a Role Playing setting, a mage, or more specifically, one called Raistlin.<br><br>The Avatar of mages, DragonLance's Raistlin embodies many virtues which a large proportion of magic users see as sacred and universal for nearly all becoming Sorcerors. What is Raistlin's most prevalent attribute? An insatiable lust for power, power which gives him influence not granted to him by his physique. Let us take another famous character, Shannara's Garet Jax. An honorable brigand, Garet Jax takes great pride in his skill with a deadly pike, which gives him a great amount of influence over others. Now let us examine a different character type, Tolkien's Gandalf, and you will most certainly note that Gandalf's maniacal drive for power is definitely not one of his defining characteristics. Gandalf, though, is unique in the important fact that, throughout most of the Lord of the Rings, he is the most dangerous living thing on Middle Earth excepting the Dark Lord. If we were to look back at a younger Gandalf, however, one which perhaps was not so well versed in the methods of wizardry, we might find that he did have some concern for advancement and progress in terms of magic power. In the Lord of the Rings, Tolkien makes it a point to express exactly how able a magician the worthy Gandalf actually is. Altogether, we might also discover that, by and large, almost all fantasy authors make it a point to focus on the traits of their main characters which give them influence over others. How do those characters achieve such admirable levels? By working hard, by striving to progress in those oh so influential domains, in essence, by "PowerGaming." Thus, with such prominent supporters of PowerGaming, even the most avid Role Playing guru must allocate some PowerGaming motivations to almost all their characters. We are all PowerGamers. (excepting very few)<br><br>Despite this prominent fact, there is still discord among the aforementioned factions of ORPG Gamers, and only a fool would label that conflict as wholly arbitrary. Actually, the basis of ill-sentiment among these Gamers is not concerning the existence of PowerGaming, but instead the extent of its pervasiveness in ORPGs. Simply put, a "good" PowerGamer is one who blends his/her search for influence with Role Playing, while a "bad" PowerGamer is one who reasons out the best methods to gain power, in or out of context with the rest of the world, and works wholeheartedly to do so and reach a "maximum" level of power. To the "bad" PowerGamer, immersing himself in the world is not seen as beneficial to the pursuit of power, and so he speaks and acts in terms of stats, hint books, web sites, cheats, etc., terms completely out of context with the game world and a mundane interruption to Role Players who attempt to immerse themselves in a fantasy environment.<br><br>There are many reasons why PowerGamers do this. Gamers who have no experience with pen'n'paper or any other forms of Role Playing may not know how exactly to properly Role Play, and so instead play ORPG's as they play any other game, Quake for instance. In that case, unfortunately, they also do not realize the joy of truly existing within another world, and the lasting entertainment provided by it. Other PowerGamers might just be bowing to Peer Pressure, for when a good Real Life or online friend brightly greets you with a "Hey Ma' Man, Duud, Wassup'?!?!", it may be hard to stay in character. Also, when a newbie asks what he should click to get his stats, a good player, Role Player or not, feels inclined to help him, even if the newbie didn't add "OOC:" (Out Of Character) before his text. Being out of character is contagious, and when other members of a party catch it, it is difficult for the group to get in character once again. Alternatively, a player may PowerGame because he feels that, even in a world designed for it, Role Playing takes too much effort, or is less fun that just playing as he would in a non-RPG.<br><br>The solution? Too often, "pure" PowerGamers do not have the will or the desire to advance to Role Playing enjoyment, yet for cases in which they do have it, it is entirely possible for them to learn. There is only one solution which will turn "bad" PowerGamers into "good" PowerGamers, and that solution is "In Context Diversification."<br><br>The difference between the types of PowerGamers is that the "good" PowerGamer diversifies himself, not purely searching for power, but involving himself in the in context social aspects of ORPG's as well. Shallow characters with only one focus, in books, in RL, or in ORPG's, are always boring. Dull for those associated with them and dull for themselves, compared with the appeal of a character with a range of motivations and attributes. Raistlin Majere not only lusted for power, but also felt deep jealousy for his brother, scorn for those less intelligent than him, a tinge of longing for trust and love, an unpleasant obligation to those he felt he "owed," pity and care for the weak and forsaken, and many other traits which gave him a deep and interesting personality. PowerGamers who similarly diversify will find their ORPG experience considerably more rewarding for themselves and also for those around them.<br><br>Unfortunately, Role Playing Gamers do not always find themselves surrounded by well-meaning PowerGamers ready to learn how to Role Play. More often, they come across those who either have no inclination to learn or whose sole desire is to interrupt the Role Playing of others. In addition, out of character arguments about the benefits of Role Playing may do more harm than good if they are done in game. When either in or out of character, Gamers teach best by example. For those Gamers who do not which to be disrupted by the bad examples, people who do not Roleplay or have no regard for its needs, luckily there are many appropriate responses.<br><br>The most important of these responses is Role Playing. If faced with "SER kOOl MACHO DuuDLEy" who asks "WassUP G?" the best response is to stay in character and Role Play. How does one Role Play in this situation? It depends entirely on the personality of the character you have created. An understanding Paladin might respond "Pardon me, Sir, I do not understand your dialect." A self-serving merchant (and FED UP Role Player) might blurt out "I have not time for fools, do not plague me!" (or a less harsh response to prevent ill will) A sarcastic thief might just ignore the player. As long as a player keeps in character, and Role Plays, there is no "wrong" option. Breaking character, however, would be the worst thing one could do. Once a Role Player loses his character, it is very hard to go back. If the purpose of playing Online Role Playing Games is to Role Play, then breaking character is the only way to lose the game. Therefore, if bothered by pure PowerGamers, either the SER kOOl MACHO DuuDLEy variety or even by someone who is just having a conversation about his new PII 450 with some friends, the automatic and best reaction of Role Players should be to keep in character and not abandon game immersion. The best response is to ROLE PLAY.<br><br>Yet what to do if SER DuuDLEy is persistant? If conversation among OOC friends does not end, and they use the ORPG world as an "IRC world" where they also get power and kill things? Simple, AVOID NON-ROLE PLAYERS. If you meet them, stay in character. If Role Playing when talking to them does not prove contagious, leave. If you have friends who pure PowerGame, then message them outside the game, asking them to Role Play when they talk to you. If SER DuuDLEy persists in following and annoying you? Create a macro, or a standard response to non-Role Playing. "I do not understand, you speak strangely" for example. (Some people might advocate "OOC: I Role Play." or responding with "OOC:" to newbie queries about interface, that's up to you.) Repeat the response continuously if their questions or comments cannot be understood in a game world context, or if they speak in too unconventional a style to be believably in context. Very important, for those Role Players who constantly complain about being hassled by rude players, or players who follow them, USE THE IGNORE FEATURES INCLUDED IN THE GAME. That is why it's there (Again, if it comes to this, then players might want to "OOC: Ignore list being used." And yes, UO has an ignore feature, and I suspect EQ, AC, ME and AP will all have ignore features. Hopefully, we can trust ORPG companies to prevent the ignore feature from filtering Spell Words, so reaction time to spellcasting is not decreased).<br><br>In conclusion, PowerGaming is an essential part of Role Playing, yet it can be taken too far. In the event that it is, there are many ways to respond to it, the most important of which is to STAY IN CHARACTER. If we, the ORPG Gaming Community, put a fraction of the effort into Role Playing ORPGs as the development teams of those games are putting in making them, then the rewards in enjoyment we will reap as we wander in fantastic and immersive worlds will be many times the work we have invested.<br><br>'Til,<br><br>'Sayeed.<br><br>AUTHOR'S OPINIONS<br><br>I hope you enjoyed or learned something from this article, now let me tell you my opinions on Role Playing and Power Gaming, which you have probably already guessed. Keep in mind that these are only my own preferences, not what is "Right" or "Wrong," but what suits ME, and may not be fact, so you may not wish to read past this point.<br><br>As you've probably guessed, I think there's little benefit to pure PowerGaming. Pure PowerGamers do not realize how enjoyable Role Playing is and so aren't getting the whole ORPG experience, and in the process of their "Quaking" they disturb the experience of other Role Players. This does not have to be caused by Murderers (PK's), and can be caused by only their conversations. It is almost impossible for pure PowerGamers to affect only themselves, for they will undoubtedly affect others. Even if a small group of players converses out of character, then those who wander by them will hear their conversation, and "suspension of disbelief" will be stretched to the limit. Role Playing and pure PowerGaming are two very contagious organisms, fighting for our support, so if pure PowerGamers are heard by others, then those others might break character, or think it is appropriate to do so, and this will catch, spread, and possibly be reinforced by other pure PowerGamers until new arrivals in the world automatically think Role Playing is not appropriate in it. Yes, we all have the example of UO to learn from (I learned a lot), no matter how much we do not want to hear about it. However, though I may be wrong, it seems like Role Playing is securing a foothold and spreading even in UO, so perhaps we can hope for better things and think more kindly of it. <br><br>I, like most Role Players, dream of a Graphic Role Playing environment, and look forward to the enjoyment I will have when such environments comes to fruition, hopefully reflecting the thrill of pen'n'paper Role Playing Games. Whether it be in Asheron's Call, EverQuest, Middle Earth, the Awakening Project, (an exciting and revolutionary ORPG project taking shape at www.dtcomputers.com/awaken) or some other graphical MUD, I know that when Gamers build this atmosphere, enjoyment will come. And yes, I say the Gamers will build it, because in the end, no matter how much effort developers go to, it is ultimately the choice of Gamers whether the world will be another Quake or a true RPG. Personally, I would love for developers to force people to Role Play and create a more enjoyable world for all, but (unfortunately in my opinion) Role Playing is not something that can be forced, and comes only from willing players.<br><br>Something I've been thinking about lately. Trends are important, and they should be set properly. When we Beta Test, it is largely pure PowerGaming. Is this a bug? Will this work? Will this paradox reveal a bug when I create it? How powerful should I be to complete this? Should this weapon be upgraded? How fast did I advance today? When the Beta Test is over, however, the final world will start fresh and new, and in my humble opinion, the PowerGaming Beta Test, in most senses, should be completely forgotten. "Oh, I was here during the Beta test." should be completely wiped from the minds of players, or at very least they should Role Play it well. Personally, if I could mix Role Playing with pure Beta PowerGaming, then I would, just to set a trend for the world, because trends stick and Beta Testers will have importance in the final world. Forming good habits is helpful.<br><br>I'll leave you with this&#8230; ROLE PLAY. STAY IN CHARACTER&#8230; DO NOT BREAK CHARACTER! No, I do not think I've said this enough times yet, and will probably continue to say it and possibly write more about Role Playing. You CANNOT Role Play too much. When you're by yourself in the Dastardly Jungle of Aruykhan, surrounded only by NPC Wild Men and trees, you should CONTINUE TO ROLE PLAY. This is for your own enjoyment, but also for the player crawling out of the pit of the Aruynien Dungeon, who, stumbling across you, may hear your character lapse. Role Playing is HABIT FORMING, it isn't hard to pick it up, and it gets easier as you learn more about your character, a learning experience which is thoroughly enjoyable. Yes, even when you're alone it is important. <br><br>To conclude, let me tell you of my brother. It may illustrate my point more clearly. <br><br>***<br><br>I was waiting for the bus to arrive one day in the town in which I lived, Awali, with my brother. While we were waiting, my brother drank a can of Coke, then threw it down into the sand.<br><br>"It's just one can." He said.<br><br>"Don't do that!" I cried, "It's littering! If others see it, they'll copy you and then the whole damn island will be littered." So my brother kicked the hot desert sands over the can of Coke until only a small bump in the sand betrayed its presence. No one was around to see him do it.<br><br>"If no one can see it, no one will copy me." He said.<br><br>I thought about that for a while, stumped, until the bus was approaching, when I realized my brother's mistake.<br><br>"But if you say that, so will they, and if everyone can use that same logic, then-" I wasn't allowed to finish, for the clamorous bus had arrived, and we both got on board and prepared for the 30 minute ride, in 40 degree heat, to school. <br><br>***<br><br>In the end, the enjoyment we get out of a Role Playing Game will be decided by how good are its Role Playing Gamers, so let's ROLE PLAY! (all the time)<br><br>(I'm going to keep saying that until I hypnotise every RPGer in the world)<br><br>'Til,<br><br>'Sayeed

<!-- End Content -->
</SPAN>
<a name="newsitem919670400,73018,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Bigotry in the Roleplayer's World</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Shadoe  (<a href="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
I guess you could say this is a rant of mine I've been keeping bottled up since Phase 4 began, but a couple of things have happened recently that have inspired me to speak up about it.  Yes, friends, today's topic is bigotry and why it's so hard to obtain in EverQuest, even though the whole EQ faction system revolves around it (more or less).  <P>  What sparked this topic off for me were a couple of letters published in this week's <A HREF="http://eqx.simplenet.com">EverQuest Express</A>.  These letters were written in response to last week's Q&A article compiled by Wynn, where he satirizes the disadvantages of playing a halfling character.  Here's what he said...  <P>  ----------  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  Q: What are the disadvantages of being a halfling? <BR>  A: Although not widely known, halflings have many problems that they would rather not be  made public. You may notice the unsightly hair covering the tops of their wide, flat feet. Not  only repulsive to their females, some poor halflings have a disease called Hyperpedofoliclia.  This results in excessive hair growth on the feet. So much, in fact, that unless regularly trimmed,  it can overwhelm the feet and legs of the halfling, causing repeated tripping and falling on one's  face. If that wasn't bad enough, the hair patches so close to the ground are the preferred latching  point for many varieties of ticks and fleas. You may notice halfling PCs or NPCs doing the  Rivervale Shuffle, where it looks like they are bouncing side-to-side or running like crazed  madmen around in circles. This is their way of trying to fling the wretched insects off their  abnormal feet. So rest assured, halflings are not just cute little forest creatures. If you think lyme  disease is bad, just imagine what you could catch from a halfling.  </FONT>  <P>  ---------  <P>  You can take Wynn's flippant attitude for whatever you think it's worth, or you can take it in the spirit it was given.  That is, of course, the prerogative of any reader.  I, personally, thought it was an imaginative quip and it brought the customary grin to my face I get whenever I read Wynn's material.  <P>  Here are the letters posted in this week's issue regarding that Q&A snippet, and the editor's response...  <P>  ----------  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  I would like to say I found you QnA section in EQ Express 61 rather disturbing. Your answer to  the question about this disadvantages of halflings was not even close to helpful and was closer  to very rude. I'm not sure why but you totally shot way out there and severly slandered halflings.  I bet if this was a question about humans or elves you would not have been so harsh. Lastly i  wouls like to say that halflings are very proud of thier foot hair and we suffer no side affects  mentioned in this answer.   <P>  William Lewis   <P>  As a regular reader and supporter of EverQuest Express I must tell you that I am rather irate  about this week's Q&A section. This weekly feature has always been a forum for EQ enthusiasts  to ask questions concerning the game and to get serious and professional answers from your  staff, namely Wynn. Don't those of us that play Halflings have a difficult enough time with the  "d00d" jokes without us having to read Wynn's response to question #12? The sender of this  question made a straightforward and serious query and it was answered with a somewhat  puerile joke-type response. I'm all for humor and parody, but in the appropriate format. A  formerly serious Q&A section of a reputable "newspaper" is not such a format. I currently lead  a large and active Halfling clan that is an officially registered guild in the EverQuest beta and I  can tell you, we of the Vale Patrol are most distressed by such a flippant attitude toward our  chosen race by once such an esteemed oranization. We are asking for no less than a public  apology and/or retraction of the offending article portion. The link to your page that once graced  the Vale Patrol's page will be removed until such an event takes place and the membership of  the Vale Patrol will no longer support your organization until our request for an apology is met.  Thank you for your time.   <P>  Verdura Silverleaf, Sheriff of the Vale Patrol   <P>  <I>We are pleased to hear from two members of H.O.B.B.I.T.T, Halflings Organized for Better  Behavior In The Tall. Speaking as a dwarf, I well know the slings an arrows oft suffered by  those who believe that anything below their waist is insignificant. Having seen these  individuals at waist height, I can guarantee that that what is below THEIR waists is truly  insignificant, in every sense of the term.   <P>  It is our policy here at Everquest Express not to publish spoilers, or discuss game strategies  which remove the role-playing from the game and rise to the level of power-gaming  strategies. As such the question on the advantages and disadvantages of a particular race  takes the "concept" out of the character, and is indeed more of a l33t dewd question than a  role-playing query. As such we decided that a satiric response was in order. If you are  indeed an avid reader, you can see that we have referred to many races in many varying  terms. As the dwarf of the staff, I am frequently called upon to keep my sense of humor  despite the jokes of the Tall Folk, and I would not presume to think that the EQX staff in any  way truly deprecates anyone on the basis of their race. We have played this game since  August playing many races and classes. Wynn in particular loves to play halflings, and had  an Phase 1 halfling rogue that rocked the Misty Forest.   <P>  My sincerest condolences on the loss of your sense of humor.   <P>  Oghma</I>  </FONT>  <P>  ----------  <P>  As you can see, some people certainly did not share the reception I gave it, and it's indicative of something I've noticed in the game.  <P>  To give you some background...  <P>  One of my characters is a female Dark Elf Necromancer - probably one of the most unpolitic race/class/gender combinations one could pick.  On top of it all, I decided that she was going to be an introvert; not overly friendly even to other Teir'dal, and certainly not one to get the warm fuzzies over if you're of another race.  This combination clearly takes the "difficult" playability rating all the way down to "totally insane."  <P>  Now, I play out this character to a fault.  She rarely starts a conversation.  She never joins a group unless she believes she has something to gain by doing so (or unless she's just bored of being alone).  When she does acknowledge other races it's only with a sneer unless an actual dialog in common tongue is absolutely necessary.  In short, she's a real bitch on the whole, and the only time she's not is when she considers the other person worthy of her attention in some way.  She's a model daughter of Innoruuk, to be sure.  <P>  This has led to some... interesting results.  <P>  No matter what overtures are made that EverQuest is a ROLEPLAYING game, people simply don't treat it as such.  This is made manifest by the fact that I've managed to piss off so many players with this character.  I remember distinctly two incidents she had.  <P>  One was with a fellow Dark Elf Necromancer who helped her locate her corpse.  She was most grateful for his assistance, and decided to be at least cordial to him.  Along came another Dark Elf Necromancer who insisted the three of them should group and raid the halfling encampment nearby.  In evaluating whether or not our group would end up victors or victims, it came about that my character only had the Cavorting Bones spell to animate her pet.  This new Dark Elf made the blindingly obvious point that Cavorting Bones sucked rocks and that she should get Leering Corpse as soon as possible.  My character, being the person she is, was incensed at this presumptuous pig for telling her what to do.  She responded by saying thanks for the hot tip, but she knows how to take care of herself.  She made it plainly obvious at this point that she had no inclination of joining with this impudent know-it-all.  The first Dark Elf said "Screw it, then," and disbanded her from the party.  She left in a huff and returned back to Neriak..  <P>  Now, is this behavior for the betterment of her enlightened self-interest?  I would think not.  In this regard she's her own worst enemy.  But that's simply the person she is, and that is the way she is played.  The reaction of her would-be companions is simply to be expected, and as her player I don't take it personally.  The problem is, I know (or think I know) the player whose character she insulted took it personally, as if it were an attack on him.  I'm also pretty sure the player of the first Dark Elf thinks I have a lot of audacity copping such an attitude, and that I'm an ungrateful jerk.  Well, the truth is it wasn't a personal attack, and I should have taken steps to let them know this out-of-character, but I was being stubborn in thinking I shouldn't have to because this is a ROLEPLAYING game.  Looking back on it, I regret not doing so.  Oh well... bygones.  <P>  Another time is when my Dark Elf ventured out of Nektulos Forest to the East Commons area.  There was a party resting there at the mouth of the canyon, one member of which was a Halfling.  This Halfling said to her "Don't go near the guards, they'll kill you!"  If that character hadn't been -PVP I'd have pounded his scrawny little arse. Well, there's that and the fact he had a full party with him.  Anyway... 1) This is a Dark Elf he's flapping his lips at, who'd just as soon skewer Halflings as look at them (the rare exception being the Halfling(s) found in Neriak's Foreign Quarter).  2) Since when do Halflings give one spit about the welfare of a Dark Elf?  The Teir'dal routinely roast the Halfling intruders who are foolish enough to hang around the ruins in Nektulos Forest, so why such sympathy so as to warn one off from a potential danger?  3) Does he say that to EVERY Dark Elf coming out of the canyon?  If so, he's doing them a disservice because most guards in the area see Dark Elves indifferently, not with hostility.  (Hmmm... perhaps that's his plan all along?)  <P>  Anyway, I didn't say anything this time because of the lesson I learned with the previous incident.  Still, I find it stifling to be forced to play my character a certain way (or NOT play it, as the case may be) out of a sense of courtesy to players who don't "get it" when it comes to roleplaying.  <P>  Okay, time for a reality check.  Yes, I know that these players were just offering a bit of friendly advice, EQer to EQer.  I accept that, and I appreciate their motives.  I do, however, hold out the contention that if I receive any more friendly advice, I inevitably lose the adventure of discovering new and wonderful aspects of the game on my own.  Spoilers are so looked-down upon with web sites, why are in-game spoilers considered fair play?    <P>  But just placing spoilers aside, players need to separate themselves from their characters, and realize that what they observe in the game is not in egocentric orbit around <I>them</I>.  It's easy for someone playing a dwarf to accept that a derogatory comment a human makes about his height isn't directed at the player, but at the character (how would anyone know how tall a player is in real life?).  It's not so easy under other circumstances when, say, an arrogant Dark Elf female insults another Dark Elf for his unknowing impunity.  <P>  Going back to the issue of Wynn's answer to the Halfling question, the players who wrote in to voice their indignant responses took Wynn's comments as attacks on their personal choice of character to play.  While the remarks Wynn made were largely out-of-character on a web site, they are the remarks Halflings should expect to receive by those who don't care for them.  If what Wynn said was said in-game by a High Elf, I think they would have probably been received in context by the players.  <P>  I also understand that this whole "freebie" playtime is still just a massive test.  I respect that by using the /bug feature anytime I come across any problem I've found, but I still <I>play</I> it as I normally would.  The argument could be made that these people are also just testing, and consider it unseemly to roleplay until the actual release. I respectfully disagree, as I foresee the game being played after release exactly the way we see it being played now.  But hey, we're all entitled to our opinions.  <P>  What all this song and dance about character context boils down to is the existence of bigotry in EverQuest, and how it enriches the game.  Not only that, but it in a world where all is setting and no storyline, bigotry does actually give EQ a sense of <I>purpose</I>.  That sounds so bad, considering the pain and hatred that bigotry spreads in the real world (I'd never advocate such behavior outside a setting of pure fiction).  But think about it... EQ revolves around conflict, and pursuant to that extent the design team has made the social system pivotal to the hatreds the different factions hold for one another.  Ogres and Trolls hate the Humans and Elves.  Shadowknights hate the Paladins.  Rogues hate the clerics.  Dark Elves hate just about everybody.  Norrath is <I>not</I> one big happy family setting, contrary to the way people are playing it.    <P>  Without this faction system, what kind of game are we really playing?  If everyone follows the Golden Rule regardless of race or caste, it transforms EQ into a game where all PCs ally against the NPC monsters, which is something you might as well turn to non-massively multiplayer games to do and duck the monthly fee.  Is this what we want from EverQuest?  No, I say!  So start mistreating your neighbors, dammit!  <P>  But seriously, folks, please keep in mind that there is a real human being attached to the other end of the character you're relating to.  So please learn from my mistakes and take steps to make sure you're not treading on anyone's feelings or their enjoyment of the game.  If there's any question as to whether or not you've hurt someone's feelings, be sure to let them know out-of-character that you're just playing your character's role.   <P>  Above all, separate yourself from your character.  While you may have to think like a Troll and act like a Troll in order to play a Troll, you yourself are <I>not the Troll!</I>  This is often easier said than done.  I remember the first time I roleplayed with a good friend of mine in Baldur's Gate.  He started talking about finding some action at the local brothel, and I was shocked!  "Rick!  You're a married man, and I've never heard you talk like this!"  I had to remind myself that he was playing a dastardly thief who had the morals of an alley cat.  As you can see, he played it well.  As another example, my wife often plays a very <I>very</I> flirtatious character with other guys online (just ask them, they'll confirm it!), and has duly approached me asking if I have any problem with that.  My response is that as long as her own feelings remain separated from those of her character, then it's fine.  She says that's not a problem, so I trust her word.  <P>  I realize that last example is a stretch for most people, and I wouldn't expect them to ascribe to that level of removal.  Still, in contrast, I see <I>no</I> removal whatsoever in the vast majority of characters I come across in Norrath, and I think it's rather sad.  They're not allowing themselves to be something they're not in real life, which is really why we roleplayers do it in the first place.  No, it's not always easy, but once people make that leap, they're usually glad they did.  <P>  And hey, while EverQuest may be a roleplaying game by design, there's nothing written in stone that you MUST roleplay.  Just keep in mind that there are roleplayers out there, and to take in everything around you with a grain of salt.  Trust me, you'll be a lot happier.  <P>  At any rate, these events have given me a lot of food for thought, and I hope it has for you as well.  I welcome any comments or new angles you have to introduce, so please e-mail me at <A HREF="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</A> and fill me in!  <P>  For now, I'm off to play on the +PVP server and see just how easy/difficult it is to be a roleplayer on that server.  You can probably expect an article about that in the next couple of weeks.  In the meantime, have fun!  <P>  -&lt;Shadoe&gt;

