<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">Avoiding a Catastrophe</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Saturnino  (<a href="mailto:eon@clan.net" class="credit2">eon@clan.net</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
Just today in #EverQuest on IRC, a few other Netizens and myself were talking about what we deemed "the good ol' days of UO". Those of you who were around before the beta of UO actually started probably know what we were talking about. The times when everyone was dreaming about what they were hyping up as "the game of the decade". The times when you looked at the screenshots with awe and could actually see yourself taking on daemons in Deceit and meeting the legandary Lord British himself. After reminiscing a bit we started to wonder what actually went wrong with UO and when.<br><br>Most of us agreed that it was partly OSI's fault for making a few mistakes but that it was mostly the fault of the people who played it. Sure, there were annoying things like the "super guards" and teleportation and recall shrinking the world from 10 hours to cross to 2 seconds to recall from one end to the other. But, as I'm sure most of you would agree with, idiot players ruined it the most. Soltan in #everquest remarked about his first time seeing an orc in UO, "I was SCARED, then I got like 10 people saying 'wassup?', "we're waiting for da spawn", and it kind of ruined it for me." I'm sure he wasn't the only one they ruined it for.<br><br>So you ask, "What does this have to do with EQ?" Well, if you think about it, EQ is almost at the same stage now as UO was was in "the good ol' days". It's time we started seriously thinking about what we as future EverQuest players can do to avoid having EQ turn sour like UO did. So you're wondering, "what can I do to make sure this doesn't happen. I'm only one person." There's a lot you can do.<br><br>First, if you get into beta you need to avoid "playing" the game like many of the "testers" in UO did and make sure you "test" the game. If you see a bug that will possibly get overlooked and might come back to haunt EQ you need to report it. You also need to start making suggestions on what could possibly make the game better. If you are tired of seeing everyone greet each other with "yo, wassup dawgz?" maybe you could suggest some sort of feature that automatically turns words like "sup?" to "what's going on?". If enough people suggest that then they just might incorporate that into the game.<br><br>Another thing you could do is start up a race specific site for say trolls that could teach other people who don't really know about what an troll would act/talk like how to act more "trollish". You could start or join a race or class specific guild for all clerics, thieves, or any other thing like that. If you put a little bit of effort into it you can get a lot out.<br><br>I'm not saying that it's all the players' responsibility to make sure EQ doesn't turn out bad. SISA will play a major role in determining if you can even do those things to improve the game. But with the addition of the PK switch(for those of you who got tired of having no control over being PKed) and the name filter(so we don't have any more of those BaDaSsm0f0's) it looks like SISA is doing their part to make the game more enjoyable, now it's up to you to make sure EQ doesn't end up with the bad rep that UO got.<br><br>Send me your comments on this editorial by using the address below.<br><br>- Junior "Saturnino" Garcia (eon@clan.net)

