<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">P.V.P. Player vs. Pimple Follow-Up</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Shadoe  (<a href="mailto:shadoe@vaultnetwork.com" class="credit2">shadoe@vaultnetwork.com</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="http://www.eqvault.com" class="credit2">EQVault</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
<FONT SIZE=-2>  [ <U>Author's Note:</U> I must apologize for the belated posting of the reader   responses.  I know a lot of you out there have been waiting for some sort  of follow-up from me, and I'm really sorry it's taken this long.    This was actually meant to be posted shortly after the P.V.P.  article was released, but because of some technical difficulties, I lost  the original, and found myself way too unmotivated to rewrite it right   away.  Recently, I happened to chance across an old, forgotten copy of it.  After celebrating my good fortune for a fortnight, I sent it in to be   posted.  As it stands, all you really have to keep in mind is that it was  written before Phase 4 started, and I hadn't really played EQ at the time.  Oh well, better late than never! ]  </FONT>  <P>  After setting up my e-mail address at the Vault Network, I was suddenly   deluged with loads of reader responses!  Some brought tears to my eyes in   glee (well, almost), others made me feel like I needed to dip myself in   alcohol after deleting them.  All in all, though, it's terrific to see   that the article provoked some thought in a lot of the readers, and   that's what really counts after the questing's done.    <P>  This has inspired me to post the occasional e-mail I get which I find to   my liking and/or which I have some sort of response to make to that   brings an angle to the topic I failed to touch on.  It's sort of my own   version of Clinton's testimony, only I don't get my own intern for it.  <P>  I really wish I had the time and resources to respond to every e-mail I  received, but I <I>do</I> have to find time to eat (though some would say   that's an arguable point!)  So to everyone who took the time to send in   their responses, thank you ever so much for taking the time to send me   your input.  <P>  Anyway, here's a reader response to "PvP" I thought was very cordial and   required a cordial response...  <P>  ----------  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  Hey I read your latest article on the PVP switch and I wanted to tell <br>  I thought you did a great job and got your points across quite well.  <br>  </FONT>  <P>  Thanks!  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  One error I wanted to point out is that you stated near the end of the<br>   article that you say sony is, I quote "a company that has proven itself<br>  to know howto consistently make money with PC games."  I work in the <br>  industry and I read the charts quite often and you should be aware <br>  that Sony has had an awful record at making money in the PC sector. <br>  In fact this will probably be their first quality product ever <br>  published.  Obviously Sony does pretty well in the Console side of <br>  gaming but the two really don't translate because console players <br>  usually expect much lower quality than PC gamers.  </FONT>  <P>  Hrm... well, I do have to admit, I'm not one to weasel my way into Sony   Interactive / 989 Studios / RedEye Interactive / Verant Interactive /   Brad's Development FunHouse Interactive Studios Incorporated's profit   margins, so I can't really say if they have or not.  So, I'll have to take  your word for it.  More on this a bit   later.  <P>  But you're right... one game alone does not a "consistent profit" make.  <P>  Still, my argument stands.  From all indications I've been exposed to,   Brad's team aren't slouches.  Hey, the fact they're not U.S. Senators has   to account for <I>something</I>.  I may make a hasty switch to reverse   gear once I actually <I>see</I> the game after release, and I may end up   ranting about why I wouldn't pay a dime to play EQ, as I did with UO.  But   from what I can tell right now, I think it's as likely as finding Sly   Stallone in a Barbara Streisand movie.  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  I think theres one more important point you might want to include as <br>  well.  Currently there are not many pvp+ players but that's mostly due <br>  to the fact that everyone is still below level 40 something.  As was <br>  the case in UO I think we will find that players who reach the upper <br>  echelons of power will eventually switch to pvp+ to add a little <br>  "spice" to their game.  This will make the argument of not having <br>  enough pvp+ players somewhat less valid.    </FONT>  <P>  Well, this is such a speculative issue, I decided it was best to wait and   see what happens after release.  The lack of +PVP characters could be   indicative of everyone's ardent desire to avoid looking over their   shoulders everywhere they go, in which case what you're saying about   levels is quite correct.  The argument against that is the +/- 4 level   restrictions for player-vs-player combat, which (if I understand it   correctly) means you're at pretty much an even risk all the way up to   level 46, for all intents and purposes.  <P>  After all that's said and done, I can think up a good number of reasons why   such an enormous percentage of players have chosen -PVP for Phase 3 --  some logical, some not.  We humans are a peculiar breed, and I've given up   on trying to interpret our behavior as a unit.  Tommy Lee Jones said it   best in Men In Black when he said that <I>individuals</I> are smart,   <I>people</I> are dumb, paranoid, and dangerous, or something to that   effect.  I know that's a depressingly cynical perspective, but I've found   it holds a lot more truth than we dare to admit.  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  I believe your statement that RedEye should just go ahead and try it <br>  anyways is the best decision though.  The reason I believe so though <br>  is that I don't see any heavy opposition to a pvp+ only server.  <br>  Therefore 989 has very little to loose and possibly a lot to gain.  <br>  As the saying goes the customer is always right.  </FONT>  <P>  Well, the customer's <I>money</I> is always right.  I've seen many companies   have customers "right" them right out of business.  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  My only objection to your article is that you constantly imply that <br>  powergamers are not allowed to be roleplayers.  This drives me nuts <br>  because I am a powergamer who enjoys roleplaying as well.  A lot of <br>  powergamers are often very hostile to roleplayers for this very kind of<br>  thing too unfortunately.  Thankfully you didn't take any tone of <br>  condecension but I've seen several Roleplayers act as if powergamers <br>  are inferior!  For example in UO in the beta several of us were <br>  sparing to raise skill levels and some roleplayer who was somewhat <br>  built up got mad because he felt sparing was powergaming and he <br>  started to attack all of the players there!  He killed several of <br>  them because they were all newbies really.  I'm not accusing you of <br>  taking such a stance but I think acting as if powergamers and <br>  roleplayers are completely different entities, compounds the problem <br>  somewhat.  Anyways just thought I'd throw in my 2 cents :).  <P>  Amaron  </FONT>  <P>  ----------  <P>  And well you should, Amaron.  The only thing I can say is that the rift   between powergamers and roleplayers does, in fact, exist.  Otherwise there   wouldn't be an issue over which people have been screaming at each other   for the last two-plus years.  <P>  Naturally, you run into exceptions whenever you cite a stereotype.    That's why stereotyping isn't too popular with mainstream society as a   whole, regardless of how much truth it may or may not hold.  It may shock   you to know that I, in fact, am quite the powergamer when it comes to   <I>power games,</I>  so you're certainly not alone in the hybrid category.  <P>  Anyway, thanks for writing in, Amaron, and for your insights.  I certainly   couldn't bring myself to introduce my thoughts to people without expecting   the same in return!  <P>  At any rate, here is another well thought out response I received...  <P>  ----------  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  Hello Shadoe,  <P>  I've enjoyed both of your articles, they are great for a laugh.  I<br>  haven't posted to the general comments board, but I wanted to give you<br>  another opinion on the PvP switch and PvP in general ( I just hope this<br>  doesn't earn me a cranial enema!!!).  I haven't played EQ yet, but I'll<br>  be in Phase 4.  <P>  I find that Player vs. Player aspect of the game very interesting, I'm<br>  what you labeled a "realism" player.  I've been a paper and pencil<br>  RPG'er for years...so for me the "realism" of  Player vs. Player is<br>  important to my role-playing, PvP and role-playing go hand in hand.  </FONT>  <P>  Nuttin' wrong with "realism roleplaying."  But I will say I think it's a   bit much to expect from the online computer roleplaying genre.  With   thousands of people online, <I>someone</I> is bound to shatter the   realism in one form or another -- PVP switch or no.  This is one reason I believe computer  RPGs will never replace the paper and pencil medium.  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  I think that a PvP server would be a good idea for the Quake 2'ers out<br>  there, kind of a deathmatch server.  I play Q2 and enjoy a good <br>  fragfest, but that is not why I what to play EQ.    </FONT>  <P>  Ditto.  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  I also agree with you that a PvP only server will not keep the other <br>  servers +pvp clean, KeWl DoOdZ players (and I can't stand them on any <br>  server) will haunt the normal servers looking for any weak role-player <br>  that is +pvp to have their way with.  There is no way to stop that type<br>  of player except by having -pvp only servers too.  I guess in a perfect<br>  world there could be 1 +pvp server, 1 -pvp server, and the rest <br>  switchable.  This gives the true powerplayer a home, the hardcore <br>  role-player a home, and a place for the hybrids (or "realism" players) <br>  to risk there necks, and (unfortunately) a place for the KeWl DoOdZ to <br>  lurk.  I think that 1 each of the +pvp and -pvp servers would be <br>  enough, because I think that both camps are in the minority,  the vast <br>  number of player will still want to go to a pvp switchable server...if <br>  for no other reason then freedom of choice.  you can be full blooded <br>  +pvp or -pvp,  you can be -pvp or +pvp and try to switch to the <br>  darkside/lightside by your actions, or you can be -pvp and duel <br>  (I think that's all of the options, as I understand them).  <P>  Well thanks for your time, if you get a chance I'd love to hear what <br>  you think about the ramblings above.  <P>  Bob Parkinson  </FONT>  <P>  ----------  <P>  Well, Bob, your outline for accomodating hardcore +PVP and -PVP players  is one of many in this cold, dark 'Net.  I would caution that, should a -pvp  server be founded, steps should be taken to ensure it's not confused with   a "roleplay only" server, citing the reasons I gave in my article on this   issue.  <P>  Really, though, I'm not in a good position to say whether or not your plan  is viable.  I could say I don't see a problem with it, but my judgement  isn't one based on experience.  That's really a question for the brainiacs   at Brad's Online Bistro.  <P>  Oh, and by the way... your letter doesn't even come close to a cranial  enema.  I only reserve cranial enemas for responses like this...  <P>  ----------  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  Dood u suck!!!  PVP rox and for u 2 say we suck like this is like <br>  making you know you turn round and make like ensult us means you <br>  ensult you'r self!  <br>  PVP RULEZ!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! man and theirs you cant do about <br>  it!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!  </FONT>  <P>  ----------  <P>  Right.  Well, now you've gone and shattered my fragile self-image.  My   therapist thanks you.  <P>  Moving right along...  <P>  ----------  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  I know you probably have gotten tons of emails about this but im a PK <br>  Power Gamer whatever.My thoughts on the whole RPG Power Gamer subject <br>  is cant they just exist togather why should the Power Gamers conform <br>  to the Role players ways and at the same time the Role players should <br>  be able to play the way they want to so why should we Power Gamers be <br>  badgered by RPers to role play anyways that was just my 2 cents.  </FONT>  <P>  ----------  <P>  I'm glad you asked that.    <P>  Non-roleplayers, by their nature of not behaving in context with their   environment, shatter the roleplayer's immersion of being in that world.  It   may not make sense to those who don't roleplay -- it may even appear   silly somehow.  But trust me, it's the truth, it hinders roleplayers'   enjoyment of the game and they are bound to complain about it.  It gets no   more complicated than that.  <P>  Now, if roleplayers' style somehow blasted powergamers' enjoyment of the   game, the scales would be far better balanced, and then you'd have a point  about conformity.  <P>  This is why I think the way I do when it comes to the controversy.    The non-roleplayers' style hinders roleplayers enjoyment by nature when   roleplayers' style doesn't hinder non-roleplayers' at all.  Roleplayers   complain about it, non-roleplayers say to quit whining and cope.    Roleplayers respond by saying non-roleplayers should go play non-roleplaying  games, non-roleplayers say they're paying customers with rights, too.  It   all goes down hill from there.  Roleplayers complain about it again... it's   a tennis match.  <P>  Such is life.  <P>  Next up is a response from a very opinionated reader...  <P>  ----------  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  I've read your [expletive deleted], and I loved it...  I laughed my ass<br>  off at the FAQ, and the PvP article was an inspirer...  </FONT>  <P>  Thank you!  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  It pisses me off though....  The whole subject of PvP, I mean, Sony has<br>   to be one of the biggest game-making corporations out there and with <br>  all the games making precedents, this has to be such a contraversial issue.    </FONT>  <P>  Well, as has been recently illustrated to me, this point is arguable, but  I digress...  <P>  Perhaps it's best to say that Sony is one of the largest companies out   there that happens to make games?  Even better: Sony is one of the largest  companies out there <I>period</I>.  Their ownership of Brad's Bungalow of Bitchin'   Badasses brings in a tiny percentage of their overall income.  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  I think that sucks.  I played "The Realm" by Sierra, and I wouldn't <br>  "compare" it to EQ, but I would say that their idea was a good one (the<br>   only thing sierra did right in that game).  <br>  <P>  >From what I've read it seems as if you're pro-no pvp which is cool,   </FONT>  <P>  Whoa!  Hold on there, hombre!  I <I>never</I> said I was pro-no-PVP!  EverQuest without PVP capabilities makes absolutely no sense to me.  I was talking about a +PVP-only server, not the switch itself!  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  I can respect the aspects of 100% EQ gaming....Quests, etc.  But <br>  player vs player can be a lot more than just two KeWlDo0ds talking <br>  cyber-smack.  And it really adds a whole 'nother element to the game.  <br>  And my suggestion is that they just stick with the switch with all the <br>  servers.  Because if you stick all the PvP players on one server, you <br>  KNOW that server is going to be...just...worthless.  It ruinsit for <br>  the "intelligent pvpers".  If I had it my way, I would just <br>  incorporate the player-killer option as an official game feature, I <br>  mean, something that IS the game, and no one could have the right to <br>  just not fight someone else, no immunity.  But I also realize the <br>  harassment issue, and I respect the people who don't want to mess <br>  with the pvp option, so a compromise would be the switch.  And I <br>  really think thats the only way to go...  If you're wondering why <br>  your email got on the eq headlines, I suppose thats my fault since I <br>  was the one who started the thread about getting in touch with you <br>  on the message board... ;P  <P>  Anyhow, keep up the good work, and write me back with a piece of <br>  mind...   <P>  --Lectral of The Black Hand  </FONT>  <P>  ----------  <P>  Actually, I rarely frequent the message boards, so I had no idea there  was such a thread... hrm.  Maybe I should get in there more often.  <P>  Here's a good one that brings me back to the issue of challenging   corporate profits...  <P>  ----------  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  This is not a derogatory comment so please don't take it as one.  I<br>  respect your ability to post your opinions whether I agree with them or<br>  not.  This email is regarding your PVP article (which I am actually in<br>  full accordance with) I am however in disagreement with 1 comment<br>  <P>  "like that and pit himself against a company that has proven itself to<br>  know how to consistently make money with PC games? It blows me away how<br>  people profess to have all the answers"<br>  <P>  Actually, this company has only released 1 other PC title.  Tanarus.<br>  Tanarus has lost a hell of a lot of money.  I know this because I have a<br>  high security level in the game and we (Sony and ops) often meet to<br>  discuss the financial burden that Vervant can face at times.  EQ is<br>  expected to make a profit, and I don't doubt that it will.<br>  <P>  Just a minor correction  </FONT>  <P>  ----------  <P>  Another reinforcing comment saying that our hosts hold a less-than-glorious  track record with PC games.  Well, perhaps so.  This means EverQuest will   be their vindication -- or at least we all hope so.  <P>  On that note, it makes little business sense for a company to be allowed   to spend so much time and money on a concept that expands on a previously  unprofitable theme.  I'm not saying it shouldn't have happened, mind you.  I'm just thinking out loud.  <P>  Anyway, this last letter is another rebuke about my "facts."  Take a look   and see what you think...  <P>  ----------  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  Shadoe made one glaring error. Well, more, but 1 will do.  </FONT>  <P>  Care to talk about that?  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  He wrote role playing is fantasy. Not true. Role playing is assuming<br>  a persona and its characteristics. This is used in business and <br>  mental health and is much more of realism than of fantasy. Businesses<br>  quite often provide role playing training for managers and even for <br>  technical people who quite often need it more. <br>  </FONT>  <P>  *jots down some notes*  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  So, role playing CAN be fantasy, but it is not ONLY fantasy. Sometimes<br>  it is fully and seriously ground in reality and RL dynamics. <br>  </FONT>  <P>  And how do you feel about that?  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  There are a lot of people who spew words about role playing and from <br>  what I've seen, 99% aren't qualified to define role playing in the <br>  least. Insofar as it applies to EQ, ANYTHING any pc does is role playing<br>  because the nature of the graphical avatar is to assume a persona which<br>  is not a carbon copy of the person behind it, but rather an extension<br>  and modification of that person's personality.   </FONT>  <P>  *nods and looks pointedly cryptic*  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  And anyone that tries to tell others how to play is a bigot and an <br>  idiot, and will be ignored, laughed at, and according to Brad, possibly<br>  even banned if they make real nuisances of themselves. <br>  </FONT>  <P>  *checks his watch*  Well, our hour's almost up... anything else?  <P>  <FONT COLOR="#0000BB">  BTW one of my degrees is in behavior modification (psychology) and the <br>  other one is in computer science so I'm fairly certain of what I'm<br>  saying.   ;p  <P>  Anjelika  </FONT>  <P>  ----------  <P>  Hehe... sorry for the therapist quips, Anjelika.  Just givin' ya a   hard time! ;)  <P>  Even without the last paragraph, it's easy to see she is into   psychology because she's talking about a totally different aspect of   roleplaying.  Roleplaying is often used therapeutically in the field to   "play out" real-world situations often through the eyes of different   people.  By that definition, even Tomb Raider is a very true form of   roleplaying... but not by MY definition.  <P>  No, no, no... what I'm talking about is roleplay <I>gaming</I>; a pursuit   of enjoyment which is, indeed, fantasy.  I'm talking  about characters with stats and exotic worlds for them to adventure in.    I'm talking about little odd-shaped dice that add a certain degree of   randomness to the game.  I'm talking about playing the knight who slays   the dragon to rescue the distressedly-inclined.  I'm talking about   character interaction!  I'm talking about escaping the real world to find   entertainment in actually <I>being</I> somebody else, preferably one who  isn't sociopathic so as to blow up every moving object.  I'm talking about   beefing up your character as fast as humanly possible so they can kick   major butt wherever they go... erm... wait.  Is that what I'm talking   about?  *scratches head*  <P>  All the same, if that's just one small facet in the holistic jewel that is   "Role-Playing," then so be it.  It is not, however, a glaring error.  So   there... <I>NYAH!</I>  :P  <P>  This is all terrific, and the list of really good e-mails I received   certainly didn't stop here.  Thanks to you all for sending in your  comments (and giving me something to submut this week, for that matter),  and keep those brain-gears turning!  Some day we'll find an answer, and it   certainly isn't going to be by watching Seinfeld re-runs all day long.  <P>  *sits back and waits for the seething Seinfeld fan e-mail to come pouring   in*  <P>  -&lt;Shadoe&gt; 

