<P>
This, friends is a satire    based on the Official EverQuest FAQ posted as of last November. &nbsp; What we've done    here is include additional answers phrased in &quot;true form.&quot;&nbsp; In other words,    we know that what we're seeing in the official FAQ contains a certain amount of tact in    the EQ team's responses, either for the purposes of proprietary information or for decorum    in 989 Studio's public relations as a respected company in the industry.&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2">We thought it would be    interesting to see how the answers would be given if the EQ team were allowed to respond    in a no-holds-barred fashion, where the REAL truth comes out.&nbsp; So, after every    &quot;official&quot; answer, we've added our own version of What They Really Mean (WTRM),    highlighted in </font><font size="2" color="black">black</font><font color="#C0C0C0"    size="2">.&nbsp; Some comments in </font><font size="2" color="black">black </font><font    color="#C0C0C0" size="2">are meant to replace the official answer, and others are meant as    amendments (denoted by a </font><font size="2" color="black">...</font><font    color="#C0C0C0" size="2"> at the beginning.)</font></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">So sit back, grab a    glass/can/bottle/carafe/bowl/trough of your favorite beverage, and enjoy!</font></p>    <hr>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2">This is the Official    EverQuest FAQ. Future updates, upon approval, will be posted here and also considered    official. The questions on the FAQ either come from email, us, or the newsgroups. The    answers come from the EverQuest team. If you would like your own questions answered,    please visit the </font><font size="2"><a href="eq_contactframe.htm" target="_top">Contact</a></font><font    color="#C0C0C0" size="2"> page.</font></font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: This is the Official    EverQuest FAQ.&nbsp; Future updates, upon approval by the high and mighty powers that be    who hold complete and total power over each of our financial futures and those of our    families, will be posted here and also considered official.&nbsp; The questions on the FAQ    either come from email, us, the newsgroups, or Sony's Board of Directors.</font></p>    <hr>    <p align="left"><font color="#FFFFFF" size="1" face="Arial">Last Update: 11/09/98</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#FFFFFF" size="5" face="Arial"><a name="Table of contents:"><strong>Table    of contents: </strong></a></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><a    href="#1.0 General questions.">1.0 General questions.</a><br>    <a href="#2.0 About the beta test.">2.0 About the beta test.</a><br>    <a href="#3.0 Features.">3.0 Features.</a><br>    <a href="#4.0 Characters.">4.0 Characters.</a><br>    <a href="#5.0 Skills.">5.0 Skills.</a><br>    <a href="#6.0 Magic.">6.0 Magic.</a><br>    <a href="#7.0 NPC and creatures.">7.0 NPCs and creatures.</a><br>    <a href="#8.0 Items and properties.">8.0 Items and properties.</a><br>    <a href="#9.0 Quests.">9.0 Quests.</a><br>    <a href="#10.0 Guilds.">10.0 Guilds.</a><br>    <a href="#11.0 Pkilling and death.">11.0 Pkilling and other player vs. player issues. </a><br>    <a href="#12.0 Character death.">12.0 Character death. </a><br>    <br>    </font></p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><a    name="1.0 General questions."><strong>1.0 General questions.</strong></a></font><font    color="#C0C0C0" size="2"> </font></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.1 What is a FAQ?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">FAQ stands for Frequently    Asked Questions.&nbsp; FAQs are designed to cover the most common questions and answers    regarding a product. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM:&nbsp; A FAQ is a    document that many people fail to read before asking things such as: &quot;Can I be an    Ogre rogue?&nbsp; That would be so totally way kEwL!&quot;&nbsp; Instead of providing a    lengthy, drawn-out explanation of why they cannot, in fact, create an Ogre rogue, it    allows us to say &quot;Read the $@##*%&amp; FAQ!&quot; instead.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.2 What is EverQuest?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">EverQuest is a real 3D    massively multiplayer online RPG. Another equally accurate way of describing EverQuest is    to call it a graphical MUD. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM:&nbsp; EverQuest is like    &quot;Ultima Online,&quot; only way better!&nbsp; Muhahahahahaaaaa!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.2.1 When will    EverQuest be released?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">EverQuest will be released    sometime this winter. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Gawd only knows.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.3 What is an RPG?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">RPG stands for Role-Playing    Game. People often debate what this really means, so we'll attempt to clarify what we    mean. When you play EverQuest you'll first create a character. This creation of yours can    be any one of 12 races and 14 classes, male or female, and you even have the opportunity    to adjust your attributes (for instance, how strong you are, or how intelligent you    aren't). You'll then immerse this character of yours into our virtual world and make of    him or her whatever you wish. You define your role in the lands of EverQuest and how well    you play that role it is up to you. People also often assume that RPG means an certain    theme or setting. While we don't necessarily agree that this is always true, EverQuest is    a traditional RPG. Our world is one of high fantasy, of sorcery and dragons, of great    wizards and marauding hordes of orcs. There are quests and puzzles to solve aplenty, but    it's up to you decide which ones, if any, to pursue. You might choose to become a warrior    bent on wanton destruction, or perhaps a merchant making his profit selling goods from one    land to another. Essentially, while we've defined the setting, you create the world. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Instead of writing an    essay about what role-playing is, we will instead direct you to your friendly neighborhood    TSR enthusiast.&nbsp; He or she will no doubt regale you with 5+ hours relating a detailed    description -- with tremendous ardor -- of exactly what a true roleplaying game is, and    why a computer could in no way replace the paper and pencil genre... <em>ever!</em></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.4 What do you mean by 3D?</b>    </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We realize that the term 3D is    loosely used almost everywhere today. In reference to EverQuest, however, we mean it quite    literally. Our engine is truly 3D -- it is not a raycaster, nor does it use a pseudo-3D    isometric view. You can walk completely around a house or any structure and then enter it,    all the while adjusting the camera view between first person and any number of top-down or    3rd person viewpoints. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: If you don't know what    3D means, then you're quite the lost soul.&nbsp; Are you SURE you've got the right web    address?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.5 What's a    &quot;massively multiplayer online game&quot;?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">While many modern computer    games support multiplayer gaming, few are designed to support well over 1,000 simultaneous    players. With EverQuest, you don't start the server program on a local network and invite    a few of your friends over to play. Instead, you run the EverQuest client program and use    the Internet to connect to our World Server. This server will run 24 hours a day, 7 days a    week, creating a truly persistent environment. Call or email your friends and tell them in    what city or dungeon to meet you, or better yet log on and encounter hundreds of other    people from all over the world and make a slew of new acquaintances. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">That's EverQuest, and this is    what massively multiplayer really means. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: It means instead of    playing a game with 4 to 16 friends across the Internet, you can play with 4 to <em>1600</em>    friends across the Internet!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.6 What's a MUD?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">MUDs (Multi-User    Dungeons/Dimensions) are online text-based RPGs that have been around for several years.    EverQuest is similar to these MUDs, except it was designed from the ground up to depict    our world using real-time 16bit color fully texture mapped graphics, as opposed to merely    a well written paragraph. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Also, while most of these MUDs    are run by a couple of people as a hobby in their spare time, EverQuest is a professional    and commercial product -- our staff will be on hand 24 hours a day to meet your needs both    as a player and as a customer. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: &quot;MUD&quot; is what    we're going to drag our competition through once everyone sees EverQuest!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.7 Who are you guys? Where    did EverQuest come from?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The EverQuest team is part of    Sony 989 Studios (formerly Sony Interactive Studios, America), the same studio that's    brought you PSX hits like Rally Cross and NFL Gameday. We've taken the console world by    storm, and now we're setting our sights on online gaming. EverQuest will be the second    online title to be released by SISA, with many more to follow. Our first online game,    Tanarus, has been released and is in stores now. It's a multiplayer futuristic tactical    tank combat game, and it's hot! Check out the web site, <a href="http://www.tanarus.com">http://www.tanarus.com</a> and    download the latest version of the client software now. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: We are many things.    &nbsp; We are the masters of NDA.&nbsp; We are the dolers of the almighty game balance.    &nbsp; We are the gods to whom the masses pray to every night for the boon called    &quot;Phase 4.&quot; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are the ones who control all you see and hear    in Norrath, because <em>you're in </em>our <em>world now!&nbsp; </em>[ Insert old 60's    ominous music here ]</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.8 What kind of hardware    and software will be required to play EverQuest?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The EverQuest client program    requires a Pentium 166 (Pentium 200+ recommended), with a Direct 3D compliant 3D card and    32 megabytes of RAM. The program runs under Windows 95 or 98. We recommend a 3D card at    least as fast as Voodoo Graphics from 3DFX. Note that this is estimate, and is subject to    change as game development progresses. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Let's just say 3DFX and    Intel are the companies to invest in <em>heavily</em> once EverQuest is about to be    released.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.8.1 Can EverQuest run on    NT 4.0 ? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We use Direct 3D, which will    need NT 5.0. It is not likely we will support the NT platform at release time.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Running EverQuest on NT    would be like using a bulldozer to drive from L.A. to New York.&nbsp; 9 out of 10 for    style, but who has the time for it?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.8.2 Will EverQuest    support operating systems other than Windows 95 and 98? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We're concentrating right now    on getting the Windows 9x version done, so we haven't given a whole lot of thought to    other platforms. We'll have to wait and see. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Oh sure, just pile more    work on us!&nbsp; As if we don't already have enough to do...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.9 Which 3D cards will you    support?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">EverQuest will use both Direct    3D and Glide. Direct 3D is a 3d API from Microsoft that allows us to support most 3D cards    currently on the market as well as future cards. Glide is a 3d API from 3DFX and works    with their cards (Voodoo Graphics, Voodoo 2, etc.). </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: More than you'd think,    really.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.9.1 I am not a    technical wizard -- could you explain what D3D is?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Direct 3D (D3D) is part of    Direct X, which is a software add-on to Windows 9x that most modern games use. Direct 3D    is the part of Direct X that allows a game or other program to utilize the various 3D    cards out on the market. If you would like to learn a bit more about DirectX or Direct 3D    please visit the Microsoft site and read the documentation. The address is <a    href="http://www.microsoft.com/directx/">http://www.microsoft.com/directx/</a>. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: D3D = Direct 3D.&nbsp;    For you non-technical wizards out there, you just click on the little button that says    &quot;install Direct X&quot; when you run EverQuests's install program, and all will be    peachy dandy.&nbsp; Really.&nbsp; Well... probably.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.9.2 Will a 3dfx card    be required to play the game?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">A 3D card is required, however    it doesn't necessarily have to be a 3dfx card (although they work fine). Your card needs    to be a Direct 3D compliant card, and should be at least as fast as a 3dfx card. You may    want to consult some of the many articles, both on the web and in printed magazines, that    compare and contrast the features, performance, etc. of 3d cards. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Nope.&nbsp; But hey,    they're cool cards and we've designed EverQuest around that standard, so why not?&nbsp; I    only wish we got kickbacks.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.9.3 What version of    Direct X will be used?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">EverQuest will require at    least DX 5, but works fine on DX 6. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Version 5 or later.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.9.4 Can anyone tell me if    EverQuest will support OpenGL? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">EverQuest will use Glide (the    native 3dfx API) and Direct 3D (Microsoft API that most modern 3d cards support). We will    not support OpenGL (nothing against it, just with both Glide and D3D, there's no real    need). </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: OpenGL sucks.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.10 Will the game be    downloadable or will it be on CD?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">CD-ROM. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, we plan on releasing    it on single-sided, single-density 8-inch floppy disks.&nbsp; CD-ROMs are only for rich    people who care nothing for backward compatibility.&nbsp; A punch-card version is    available upon request, plus $329.95 shipping, handling, and crane rental for delivery to    your door. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.11 What kind of music    will there be in EverQuest? Midi files, or directly off the CD?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We aren't releasing that info    at this time.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Uh... we're not really    sure yet.&nbsp; We'll worry about that tomorrow.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.11.1 Has any    consideration been given to the use of 3D sound in EQ?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, we are looking into 3d    sound, and are very pleased with how our sound department is proceeding with music and    sound in the game. I think you will be pleased with its sophistication. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Could just maybe happen,    if someone lights a fire under our sound department...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.12 Will game info be    saved on servers or on our Hard drive?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Servers. We are very sensitive    to the fact that hackers exist, and are implementing several plans to guard against them. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yeah, right... nice try,    you Diablo guys!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.12.1 With a rough    cap of between 1,000 and 1,500 people per server, are you expecting to have enough servers    to meet demand?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, while this may or may not    mean more servers, we feel it's worth it to keep the server based lag down and to preserve    a sense of community on each server.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Well, yes, but don't    quote us on that.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.12.2 How much of the    world will actually be on the client side? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Basically, like any other    game, your graphics and world is on the client side, but your critical data like    characters are on the server side. Static information that isn&#146;t going to change is    on the client side. And that typically is most of your graphics -- you don&#146;t want to    be downloading those.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Trust us... cheats by    way of editing client-side data would be a waste of time and effort.&nbsp; No kidding.    &nbsp; Seriously.&nbsp; Don't even try it at all.&nbsp; It's not gonna happen.&nbsp; We    will mock you if you do... and make you cry, even.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.13 Will there be hot keys    or programmable macros in the game?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Aye, laddie.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.14 Do you plan to    continuously update the game after its initial release?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Absolutely. The world of    EverQuest will be a constantly evolving and expanding universe. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ... The days of    &quot;what you see is what you get&quot; in the computer game market are on the way <em>out,    </em>baby!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.14.1 Will the patches be    real time as you&#146;re playing the game?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">It will check your version    when you log in -- if we&#146;re doing a major change it will force you to log out. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Dream on.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.15 How much will    EverQuest cost me in the stores?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">This is another good question,    but one that is also a bit too early to elaborate on. Suffice it to say that EverQuest    will be very competitive with other games of the same genre. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Save up those nickels    and dimes.... and quarters, and silver dollars, and 1942 double-die Denver mint pennies,    and....</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.16 Will there be a    monthly fee to play this game? And if so, how much?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes there will be a monthly    fee for the actual retail game. How much and any other details are something we aren't yet    releasing however. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Heh-heh-heh...    &quot;money for nuthin' and the chicks fer free!&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.17 Is there a plan    to include a manual with EQ?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, plans are to include a    manual in the box. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Sure, why not?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.18 In the final    version, how will EQ staff handle player complaints about lost stats or equipment due to    bugs?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">On an individual basis. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Bribes gladly    accepted....&nbsp; *wink*</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.19 Will the    EverQuest team actually play the game or will they just take input from their    &quot;playing&quot; designers?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">When we assembled the team we    made sure many of the artists, programmers, and world builders were into this genre. The    entire team's input counts and they've all contributed to this game quite a bit.    Accordingly, we wouldn't be a bit surprised to see most all of them play the game quite    often. This is a game we've all wanted to make and PLAY for many years. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Unlike <em>SOME</em>    companies out there, we wouldn't create a game we wouldn't want to play ourselves.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>1.20 How do you intend    to build an online cohesive society in EverQuest? What elements do you think will add to    this environment?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We think the focus we have on    this not just being a player vs. player game but rather also a very cooperative game will    help build a sense of community. Allowing people to group, to talk to other party members,    and to talk to people regardless of where they are will help this. And the ability to    split experience amongst a group will add to this as well. Also, keeping the server    population down will enable people to recognize names more easily. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: I'm glad we asked that    question!&nbsp; Aren't you, Brad?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>1.20.1 Are you trying to    create a &quot;realistic&quot; world for EverQuest? i.e. attempting to essentially create    a living, breathing world &quot;simulation&quot;, where non-player characters have their    own daily schedules, the world has its own interactive &quot;ecology&quot; and there is an    overall dynamic &quot;economy&quot;. </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, but only where it really    adds to gameplay. EverQuest is not an experiment or a simulation, and our focus is on    making the game world fun. Our emphasis is on adventure and exploration, and making sure    the game mechanics are fair and enjoyable. Game balance definitely takes precedence over    any attempt at creating a super realistic virtual world.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Relax, the sins of the    founding fathers of massively multiplayer gaming *cough*UO*cough* are not passed to their    children *sneeze*EQ*sneeze*.</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><a name="2.0 About the beta test."><font    color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><strong>2.0 About the beta test.</strong></font><font    color="#C0C0C0" size="2"> </font></a></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>2.1 What phase of beta    testing are you at currently?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We are currently at Phase 3 of    our beta test, which just began in early November. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Oh yes, we and all the    lucky people who lied on their applications better than you did are loving life in Phase    3.&nbsp; Nyah nyah nyah!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>2.2 So what's after Phase    3?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Following Phase 3 will be    Phase 4, which is open to all who applied for beta testing with a small fee (mostly to    cover the cost of the CD and shipping). </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Well... certainly not    phase *5*&nbsp;&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>2.3 Do you know how many    people you'll accept into Phase 4?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Anyone who signed up for the    beta test (the application was online between March and October of this year) will have    the opportunity to participate. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: We'll let in all the    losers who were hoping to get in before anyone else, just to see if we can scare them off    by the time we release.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>2.4 How long will Phase 3    and Phase 4 last?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There's no way to predict that    at this point in development. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Rest assured phase 3    will last way longer than phase 4.&nbsp; U SUCK!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>2.5 How will the selection    be made for Phase 4?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">See 2.3. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: In phase 4, we will    select only those people whose applications we haven't lost.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>2.6 Do I get to keep my    beta character with all stats and items intact when the commercial version ships?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">This really hasn't been    determined yet -- probably not, however we are planning on rewarding beta testers in the    game after the commercial version ships. Keep in mind, though, that we also need to make    sure that all things are fair for those who did not participate in the beta. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Is <em>that</em> ever    wishful thinking!&nbsp; Follow our advice: don't get too attached to your beta characters.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>2.7 How much will the beta    CD cost? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There will be a shipping and    handling fee for the CD, however the final price has not yet been determined. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: If you have to ask, you    can't afford it.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>2.8 Will their be    certain incentives in beta for reporting bugs to the GM's? Perhaps a reward (in-game or    out) if a tester meets a certain bug report quota?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The incentive will be that if    a tester does not report bugs, they won't be a tester for long. Closed testing in EQ will    not be an opportunity to play the game for free, but rather it will involve people making    commitments to help us debug and balance the game, and those failing to meet those    commitments will not be testers for very long. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...Nevermind that you    keep hearing about imbeciles who have been accepted into phase 3 who complain about the    game rather than reporting the bugs they find as beta testers should.&nbsp; Nevermind that    you have a Ph.D. in Computer Entertainment Quality Control Sciences from both Harvard and    Oxford Universities, and we happened to pick a guy named &quot;KiCkBuTt&quot; for phase 3    and not you.&nbsp; Nevermind that this guy is still playing the game after two whole    months of constantly posting messages explaining why EQ will never work as a commercial    game.&nbsp; Believe us when we say that it speaks nothing about our highly discerning    selection process, which involved a hat, twelve chimps in a sealed room, and Whitney    Houston played at exactly 80 decibals.&nbsp; Hey... it was a <em>nice</em> hat.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>2.9 How effectively    will you handle the catching and punishment of bug exploiters?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We will be VERY strict upon    release of the game in regards to cheaters. Cheating will not be tolerated, and will    result in the player being banned from the game. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...So be good, for    goodness' sake.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>2.10 Will you be    expanding the world during the test, or will bug issues and other things take precedent    over it?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Both. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>2.11 How severe will    the NDA (Non-Disclosure Agreement) be? For example, can we maintain journals of our beta    adventures if we do not make specific technical references or include pictures?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The NDA for the first few    phases will have to be very strict, which means no information regarding the game can be    published.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM:&nbsp; None    whatsoever.&nbsp; Zero.&nbsp; Zip.&nbsp; Nada.&nbsp; You can't even hint that you might    possibly introduce the mere notion that you might think about the idea that you are in the    beta, or we'll spank you!&nbsp; Hard!&nbsp; We mean it!&nbsp; This means you!&nbsp; You're    not even allowed to talk about the NDA!&nbsp; In fact, merely saying the letters N-D-A    while under NDA violates the NDA!&nbsp; Don't you dare test us on this! This isn't a game,    people!&nbsp; Well it is, but...you know what we mean!</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><a name="3.0 Features."><strong>3.0    Features.</strong></a></font><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2"> </font></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.1 What's the screen    resolution for the game and number of colors?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">640x480 16bit color (that's    64,000 colors). </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Would you believe    640x480, 16 bit?&nbsp; No?&nbsp; Didn't think so, since we've already released plenty of    higher screenshots.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.1.1 I absolutely    loved the graphics in the screenshots. I have noticed, though, that most games who    dedicated too much time on graphics lack good Artificial Intelligence in their monsters,    etc.</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Well, here's what one of our    beta testers had to say on the subject of EverQuest's AI:</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><i>I have seen many game    companies striving toward a graphical work of art often overlook the basic AI of the    opponents. This has not been the case in EverQuest. This game has the most advanced AI    I've seen. Bar none. Even the little intricacies that make the game more believable were    taken into account. As I am battling one creature (say a large bat for this purpose), I've    seen a giant rat come up to me, stop, and watch the fight as if sizing me up. You really    get the feeling that these things are looking you in the eye, and trying to decide if you    are dinner, or something to be feared. </i></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><i>Some attack without    warning, others circle in from behind. Still others will act like they are going to go    right past you, and suddenly turn around and lay into you with swords, fists, or teeth.    The AI definitely appears to be modeled on creature intelligence, some just fight smarter    than others. The smart ones will even retreat from a fight and go get help. I have no    doubt that the AI programmer is somewhat of a sadist. A sadist with a sense of humor. </i></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><i>You'll know that sense of    humor when you see a hill giant way off in front of you in the distance, and 2 minutes    later find that it has made a wide circle to sneak up on you from behind. </i></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><i>Add to this some truly    impressive tracking and following code, and SPEED. These creatures are FAST. There just    isn't any outrunning some, you better hope you have the strength or the speed to get away    quickly, and they will follow you for a great distance. I have seen one gnoll retreat from    a fight, go get helpers, and return on two different tangents to surround the intruders.    I've seen groups split up, half appearing to have lost interest in the fight, only to turn    and rush in. </i></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><i>I've really got to put my    hats off to this AI programmer, I think he could give the ReaperBot guy pointers. </i></font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: We've made the AI more    intelligent than the average senator from Massachusetts, okay? &nbsp; So chill out.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.2 Can we run the game at    higher resolution if we have the horsepower for it?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes -- currently, in Glide    mode, you can run at 800x600 on a Voodoo 2, and 1024x768 on with 2 Voodoo 2s in SLI mode.    We may also support higher resolutions with Direct 3D cards as well.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yeah.&nbsp; We knew we    couldn't keep you people snowed for long. (See 3.1)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.2.1 Does high resolution    cause more lag if only using a modem (assume very fast machine and SLI voodoo2)? Does more    information need to cross the phone lines if in high-resolution?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The resolution you run EQ in    has nothing to do with Internet lag -- the exact same amount of information is being    passed between your client and the server.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...High resolution just    means you see things more clearly.&nbsp; It's like finding the meaning of life in a Mel    Brooks movie.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.3 How big is the game    world?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Huge. It should take a very    long time to walk from one end to the other. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Huge.&nbsp; We we don't    want to go out on a limb by giving any specific size, since the last time we heard it    would take 10 hours to cross a virtual world it turned out to be more like 20    minutes...&nbsp;a margin for error wider than Liz Taylor's jeans.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.3.1 Since the    current map is only one hemisphere, what is on the other side?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">That's for future expansions    -- the world will grow and grow. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Wouldn't YOU like to    know!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.3.2 Will the overall    size of the world get bigger, or will more things just be put in existing space as the    game gets older?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Both. We will fill in empty    portions of existing continents, as well as add more lands and planes and such. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Are you gonna eat that    pickle?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.4 What kind of    communication will there be in the game? Will we be able to send messages privately or to    broadcast to the entire server?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You'll be able to do the    following: </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">1. Say things to people in    your general area<br>    2. Shout things across the zone you are in<br>    3. Tell someone a message privately<br>    4. Say things such that only people grouped with you can hear.<br>    5. Say things such that only people in your guild (if you are in a guild) can hear.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Communications will be    via your keyboard.&nbsp; Any further information involving smoke signals is on a    need-to-know basis.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.4.1 How exactly will    communication work, i.e. when a character says something how will nearby characters see    it?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">If a character says something,    any other players nearby see it displayed in the input/output section on the screen. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...Pay closer attention    to the screenshots, if you're still confused.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.4.2 Will chat    programs like ICQ or IRC be disabled during the game?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">If your 3d card allows it, you    can run ICQ if you want. But in that you can 'tell' to any player in the game it's not    really necessary. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Why would anyone want to    use those things while playing EverQuest?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.4.3 What happens to    the people who follow you around spamming you, etc.?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You type ignore &lt;character    name&gt;, and then you don't see his spam anymore. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: If deliberate homicide    is not your cup of tea, you can always ignore them like the navel lint they are.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.5 The game will be server    based -- can I switch servers to go meet friends on another server?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Wellllllllll.........    yeah.&nbsp; But don't draw any conclusions about what this means until you've read the    answer to 3.6...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.6 Will people be    able to switch servers and take their character with them?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We would like to allow people    to move characters from one server to another, but if we allow this, there will be    limitations in regards to which if any items they could move, and how often we would allow    such a move. In other words, you will not be able to arbitrarily switch between servers at    will. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: What do you want from    us?&nbsp; <em>BLOOD?&nbsp; </em>I mean, sheesh!&nbsp; You hand people a new world, and    they want the universe!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.7 Will there be some    other ways to travel than walking? Horses, boats or teleport spell?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Ships and teleport spells,    yes. Horses will not be available at ship (meaning, possibly after ship, as an update or    expansion - this has yet to be determined). There will also be a few other more exotic    ways to traverse the lands of Norrath.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, but we're not    telling anyone what they are because we're mean.&nbsp; Trust us, though, they will be so    drop-dead cool that you will never want to play another game as long as you live. &nbsp;    And if you think our means of travel are impressive, just wait until you see Mona the    Monkey-woman in Queynos!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.7.1 When traveling in the    wilderness between towns, is the player's view going to be first person the entire    duration of travel, or will there be an overhead view of the map of the region?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Traveling long distances is    exactly the same as walking around a city or dungeon. The views themselves are the same    throughout the game -- you can choose from first person or from several third person    viewpoints. As for the time it takes to walk from one zone to another, depending on the    distance, it could take a while. Now that doesn't mean there won't be high level spells    and perhaps some other ways to 'shorten' those distances.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Traveling long distances    is exactly the same as walking around a city (except there are no buildings or guards or    merchants or so many other people) or dungeon.&nbsp; The views themselves are the same    throughout the game (except they change depending on where you are) -- you can choose from    first person or from several third person view points.&nbsp; If you're looking to see    things from the viewpoint of the monster who is currently gnawing on your nearly severed    ankle, you will be disappointed.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.8 How will fighting work?    Real time or turned based?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Real time, but we must stress    that this is not a 'twitch' game. It won't matter how quick you can click that mouse    button. Weapons have speeds, and they will 'go off' (i.e. swing, fire, etc.) at that    speed. It's like playing the piano to a metronome -- it's real time, but you can't exceed    a set pace. Every weapon has a speed. A dagger has a lot of attacks, whereas a big two    handed sword hits harder, but you&#146;re only going to be able to attack so often.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><font size="2"><font color="black">WTRM:    Turn-based?&nbsp; With upwards of 1500 people online at a time?</font></font><font    size="2" color="black">&nbsp; Wow... nevermind how long it takes to walk across the </font></font><font    size="2" color="black" face="Arial">world, start worrying about how long it takes to    walk from the front door to the mailbox!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.8.1 So EverQuest isn't a    &quot;twitch&quot; game -- does this mean there will be no advantage to having quick    reactions (at least in melee combat)? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Well, you can&#146;t rule out    the player&#146;s reactions completely &#150; he or she does have to control the game    either via the keyboard or mouse. But the emphasis is definitely on the player&#146;s    character&#146;s stats, not the player himself. Weapons and spells have speeds, characters    have attributes and skills, and these are the components of combat. The game is in real    time, but not at the pace of a shooter like Quake or Unreal.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Naw!&nbsp; In fact,    we've made the client so intelligent, you could literally create a character and walk away    from your computer for days.&nbsp; No hassling with bothersome quests or annoying player    interaction.&nbsp; Simply switch on the autopilot, and when you come back in a month    you'll have a level 50 character all set to go!&nbsp; It takes the tedium out of working    to build and make your character what you want it to be.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.8.2 Does your sword or    other weapon swing automatically?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, we call it auto-attack,    which allows you to concentrate on different skills and other combat options in the heat    of battle. For instance, warriors can kick and monks have a lot of special attacks. It    allows you to do those while you do your basic swing.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: See WTRM 3.8.1</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.9 Will someone with a    better connection have an advantage over someone with a poor connection?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Not during combat or other    critical times. Certainly having a better connection will reduce lag and some warping, but    it won't put you at a disadvantage necessarily in terms of game play. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Absolutely they    will.&nbsp; Web sites load faster, shareware apps download quicker.&nbsp; Unfortunately,    as far as EQ goes,&nbsp; it doesn't give your character squat!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.9.1 How is the gameplay    going to be through a 28.8 connection? I have played online RPGs and lag seems to be a big    problem. </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We don't think most of the lag    people are experiencing on these games is because they are using a 28.8. It's usually    either server based lagged or their ISP&#146;s, or somewhere in the Internet between them    and the servers. We are designing the game such that we aren't sending out more data than    a 28.8 can handle. Also, we are doing several things to reduce lag, including using very    mature network code (descended from our Tanarus game), as well as keeping the number of    people down per server, to reduce server lag.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Don't bother us with the    trifling Server Side Lag (SSL) problems of our predecessors!&nbsp; We made EverQuest    RIGHT!&nbsp; Any drunken imbecile with half a brain can write server code that doesn't    choke whenever a player sneezes the wrong w-... okay, I'll stop now.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.10 Will there be night    and day and how long does an EverQuest day last in real time?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, there is a night and day.    We are still tweaking how long each period will last -- this will be determined in the    betas. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, and we dunno    yet.&nbsp; Have patience!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.11 How dark is night? Do    I need a spell or torch to see at night?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Well, many areas are    lighted... but if you're talking about whether you can see with no torch or spells in the    bottom of a cave, I'd say no. Unless you have infravision... </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: In EverQuest,    &quot;dark&quot; means &quot;no light.&quot;&nbsp; &quot;Dark&quot; does <em>not</em> mean    &quot;a tad dimmer than full daylight.&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.12 Will there be an    active economy in the game?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, there is an economy in    EverQuest. Price will change according to supply and demand. If an item is offered more    often then bought the price will go down. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, and a far better    one than Al Gore has to offer.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.13 Will there be weather    in the game?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, you will see rain, fog,    wind, and this will affect gameplay (i.e. visibility, slippery surfaces, etc.). </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, so bring a sweater.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.13.1 Will there be    damage from the elements without proper protection? (i.e. Frostbite and Cold damage on    Velious without proper clothing?)</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, in fact you can see the    resistances to cold, fire, etc. on the screenshots of the inventory screen we've released.    </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No trolls sunbathing on    The Frigid Plain, I'm afraid.&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.14 How many cities and    other zones will there be in the game? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There should be 11 cities, and    well over 40 outdoor and adventure zones. And remember, the world will continue to expand    after the initial release. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Definitely more than    three.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.15 EverQuest is playable    from different viewpoints. Has any thought been put into ensuring that no one viewpoint    has an undue advantage over another?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">It's pretty hard to look down    a hall or a tunnel or a street in the top down view. Also, there's a lot of information    and detail in the background textures that you might miss if you're not in 1st person    mode. By their natures, different views have different advantages and disadvantages. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: What... are you saying    you don't think we know how to do our jobs?&nbsp; Huh?&nbsp; Is that what you're saying???</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.15.1 Is the EverQuest    development team doing what they can to ensure a player won't be &quot;unduly&quot;    hampered (or favored) by his or her choice of view?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">If a person were to stick to    any one view they would be at a disadvantage. The plan is to have several different user    definable camera views that are toggled between depending on the situation. &quot;Hmm, I    can't tell whether or not I can jump across this ravine... (toggle to top down view) Oh    man! That is farther than it looked in first person view.. I better find another    way.&quot; Or (in first person view) &quot;Get ready! There are a band of Orcs coming out    of the forest!&quot; (I would not have seen them if I were in top down view until they we    almost upon my party and me.) So yes, if you stick to one view and only one view more than    likely you will not live as long as someone who takes advantage of all the possible views.    </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Well... your preferred    choice of view will be determined by how well it works for you, right? &nbsp; Right?&nbsp;    Am I right?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.16 As I recall, no    existent screenshot of the adventure window shows a character from a    first-person-perspective viewpoint equipped with either weapon or shield, a la Daggerfall,    Meridian, and countless Doom clones. Why?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The August 1997 screen shots    show swords in just about all the character's hands. Different weapons and shields will    indeed appear wielded or worn by the character. Also, all the screen shots from August    were taken from first person perspective mode. But in any case, the weapons and shields    and such will show regardless of where the camera is.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Sure they are... they're    almost ALL shot from 1st person, you fool!&nbsp; You don't see the character's own weapons    because they'd be IN THE WAY, like a thumb over the camera lens.&nbsp; Now, would that be    professional photography?&nbsp; <em>I think not!</em></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.16.1 The August 1997    screenshots (or most of them) show characters being looked at with swords in hand.    However, the character that is doing the looking doesn't appear to be holding anything.    Why?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The sword just isn't visible    from the first person view because of where it is (kind of to your side). Were you to    swing it or do one of many other animations, you would see it as well as your hand, arm,    etc. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: See WTRM 3.16</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.17 How will we control    our characters? Keyboard, mouse, joystick, or combination?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Keyboard or mouse &#150; we    will support mouselook. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Keyboard, mouse, and    telekinesis.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.18 Will there be a screen    capture utility in EverQuest?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Aye, laddie!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.19 On the creatures page    there are deities. Will there be some kind of religion in EQ?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There are many different    religions. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Relax, all the    denominations will be represented.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.19.1 Will religions    affect how I should role-play my character in some ways?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">How you role-play your    character is up to you. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Not especially.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.19.2 Will there be    specific places of worship for each of the deities in the game? And what deities are there    in the game?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You will find temples    dedicated to the various gods of the pantheon spread throughout the lands of Norrath. At    this time, however, we are not ready to list every member of that pantheon beyond those    we've already revealed. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Gods are kind of    pointless without their dedicated holy places, no?&nbsp; A fully complete list of all EQ    deities can be found if you click <a href="Full_List.htm">here</a>.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.20 Can you give us hints    as to the storyline? What will be one's purpose in the game?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There's no set storyline...    just a vast history and background to the world. The players will make the stories by    interacting with the world. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: We spent all our    development dollars on management, the engineers, coffee and the company cocktail    waitresses, so we couldn't afford an actual writer for any so frivolous as a    storyline.&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.20.1 Is there a    central plot or just mindless wandering and killing things?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There is a rich history,    plenty of quests, and also the ability to mindlessly wander and kill things -- it's up to    the player to determine how involved he wants to get. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, that pretty much    sums it up for players with no imagination, like yourself.&nbsp; We all pity you.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.20.2 Will    religions/race histories be completely written by the EverQuest team? Will you accept    submissions, maybe doing contests?</strong> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The religions and histories of    the world before you players arrive will be written, but after that, you players will be    making the history and events in the world. You are welcome to chronicle those events, and    we would like submissions as well of those events. Perhaps we will post certain ones on    the web page and such, once the game has been released. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Hey!&nbsp; We know what    we want out of Norrath.&nbsp; If you want, send in a submission, and if it meets with our    scheme, we may make it official.&nbsp; Who knows?&nbsp; Life sucks when you're an    underpaid schlub working for a mega-corporation on a project that's slated to make    millions of dollars in the first quarter, slaving away day after day, no weekends, barely    any holidays, and for what?&nbsp; So don't get on my case you [expletive deleted], or I'll    [censored] all over your [*bleep*] without [*bzzzzzt*] [*whoooop*] [*clang*] [*crunch*]    [*aauugghh!!*] as did the shrunken head, dangling from a chandelier!!!!&nbsp; So, watch    it!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.21 Will +mlook be    supported in 1st person view?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Hey... how'd you know    about that?!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.22 Will towns be closed    after dark, ala Daggerfall?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">They might lock the main    gates... but since when did gates keep out a good rogue... </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Officially, yes. &nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.23 When adventuring can    we form parties?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes. In fact, you are    encouraged to form parties. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: CAN you?&nbsp; Just try    playing it solo, and count how many people laugh at you!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.23.1 What about people    who prefer to play solo? Will the solo player be &quot;crippled&quot; to the point of    unplayability or will it just be limited in where you can go what you can do?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">It will be a bit limited in    where you can go and what you can do (especially in more difficult areas), but definitely    not 'crippled' -- there are definitely race/class combos in EverQuest (Troll Shadowknight    comes to mind) that do fine as a solo character.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: That's very much a    matter of opinion.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.23.2 Will experience be    shared amongst party members? And how?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">It is, but we're not going    into details on that yet. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Oh yeah! &nbsp; That's    what I forgot to do last week... doh!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.23.3 If I'm in a party    and we kill a monster, is the experience shared the same way as if two people not in a    party kill a monster together?</b> </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No, it's different. You will    want to group up when fighting monsters. Consider this: a warrior makes the kill, but a    cleric has been healing him -- the cleric should get some experience too.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Not even close.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.23.4 Is there a limit to    the number of players that can be in a group? If so, how many?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We are currently limiting    groups to six party members.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Six shall be the number    of the counting... and the number of the counting shall be six.&nbsp; Seven shalt thou not    count, neither shalt thou count five, unless thou proceed to six. &nbsp; Eight is right    out!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.23.5 Is there command to    divvy up the gold the group (party) collects? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Good idea... let's do    that.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.24 Will there be huge    underwater areas, sort of like an underwater continent?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Not an entire continent, but    entire zones, yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Uh... how huge is    &quot;huge?&quot;&nbsp; I guess turnabout is fair play.&nbsp; (See 3.3)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.24.1 Can I fight    underwater?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Depends... are you    wearing full plate armor?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.25 Will there be a    notoriety system in which one can tell thieves and murderers apart and so they are    punished by the law or a bounty system?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, however we would hesitate    to call it a <em>notoriety</em> system, because it works very differently than other    systems you might be familiar with.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Uh, we don't use the    &quot;N&quot; word here.&nbsp; The system we use actually <em>works.</em></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.26 Are there any    plans for special servers just for those players who role-play &quot;properly&quot;?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Probably not. The debate as to    what exactly role-playing means is eternal, with few who agree with each other. Also,    servers are very expensive, so we're not sure how many we will set up and under what    conditions.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Unlikely.&nbsp; You can    talk server costs all you want, but we really don't want to offend the powergamers and all    the other factions who want the game to be played <em>their</em> way.&nbsp; Before you    know it, everyone's got their own servers, and it quickly becomes the next Diablo.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.27 Will you be able    to see the names of others just by looking at them?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">That will probably be an    option.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, you'll have to ask    to see a picture ID first.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.28 Any thought given    to cut scenes/cinematics in the final version?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We will have cinematics in the    beginning, to introduce the game, similar to most games.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: There's a thought.    &nbsp; I guess we'd better do that...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>3.29 Will there be a    &quot;rent&quot; system? Will there be restrictions as to where you can rent, and will the    items you rent with have upkeeps?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You can rent at inns, and camp    in the wilderness. As for upkeeps for your equipment, that is undetermined at this time.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Renting: good. &nbsp;    Weapon upkeeps: bad.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.3 Will there be central    meeting places like Tavern's or Fountains to meet other people? (new)</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Wh-what?&nbsp; You want    to actually meet other people in places?&nbsp; Oh, great!&nbsp; Chalk up another rewrite,    guys... we're gonna be working until 1 a.m. again.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.4 Will there be player    owned vendors in the game, and will they have a weight and item limit? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We think a significant portion    of the economy will be people who buy, sell, and trade in towns and elsewhere. We don't    feel we need to make them merchants 'officially' for them do be able to do this, nor do    they require any additional abilities. Basically, anyone can be a merchant or a vendor.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...or are you talking    outright NPC slavery like in other games?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>3.5 How will you prevent    the gaining of wealth by continually creating new characters for their starting items? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">When you begin the game, your    character starts out with items that are neither tradable nor droppable.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...nor stealable, nor    losable, nor spendable, nor destructable, nor edible, nor ...</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><strong><font color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><a    name="4.0 Characters.">4.0 Characters.</a></font><font color="#C0C0C0" size="4"> </font></strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.1 How many characters can    one person have on one account?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Eight at this time. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Exactly as many as it    can hold.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.2 If I have more than one    character, can I have both online at the same time and trade between them?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No, you may only have one    character online at any given time.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: As a corporation, we are    big supporters of the family unit... except when it comes to employees working overtime,    and <em>players</em>.&nbsp; So, if you want to play both at the same time, you gotta buy    two accounts.&nbsp; That's just the way it is.&nbsp; Business, you know.&nbsp; Sorry.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.3 Will character    improvement be skilled based or level based?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Both, and more.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes+.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.4 How many classes and    races are there? And what are they?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There are 12 races: Barbarian,    Dark Elf, Dwarf, Erudite, Gnome, Half-Elf, Halfling, High Elf, Human, Ogre, Troll, Wood    Elf. There are 14 classes: Bard, Cleric, Druid, Enchanter, Magician, Monk, Necromancer,    Paladin, Ranger, Rogue, Shadow Knight, Shaman, Warrior, Wizard.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: There are 12 races and    14 classes, and they're all good to play.&nbsp; A complete list of all races and classes    can be found <a href="http://Full_List.hem">here</a>.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.4.1 Will there be the    possibility of adding new races/classes as the game expands?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Absolutely. We look forward to    adding quite a bit to the game.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: What, 12 races and 14    classes not enough for you?&nbsp; With the existing race/class combinations right now, you    have 66 different characters to play!&nbsp; Add to that each gender, and you have 132    separate possibilities!&nbsp; Still not enough?&nbsp; Fine, we'll add more later.&nbsp; I    can't <em>believe</em> these people...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.5 Can a character be    multi-class like a warrior-mage?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There are some hybrid classes,    like Paladins (warrior-clerics), and Shadow Knights (warrior-necromancers)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Brad says no.. the rest    of the team says yes... the answer: no.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.6 Are certain classes    reserved for certain races or can all races be of any class?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, certain classes are    reserved for certain races. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Look back on WTRM 4.4.1    and do the math.&nbsp; If it looks like every race can be every class to you, maybe a    tutor is what you need.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.7 Will there be alignment    in the game? And how much of an impact will it have on gameplay?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, and a lot. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: &quot;Alignment&quot; is    a strong word.&nbsp; We prefer &quot;societal philosophic strictures set in    concrete.&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.8 Can we play male or    female characters?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...but only if you    prefer to.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.8.1 Are there    inherent differences between male and female characters?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">At this time, choosing male or    female only affects your appearance, and not necessarily your gameplay (other than the way    you personally choose to role-play).</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Uh... it affects how    many male characters hit on you, that's about it.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.9 Will we be able to    select how our character looks? I mean eyes, hair and such?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Depends on race -- some races    are more customizable than others. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Mostly, sort of... a    little... I guess.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.10 Will clothes, armor    and weapon be visible to other players?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, everybody's naked...    yes, even the ogres.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.11 Can I have a shop or    be a blacksmith like in Ultima Online?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There is no 'blacksmith' class    or official occupation per se, because we don't feel this is necessary. Any player at any    time is welcome to sell or trade items, and there will be in-game features to accommodate    players who like to do this often.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...but since we didn't    really answer the QUESTION, you can just put down &quot;no comment.&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.12 Will there be a set of    attributes we select at the creation process that will remain the same through the game    like intellect, strength and so on?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, to a point. There will be    attributes like strength, charisma, stamina, wisdom, intelligence, dexterity, and agility    -- however, these can increase or decrease with special items and spells.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No... all combat rolls    are totally random.&nbsp; Stats like strength and intelligence are just window dressing.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.13 Will I be able to put    a biography on my character for when people look at me?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">This hasn't been determined as    of yet.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: We're still trying to    convince Brad we should include that.&nbsp; Give us a while, and we're bound to find    something good to blackmail him with, so be patient.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.14 Will my character age?    And if he does can he die of old age?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">This hasn't been determined as    of yet.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Ermmmmmmmmmmm, good    idea, but with the traditional aging speeds of each race, it adds another level of play    balance for us to work out.&nbsp; We're feeling lazy right now, so, probably not.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.15 Can my character eat    and is it actually required to survive?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, your character can and    will need to eat. However, eating and drinking is not tedious, and one cannot actually    starve to death.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Just because you don't    need food to survive, doesn't mean you won't get hungry.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.16 Can my character    sleep?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There are ways to rest in the    game.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: &quot;Sleep&quot; is a    strong word.&nbsp; We prefer &quot;unconscious newbie fodder.&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.16.1 Will resting    replenish hitpoints?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, but having a cleric as a    friend is more efficient.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Fer cryin' out loud...    *yes, it will.*</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.17 Will I be able to wear    disguises?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You can alter what you wear,    which will change your appearance.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: &quot;Disguise&quot; is    a strong word...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.18 Is there a maximum    level my character can attain?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Currently, the maximum level    is 50, but that is subject to change.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: &quot;Maximum&quot; is a    strong word...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.18.1 What are your    strategies for preventing &quot;topping-out&quot; with experience points?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">At this point experience caps    aren't planned, however it will become harder and harder to make levels, so it should take    some time to reach higher levels.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: &quot;With&quot; is a    strong word...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.19 How many items can I    wear or have equipped?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There are 21 body locations in    which to wear items, as well as general inventory in which you can hold containers that    allow you to carry even more.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: 21 highly essential body    locations, not counting the head, arms, legs, and torso.&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.20 When our characters    gain experience will they change forms or change into a higher form in the class, e.g.    wizard-sorcerer, knight-paladin?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There will be titles based on    level and accomplishments.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.21 Will there be a    location available to a &quot;medley&quot; of races to begin their adventure in Norrath,    or will all starting characters be &quot;restricted&quot; to geographic areas based on    race?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Some of the races have more    flexible starting points than others, but there is no starting point for all races, no.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes and no. &nbsp; We've    tried to make a flexible system here, and if you can't find it in your heart to give a    little on your end, then go and spend your money someplace else!!&nbsp; That's    right!&nbsp; Go on, git!&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.22</strong> <strong>What    is the state of the 'name filter'. Is that something that is truly going to be    implemented?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The names you choose for your    characters in EverQuest need to fit in a setting of High Fantasy. Also, names must be    unique -- no two characters can have the same name on the same server.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, it is. &nbsp; Yes,    we mean it.&nbsp; Yes, we'll enforce it.&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.22.1 What if I    switch servers and some one has my name on the new server?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The person who was on that    server first will get to keep the name, you will have to assign a new name.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: You lose your name,    guy.&nbsp; Pick another name.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.23 How will height    affect combat?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">An example as to how height    affects combat would be that a troll will have to look down before swinging at a gnome,    otherwise he will miss.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ... Ever tried fighting    off Danny DeVito?&nbsp; Same principle.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.24 Will a character    take any damage from high falls into water, or does the fact that the player lands in    water negate damage from any height?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">If you fell far enough and    into water, you would take damage.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: If you fell far enough    into water, it would take damage.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.25 Will races have    bonuses associated with being in their preferred environment? And drawbacks relating to    the environment as well (e.g. Dark Elves in sunlight)</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Races have innate abilities    and disadvantages.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...We don't want to get    into specifics, because you already know too much.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.26 Will players be    able to save their player info at any time to avoid crash losses?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Probably not, however the    servers save character data whenever anything significant changes about them such that the    chance of a server crash causing losses is slim (note that this is a very different than    saving the entire game state every so often like other games do, which can lead to severe    crash losses).</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, but with the    character saving system we've worked out, you won't need it.&nbsp; Yes, you will be at the    mercy of this system, with no means of controlling the preservability of your character,    but that's the way -- uh huh, uh huh -- we like it!&nbsp; Uh huh, uh huh.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.27 Will GM's be able    to address problems caused by the game? if I lose skills/stats/items from bugs, can a GM    restore me?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">GMs will be able to fix    problems resulting from bugs if that bug is verifiable, and we feel it is important that    we are able to verify the vast majority of bugs and address (i.e. fix) how they wrongly    affect the game and gameplay.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: We take the term    &quot;Game Master&quot; literally in EverQuest.&nbsp; (See also WTRM 1.20.1)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.28</strong> <strong>Will    aiming at specific parts of the body be a part of combat? What about special attacks such    as tripping your opponent or impaling him with a polearm? Or is it just    stick-the-pointy-bit-into-the-soft-bit? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There is more to combat than    just swinging your weapon -- there are many combat related skills that can come into play    during combat.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Oh sure.&nbsp; It's easy    for <em>you</em> to say &quot;just stick-the-pointy-bit-into-the-soft-bit,&quot; but how    do you think that poor character of yours feels, huh?&nbsp; HUH???&nbsp; I'm not answering    until you develop some sensitivity, young man!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.29 Will there be a    kind of &quot;super class&quot;? (i.e. If you are a high enough level necromancer, you    could complete a special quest and become a lich?)</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We personally like very much    the idea that a necromancer could turn into a lich at a certain level, and other similar    ideas, but we're not sure we can get that into the first version of EverQuest. Let's both    cross our fingers and hope on that one.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...And the cleric could    even turn into a demi-god.&nbsp; And the druid could turn into an elemental. &nbsp; And    the bard could turn into a maestro.&nbsp; And the paladin could turn into a heroic    egotist.&nbsp; And the shaman could turn into a sentient life form.&nbsp; And...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.30 Do races have    different languages and if there are can we have spells to translate ?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There will be languages, the    specifics of which we cannot reveal at this time. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, but in order for us    to explain the specifics of languages, you'd have to speak trollish.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.31 In the case of a    Knight/Paladin will there be certain acts if committed that would strip the Paladin of his    bonuses... thus becoming a fighter?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There will be restrictions to    certain classes, and it is possible they could lose some or all of their powers.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.32 Will there be a    notoriety/alignment system ?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There will be alignments of    sorts, but that is one of the areas in EverQuest (like magic) that we are keeping to    ourselves for a while.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.33 Will certain    armor/weapons be off limits to mages? (no mages in full plates wielding 400lb halberds)?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There are race and class    restrictions to items.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.33.1 Can Paladins and    Shadow Knights (both hybrid classes that can fight well and use magic) cast spells while    wearing plate or other heavy armor?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Both classes may cast in full    plate, and even pure magic-users can still hold staffs and such while casting (no, they    can't wear plate). Why? Because it becomes very tedious, regardless of 'realism', swapping    items in and out all the time before casting.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.34 Will clerics be    able to wield weapons?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, they will be able to    wield weapons such as maces. They are turning out to be formidable fighters.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Some, yes.    (&quot;Some&quot; meaning the weapons, not the clerics.)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>4.35 Will bards be a    viable class?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, one of our programmers    has a soft spot in his heart for bards so they are well taken care of. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Some, yes... er... I    mean &quot;yes.&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.36 Trolls traditionally    have innate regeneration -- do they in EverQuest and what does it do?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, trolls heal (get their    hit points back) more quickly than do other races.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Trolls heal faster than,    say, an elf with diabetes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.37 What exactly are    Shadow Knights? Are they similar to Paladins (warrior/clerics) or more like the    traditional anti-paladin?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Shadow Knights are    warrior/necromancers, not warrior/necromancer/clerics (that would be too powerful). Nor    are they warrior/evil clerics because we didn't want them to just be stereotypical    anti-paladins -- we wanted them to be something new and different. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Shadow Knights are    warrior/wizard/enchanter/necromancer/cleric/magician/fighter/druid/monk/paladin/ranger/rogue/bards.    &nbsp; But hey, don't let that influence your choice of class to play.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>4.38 After looking at all    of the exotic races one can play in the game, why would someone want to play a human?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There are several reasons, the    significance of which will depend on what one wants out of a character, of course. Among    the best of these is that innate ability in one more areas is offset by deficiencies in    other areas; for example, if a player's priorities lie in the area of brute force, then    s/he is likely to play a troll or an ogre, but with the drawback of below average    resistance to some spells, due to a very low intelligence. Dark elves, who can see in the    dark and who tend to make excellent magic-users, are generally despised by many of    Norrath's inhabitants, which makes it more difficult for them to find merchants who will    sell them anything, or even purchase any goods they might have to offer.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Humans, on the other hand, are    probably the single best well-rounded race in the game. While it is possible for a human    to excel and specialize in some class or trade, they are comparatively neutral in their    inborn statistics, so while they don't have the strength of an ogre or the enhanced senses    of an elf, they don't suffer any special drawbacks, either (comparatively speaking). It's    all a question of that with which a player is willing to live.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Hey, if you feel that    way, then we can think of NO reason you'd want to play a human!</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><strong><font color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><a    name="5.0 Skills.">5.0 Skills.</a></font><font color="#C0C0C0" size="4"> </font></strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>5.1 Are all skills    available to all classes or races or are some race or class specific?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Some skills are available to    all races and classes, for instance swimming. Some, however, are available to only certain    races and classes, for instance stealing is only a skill for the rogue class.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Some skills are    available to all races and classes, for instance ritualistic homicide.&nbsp; Some,    however, are available to only certain races and classes, for instance    pointy-eared-ring-tossing is only a skill for the elf race.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>5.2 Can you tell us some of    the skills that will be in the game?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We can name a few (swimming,    backstabbing, stealing, dual wielding, bandage), however we won't post a detailed list    until we are very near open beta.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: For a complete list of    skills, please click <a href="Full_List.htm">here</a>.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>5.3 Do I have all the    skills available to my character at the beginning or do I need to learn them?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You start with some, you earn    others as your character progresses.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Both.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>5.4 How do I learn new    skills? From NPCs or can other players teach me? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">To learn new skills and    improve on old ones, you must find a trainer or go to your guild hall.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: You learn skills through    total psychic and spiritual immersion in the game.&nbsp; Only then will the true skills of    your character manifest themselves unto you.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>5.5 Do skills deteriorate    when not used?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Probably not.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...And we mean that from    the heart.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>5.6 Can I learn all skills    at the beginning or do some have restrictions like being a certain level or having another    skill?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Some skills will have    restrictions, and some skills are not learnable until higher levels.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...and some skills can't    be learned by ANY race!&nbsp; Wrap your mind around that one, Stephen Hawking!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>5.7 Will dual weapon    combat be available?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Dual Wielding is a skill some    classes get. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, but only for races    with two arms.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>5.7.1 Will two weapon    fighting be limited to the warrior/ranger class, or will it be available to a wider range    of classes (rogues and paladins?)</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Depends on how testing goes --    if one class is determined to be too weak, we might add more skills and abilities to that    class. So it's really too early to say exactly which races and classes will have what    abilities and skills, other than a few general and obvious ones.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: We dunno.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>5.8 How will skills be    raised? Will it be on a level/distribute points scale or more along the lines of practice    a lot while you level?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Your skills go up as you use    them, but they can only go up so much per level, and certain skills won't be available to    the player until he reaches certain levels.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No comment.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>5.9 What miscellaneous    skills will there be? Will there be other arts like bandaging?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There will be many skills,    many related to combat, but then also non-combat related skills as well. Bandage is one    skill, yes, however we're not ready yet to release a list.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No comment.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>5.10 Is swimming    available to all races or is it limited?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">All races start out with    swimming as a skill.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Tsk tsk tsk.&nbsp; You    didn't read question 5.1, did you?&nbsp; For shame!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>5.11 How are skills    activated? Are they automatic or do I have to use them manually? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Some skills trigger    automatically, while others are activated manually</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...Ever drink    half-and-half cream right out of the carton?&nbsp; That would be a skill that could not be    triggered automatically (or by accident).</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>5.11.1 If some are    manually activated, how will I access them? Buttons, quick slots, hot keys, or what?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">In your interface you will    have 6 quick slots for combat related skills and 12 slots for social skills. You can also    assign skills by adding them as buttons to your screen.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: It's called an    &quot;interface,&quot; and EQ comes with one for your convenience, no extra charge.</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><strong><font color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><a    name="6.0 Magic.">6.0 Magic.</a></font><font color="#C0C0C0" size="4"> </font></strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>6.1 How many types of magic    are there?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">5 primary schools of magic. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...Count 'em! &nbsp;    Red, Orange, black, Green, Blue, and Purple!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>6.2 Can you tell us some of    the spells?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We can list some at this time:    levitate, water breathing, healing, and fireball and other offensive spells. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: For a complete list of    spells, click <a href="Full_List.htm">here</a>.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.2.1 When will you be    releasing some spells for each class?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We won't be releasing    information on magic until we are very close to open beta.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Why'd you ask that    question?&nbsp; We've already done that!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>6.3 Will magic be mana    based, or reagents, or spellbooks?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The magic system is primarily    mana based, but that doesn't necessarily rule out reagents completely.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, yes, and yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>6.4 Do I have all the    spells available to my character at the beginning or do I need to learn them?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You start with some, you earn    others as your character progresses.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Spells are like    skills... see question 5.6</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>6.5 How do I learn new    spells? From NPCs or can other players teach me?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We can't go into that yet.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: The way it works, is...    I tell you all about the magic system and Brad fires my sorry butt, see.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>6.6 Do spells deteriorate    when not used?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Probably not.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, atrophy is an absurd    idea for any massively multiplayer online roleplaying game.&nbsp; I mean, the very thought    is an abomination to the entire industry!&nbsp; Who have you been talking to?&nbsp; Tell    me!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>6.7 Can I create new    spells?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Nay, laddie.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>6.8 Can I enchant weapons? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The Enchanter class can    enchant weapons.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, players can <em>not</em>    enchant weapons.&nbsp; Enchanter-class <em>characters</em> you play can.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.8.1 Is that all the    Enchanter will be good for, enchanting magic items?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No. The Enchanter class can be    a very valuable member of any party.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...Hmmm, though that    statement is under scrutiny of late... Let's just say that the operative phrase here is    &quot;can be,&quot; and we'll leave it at that.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>6.9 Area effect spells --    will PKers be able to kill non-PKers with them?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No, PK area affect spells will    only affect other PKers and NPC's.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Heresy you speak! &nbsp;    </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>6.9.1 How are area effect    spells handled. Are my group members immune form my area effect spells? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, they are immune from    offensive area spells cast by a caster in their group.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Group members are not    immune to area effect spells that are never cast by someone who is not in the group, ever.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.10 Can you elaborate    on how balanced magic and non-magic attacks will be?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The idea behind having a class    system is that the different classes will have advantages and disadvantages. If we do our    jobs and balance these classes, then none of them will have inherent advantages over the    other. A mage might beat a warrior under certain conditions, and vice versa.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: A sword through the    skull about does in a wizard.&nbsp; A lightning bolt through the skull does pretty much    the same thing to a warrior.&nbsp; And that's all she wrote.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.11 Are you going to    try to emphasize the use of ships for long distance travel, instead of making a transport    type of spell commonly accessible?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Transport spells will exist,    but they will be very high level and hard to come by. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, no &quot;beam me up,    Scotty&quot; in EQ.&nbsp; Well... <em>some.</em></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.12 Concerning spell    targeting, will spells automatically hit it's target or will some actual aiming be    required in order to hit your target with a spell?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">I'm afraid we cannot comment    on the mechanics of targeting and spells at this point.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...&quot;and I did <em>not</em>    have sexual relations with that woman!&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.12.1 From how far    away will I be able to cast a spell on a target?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The effect of long distance    spell casting is directly related to the type of spell (in other words, it depends on the    spell).</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No farther than twice    the length of a troll's toe after being crushed by the tip of Veeshan's talon.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.13 Will the    Necromancer be able to Summon, Command, or Create Undead?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, but only if the    undead is willing to answer to the name &quot;Hazel.&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.13.1 Will there be a    limit as to the number of undead a single necromancer can create/control at one time, and    if so, will greater experience allow you to create/control more?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, a limit. The higher the    level the more powerful the undead -- not necessarily the quantity here, but rather the    quality.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Animate in the    underworld, and the underworld animates with you.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.14 Will spells be    scroll based or book based?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Both. You will obtain new    spells by finding scrolls. Once you have a scroll you must scribe it into your spell book.    Once the spell is successfully scribed, the scroll will disappear. It is then permanently    scribed into you spell book.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Neither.&nbsp; Spells    will be controlled by bashing rocks together like the cavemen in 2001: A Space Odyssey.    &nbsp; It was either that or having the characters speak certain words, emote certain body    movements using various reagents, and memorizing spells but we didn't want to go through    the trouble.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.14.1 Do I have to    learn a scribe skill to do this?&quot;</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No. You &quot;scribe&quot; it    into your book by simply dragging the scroll to an open slot in your book. This process    takes some time to complete. You can be interrupted while doing this.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: You have to learn the    very deft skill of dragging the scroll to your spell book using that mouse thingy    connected to your computer.&nbsp; Depending on the particular player, this can take    anywhere from one month to a year of real time to master.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.14.2 How will I find    new scrolls?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">By killing monsters, finding    treasure, and completing quests</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: You find a GM and say    that you lost all your scrolls in the last server crash.&nbsp; If you're convincing    enough, you may get them to help you.&nbsp; Whining, tantrums, bribes, crude insults, and    unrelented sobbing can each play a big part in this process.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.15 How many of the    spells in my spell book will I have immediate access to?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You can have access to 8 of    your spells at one time. These spells are &quot;memorized&quot; into your 8 interface    slots.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Assuming you've    convinced a GM to give you any spells, you may then access them by hitting Alt-F4 many    many times repeatedly until it does what you want.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.15.1 How do I    memorize these spells?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">By dragging the spell from    your spell book to an open slot on your screen. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Well, you're not going    to learn anything by using your spellbook to balance the kitchen table, now are you?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.16 Will there be    very powerful spells?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, although they will be    very hard to come by and very hard to cast. Some may require that you complete long quests    just to cast them. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, in fact we thought    it wise to include a spell that will completely obliterate the coherent intellect of every    living creature on the server, by turning them all into Al Franken.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.17 Will spells cast    instantly or have a casting time?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Different spells will have    different casting times, which can also be affected by your skill in that magical art.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ... The effects of the    Al Franken spell take place <em>before</em> you even cast the spell.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>6.18 Are Clerics going    to just be traveling healers?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No. Clerics are pretty    formidable fighters and can wear armor and wield maces.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Clerics pray softly, but    they carry big sticks!&nbsp; (But not in the RUDE sense.)</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><a    name="7.0 NPC and creatures."><strong>7.0 NPCs and creatures.</strong></a></font><font    color="#C0C0C0" size="3"> </font></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.1 How much interaction    will there be with the NPCs? Will they just sell and buy stuff?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">They'll do a lot more than    that, including providing in-game information and quests.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Not at all... you can    also hug them, and squeeze them, and call them &quot;George.&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.2 Can you kill NPCs?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, and that's fairly    integral to the game. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...They may protest this    by sliding their blade through your soft, quivering abdomen... but hey, you're welcome    give it a go.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>7.2.1&nbsp; If an NPC    dies, will it be replaced by another, or will it just return? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The NPC may or may not return    right away, nor will he necessarily be in the same place.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: The NPC returns to the    world of the living as a spectral apparition that haunts you until you can't see anymore    because of all the dead NPCs who are constantly in your line-of-sight.&nbsp; Eventually,    in the heat of a panicked frenzy, you blindly plunge yourself into a deep chasm, losing    yourself in its abysmal depths for the whole of eternity.&nbsp; It never fails.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.3 Will monsters all act    the same during combat? Or will some retreat when hurt, or follow you until either they    are dead or you are?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The latter, depending upon the    intelligence and type of the monster with whom you are fighting.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Every creature in    EverQuest acts the same.&nbsp; It doesn't matter if you're fighting a dragon or a puddle    of semi-evolved sinal mucus... you should use the same tactics all the time, no matter    what.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.3.1 Are we going to see a    change in monsters and NPCs depending on time of day?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">It all depends on the NPC. For    instance, we can assign a skeleton to only appear during the evening.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...We can also assign    Wayne Newton to only appear during cocktail hour, for your enjoyment.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.3.2 Will NPCs treat    different members of a group differently, depending upon the level of the party member or    for other reasons?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Again, it really depends on    their intelligence. Certain NPCs will go after spell casters, certain NPCs will go after    who hit them the hardest last, certain NPCs like an animal will attack whatever is closest    since they don&#146;t know any better, certain ones will flee at certain times, certain    ones will fight to the death &#150; it all depends on the NPC.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ... So, don't expect a    gelatinous cube to show a level 50 necromancer any more respect than the pile of roaches    it found in the corner of its room and consumed the other day.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.4 Will NPCs use magic?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Some, yes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...But they would never    do something so vicious as try to use it against <strong><em>YOU!</em></strong> &nbsp;    That would be mean and in poor taste.&nbsp; So they will only use magic against players    whose intelligence are, in their estimation, denigrated by their own computer AI. &nbsp;    Man, do we ever feel sorry for <em>those</em> sorry people.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.4.1 Are some of the    creatures going to use spells during fights?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Some, yes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Could you repeat the    question <em>one more time</em>, senator?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.5 Will some of the    creatures/monsters be the same races and classes as our characters? I mean can I fight a    human mage NPC?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: The NPC human mage has a    propensitory disposition toward that which is apocryphal in nature.&nbsp; By and large, an    immediate aptitude for bipartisan interaction over and above any human moral certitude is    defined by his innate ability to override the predominant characteristics of being the    subject of automated computer manipulation.&nbsp; Further complicated by the gratuitous    notion of disparaged, unrelented violence, the aural and ocular sensory perception    proceeds to rectify the cranial stimulation of the hypothalamus, whereby resulting in a    continual state of euphoric certitude on the player's behalf.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.6 How many types of    monsters will there be in the game?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There should be well over 40    types of monsters -- see the Bestiary in the almanac section for a partial listing.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: For a complete listing    of the monster types, please click <a href="Full_List.htm">here</a>.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.6.1 Is that 40 monster    types or 10 types with palette swaps?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We'll try to get as many in    there as we can. Look at it this way: there will be far more than 40 monsters, but how    different they will look from one another is a different story. For instance, will an Orc    slave look different from an Orc commoner... probably not, but we shall see.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ... Hmm, well... I    suppose it <em>is</em> only 10 monster types with palette swaps.&nbsp; Maybe the NPCs are    only using magic against <em>us</em> after all. (See WTRM 7.4)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>7.7 Can I hire an NPC to    protect my belongings for me? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Magicians can summon    elementals, and Necromancers can raise the dead -- these creatures can be instructed to    protect their master from harm.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Sort of, but not the way    you're wanting to.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>7.9 Will there be    animals, and if so, maybe a taming skill?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There will be animals, and    other monsters, and these animals may be charmed. (please read the description of    Enchanters)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Taming skill?&nbsp; Pah!    &nbsp; If you want NPCs to do your bidding in EverQuest, ya gotta be able to do more than    housebreak the average cat!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>7.10 Traditionally    Orcs, Goblins, and the like have a hierarchy of leaders. What most fantasy games lack is    the portrayal of this system. In EQ, will beasts travel in packs with obvious leaders and    obvious goals (e.g. to acquire gold, hunt for food, etc.)?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The more intelligent the    monster, the more intelligently it will act. We are putting a lot of effort into our NPC    AI system.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: We're trying our best.    &nbsp; Why don't <strong><em>YOU</em></strong> try sitting behind the screen day after    day, coming up with a way to make an Alpha workstation act like a <em>positronic brain</em>    sometime and see how you like it, Mr. Fancypants?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>7.11 Will    &quot;evil&quot; races such as Trolls, Ogres, and Dark Elves, have towns and cities that    reflect their general alignment? Like killing members of other &quot;hated&quot; races on    sight? Or perhaps some other method to discourage unwelcome tourists?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There are definitely hatreds    between some of the races on the world of Norrath, and those races would not allow each    other to enter their cities and other areas they control.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, they have a    tendency to barbecue any enemy race that comes near their territory.&nbsp; Discouraging    enough for you?&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>7.11.1 Is it possible    for a member of an unwelcome race to sneak into another race's city and stay out of sight    to spy or something?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, it would be possible    under the right circumstances for an unwelcome race to sneak into another race's city.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, it is possible for    a member of an unwelcome race to sneak into another race's city and stay out of sight to    spy or something.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>7.12 Will there be    outside GMs (in other words, GMs that don't work for Sony)?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">A decision on that hasn't been    made yet, but we personally would like that opportunity to exist (non-Sony GMs). Hopefully    in the future we'll be able to announce whether this will occur or not.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: See 12.8.1 for detailed    information on how to sign up as a GM.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>7.13 Can a player flee    from Guards if they're fast enough? If guards are not invincible, will they team up (call    for back up) if they are being beat?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">It is possible that you could    flee successfully from a guard, and yes, they will team up on you.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Relax, we don't believe    in teleporting, invincible, juggernaught guards in EverQuest.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>7.14 If someone is    attacked by an NPC and runs to town to obtain help from the guards, will a guard kill the    monster with one hit?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">That would depend on how    powerful the monster is and how powerful that particular guard is.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Relax, we don't believe    in teleporting, invincible, juggernaught guards in EverQuest.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>7.15 Will guards    &quot;Spawn&quot; like they do in UO or will a group be able to kill off the guards of a    city and effectively fend off the other guards by, for example, sinking their ship when    they attempt to retake the city?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The details of how NPCs spawn    or repopulate is not something we can go into details on, other than to say it is <strong>very</strong>    flexible, and will depend on the zone and situation you are in.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Relax, we don't believe    in teleporting, invincible, juggernaught guards in EverQuest.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>7.16 Are horses yet    created as a means of travel. And if not, have you ever considered the possibility of    dragon travel? This also opens the option of Air-to-air combat.</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Horses may be added post-ship,    but won't be available at release. Air to air combat and dragon riding won't be in the    game.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Listen, little pimple,    riding dragons ain't gonna happen, okay?&nbsp; Learn to accept that and move on to bigger    things in life... like dressing yourself.</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><strong><font color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><a    name="8.0 Items and properties.">8.0 Items and properties.</a></font><font color="#C0C0C0"    size="4"> </font></strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>8.1 Will there be some    magic items in the game?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Not some, a lot! </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Saying there will be    &quot;some&quot; magic in EverQuest is like saying the ocean has &quot;some&quot; water in    it.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>8.2 Are some items going to    be unique, where there is only one in the game?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, we call them artifacts.    They will be awarded to characters who do remarkable things. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...like tweak Aradune's    nose and live to tell about it.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>8.3 Are there going to be    some weapons or armor that are the best in the game? Will everyone be wearing the same    armor or use the same weapon because it's the best there is? Or will armor and weapons    have advantages and disadvantages?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">'Best' will be very subjective    and relative to what the player wants for his character. It will also be situational. If    one item gives you fire protection, it may be essential in the volcano level, but useless    in the underwater zone. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Come to think of it,    there is a type of armor called &quot;Super Molecular-Enhanced Plate of Unsurpassed    Protection Against All Harm&quot; and a kind of weapon called &quot;Ultimate Sword of    Unbeatable -PVP Slaughtering.&quot; But other than that, absolutely not.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>8.4 Are all items useable    by all races and classes?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Some are, some aren't. Weapons    can be set to be usable by only particular races and classes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Depends on the item.    &nbsp; A halberd is one thing, but not every race can figure out how to program their VCR.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>8.5 Will weapons, armor and    other items wear out with use? If so will we have a blacksmith skill to repair them, or a    spell, or will some NPCs be able to do it?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We&#146;re haven&#146;t    decided that yet.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: As developers, we have    to say that we think it would make the game more realistic, but as players, we never liked    it ourselves.&nbsp; So really we think the solution is to take a cookie break as a team,    break up into discussion groups, and just think about it.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>8.6 Can we set up a    &quot;safe&quot; house or rent a &quot;safe&quot; room? Or maybe safety deposit boxes in    banks in major cities? Just a place to store items and treasures? Note: this implies that    you go adventuring in order to afford rent.</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">A house will be as    &quot;safe&quot; as you make it. Some may be vulnerable, some may not be, and some may be    in-between.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...We realize this    sounds suspiciously like hype from a certain other massively multiplayer online    roleplaying game out there, but...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.6.1 What will be    done to curtail the &quot;urban sprawl&quot; of houses?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Houses will not be allowed to    be arbitrarily built&nbsp;anywhere, and the cost of building a house will be very    expensive.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ... We realize that not    only does this sound suspiciously like hype from a certain other massively multiplayer    online roleplaying game out there, but it also <em>smells</em> like hype that's turned    into waist-high manure in the past.&nbsp; But please bear with us... really!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.6.2 Will certain    races have different player-buildings than other races?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Races definitely have    different styles of architecture, which would extend to houses built for players.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...But when it comes to <em>player</em>-owned    houses, well, one cardboard box looks about the same as another.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.6.3 Will houses have    locks that require a key to open them, and the key is in turn stealable, or will there be    another system, like a combination?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We're not going to go into    details on exactly how keys and/or combinations work at this time.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Locks?&nbsp; Keys?    &nbsp; Sheesh, we're not <em>gods!</em>&nbsp; Then again, we are...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.6.4 Will we be able    to have player bought houses underground? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We have no general problem    with them underground, however do keep in mind that one will be restricted in general as    to where one can have a house built.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Uh... we dunno. &nbsp;    Maybe.&nbsp; Okay sure, why not?&nbsp; Well, on second thought, maybe not...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>8.7 Will a long sword,    broad sword, and short sword all look the same or will they each have their own look?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We'll fit as many different    images as we can in, for each type of item. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...Players can be so <em>DEMANDING</em>    sometimes!&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.8 Will there be    ship-ship combat? If so, will it be with projectile weapons and spells of crew members or    will ships have their own methods of attack (i.e. Cannons)?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No, the emphasis in EverQuest    is on that of interacting with your character and other characters, not on vehicles.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: You want ship-to-ship    combat?&nbsp; Go play Wing Commander!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.9 Will we be able to    interact extensively with our environment? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We are very happy with how    interactive the world is, and just how many places you can go. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...and as long as we're    happy, that's what's important!&nbsp; Feed us, we're hungry.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.10 Will people be    able to purchase 'safety deposit' boxes or some such in order to store items and other    valuables?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">One can store items and money    in banks, which are typically found in the various cities of Norrath.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: To make a long    explanation short (too late), yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.11 Are boats hollow?    i.e will things be able to be stowed away below deck, and will you be able to go down into    the boat?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The larger ships are indeed    explorable and have rooms and such.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Ditto.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.12 Will there be a    &quot;decay&quot; rate, as in certain items only last so long? This would prevent certain    people from having the &quot;invincible&quot; set of equipment and require them to    actually go out and get it again?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We can't comment on 'decay'    rates at this point, sorry.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Sure, you want mayo with    that?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.13 Will rivers be    barriers to travel without swim skill? If so, will bridges/ferries come into play (as    strategic chokepoints)?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There will be ferries and    bridges and you can swim.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Rivers will be barriers    after a fashion, but since the swimming skill is inherent in every character, I wouldn't    recommend placing your valuables behind just a moat.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.14 Will we be able    to build and destroy buildings and boats?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: You sadistic psychopath!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.15 Is there an    upkeep associated with owning a house? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes. Not only are houses    extremely expensive, but there will be a periodic fee that guilds and players must pay,    lest they lose ownership of their houses and halls.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Ohhhhh yah!&nbsp; Count    on it!&nbsp; Whooo baby!&nbsp; Big-time!&nbsp; You just have no idea.&nbsp; I'm tellin'    ya... etc.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.16 How will the    money system work? i.e. just gold, or gold, silver, and copper, all of certain worth?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Platinum, gold, silver, and    copper. Also, some gems and such.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM:Gold alone would be    sooooo boring.&nbsp; Who would want that?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.16.1 What are the    relationships between the different types of money?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Currently 1000 Copper=100    Silver, 100 Silver=10 Gold, 10 Gold=1 Platinum.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: It's a 10:1 relationship    between all currencies.&nbsp; If you don't know what that means, then we suggest you go    play Mickey's Math Wonderland until you do.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.17 Will we be able    to log off safely on ships?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Probably, yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Try it when we release    the game and see.&nbsp; We have enough to worry about without being bothered by such    trifles.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>8.18 Will there be    public ships/caravans that can take you safely from city to city or continent to    continent?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">In some cases, yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...but ONLY in some    cases!&nbsp; Don't forget that!</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="4" face="Arial"><a name="9.0 Quests."><strong>9.0    Quests. </strong></a></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>9.1 What kind of quests can    we expect in EverQuest? Simple quests, like go fetch something for an NPC, or more complex    quests that will require either teamwork or finding clues as to how to accomplish the    quests?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Both. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...There's another    question I'm glad we asked.&nbsp; (See also 1.20)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>9.2 Are the quests    generated automatically or will there be some kind of GM introducing major quests once in    a while?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Both. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ... And another. (See    9.1)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>9.3 How will the quests be    reset? I mean can I do the same quest over and over?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We can't go into this right    now. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Get away from me, kid.    &nbsp; Ya bother me.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>9.4 Will quests be    reserved for larger guilds, or will we see NPC dictated adventure for those who opt for a    party-based system? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There will be plenty of quests    for all sorts of people, whether individual, or in parties, or members of large guilds. As    for GM run quests, we don't have infinite time and resources, so these will be limited,    but not necessarily limited only to guilds. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No promises... but we    assure you it will be so totally way kewl, you'll just want to run outside and scream    loudly and hurl large objects at everyone who isn't playing the game at the moment.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>9.5 You mention that    GM's would be able to provide quests/adventures for any player at any time. However, how    do you plan to actually accomplish the feat of having GM's provide quests for 1000 +    players per server? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Certainly our GMs will not be    providing custom quests at all times of the day for all players. However, they will quite    often do so, meaning they will create dynamic custom quests. If you the player are in the    right place at the right time, you may encounter a GM instead of an AI controlled NPC.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: We'll handle it one way    or another. But keep in mind, with upwards of 1500 people on a server at one time, your    chances of you accidentally coming across a GM in drag is as likely as truth from the    White House.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>9.6 Will there be a    bulletin board in the towns that tell of quests and things that are occurring?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Sure, why not?&nbsp; But    don't let anyone else know, otherwise everyone will want one, too.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>9.7 Will there be    raids/bands of orcs, or whatever type of main monster or race? If so will they be real    raids as in attacking towns and such? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Sure, why not?&nbsp; But    don't let anyone else know, otherwise everyone will want one, too.</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><a name="10.0 Guilds."><strong>10.0    Guilds.</strong></a></font><font color="#C0C0C0" size="3"> </font></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>10.1 Will there be guilds    in the game? Game operated guilds like a thieves guild or just player run guilds?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Both. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>10.2 Will there be special    guilds functions? Like ranks or the ability to buy a guildhall?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Both.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>10.3 Can guilds have    special clothes or uniforms, or a logo on their shield?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">If we can accommodate this to    some degree, we will try. This all depends on memory constraints and how busy things    become after release of the retail version of the game.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: That's a good idea we'd    like to create, but not everyone has a 5 gig hard drive just to hold all the millions of    guild skins,&nbsp; coats-of-arms, etc.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>10.4 If my guild becomes    very big and active, will there be special quests for it? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, sometimes we will    introduce quests for very active guilds.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ... <em>very </em>active    guilds.&nbsp; We're talking &quot;New York&quot; here, not &quot;Mayberry.&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>10.5 What will the    government be like in EQ? Will there be company rulers (Like Lord British and Blackthorn),    or could players start their own government? If so, will you support them in some way,    give them tools or such?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There is no overall ruler of    the lands of Norrath -- there are many kings, dukes, lords, etc. ruling different parts of    the land. As for players starting their own government, they could take over an area, and    attempt to hold it and enforce their own laws should they choose to do so.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ... As for tools and    such, we'll be happy to give out party hats to those campaigning for office.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>10.5.1 Will players be    able to take over cities and the surrounding lands? How will this be handled if it is    possible?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">I assume one would take over    an area by enforcing your rule upon it, by threat of violence or something else. A group    could certainly kill NPCs in an area, and all PK players, and in that way 'take over' a    section of the world.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Ever heard of the Third    Reich?&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>10.6 Will guilds be    able to declare war and fight without interruption or penalty?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">It depends where they choose    to conduct their battles. A guild war in the streets of Qeynos will not be tolerated by    the guards.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: ...unless, of course, a    particularly large guild declares war on the guards themselves.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>10.7 Is there some way    that newbies will be introduced in-game to other newer players to adventure together, or    will everyone just be thrown into the common &quot;town center&quot; to fend for    themselves?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We're creating a game with an    emphasis on cooperation and group play, however we don't feel we can force new players or    otherwise to interact with others. We can only provide the tools to make it easier for    them to do so (the fact that you can 'tell' to a person anywhere in the world, 'gsay' to    people in your group, sharing experience with people in your group, etc).</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes, Pro Wrestling is    fake.&nbsp; Next question...?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>10.8 Will guilds be    officially recognized in some way in the game?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Of course they will.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>10.9 Will you work    along with famous, very dedicated guilds or players? Perhaps honor them with a role of a    villain for players to battle against, or give the guild special privileges and a guild    house in town? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Of course we will.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>10.10 Will there be a    way for players to declare their own quests in game through a sort of world wide notice? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, through in-game bulletin    boards.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Of course there will    be... it's called &quot;EQ Vault!&quot;&nbsp; (<a href="http://www.eqvault.net">http://www.eqvault.net</a>)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>10.11 Will there be a    limit to the number of official guilds on the game? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Most likely, yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Of course    there...uh...what do you mean by &quot;official?&quot;&nbsp; Are you saying something bad    about our mommas?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>10.12 Is it okay to    have a multi-race guild?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Sure, you are welcome to make    a multi-race guild.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: If you think you can    pull it off, then go for it.</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><strong><font color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><a    name="11.0 Pkilling and death.">11.0 Pkilling and other player vs. player issues.</a></font><font    color="#C0C0C0" size="4"> </font></strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>(note that in this section    two new terms are used: +pvp and -pvp (pvp stands for player vs. player). Previous FAQs    have used the term PK and non-PK. Essentially, +pvp means PK, and -pvp means non-PK).</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.1 Will player killing    (PK) be allowed in the game?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Player killing is a subject    that is debated constantly on the net, and both sides to this eternal argument have great    points. We want to accommodate both gameplay styles (player killing and non-player    killing), but we don&#146;t want to separate the players in terms of which servers they    can play on. So soon after a player creates a character, he or she will choose whether    they want to participate in player killing or not. If they choose not to, then they will    be immune to other player&#146;s assaults, and can only die in battle against NPCs. But    those who like the added danger of player vs. player competition can simply create their    character with player killing switched to on and then do battle with those who have chosen    similarly.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There has been some concern    that this feature could limit freedom and role playing, but if you really think about it,    the bottom line is that the only thing you can&#146;t do in EverQuest because of the PK    switch is kill another player who doesn&#146;t want to be killed. And while this will    purposely curtail the few who can only have fun at the expense of others&#146; enjoyment,    the rest of us can go ahead and have a great time playing the game, regardless of whether    our personal definition of role-playing includes player vs. player or not.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.2 I've heard about this    PK switch. How will this work? Is it something you select at the beginning when creating    your character or is it something one can toggle on and off at will?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Shortly after creating your    character, you have the option of becoming +pvp (by solving a simple quest). If you choose    not to PK, only NPCs can kill you. Certain actions can switch you from -pvp to +pvp, and    it may be possible to switch back, although if we do allow this, it will be a long and    hard series of tasks one must complete before switching back to -pvp. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, it can't be    exploited to make overall combat unfair.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.3 If I have my PK switch    set to -pvp, can I heal a friend while he fights another player?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, but that will most likely    result in you switching to +pvp (you are given fair warning before this occurs). </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, it can't be    exploited to make PVP combat unfair.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.3.1 If I have my PK    switch set to -pvp, can I heal a friend while he fights a monster without turning +pvp?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">A -pvp cleric will become +pvp    anytime they heal a +pvp player (again, you are given fair warning before this occurs). </font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, it can't be    exploited to make NPC combat unfair.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.3.2 If a healer    heals a +pvp person while they are *not* in battle, will the healer's PK switch also be    turned to +pvp?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, any aid a -pvp character    renders to a +pvp character would result in his own status switching to +pvp.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">WTRM: No, it can't be    exploited to make healing unfair.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.4 Can I steal items, or    pickpocket, with a -pvp character? Wouldn't that make it impossible for people to    retaliate? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You may not steal from another    player if you are -pvp. You can, however, steal from NPCs. If you are +pvp, you may steal    from both +pvp players and NPCs.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><font color="black" size="2">WTRM: No, it can't be    exploited to make stealing unfair.</font><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2"> </font></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.4.1 If I am -pvp and go    adventuring with my friend who is +pvp and another player kills him, can I take his stuff    before the killer steals it?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No, a -pvp character cannot    loot a +pvp corpse. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: No, it can't be    exploited to make looting unfair.&nbsp; Give it up, already!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.5 Are there negative    consequences to Pkilling? Like getting arrested in cities, not being able to shop, and    other similar deterrents?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">In general, yes, but keep in    mind that with 12 races, many of which simply do not get along well with each other, there    will be plenty of cases where Pkilling makes sense in terms of role-playing.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: If a player decides to    go on a rampage and try to slaughter every living creature he comes by, then he will    definitely have a few problems building a social life.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.6 Will some areas be    safe-zones or can you be killed anywhere even in shops?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No safe-zones, but there will    be consequences if you do it in civilized areas. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: &quot;Guards! &nbsp;    They're stealing!&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.7 Will there be guards    in the cities?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, and they don't react well    to PKilling.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: No, the guards will be    out in the wilderness, making sure nobody hurts the monsters.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.8 Will there be any    environments where a -pvp player can challenge another -pvp player? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, there will be Arenas and    other locations where -pvp characters can fight one another -- the fight is not to the    death, but rather to unconsciousness, and the victor will be unable to loot the loser's    corpse. Also, a -pvp player can challenge another -pvp player to a duel, and if both    consent, they can fight to the death just as if they were +pvp.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: ... got all that? &nbsp;    Good, 'cuz we ain't repeating it!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.8.1 Can someone I'm    dueling have his or her friends heal them during the fight? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No, no one else may interfere    in any way.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Nope, it's like    Highlander.&nbsp; If you're &quot;immortal,&quot; you have certain rules of combat. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.8.2 Is there the    possibility of allowing multiple people to participate in duels? </b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Not at this time, but we'll    toss the idea around. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: The team thinks that    would be great... but the coders are feeling lightheaded at the notion, though, so we'll    have to get back to you on that.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.8.3</strong> <b>Isn't    dueling technically PKilling? Why should someone who is -pvp be allowed to duel?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">The -pvp option is designed to    allow adventuring without the necessity of dealing with non-role-playing attacks from PKs.    The dueling option is meant to further player interaction in a role-playing context. If    someone you've never met or heard of challenges you to a duel, it is probably out of    context and you have a right to refuse the challenge if you feel it does not fit in with    your perception of the game story line. If, however, a particular player has really    started to bug you (or vice versa) in a way that makes sense within the gaming parameters,    you can interact with that player in an aggressive manner without having to relinquish    your -pvp status. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Jes SHADDAP!&nbsp; These    questions give me a headache!</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.8.4</strong> <b>Given    the dueling option, could not EverQuest just eliminate PKilling completely?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Absolutely not. The switch    allows players who get a thrill of living dangerously the opportunity to do just that with    other like minded individuals. +Pvp players don't need to request a duel with each other    -- they can just start swinging.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Yeah, right.&nbsp; Like    we'd ever do something like that.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.9 Will there be an    in-game explanation provided for the PK switch? i.e.: blessing of a god of peace, or    something like that?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes -- we want it to make    sense in the world and have context. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Well, after a fashion...    it makes as much sense as a congress that determines its own salaries, we suppose...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.10 What measures    will be taken given that -pvp players are free to go anywhere they want? What if they got    in your guild house and just sat there?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You'll need to lock the doors    behind you.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Then you'll just have to    deal with it your own way.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.11 Will EverQuest    GMs be biased against pkillers, and will they interfere with a player's game play?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We really don't need to with    the PK Switch. We will favor neither +pvp nor -pvp players.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: GMs will be the    Switzerland of EverQuest.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.12 Any news on the    reward for killing staff people?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No new news, but there will be    one. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Guess we'll have to do    SOMETHING, won't we?&nbsp; Grrrrr....</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.13 What are the    consequences if you PK a lot, randomly?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">There will be consequences to    this, but we're not revealing details at the moment.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: See WTRM 11.5.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.14 Will there be an    option such that a player can tell if another character is +pvp or -pvp?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, it will be visually    apparent to players whether a character is +pvp or -pvp.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: The fact that your    Halberd-of-Ungodly-Peril isn't hurting them might be your first tip-off.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.15 Any chance of    there being a way for +pvp players to kill -pvp players, maybe by contract or something?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Very unlikely.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Sure... but they'll have    to agree to a duel <em>and</em> lose before anyone can collect on it.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.16 Will races be    balanced such that one race is not that much stronger than the others in player vs. player    combat?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Well, we are in the process of    balancing the races and classes, but that doesn't necessarily mean that each race/class    combo should be able to go toe to toe with each other and be about even. Our idea of    balance is that each race/class has a compelling reason behind it, such that they will all    be needed in adventuring and questing. There will undoubtedly be some race/class combos    that do better one on one, especially in a PK situation (note, that's one on one-- some of    these 'weaker' race/class combos might be extremely deadly when they work together, which    adds another dimension to the whole PK environment).</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Don't hold your breath.    &nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>11.17 Which is the race the    most interesting for player-killing?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">That's rather subjective, and    we encourage everyone, when you play the game, to try them all out and come to your own    conclusions and preferences. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: What do I look like,    your personal agent?</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>11.18 Will you receive    experience points for killing another player? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No. In EverQuest, if you want    experience, go quest and adventure. If you want to PK somebody, go ahead, and if you win,    loot him. But you won't receive experience, nor will your skills go up in PK combat. This    is to avoid inherent potential abuse -- for example, two players sparring with one another    to increase their skills.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Nice try.</font></p>    <p align="left">&nbsp;</p>    <p align="left"><font face="Arial"><strong><font color="#C0C0C0" size="5"><a    name="12.0 Character death.">12.0 Character Death.</a></font><font color="#C0C0C0"    size="4"> </font></strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>12.1 How will you deal with    death? Is it permanent or do you just lose some stats, skills, and items?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">It is not permanent, however    there are serious penalties. You will want to seriously avoid death, but if you do make an    error, it doesn't mean that your character you've worked hard on for six months is gone. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: We personally attend a    funeral and console the surviving family.&nbsp; Rest assured (no pun intended) in    EverQuest, death isn't quite the handicap it is in real life.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>12.1.1&nbsp; Is there    the possibility of a character being &quot;permanently&quot; killed? (i.e. Permanent    Death)?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We feel that part of the    allure of EverQuest is the pride you take in building up a character over time. And given    the fact that nastiness can happen in an online environment... like your ISP croaks, your    modem dies, or whatever, that permanent death just isn't yet viable in this genre.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Yes.&nbsp; It's called    &quot;cancel my account.&quot;</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>12.1.2 But in most    paper &amp; pencil RPGs if you get killed in combat, you're forever dead. Why isn't this    going to be the case in EverQuest? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Because you can't control    every aspect of the game environment like in paper &amp; pencil RPGs. You might avoidably    go link dead in a fight and die.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Because it's not    possible to &quot;lose carrier&quot; in a paper and pencil game.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>12.2 Is there a limit to    the number of times you can die?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">No official limit, but given    the penalties, you won't want to do it often. </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Try it and find out.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>12.3 When monsters die,    will they remain as sprites or fade away slowly like in Quake?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Corpses deteriorate over time.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: They remain as 7-Ups.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>12.4 When you die, do    you &quot;resurrect with penalties&quot;? Must you run off to a temple in    &quot;ghost&quot; mode, or what?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You do come back with    penalties -- but not as a ghost, nor where you died.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Resurrection with    penalties... that sounds so familiar.&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>12.5 Any idea how much    stats you will lose when you die?</strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We're not releasing details on    death penalties at this time.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Just enough to hurt    really bad.&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><strong>12.6 Can you fall from    great heights, and will it kill you? </strong></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">You can fall, and you will    take damage, and that damage can kill you.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: ... Ironically, you're    completely safe should you be directly below such a fall...</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>12.7 Can I log off from a    fight to survive?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">If you log off, your character    will still be in the game for a few minutes. He will defend himself, but I'd say it's    certainly not without significant risk.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Technically it's not <em>impossible</em>,    but I really wouldn't recommend trying it if you value your character.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>12.7.1 In Tanarus, if you    hit the ALT-Q, you actually send a signal to the server indicating you want to willingly    leave the game. But if you lose your connection (local brownout, blackout, rodent chews    through power cord, etc.) this signal is not sent. In this situation, couldn't you simply    be listed as &quot;XXXXX has been disconnected&quot; without any penalty and without your    character remaining in the game for a few minutes?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">We would have to handle both    cases in the same manner to avoid abuse by the less than honorable who would intentionally    drop signal (ctrl-alt-del, reset, etc.) to avoid defeat.</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: Another nice try, but    no. (See 11.18)</font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial"><b>12.8 If I lose connection    during a fight, will my character defend himself or will he remain there doing nothing?</b></font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">Yes, see #12.7. </font><font    color="black" size="2" face="Arial">(&lt;-- &quot;Yes???&quot;&nbsp; Huh?)</font><font    color="#C0C0C0" size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp; </font></p>    <p align="left"><font color="black" size="2" face="Arial">WTRM: If I scoop out your    brains, will your body defend itself, or will it remain there doing nothing?</

