<a name="newsitem-1,62401,"></a>
<SPAN CLASS="pagesub">The truth about player killing?</SPAN><br>
<img src="/images/topback.jpg" valign="bottom" width=475 height=2><br>
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Author:</SPAN> 
<span class="credit2">Cerastus  (<a href="mailto:N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a>)</SPAN>&nbsp;&nbsp;  
<SPAN CLASS="credit">Organization:</SPAN> <a href="N/A" class="credit2">N/A</a><br>

<SPAN CLASS="regtext">
<!-- Begin Content -->
<P>
After reading several recent posts on this message board regarding the defense of player killing, we have decided to express our opinion on the invalidity of the arguments for removal of the player vs. player switch.</p><p>First, we'd like to state that there is a time and place for killing other players; soldiers exist in the real world too, and gladiators have been testing their skills for millennia.  The bulk of player killing, however, has little to do with honor or realistic role-playing.  There are exceptions, and we will address them at the bottom of this post.</p><p><b>Player killers shouldn't have to role-play-it's only a game, and people should let others do what they want.</b></p> <p>Serious role-playing involves playing the role of the character you have created--acting as you think they would, not spouting out ridiculous remarks while attempting to act as if you are from olden tymes.  People's main complaint regarding player killers' role-playing ability isn't their modern speech.  After the work that some players put into making their characters as believable and original as possible, becoming the target of a random homicidal maniac's rampage can be very frustrating.</p><p>After spending so much time and effort on creating their characters, average players do not appreciate being killed by someone who laughs at their pain, and is not actually making an effort at role-playing.  If you don't want to be forced to role-play, a better solution might be to restrict killing to those like yourself who don't care about the deeper aspects of the game.  The proposed player vs. player switch offers this opportunity.</p><p><b>I shouldn't be forced to play according to someone else's rules!</b></p><p>This argument is ironic because player killers rob others of options by focusing the game on combat to the exclusion of other pursuits.  By constantly attacking players and attempting to rob them, you effectively force them to change their playing style.  Combat skills become a required part of any successful character's life; this places restrictions on how to play successfully in the game world.  Contrary to popular misconception, the primary challenge of a true role playing game is *not* becoming increasingly adept at killing things.</p> <p><b>Player killers *are* role-playing; there are villains in any society.</b></p><p>If the majority of player killers were actually attempting to be criminals and role-playing it, then this would be a good argument.  Unfortunately, the large majority of player killers parade around destroying other people's work for no reason excused by role-playing-unless you claim to be role-playing a psychopath.  If you are trying to say that player killers are realistic...  Just a few people doing this might be. If an entire quarter of society was made up of mass murderers and thieves, there would soon be no society left.  When the first Mad Max CRPG is introduced, then the idea of random killing as a standard lifestyle might be more acceptable.</p><p><b>Player killers work just as hard at character development-if not harder-than non-player killers.</b></p> <p>Raw investment of time in a *game* is not work... especially when all that time is spent running around like a madman or hitting the same keyboard combination for hours at a time. Power-gaming--finding the easiest possible way to improve a character's statistics, and doing it repeatedly, regardless of whether or not it actually fits the character's profile-is a relatively mindless activity.  It does not require hard work; it just requires patience.  The fact that your character's statistics are improving does not imply that you have put creative effort into your character's development.  If you have sore wrists from your macros, that's your problem.  Try automation.</p><p>There are people who have invested many hours of thought into their criminal characters; we aren't proposing that all evil characters are inherently mindless keyboard products.  The people we are referring to as player killers in this discussion are the people who are pumping up their statistics and then marching off to cleave newbies without regard to why they are doing it.</p><p><b>Player killers take large risks; there is always the chance of losing a battle to another person.</b></p><p>If, in fact, player killers' common victims were their equals in combat, there would be a risk to player killing.  However, most killers simply gang up on the little guy-usually a newbie or a non-combat character.</p> <p>If there is an actual risk, most player killers run away.  The idea of actually taking the risk that they claim to be running is evidently not acceptable.  As anti-player killers in _Ultima_Online_, we spent many hours hunting down newbie killers.  While that might seem hypocritical, it is the one time when risk becomes a factor in killing another player-when two characters tailored for combat meet, the argument above applies.  The player vs. player switch guarantees that killers will fight characters meant to be adversaries, rather than imitating Lancelot's charge in _Monty_Python's_Quest_for_the_Holy_Grail_.  There is no risk in killing flower girls and bridesmaids. </p><p><b>Player killing is necessary because of the mobs of angry newbies roaming the countryside!</b></p><p>Player killers like to argue that they must gang up and wreak havoc for their own survival, because anti-player killers form large bands to hunt them down.  While it's true that large hunting parties form to kill notorious player killers, many of these parties consist of victims seeking revenge-because they were initially killed by their targets, it is only logical that they will need others to support them.</p><p>In addition, if you are going to justify player killing as a part of real life, lynch mobs should be allowed to form, too.  If you are going to have "realistic" crime, then punishment should also be included in the game world.  If a player wants to do something socially unacceptable, then there should logically be consequences.  If you're worried about being the innocent victim of a mob, then turn off player vs. player killing.  It's another risk that comes with killing characters.</p><p><b>Give player killers a break-they have difficult lives.</b></p><p>We've heard that, "Giving up access to towns, and your precious bank box, and building up your character are all hard work."  We've already dealt with the last part of this quote above.  See the point about sore wrists.  The truth of the matter is people that have chosen to player kill in other games have always had it easier than the victims, and it isn't hard work on their part when they pick out easy targets and then bum rush them in a group.</p> <p><b>People get too upset over computer games; they need to wake up and realize how pathetic it is to become absorbed in an alternate reality.</b></p> <p>If you believe that sitting behind a keyboard detaches you from responsibility for your effect on other people's feelings, I suggest that you try calling your victims on the phone after you kill them.  Laughing about other peoples' pain is not more acceptable over an internet connection.  Regardless of your opinion of people who become attached to a computer game character, the practice of destroying their effort for the pleasure of seeing them typing incoherently in anger is cruel.</p><p>Furthermore, human interchanges are not boring without combat.  If your attention span can't handle more complex interactions, I suggest you watch _Power_Rangers_-it is very flashy, involves violence, and will give you the adrenaline rush you crave.</p> <p>Alternately, if you really want the challenge of playing other skilled fighters, we would like to offer two solutions: either play games designed for combat, or attack people with a mindset similar to your own.  The player vs. player switch gives people an opportunity to decide if they want to focus on combat while playing. </p><p><b>Player killers provide the only true excitement in the game; without them the game would be lifeless.</b></p> <p>Some of the more obnoxious player killers have suggested that being nearly killed is the greatest thrill available in the game.  If this is true for an individual, there is no reason why that person can't remove the switch, allowing himself or herself to be vulnerable.</p><p>Forcing all people to face death from other players every time they travel does not add to the longevity or potential enjoyment of a game-if that was the case, the entire player killer debate would not exist.  It is far better to leave this choice to individual tastes than to impose a decision on a game's entire population.  The blatant truth is that most player killers enjoy their work solely because they know that they are forcing someone else to do something against their will.</p><p><b>If people can't defend themselves, then they deserve to be killed anyway.</b></p><p>If we were discussing Quake, this would be a valid argument.  In role playing games, however, the scale of success is not related to the raw killing power of a character-in this sense, a game like Diablo is more a hybrid of action and role playing games than a true RPG.  In a game where character interaction is the focus, being successful as a physically weak character is more noteworthy than having perfect statistics.</p><p><b>Player killing is the only way to gain fame.</b></p><p>If you want to become known as the greatest fighter on the server (or something to that effect), then you don't need to kill everything that moves-just the things that move well.  Killing lagged newbies earns you the wrong kind of fame.  If you want to be the prize a**hole of your home server, we feel for you.  If you want to be known for your steel, use it against worthy opponents, and leave the little guy alone.</p><p>As we mentioned in the section immediately above, it is sometimes more noteworthy to play well with the deck stacked against you than to have all the cards on your side.  You might not gain worldwide fame, but other players that you see regularly will respect you far more than a player killer's victims would.</p><p><b>Wait!  Not all player killers do the things that you describe above!</b></p><p>We agree-and we appreciate a well-considered fighter character as much as the next person does.  Like we said above, if you're interested in proving that the time you've invested in your fighter was well spent, you would be best off fighting other people who want to test *their* fighting skills.  Those people will be the ones with the player protection turned off.</p><p>Thank you for reading,<br>Cerastus<br>XP-Cagey</p>

